<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPICION TARNISHES GRAND DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ ``Just write about the race,'' John Toffan,
co-owner of Free House, winner of the Pacific Classic here
Saturday, admonished a room full of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   OK: Nice race.
</P>
<P>
   And now: About the drugs...
</P>
<P>
   Free House, an otherwise lovable galoot of a horse, with affable
owners and a nice-guy trainer and one of the all-time great
jockeys, now embodies one of the saddest facts of modern racetrack
life, which is that the mere hint of drugs will sour even the
sweetest day.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you talk about it or not. Whether you write about it or
not.
</P>
<P>
   In a swirl of events that, thankfully, is rare, a first-rate
colt raced in a million-dollar stakes Saturday with a medicinal
cloud hanging over him.
</P>
<P>
   After his previous race, a smashing victory at Hollywood Park in
July, Free House tested positive for clenbuterol, a
performance-enhancing drug that's permitted in training but not in
competition. He's one of 20 California horses, spread among seven
trainers, who have had positive tests for clenbuterol in the three
months since lab procedures were refined.
</P>
<P>
   In Free House's case, his handlers are waiting for the
California Horse Racing Board to deliver results of a second test
on the urine sample, which could exonerate them or could set them
up for major sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   For horseplayers, trying to pick a winner based on their recent
form, the lingering questions about Free House added confusion to
an evenly matched Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The fact Free House won the race, defeating important older
horses Gentlemen and Touch Gold in the process, didn't make things
any better.
</P>
<P>
   Either some cheaters won Del Mar's biggest race, and got to
enjoy a guilty party in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Or Toffan, co-owner Trudy McCaffery and trainer Paco Gonzalez
are innocent and it's a crying shame their biggest victory is
tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   With drugs, or the suspicion thereof, there can be no happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   Which is way No. 62 of saying that racing needs to get a handle
on this drug thing.
</P>
<P>
   Or, Just say Neigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, just put yourself in our shoes,'' Toffan said,
increasingly testy as the subject kept coming up after the race.
``That's all I got to say. What kind of emotions would you have?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do anything wrong. We haven't heard back from the
racing board. Whatever happened, happened. But I'll guarantee you
Paco didn't do it. And that's all I can say at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Toffan and McCaffery, Canada natives who are pillars of the
California racing industry and are normally the most media-friendly
of owners, have been careful to have little to say since the
clenbuterol scandal began to brew two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't returned reporters' phone calls. They skipped the
Pacific Classic post-position draw ceremony and press conference on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, it was the owners and Gonzalez who confirmed
the rumors of a positive test to reporters in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffery, Toffan and Gonzalez are not the picture of racetrack
cheaters.
</P>
<P>
   She's a real softy. She cries when her horse loses. She cries
when her horse wins. She probably cried at ``Blazing Saddles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love all my horses,'' McCaffery said in a typical quote. ``I
loved Bien Bien (a top turf horse of the early '90s). But there's
something about Free House that captures you. He's a very sexy
horse. Most horses look straight at you. He kind of does this.''
And Trudy cocked her head and shot you a sly look.
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend, Toffan, is a straight-shooting guy, a success in
oil and gold mining, with the old-fashioned notion that part of the
good life is breeding and owning thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is a friendly, bashful man without a hint of scandal in
nearly a decade of training at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, in his brief comments on the subject, has denied using
clenbuterol. But if the second test comes back positive, the
natural conclusion will be that Free House received clenbuterol
legally in training and traces of the substance were still in his
system when he raced at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   In which case Team Free House will be guilty of nothing more
than miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffery said Saturday she feels ``vindicated'' by Free House's
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast. The laboratory jury is still out.
</P>
<P>
   Until it speaks, all we know for sure is that where racetrack
drugs are concerned, suspicion can happen to anybody. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
