A5927 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-AZR &LR;      08-16 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON INVESTIGATION CAUSES TOUGH QUESTIONS FOR PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He meticulously prepares for an inquiry like none he's faced,
crafting the precise words to be forthcoming, without saying too
much.
</P>
<P>
   But still, he fears a single question:
</P>
<P>
   Daddy, what is oral sex?
</P>
<P>
   He is Chris Hernandez, a Tempe father of two. And, like many
parents, he faces a dilemma in the wake of a presidential scandal
that has mainstream media tossing out intimate _ and very adult _
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he will have to explain the situation to his
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem telling them what's right. My job is to
prepare them for life, and it is part of life,'' said Hernandez,
who has two sons, ages 14 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that parents should be honest with children if
they ask about the allegations against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, you want to give the child a small amount of
information and then see if they need more information,'' said Dr.
Pamela Frazier, a Valley psychiatrist who works with adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier suggests that parents avoid letting their children watch
if Clinton decides to make televised remarks after he testifies
before a federal grand jury Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably is going to be over the child's head, and it may
give him or her more information than she's ready to deal with,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Brinkerhoff, a counselor who works with young children,
said, ``Certainly, talking about values is important, and honesty
is one of those values.''
</P>
<P>
   She also advised parents to avoid detailed explanations if
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose the younger the child, the less specific you are
going to be about behavior,'' Brinkerhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier urged parents to provide explanations about the news
events that are consistent with their own values.
</P>
<P>
   ``A young child they might feel confused that the president is
accused of being involved with a woman that's not his wife,''
Frazier said. ``The parent then would be in a position of perhaps
saying, `Well, sometimes adults do have relationships with other
people, and it's not necessarily what we think is right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Doren, a Tempe mother of two, said her 6-year-old daughter
already has asked why Clinton is often shown with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too long ago, we had a ``Newsweek,'' and she asked me,
`Mommy, why is he always in pictures with that woman?' '' Doren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, she fears, the questions might get more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan: ``Don't give them any more information than they ask
for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Degon, a mother of three girls, ages 10, 8 and 7, from
Arizona City, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are too young to know the nitty-gritty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez hopes he never has to answer graphic questions about
the presidential sex life. He hopes that, perhaps, for his boys,
the bustle of starting school will be more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he doubts they'll look to the president as a role
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're into sports and cartoons,'' he said. ``Clinton is not
a hero to them. Sports figures are _ you know, Tiger Woods and Mark
McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   But, if the boys do ask about the allegations against the
president, Hernandez said he'll be straight with them:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's human. All humans can do wrong.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Alexa Haussler can be reached at 444-7481 or at
alexa.haussler &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
