r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SIDEKICKS-KNIGHTS     08-16 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SIDEKICKS-KNIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDEKICKS RECOVER, TATTOO KNIGHTS, 10-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's a familiar, peculiar habit the Dallas Sidekicks
have developed the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Look awful on the road. Look stunning at home the next game.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Sidekicks (1-1) followed a poor effort with
another outstanding game in a 10-2 victory against the Sacramento
Knights before 10,621 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Dallas lost at Sacramento, 8-1. The Knights
appeared the team to beat in the new Premier Soccer Alliance at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wallop us, we wallop them,'' Sidekicks player/coach Tatu
said. ``So far there's no edge. We can't put ourselves as favorites
until we win with consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Goals by six different Sidekicks, including two by Tatu, fueled
a 7-1 halftime lead. Tatu scored his first goal with the Sidekicks,
threading the defense on a free kick for an early 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tatu assisted on three Dallas goals and punched a shot through
the legs of a Knights defender for his second score.
</P>
<P>
   Except for newly acquired veteran Dale Ervine, Sacramento showed
little on offense. Dallas defenders Mike Powers, Beto and Rusty
Troy formed a wall in front of goalie Shawn Ray, helping him to
shut down the Knights, including a 53-minute scoreless stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tribute to our team defense at home,'' Troy said. ``On
the road, we just need to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The night ended badly for Ray, who limped off with a bruised
thigh after a first-quarter collision.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Stavrou and Gary Young scored two goals apiece. Giampaulo
Pedroso, Tatu and others set up goals with deft passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outmuscled us, outran us and completely dominated us in
Sacramento,'' Tatu said. ``Losing 8-1 to those guys pumped me up.
We had to prove a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento was scoreless the final 27 minutes of the first half
after a goal by Ervine was waved off. Officials ruled Sacramento
had too many men on the carpet when Ervine scored. The game was
then delayed 10 minutes while Ervine and Knights coach Iain Fraser
argued the call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
