<HEADER>
A5932 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-DODGERS-LA     08-16 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS FLEA COLLAR TOO TIGHT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You see the woman on the first-base side masquerading as a
poodle _ the floppy ears, cotton candy tail and jewelry-studded
collar and leash were something to behold _ and your first thought
is: Finally, someone came to Dodger Stadium dressed for the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The dog days of this Dodgers season continued Saturday afternoon
with a 5-3 loss to the National League's front-runners, the Atlanta
Braves. It was the Dodgers' eighth loss in 11 games, begging the
question: When, exactly, do they plan to stop chasing their
collective tail and go after the bone that is the wild-card berth?
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was as fine a day as any to make a little headway in
the pennant chase, as the Braves, in a twist, weren't nearly as
stifling as the sticky weather. The NL East leaders stranded 12
runners, starting pitcher John Smoltz struggled and second baseman
Tony Graffanino gift-wrapped the Dodgers' scores in the first
inning by bobbling the ball on a sure-fire, inning-ending double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino's gaffe loaded the bases and Bobby Bonilla emptied
two of them with a one-out single. Bonilla and first baseman Eric
Karros were stranded after Matt Luke struck out looking and Mark
Grudzielanek went down swinging.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers would manufacture only one more run, on Eric Young's
solo homer in the fifth. Nothing new there. The Dodgers had scored
three or fewer runs in seven of their previous 10 games (and lost
five of the seven).
</P>
<P>
   That's why hearts in the Dodgers dugout sank when Andres
Galarraga sent starter Chan Ho Park's 16th pitch of the game into
the center-field seats to put the Braves ahead 3-0 before any
Dodger had taken a swing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Dodgers' bats have been so quiet, they belong in
library stacks, not dugout racks. Grudzielanek's single in the
sixth was his first hit in three games; Luke's grounder to third in
the fourth was his first contact with rawhide in six at-bats;
Cedeno is hitless in this series, which concludes today.
</P>
<P>
   Luke is a rookie, Cedeno is in his first full season in the
majors and Grudzielanek is adjusting to his surroundings, having
been a Dodger for all of two weeks. Those looking for scapegoats
could round up those three and herd them off to the guillotines
along with struggling first-year players Trenidad Hubbard and
Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for excuses could blame injuries to two starting
pitchers (Ramon Martinez and Ismael Valdes) as well as another
starter, shortstop Jose Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for answers would do well to look hard in the
mirror (president Bob Graziano and general manager Tommy Lasorda,
that goes for you, too).
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't reflect well on the leadership in the clubhouse that
center fielder Raul Mondesi was charged with driving under the
influence earlier in the season or that outfielder Gary Sheffield's
family had to be bought off (in the form of all-expense-paid trips
to Denver) before he would agree to participate in the All-Star
game at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't bode well for the chemistry in the clubhouse when
Karros, another avowed leader, points a finger of blame for the
Dodgers' recent bumbling and stumbling in the general direction of
the younger players, as he did after Saturday's setback.
</P>
<P>
   How, pray tell, is Hubbard helped by Karros pointing out a day
after the fact that the key to Friday's 5-2 loss was not
Galarraga's three-run homer but Hubbard's at-bat in the fifth
inning? Hubbard stepped up to the plate with two outs, runners on
first and second and the Dodgers down by three, chased a 3-1 pitch
and popped out to end the inning with Mondesi on deck.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hubbard could have tried to draw a walk _ or at least
a full count. But before teeing off on his teammate, Karros should
have considered this: Maybe Hubbard has seen one or more of the
veterans' baleful stares and was trying, with one mighty swing, to
show them he deserves to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to prove he belongs in the big leagues,'' Karros
conceded in an effort to cushion his criticism. Next time Karros
should try a pat on the back, administered in private.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the target is the playoffs, a pitch (or a teammate), the
Dodgers might as well be swinging at rainbows. They entered the
weekend six games behind the Chicago Cubs in the wild-card race. If
the Cubs win 50 percent of their remaining games _ hardly a Ruthian
task considering 21 of Chicago's next 27 games are against teams
with losing records _ the Dodgers will have to win 26 of their
final 39 games to erase the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Winning two in a row would be a start. Winning four in a row
would be a first.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to make some run,'' Bonilla said.
</P>
<P>
   But how, if not with stellar pitching or timely hitting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can hold a seance,'' Bonilla joked.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they should summon Fifi, the Poodle Lady from San Pedro,
who said she wasn't dogging it to make a statement about the team
but rather ``to entertain the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   All you know is her bark was worse than the Dodgers' bite. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
