r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX     08-16 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNING AHEAD KEEPS BRONCOS ON TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Switzer is long gone, so we've all put back into the
woodshed that tar, those feathers and those nooses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, allow me to dig up a Fisher forecast, pre-Chan Gailey's
hire, that went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry says he plans to keep the next coach from `being saddled
with the sort of criticism that surrounded Barry.' Jerry, I don't
wanna bet. That's almost a certainty, not just because it's your
plans, but because it's ours. Prediction: ... The next coach gets
more free rides here than a supermodel hitchhiker.''
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the Cowboys' exhibition-opening couple of weekends,
complete with everything from scenes from a game of Clue (''Col.
Mustard in the kitchen with a candlestick; ``Michael Irvin in the
dormitory with a scissors'') to four 12-men-on-the-field violations
in one sequence against Seattle to a 16-3 loss to Oakland that was
even more embarrassing than the previous debacle against the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Amid it all, Gailey receives nothing but praise and
understanding as the media assessors keep pumping gas into the Chan
Gailey Honeymoon Limousine.
</P>
<P>
   How did it go again? Switzer's successor ``gets more free rides
here than a supermodel hitchhiker.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, however, it should be pointed out that training
camp is the time when organizations must work out their kinks. Some
are fortunate enough to be able to do it smoothly, like the Denver
Broncos have. Others, like the Oakland Raiders, probably outkink
even the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   A training-camp tale each from two AFC West cities:
</P>
<P>
   We go to Oakland, where it was only a brief line of agate type
in the transactions one day, and then another brief line the next
day. But it represents an NFL personnel guy's training camp
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   First the Raiders announced the signing of defensive lineman
Shannon Clavelle. Then a reporter informed Raiders boss Al Davis
that Clavelle has something of a shady background.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that days before his signed with Oakland, Clavelle had
been arrested in Stillwater, Okla., on charges of being a prowler.
When Stillwater police were booking him, they discovered he was a
fugitive from justice in Colorado and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Clavelle made bail and started his trip to California. But
before he could be fitted for a uniform, he was out of a job. Davis
had cut him, meaning Clavelle got to be a Raiders Bad Boy for just
20 hours, upon which time he was forced to return to his day job _
Real-Life Bad Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Now we go to Denver, where they're already looking forward to a
fifth exhibition scheduled for 1999. Why? Because, coach Mike
Shanahan says, the game in Sydney, Australia, against the Chargers
will come in handy for whomever replaces the then-retired John
Elway at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``\ROwner\S Pat Bowlen asked me about a fifth game next year and
I said, knowing our current situation, I'd be for it,'' Shanahan
says. ``You would really like that fifth game, to put an
inexperienced quarterback or an experienced quarterback in a
situation where he could have as many reps as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are scheduling 1999 exhibitions based on the
anticipated retirement of players? Now that's the sort of luxury
planning of which the Cowboys and Raiders can only dream.
Numbers game
</P>
<P>
   The lucky number for the Vikings is five:
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings might have stability in ownership now with the
takeover by Red McCombs. Now if they get some stability at
quarterback going into the playoffs. In coach Denny Green's six
seasons, the Vikings have reached the playoffs five times. And in
each of those five tries, they've been quarterbacked by a different
guy: Sean Salisbury (1992), Jim McMahon ('93), Warren Moon ('94),
Brad Johnson ('96) and Randall Cunningham ('97). Keep Johnson
healthy this year, say the odds, and Green keeps his playoff streak
and his job.
Trivial pursuit
</P>
<P>
   From the You'll Never Guess Department: Who leads the NFL in
interceptions in the last three years? Try Keith Lyle of the Rams
with 20.
Quotable
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy Central'''s Craig Kilborn cracks wise on the proposed
new pro football league: ``Analysts are excited about the new
league and predict it will offer many exciting new opportunities to
exclude blacks from coaching and management jobs.''
Check out. ...
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Doug Flutie, already a fan favorite in Buffalo, but
growing tired of some observers' negativity. ``For eight years in
Canada nobody asked how tall I was,'' says the 5-foot-10 Heisman
Trophy winner. ``Nobody cared. Did you win? That's all that
mattered.'' Flutie had a few go-rounds in the NFL, remember, with
New England and Chicago, before becoming a CFL superstar. In his
past two seasons in Toronto, he won two Grey Cup titles, threw for
11,000 yards and 76 touchdowns with 41 interceptions. He begins the
season backing up big-monied ex-Jag Rob Johnson, but if the Bills
struggle, Flutie is certain to be the people's choice.
</P>
<P>
   THE BUZZ NFC
Arizona first-round draft choice Andre Wadsworth, the pass-rusher
who was supposed to help turn the franchise around, has instead
spent the week talking of returning to school at Florida State, one
more example of why the Cardinals will remain the Cardinals as long
as the Bidwill family is in charge. ... Bam Morris is in the Bears'
camp, the running back-turned-drug offender now weighing in at 257
pounds. Bam's supporters say he's athletic enough to handle the
extra tonnage, but he's running 40-yard dashes in the 5-second
range, meaning Cowboys offensive lineman Larry Allen could smoke
him in a sprint. ... Packers general manager Ron Wolf says Green
Bay's only real problem is depth in the secondary. ... The Bucs
have beaten the bushes for talent, which is why the college with
the most representation on their roster isn't anywhere near Notre
Dame or Nebraska or Florida State. It's Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville, the
Division II school with five of its former players in the Bucs'
camp. ... Robert Brooks' back problems could cause him to miss the
next month, a far bigger story if not for Green Bay's astounding
ability to overcome lineup changes at wide receiver. ... With
Carmen Policy no longer running the 49ers, look for the natural San
Francisco-Oakland preseason meetings to become an annual event.
Policy's dislike and distrust of Al Davis is among the reasons the
series was discontinued after 1993 despite a history that dates to
1967. ... Watching Mike Ditka coach the Saints is like watching
classic Warner Bros. cartoons: You don't know exactly when it's
going to happen, but you know it's going to happen. And you know
it'll have something to do with an anvil, some ACME dynamite, or an
unseen cliff. ... Most popular attraction at 49ers camp? Julie
Cialini, the 1995 Playboy Playmate of the Year and girlfriend to
quarterback Jim Druckenmiller. This is apparently the way things
work in San Francisco: Play quarterback and date a model. Ask Joe
Montana.
AFC
</P>
<P>
   Interesting little trick the NFL included in the fine print of
its rules regarding the Cleveland franchise: The club, which has
the benefit of extra draft picks, cannot use any of those picks to
pry a coach loose from his current club. This is to prevent a
repeat of that nasty Jets-Patriots-Bill Parcells business. It also
makes Green Bay, Kansas City and Pittsburgh feel more secure about
the respective futures of Mike Holmgren, Marty Schottenheimer and
Bill Cowher. ... Pro Bowl tackle Gary Zimmerman isn't doing this to
the Broncos on purpose, but the way he sort of winks every time he
says he's retiring (again) is a Denver disruption. ... Bengals
runner Corey Dillon, coming off a fine rookie season, is setting
his sights on a 2,000-yard season. Two problems: One, Dillon
probably doesn't have that sort of talent; Two, to rush for 2,000
yards your team must be ahead frequently late in games, and
Cincinnati definitely doesn't have that kind of talent. ...
Parcells says he is trying to avoid a quarterback controversy with
the Jets yet he starts Glenn Foley one week and starts Vinny
Testaverde the next week. A contradiction? Yes, but Parcells'
handling of quarterback controversies (see: Phil Simms, Chapters I
and II) makes him beyond reproach in this area. ... Did you hear
about Jimmy Johnson going berserk on the sideline after Dolphins
cornerback Terrell Buckley got too physical with a Redskins
opponent last weekend? Buckley got too physical, so Jimmy grabbed
Buckley by the facemask and did the same. ... Fernando Smith had
asked the Cowboys and other clubs for $1.3 million for a one-year
deal. The ex-Vikings defensive end took one more shopping trip
around the NFL and landed in Jacksonville _ at a cost of $1.6
million. ... As with Troy Aikman and his frequent salary
restructures, Denver quarterback John Elway is being made out a
hero because he's re-done his deal to lower his 1998 salary to an
eye-popping $300,000. It makes for a good story but remember: These
quarterbacks aren't giving back money; they're just deferring it to
another year, in many cases at a higher rate to reflect interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
