<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX     08-16 2610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD SPORTS TAKE ROOT WHERE CIVILITY ONCE THRIVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Curry is not one to say sport was kinder and gentler in his
day, the 1960s and 1970s, when he played in the NFL for Vince
Lombardi and Don Shula, or the 1980s, when he coached at Georgia
Tech and the University of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never nice and gentlemanly in the NFL,'' he states.
``We always kicked each other in the pile.''
</P>
<P>
   But Curry has noticed a change in the level of sportsmanship
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls a freshman player he coached at the University of
Kentucky in 1993 who, on the opening kickoff of the season, drilled
the return man at the 20-yard line and proceeded to strut his way
into the opponent's end zone, drawing an unsportsmanlike conduct
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, I don't know why I did that,'' Curry recalled the
suddenly contrite player saying on his return to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew why,'' Curry said. ``That's all he'd ever seen on TV
growing up. You've got a bunch of 18-year-olds today who've been
told they're great and who see their heroes mouthing off on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture is not interested in civility. Naturally, that
carries over into the athletic arena.''
</P>
<P>
   A great many other people involved in sports, including players,
coaches, administrators and fans, agree with Curry's blunt
assessment. Sportsmanship, they say, is declining at a rapid rate.
And society is the poorer for it.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when pro basketball players choke their coaches,
baseball players spit on umpires and college athletes expect their
teammates to cheat in order to win, has sportsmanship lost all
relevance in today's society?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who has followed athletics in America over the past 20
years must conclude there has been a general erosion in the
standards of acceptable conduct for coaches, athletes and fans at
competitive events,'' says Big Ten Conference Commissioner Jim
Delany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sportsmanship is dead,'' Vic Bubas, former men's
basketball coach at Duke and former commissioner of the Sun Belt
Conference, said in The NCAA News. ``The state of it is pitiful,
awful. (And) I think the worst is ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is as pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Many athletes and sports officials believe sportsmanship is
still a viable notion. What's more, they say, as long as bad
sportsmanship is noted and criticized, there is still hope that it
will improve. Yet, even optimists acknowledge the situation has
been getting worse in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in sportsmanship, some observers say, reflects a
larger societal problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' says tennis great Billie Jean King.
``Look at life. Look how fast the world moves. I just think people
are more outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a society whose character, whose moral fiber, is
definitely being challenged,'' says Alan Page, an NFL Hall of Fame
lineman who now is an associate justice of the Minnesota Supreme
Court. ``Athletes are only the very visible tip of the iceberg in
this problem, but they have a special obligation to be people of
character.''
Roll call of bad sports
</P>
<P>
   No one can pinpoint just when the alarm sounded that signaled a
decline in sportsmanship. But several high-profile events likely
set it off.
</P>
<P>
   Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Orioles' infielder Roberto Alomar's spitting at umpire
John Hirshbeck during an argument in a game late in the 1996
baseball season. This is widely cited as a symbol of the eroding
control of authority figures in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bulls forward Dennis Rodman head-butting a referee,
kicking a courtside photographer in the groin during a game,
routinely skipping practices, and fighting with and mocking
opponents _ yet keeping his job on a world championship team and
being idolized by many youths. More than anyone, Rodman
demonstrates that in today's world of sports, an athlete can
disrespect everyone, including himself, and still prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State Warriors guard Latrell Sprewell choking his coach,
P.J. Carlesimo, during an argument at a basketball practice,
tearing down, for good, perhaps, the invisible wall of restraint
between player and coach.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer Mike Tyson biting the ear of fellow heavyweight Evander
Holyfield during a fight in Las Vegas, registering a new low even
in the most maligned of sports.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there have been any number of baseball beanball
brawls, on-court basketball battles and hot-dogging and showboating
scenes by touchdown-scoring football players and slam-dunking
hoopsters.
</P>
<P>
   Then there have been the cheap shots, the low blows and the
chemically enhanced performances, plus fan riots, referee baiting
and opponent taunting. Finally, there are coaches who run up the
score to assure their ascent in the weekly polls or who push
recruiting regulations to the limits in order to procure the best
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the on-the-field unsportsmanlike behavior occurs ``in
the heat of the moment,'' according to athletes, and even sports
ethicists reluctantly accept such actions as an occasional part of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   There also are those who argue that the appropriateness of some
acts widely regarded as unsportsmanlike _ ``excessive'' celebration
and taunting, to name two _ is in the eye of the beholder.
According to that argument, an athlete's cultural background
determines his behavioral boundaries on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   But other recent acts, the Sprewell choking incident for one,
clearly go beyond these boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Not that sport was ever pure, its athletes completely virtuous.
Certain unsportsmanlike acts from the past stand out years, or even
decades later.
</P>
<P>
   For violence in the playing arena, look back to 1972 when
several players on the University of Minnesota basketball team
brutally attacked an Ohio State player during a game for the Big
Ten Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ohio State football coach Woody Hayes' punching of a
Clemson University football player on the sidelines at the end of
the 1978 Gator Bowl is forever frozen in our memories. Indiana
basketball coach Bobby Knight's ongoing physical confrontations
with his own players (hitting) and with officials (chair tossing)
is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali, renowned today for his statesmanship, helped
legitimize taunting in sports with his merciless baiting of
opponents ranging from Sonny Liston to Joe Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball great Ty Cobb is remembered for his ruthless ways with
opponents and fans as well as for his Hall of Fame playing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can go back 20 years or 30 years or 40 years and find the
same sort of thing,'' Page says of unsportsmanlike behavior. ``But
maybe there's been an increase in the level and the quality of the
misconduct. I have a sense that it's increased.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that even the most laissez-faire modern-day
athlete would sanction outright violence in the sporting arena, but
many see nothing unsportsmanlike about the theatrics that often
accompany a big basket, a game-turning touchdown or a monster home
run.
</P>
<P>
   What old-time ballplayers, sports officials and administrators
regard as taunting or excessive celebration, many contemporary
athletes regard as a style of celebration. To them, standing at
home plate and watching their home-run ball leave the park,
prancing into the end zone after a score, or mugging for the camera
after a slam dunk is all just part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran NFL defensive back Ray Crockett explained that position
in an ESPN interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever been out on the island, one-on-one, for the game
winner,'' he asked, ``and they throw the ball and you knock it down
or intercept it? Have you ever had that feeling?''
</P>
<P>
   If you had, Crockett said, ``You might want to high-step like
Deion Sanders for a minute and say, `That felt good.' You know what
I mean?''
Hard to define, easy to spot
</P>
<P>
   Sports philosophers don't offer a single definition of
sportsmanship, but most say it is rooted in ethics and hinges on
fair play and respect for one's self, one's opponent, officials,
spectators and the game itself. Though tough to define, just about
anyone involved in sports knows good or bad sportsmanship when they
see it, and no society would say it is unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of sportsmanship is absolutely essential precisely
because it captures the ethical dimension of our games,'' said
Russell Gough, a Pepperdine University professor and author of
``Character is Everything: Promoting Ethical Excellence in
Sports''.
</P>
<P>
   In sports, as in society, there must be a minimum, basic ethical
foundation or a minimum of ethical values, Gough told ``The NCAA
News''. If not, he adds, ``Our games will self-destruct.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, says Diana Nyad, a record-breaking long-distance
swimmer who is now a sports journalist: ``We have come to a point
where, like in war, everything is tolerated. This is sports, and
everything is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are frequent examples of good, even
outstanding sportsmanship. On one recent Sunday, sports fans got to
see Iranian soccer players present white flowers to Team USA before
their World Cup match. Afterward, the players exchanged jerseys.
The scenes gave some small hope that through sport, ruptured
political relations between the nations might someday be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   On that same day in June, golfer Payne Stewart showed true grace
after losing a substantial lead and the U.S. Open championship to
Lee Janzen. Stewart not only complimented Janzen and faced the
media with honesty and openness, he flashed a self-deprecating
sense of humor that put the tournament and the role of sport in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   At the Winter Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan, gold-medal
cross-country skier Bjorn Daehlie waited in the cold for the
last-place finisher, Philip Boit to cross the line. When Boit, the
first Kenyan to participate in the Winter Games, completed the
event, Daehlie, without fanfare, was there to give him a pat on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   These examples of good sportsmanship do offer hope to future
generations of athletes and fans. As it is, concerned sports
officials say, bad sportsmanship by adult athletes is having a
negative effect on children.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Alliance for Youth Sports, a
Florida-based nonprofit organization, 70 percent of children will
quit sports by age 13 ``because it isn't fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance says 45 percent of children have been called names
and insulted while playing sports, and 71 percent wouldn't care if
no score was kept _ so severe are the consequences of having to
win.
</P>
<P>
   Those alarmed about the decline in sportsmanship at lower levels
of competition cite the influence professional athletes have on
youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys (pro athletes) have become heroes to the younger
generation. They dominate the stage of the child's imagination,''
says Jeff Benedict, former research coordinator at Northeastern
University's Center for the Study of Sport in Society. Celebrity,
status, wealth and fame, Benedict says, are now more important than
character, truth and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Many athletes say they are aware of the influence their actions
have on young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pattern themselves after us,'' says Mike Modano, the most
prominent member of the Dallas Stars. ``They act like us on the
playing field.'' For that reason, he adds, ``You really have to be
on your toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal evidence suggests that the emphasis on winning by any
means necessary has had a detrimental effect on the behavior of
young athletes. High school sports have seen a shocking series of
unsportsmanlike acts in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In Albuquerque, N.M., the dentist father of a high school
football player filed down the metal buckle on his son's helmet to
a razor-sharp edge that subsequently cut and injured five opposing
players. The father hoped to prevent opponents from grabbing his
son's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   In Colville, Wash., a high school wrestler, incensed that a
referee had penalized him a point for throwing a shoulder into his
opponent, head-butted the official, knocking him unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my temper, I guess,'' the wrestler explained.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Fred Gomez, the father of defending Class 4A doubles
tennis champions Jessica and Vanessa Gomez of Colleyville Heritage,
was ejected from the regional tournament in Denton after he was
accused of throwing orange peels at a Highland Park player in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Nathan Shafer, a former wrestler at MacArthur. He
pushed a referee, shoved a camera into a photographer's face, got
into an altercation with a security guard and knocked over a food
table after losing a semifinal match at the Texas State High School
Wrestling Championships last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, sportsmanship is in serious trouble,'' says
Ken Mays, a 33-year-old probation officer from Arlington and coach
of a girls youth basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the time you'll find parents and coaches with the
wrong attitude,'' Mays says. ``Winning can't be the sole reason for
being out here, especially at this age.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays found it necessary to go out to the bleachers before a
recent game and tell parents: ``Remember, these are kids. We're out
here to encourage them and support them. If they mess up or don't
do as well as you think they should, please don't get on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays touches on a point made by sports psychologists when
discussing the erosion of sportsmanship. That is, there is a
greater emphasis than ever on winning in sports. No longer is it
honorable simply to play your best and to play fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, society right now is `win at all costs,''' says
Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman. ``I don't believe in
winning at all costs. You do everything you can to win, but you've
got a certain set of rules.''
Providing good examples
</P>
<P>
   If anything positive can be taken from the discussion of the
sorry state of sportsmanship, it is that groups have begun to
organize to call attention to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   National Sportsmanship Day, an annual event since 1991, was
developed by the Institute for International Sport, ``to create an
awareness of the issues of ethics, fair play and sportsmanship in
athletics and in the broader context of society.''
</P>
<P>
   The event provides a forum for athletes, coaches,
administrators, fans and parents to discuss those issues. More than
10,000 schools participated in the event this year.
</P>
<P>
   Further, resource materials such as instructional videotapes are
being produced and made available to student-athletes and their
coaches to teach players the basic principles of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Big Ten Conference now distributes a pamphlet
to athletes and coaches that calls for a ``commitment to fair play
and ethical conduct in sports,'' according to Jim Delany.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the pamphlet states that, ``Conduct intended to
intimidate, embarrass or demean the opponent by players, coaches or
fans is contrary to the educational mission of intercollegiate
athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   The guides come none too soon for Delany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on a slippery slope on the sportsmanship issue,'' says
Delany. ``The conduct of the playground was coming into
intercollegiate athletics. It was not just the examples of taunting
or unsportsmanlike conduct, but also the increasing presence of
self adulation masquerading as celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts offer hope that sportsmanship, however wounded, is
not dead. But even more Draconian action may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's time,'' says Alan Page, ``for the sports world to
consider a code of conduct, a code of ethics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
