<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SPORTSMANSHIP PACKAGE 
GAMESMANSHIP VS. SPORTSMANSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A popular television commercial of a year or so ago featured
retired bad-boy basketball player Bill Laimbeer instructing
nice-guy basketball star Grant Hill in the finer points of on-court
gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Flopping, ref-baiting, the undetectable elbow.
</P>
<P>
   It was a funny spot, but it also showed just how accepted
gamesmanship has become in sports. And sports ethicists say it's
another sign of the general erosion of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Gamesmanship does not include breaking the written rules of the
game, but it does go well beyond the standards of good
sportsmanship, says Scott Kretchmar, who heads the graduate program
in sport philosophy at Penn State University.
</P>
<P>
   Kretchmar calls gamesmanship, ``the art and science of gaining a
strategic advantage through morally questionable means.''
</P>
<P>
   A lack of moral courage ``has allowed for an increasing amount
of gamesmanship,'' Kretchmar said. ``It's been reduced to the point
where wins are valuable, not the way you win.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent example of gamesmanship: A baseball manager has
the bat of an opposing batter who's on a hitting tear checked for
cork, even though he knows it's not corked. The idea is to distract
the batter and reduce his effectiveness at the plate. Two variants:
have a pitcher checked for a foreign substance on his body, merely
to throw off his rhythm; call time-out before the opposing kicker
attempts a game-winning field goal in order to ``ice him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamesmanship, sports ethicists say, is unsportsmanlike precisely
because it takes away from the legitimate means of determining who
is the best on a given day in a particular sport.
</P>
<P>
   It is a practice, they say, that disrespects the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, acts of gamesmanship have become standard practice.
Kretchmar notes that nowadays ``there is no tension between
sportsmanship and gamesmanship,'' meaning that people don't
distinguish between the two anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5936 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEHAVIORAL-AZR &LR;      08-16 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEHAVIORAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHAVIORAL QUESTIONS DURING INTERVIEW BETTER INDICATOR OF JOB
PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
You're cool, calm and collected, and all of a sudden the
interviewer wants to know if you ever ran out of Halloween candy
while there were still trick-or-treaters on your street.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you turn out the lights and pretend you weren't home, or,
did you improvise with some nuts or cookies from the kitchen?
</P>
<P>
   Your first reaction is, ``Huh?'' But, if you're involved in a
behavioral interview, your job prospects depend on giving the
correct answers to such seemingly irrelevant questions.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a new concept, but it is increasingly thought to be a
better predictor of job performance than traditional interviews and
is growing in popularity among recruiters and human resource
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hot right now,'' said Rick Camp, who teaches
strategic inter viewing in the University of Michi gan Business
School's executive program. ``Everybody who is state of the art is
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Behavioral interviewing seeks to evaluate candidates by
assessing their specific actions and behaviors in given
circumstances. It is loosely based on the concept of behavioral
consistency in which past behavior is thought to be the best
indicator of future actions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to eliciting general infor mation about a
candidate's knowl edge or expertise, interviewers, using the
technique, encourage subjects to recount, in detail, job situations
and the results of specific actions, even for seemingly minor
tasks.
</P>
<P>
   An airline customer service agent has to be able to deal with
angry people, so an interviewer might ask appli cants to describe
their last experience with an angry person, or customer.
</P>
<P>
   People in sales have to occasionally put people in uncomfortable
situa tions, so a candidate might be asked to describe the last
time they had to deliver bad news to a group or individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazingly effective,'' said Marc Blessing, vice president
of corporate development Management Recruiters International, a
Cleveland-based search and recruitment firm, that trains companies
how to use the technique. ``An interviewer can tell much more about
a person's atti tudes, work habits and skills by hearing them
describe real actions taken in real circumstances than by letting
them go on in abstract terms about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Deb Johnson, a recruiter with U-Haul International in Phoenix,
has been using the technique for about three months and swears by
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very effective means of interviewing,'' she said.
``You're able to determine how a person would approach a situation
in the future based on what they did in the past.'' She said it
also is an effective means of reducing turnover, by improving the
odds of hiring the right person in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Blessing noted that some employers estimate the cost of choosing
the wrong candidate at three times the employee's first-year
salary. And that doesn't include the cost of having the position
effectively vacant until a productive individual can be found, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the cost of a bad hiring decision and the generally tight
prevailing labor market, Blessing said companies are looking at be
havioral interviewing as a means to improve their odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's market you can't afford to make a hiring mistake or
to miss out on talent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blessing said studies have shown that conventional interviews in
which candidates are asked to give opinions on their abilities can
be no better at picking the right candidate than flipping a coin.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have rehearsed answers and fancy comebacks to the
questions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief advantages of behavioral interviewing,
according to Camp, is that candidates are unable to prepare for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't just come up with a canned answer, he explained.''
</P>
<P>
   But to get the most out of the process, the interviewer needs to
know what success is and what questions will measure that success.
But most importantly, the inter viewer needs to know what answers
demonstrate the level of success required.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are doing behav ioral interviewing, but they
are ask ing the wrong questions and anticipating the wrong
answers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the movement there is debate whether the questions should
ask what candidates did in a particular situation, or what they
would have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some candidates may not have had a particular experience, but
they have the knowledge insight and skills to have handled it
properly,' Camp said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's harder to rehearse answers to behavioral interview
questions, some candidates can gain an advantage over others if
they recognize the technique and are prepared to answer questions
in an appropriate way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more a question of making the interview go a little
better by know ing what's required of you,'' blessing said.
</P>
<P>
   He offered candidates these sug gestions for recognizing
behavioral techniques:
</P>
<P>
   _ Behavioral interviews often begin with a statement that the
interviewer will be looking for specific instances from real
situations in answer to the questions and that the candidate should
not be nervous about pausing to consider answers.
</P>
<P>
   _Questions often begin with words such as, ``Tell me about a
specific situation in which you . . .''
</P>
<P>
   _When the candidate wanders to ward generalities, the
interviewer will often coax the candidate back to specific
examples, asking for the names of people, their titles and other
concrete details. Often the interviewer will rephrase the question
so it sounds different, but elicits the same information.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the possibility of a behavioral interview,
Blessing offers this advice:
</P>
<P>
   _Decide what your chief skills or strengths are and fix in your
mind actual experiences that exemplify them. Be sure to recall or
remind yourself of dates, names, quantities or other measurements
of success.
</P>
<P>
   _Understand the description of the job for which you are
interviewing and be prepared to recall specific actions and
behaviors which address the skills needed for the position.
</P>
<P>
   _Specificity is more important than vague proclamations of
skills. Small but telling actions and behaviors are more important
than unsubstan tiated claims of job success.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expects you to have sin gle-handedly saved the world,
the company and your immediate boss from sure ruination,''
Management Recruiters President Allen Salikof said. ``They simply
hope that you're the one who can effectively do the job they're
hiring for.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Max Jarman can be reached at
 &UR; 444-7351 or at max.jarman &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
