<HEADLINE>
RIP SPORTSMANSHIP: IT SEEMS AS THOUGH WE HARDLY KNEW YE 
WITH SPORTSMANSHIP PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sportsmanship used to be winning and losing with grace.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsmanship was respecting your opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsmanship was respecting the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsmanship, ultimately, was knowing how to behave.
</P>
<P>
   We are gathered here today, therefore, to mourn the passing of
Sportsmanship. It died, without so much as a mention on
SportsCenter, after a long and fitful illness.
</P>
<P>
   Pallbearers included its former allies Humility, Honesty and
Fairness. Two more recent acquaintances, Greed and Selfishness,
were invited to carry the casket, but, without calling anyone,
elected not to show up.
</P>
<P>
   The great Jim McKay, who spent a career extolling Sportsmanship,
delivered the eulogy. Conversely, out of respect for Sportsmanship,
all ESPN anchors and radio talk-show hosts in attendance were
ordered to tape their mouths shut.
</P>
<P>
   Attending physicians weren't certain exactly sure how
Sportsmanship died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody charged the pitcher's mound and pummeled him to
death,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Another doctor offered, ``I think somebody forced him to take
anabolic steroids and try out for the East German Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the possibility, police say, that Sportsmanship's
death was hastened by foul play.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects include Mike Tyson, Latrell Sprewell, Ben Johnson,
Rosie Ruiz, Jackie Sherrill, Dennis Rodman, Olympic snowboarders,
Albert Belle, Bryan Marchment, Jerry Tarkanian, Tonya Harding and
nearly all of the 1980s Southwest Conference football teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list is a lot longer,'' a detective said. ``Sportsmanship
just wasn't important to a lot of people anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper files show that Sportsmanship survived an early
assault at the hands of the 1919 Black Sox. But Sportsmanship
developed chronic pulmonary problems from recurring college
football and basketball scandals. In the late 1970s, Sportsmanship
also began to lose its voice, unable to be heard over the din from
people like John McEnroe and Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roberto Alomar spat in the face of Sportsmanship once,'' a
local historian recalled. ``A lot of other athletes knew
Sportsmanship was good, but they kept looking in their mirrors and
never could find him.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the public blamed the media for its role in
Sportsmanship's passing. People pointed to the media's increased
coverage of Sportsmanship's longtime nemeses, Rule-Bending and
Showboating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it _ Sportsmanship had become dull,'' a network
official said in defense.
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral service, a special section of the pews was
reserved for professional golfers, who stoically bore the news of
Sportsmanship's passing. A book in the vestibule listed the names
of all golfers who voluntarily disclosed that they would not be
able to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Colin Montgomerie said he wouldn't come to
Sportsmanship's funeral ``because I only vaguely knew the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the choir loft were Little League coaches and assorted
voices from various youth sports leagues. Some planned to sing an
earnest tribute to Sportsmanship; others, having neglected to learn
the lyrics, instead chose to merely lip-sync them.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the coaches scanned the church and expressed their
displeasure that the sanctuary did not have a scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It figures,'' said one disgruntled coach. ``Sportsmanship
never made a big deal about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the pulpit, the Honorable Fair Play, judge and longtime
friend of the deceased, brought to mind some of Sportsmanship's
finest friends and moments:
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Jr. ... Wayne Gretzky ... NHL players shaking hands
after each Stanley Cup playoff series ... marathoner Frank Shorter
crossing the finish after 26 miles, and then standing at the line,
greeting each competitor as he finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly,'' Sportsmanship's old ally said, ``the list isn't as
long as it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sportsmanship will be remembered as good and decent, and as
ethical and moral. Why people turned their backs on Sportsmanship
may never be known, but it is believed that the indifference
started at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't important,'' said a parent at the burial. ``I
mean, it's not like it was going to help my kid get a
scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Sportsmanship is survived by its close cousins, Manners and
Hope.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to maintain dignity, Don King was not allowed to
show the funeral on pay-TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
