<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARANTEED: LASORDA FEELING WEIGHT OF LOSSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tom Lasorda was Dodgers manager, he always took the losses
hard. But nothing like this.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, he always had a job, no matter his place in the
standings or the general manager's heart. Now, that position is
his, but with no guarantees for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty showed on his face Saturday afternoon as he
emerged from manager Glenn Hoffman's office after a 5-3 loss to the
Atlanta Braves in front of 41,240 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda spent more than 15 minutes in his former office with
Hoffman. The pictures of Rickles and Sinatra were gone.
Unfortunately, so were Garvey and Cey.
</P>
<P>
   He never got loud like that day in Cincinnati years ago when his
voice pierced two concrete walls and a glass partition. But the
pain was still there.
</P>
<P>
   As general manager, he has made moves and they aren't helping.
He has been working the room trying to keep spirits afloat, but if
the eighth consecutive loss to the Braves over two years was any
indication, he can't get blood out of this Dodgers stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough on him,'' Hoffman said. ``It's tough on
everyone. We aren't out of it, but we can't seem to get this turned
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more painful for Lasorda is knowing that someone
else will be in his chair next year. The owners at Fox have
reemphasized the search for a new GM in 1999. Lasorda knew the only
way to keep the job was to win and go deep into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He even guaranteed the Dodgers would win the wild-card race
three weeks ago when he was in Cooperstown. Now, they are 6{ back
with 39 to play and Lasorda has gotten permission from several
clubs to talk to prospective GMs. That list is expected to include
Florida's Dave Dombrowski and Cincinnati's Jim Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them have experienced games like Saturday, when the
Braves won despite playing poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta got a first-inning, three-run homer by Andres Galarraga
off Chan Ho Park (10-7) and never gave up the lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive game Galarraga won with a
three-run shot. It also was the second game Dodgers pitchers walked
Chipper Jones before Galarraga homered.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves gave two runs back in the bottom of the first when
second baseman Tony Graffanino botched a potential inning-ending
double-play grounder and Bobby Bonilla followed with a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bonilla started at third in place of rookie Adrian Beltre,
just two games after the Dodgers benched him for injuries and poor
play. They also didn't want to expose Beltre to Braves right-hander
John Smoltz, who is now 11-2 after coming off elbow surgery last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them a bunch of opportunities,'' Smoltz said. ``But
fortunately things aren't going well for them right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla also singled in the fourth and walked in the eighth. He
caught a difficult popup near the Dodgers dugout in the second
inning. He cleanly handled five chances, including an inning-ending
double play in the first after the Braves threatened to keep the
rally alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If playing once in a while is the way it's going to be, then
that's what I'll do,'' said Bonilla, who will start at third in the
series finale against Braves left-hander Denny Neagle. ``You aren't
going to see me fight the Dodgers on this. I will do what they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   What they want most of all is runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers played without Gary Sheffield (sore right thumb) for
the second consecutive day. When Sheffield pinch hit for struggling
Matt Luke with runners at first and second and no outs in the
eighth, he represented the go-ahead run. The Braves replaced Smoltz
with left-hander John Rocker and Sheffield grounded into a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Things looked better in the fifth, when trailing 4-2, singles
hitter Eric Young homered to left. It looked like it could be a
boost, but it also might have hurt. Young flied out in his next two
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which has the National League's best record (82-41),
added a run in the sixth when Jones doubled home Michael Tucker.
Park had walked Tucker, one of six in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He came back to strike out Galarraga, but was done for the day.
Park now has dropped two in a row after winning 11 straight at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Park was one of the pitchers who responded when Lasorda and
Hoffman replaced the fired Fred Claire and Bill Russell on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   That used to make Lasorda smile. Now, nothing works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
