<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NEED TO REDO GONZALEZ'S CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something for the Rangers to start thinking about:
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro turned down a three-year, $21 million contract
from the Orioles the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle will make $11 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa will be in the second year of a four-year, $42
million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield has a six-year, $62 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers hold options on Juan Gonzalez for $7.25 million
in 1999 and $7.5 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   By comparison to those players mentioned above and many others,
Gonzalez will be playing for loose change the next two seasons. One
of baseball's most productive hitters will be making $3 million a
year less than players who can't carry his socks.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rangers' brass can clap their hands and celebrate their
good fortune in having such a bargain on their hands for the next
two seasons ...
</P>
<P>
   Or they can do the smart thing and work out an extension for
Gonzalez _ with a healthy signing bonus _ in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   He is still just 28 years old with his prime hitting years ahead
of him.
</P>
<P>
   He is also smart enough to know his value and moody enough to
let it bother him if he feels his team isn't showing him the
respect he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were incredibly far-sighted when they signed him to
a long-term contract following the '93 season. What was big, big
money then now seems truly economical today.
</P>
<P>
   They will look even smarter if they act quickly to keep their
most important player happy and locked up with this team far into
the future. ...
</P>
<P>
   You may have heard lots of talk on the radio about the stiff
neck that sidelined Gonzalez for three games last week, but
insiders say there have been absolutely zero raised eyebrows in the
Texas clubhouse, where his teammates seem to appreciate all he has
done to keep himself in the lineup this season. ...
</P>
<P>
   Message to Johnny Oates: Your catcher looks like he needs three
or four days off to recharge his batteries. Remember when Kevin
Elster wore down in September of '96 in the middle of a pennant
race? ...
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Chan Gailey, because of his daily afternoon press
briefings during training camp, has been the Cowboys' point man in
dealing with the Irvin-McIver dorm incident with the media. That
concerned his family, who really hadn't seen him quite like this
before. ``They would call and ask me how I was doing,'' Gailey
says. ``They weren't worried about what was going on with the team,
they were worried about me. I appreciate that and I love them for
it.''...
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys' officials wonder why Will Clark was able to leave the
Rangers for three games for ``personal reasons'' earlier this
season without a full-scale media investigation while the Cowboys
couldn't handle their own internal situation the same way without
wholesale protests. Answer's easy: Because good citizen Clark was
involved in the former, Michael Irvin in the latter. Get it? ...
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones admits that Gailey's honeymoon with the media
probably kept this situation from being even worse than it has
been. ``I think Chan has gotten some of the benefit of the doubt
that Coach Landry would have received,'' Jones says. ``It is
recognized that this man has standards. Had it not been Chan, this
could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan has come in here and helped create what has been a good
feeling about our team and he deserved that. But let's face it,
along the way, Chan is going to have bruises.''...
</P>
<P>
   Gailey may sound like he's cutting rookie defensive end Greg
Ellis a little slack when he says that the first-round draft pick
has been put into a difficult situation by being thrust into a
starting role in his first year, but when pressed on how Ellis will
be graded, Gailey pulls no punches. ``He'll be graded,'' Gailey
says, ``as a starter who has to make plays.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has also grown tired of watching tight end David LeFleur
drop passes. ``If \RLeFleur\S catches the next 30 in a row, his
average will be pretty good,'' Gailey says. ``Right now, it's
pretty bad. That's what we're assuming will happen \Rthat he'll
catch 30 in a row\S.'' We won't hold our breath. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bates is a super person and was an over-achiever as a
player. But Ring of Honor? Please. ...
</P>
<P>
   Before they dumped Elster, the Rangers discussed moving Fernando
Tatis to shortstop to get more athleticism at the position, but
decided against it. Infield coach Bucky Dent thought he could teach
Tatis to play second, but not short. ``That's not something you
want to do when you're trying to win a pennant,'' Oates says. ...
</P>
<P>
   A National League scout says that when Rangers were talking
trade with the Expos for left-hander Carlos Perez, they told
Montreal that minor league infielder Warren Morris was untouchable.
Then they traded him to Pirates for Esteban Loaiza. Good choice.
...
</P>
<P>
   Conventional thinking is that Orlando Hernandez is likely the
odd man out of Joe Torre's postseason rotation, but if it's the
Yankees and the Rangers, how can he not start ``El Duque'' against
Texas after watching Thursday night's two-hit, 13-strikeout
masterpiece? ...
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Oates plays the percentages as much as any
manager in baseball, and that right-handers were hitting .144
against Hernandez, you have to wonder why he started Mike Simms in
right field when he had left-hander Warren Newson and switch-hitter
Luis Alicea on the bench. Rangers right-handers went 1-for-15
against Hernandez, and Simms struck out three times....
</P>
<P>
   Combat pay: ``Star-Telegram'' Rangers beat writer Johnny Paul
was hit square in the mouth by a ricocheting baseball in the dugout
in Cleveland last week. No loose teeth but you could read Gene
Budig's signature on his right front tooth. ...
</P>
<P>
   And former Metroplex author, sports columnist and talk show host
Skip Bayless, now with the ``Chicago Tribune'', escaped with bumps
and bruises despite broadsiding a semi en route to an interview at
the Bears' camp a couple of weeks ago. Trying to check his map,
Bayless says he skidded through a stop sign on wet pavement....
</P>
<P>
   Reports that Cubs' phenom Kerry Wood has a ``dead arm'' amuse
veteran right-hander Orel Hershisher. ``I wish I was tired and
could throw 97 miles an hour,'' Hershiser says. ...
</P>
<P>
   Former DePaul and Mavericks' star Mark Aguirre is among 17 who
will be inducted into the Chicagoland Hall of Fame on Sept. 24.
Harry Caray is also on that list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
