<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS ON SOUTHERN CULTURE SAY IT'S TIME FOR ATONEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The months of singing, clapping and praying are
nearly over, and it's time for Bill Clinton to present himself for
atonement in the Baptist tradition.
</P>
<P>
   For those Americans who have been watching the presidential sex
scandal with mounting incredulity, experts on Southern politics and
religion have an explanation:
</P>
<P>
   The legal drama is actually a Southern religious pageant about
redemption. It is less about small perjuries and more about large
sins like adultery. And in this tradition the customary conclusion
is the big, public, tearful confession. Witness televangelist and
Louisiana Pentecostal preacher Jimmy Swaggart.
</P>
<P>
   Both Oran P. Smith, author of ``The Rise of Baptist
Republicanism,'' and Charles Kimball, a Baptist minister and
chairman of the Wake Forest University religion department, say
they are surprised that Clinton hasn't chosen to take the
traditional Baptist way out of his dilemma, rather than waiting for
the grand jury to do it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep expecting President Clinton to walk down the aisle of
the Billy Graham Crusade,'' Smith said. ``It almost couldn't fail
for him to say he is a fallen creature like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Swaggart, photographed with a prostitute in 1988, tearfully
begged his congregation and his family for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made your load heavier. I have hurt you,'' he said in
husky whisper. ``Please forgive me for sinning against you.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of his repentance, Swaggart regained his
ministry and was rebuilding his national television following when,
in 1991, he was again photographed with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   It's time, Smith said, for Clinton to ``walk the sawdust
trail,'' the trip up the aisle of the revival tent after the altar
call, where the sinner asks for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did do something he has to apologize for, then I think
if he were to come forward and repent in some way, the probability
of forgiveness is much higher,'' Kimball said, echoing the
sentiments of Sen. Orrin Hatch, a devout Mormon, just a few days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   If many Americans are confused by the events in Washington, it
may be because they fail to understand how much Washington has
become dominated by Southern political culture, including its
fundamentalist faith.
</P>
<P>
   Special prosecutor Kenneth Starr, a Texan, is a devout Sunday
school teacher and son of a minister in the fundamentalist Church
of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the leaders in Congress are Baptists, the
largest single religious denomination in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Republican leadership, such as House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, President Pro Tempore
of the Senate Strom Thurmond and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes a majority of Democratic leaders, including the
Arkansan Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, who hails from Tennessee,
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Senate
Minority Whip Wendell Ford of Kentucky. Baptists all.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Southern Baptist Convention, the apparatus of the
Republican Party is now largely controlled by religious
conservatives. It is they who are awaiting Clinton's trudge up the
sawdust trail, and there is the sense that nothing less will
satisfy them than the old ending to the central story of the faith.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is more to this case than politics and religious
pageantry, Kimball warns.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the Clinton scandal, ``You do have a question of
morality and leadership. Someone who is sworn to uphold the
Constitution and the laws of the land makes it more difficult to
just wink at an issue like this,'' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; You can reach Adrianne Flynn at 202-662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
