<HEADLINE>
GOLF ENTHUSIASTS GET ONE SHOT AT MONITORING TOUR EVENT ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf fans tend to get defensive with critics who contend that
watching the sport on television is boring.
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's see how they defend watching the sport on monitors
smaller than most TV screens and listening to soft-talking
announcers on audio that sounds like AM radio.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at noon tomorrow, PGATour.com will join forces with CBS
Sportsline, GolfWeb (www.golfweb.com) and USA Today Online to
produce live Internet coverage of the $2.5 million AT&AMP;T Pebble
Beach National Pro-Am in Pebble Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   It's unprecedented because the one-day event _ which began in
February but was postponed when rains swept through Monterey Bay _
will not be televised, not even by the Golf Channel.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The whole shooting match is online.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Broadcast.com will provide live audio from the
tournament's three courses. Simul-Sports will furnish panoramic
digital photographs for an interactive view, which will be combined
with the audio feed and the PGA Tour's real-time Java-enhanced
leader board powered by the IBM Corp. PGATour.com provides links to
the necessary multimedia plug-ins.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds so high tech, but it's simply one more way to watch
golf these days.
</P>
<P>
   Golf fans can get a head start watching the 'Net by accessing
the 80th PGA Championship's official site (www.98pga.org), which is
being produced by PGA Interactive and CBS SportsLine, for today's
final round.
</P>
<P>
   The Pebble Beach event is a one-time shot because the tournament
is not going to be televised, said Jerry Milani, a spokesman for
CBS SportsLine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on the success, it might be something that will be
done more often.'' Success will be measured by viewership numbers
and feedback from viewers about the quality of the cybercast,
Milani said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting to see how this all translates to
the Internet,'' Milani said.
Bytes
</P>
<P>
   Vanity e-mail: It's possible that any of us could have an e-mail
address that reads baberuth &LR; baseball.com or
tomlandry &LR; footballmail.com. CNN/SI and CBS SportsLine are offering
free personalized e-mail accounts through iName Inc. The accounts
are free at CBS SportsLine. CNN/SI plans to charge a fee for its
users.
</P>
<P>
   Chat highlights: Boxing referee Judge Mills Lane, the man in the
middle of the Mike Tyson-Evander Holyfield ear-biting bout, is the
scheduled guest at 7 p.m. tomorrow on Athlete Direct on America
Online (keyword: adboxing) ... Olympic softball star Dot
Richardson, 6 p.m. Wednesday, Athlete Direct (keyword:
athletedirect).
Review: Outdoor International (outdoorinternational.com).
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, Outdoor International plans to introduce a
directory of international online hunting and fishing guides, which
would make this well-done site ``true'' to its name.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Outdoor International, created by Dallas
resident Mitch Lewis, gives outdoor enthusiasts plenty of resources
for planning their next domestic fishing or hunting trip.
</P>
<P>
   The site allows visitors to search through more than 18,000
professional guides and outfitters. Users can search by city,
state, game and fish species, saltwater, freshwater or even their
favorite lakes and rivers. Users can also receive weekly fishing
reports via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors International also includes a news ticker for the
latest on events in the outdoors world. Links on the site direct
users to information regarding hunting or fishing dates, seasons
and limits. One of the more interesting features is Bragging
Rights, where users can tell tall tales of their outdoors exploits.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are to create a trading area, a retailers database and
message boards. If those features pan out, it will be hard to find
a site that can top Lewis' effort.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is an avid outdoor enthusiast who, with his wife Amy,
hunts in South Texas near El Campo and tries ``fishing anywhere and
everywhere as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the work necessary to maintain such an elaborate
site, it brings up the obvious question: When do they find the time
to hunt and fish? Rating: HHHH (out of five stars)
</P>
</TEXT>
