<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros nip Cubs on errant throw by Mulholland
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The Astros spent 3{ hours trying to take a victory away from the
Chicago Cubs, and Terry Mulholland gave them one in a matter of
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Call it luck, call it destiny, or just simply call it Astroball.
The Astros have found some dramatic and creative ways to pull out
games in the late innings, but Saturday night's 5-4 victory over
the Cubs was a new one for the comeback kids.
</P>
<P>
   After walking the bases loaded in the 11th inning, Mulholland
induced a two-out hopper back to the mound from Derek Bell. The
veteran lefthanded pitcher seemed to hurry his throw, which sailed
over Mark Grace's outstretched arm at first base, and pinch runner
Tim Bogar hustled home with the winning run in the Astros' 21st
victory in their final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got very lucky tonight,'' said Astros closer Billy Wagner
(3-3), who struck out five of the six batters he faced and
qualified for the victory. ``Any time something like that happens,
you know someone is looking out for you. You're not going to see
very many games end like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it comes to the Astros, local fans have learned
to expect the unexpected. The prospect of losing all three games in
their series with the Cubs looked real in the third inning when the
visitors took a 4-0 lead. After dropping Friday's series opener, an
early deficit was not a good sign, considering Kerry Wood will be
on the mound today for the Cubs, who fell one-half game behind the
Mets in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros steadily chipped away at the deficit, thanks in
large part to a heroic effort by Moises Alou, who hit two homers,
singled and scored three times to spark his team's 37th comeback
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I have enough superlatives to talk about the
kind of season he's having,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said of
Alou.
</P>
<P>
   It would be about the same as talking about the kind of season
the Astros are having. Their 76-47 record is the best 123-game
start in franchise history, and they increased their National
League Central lead over the Cubs to nine games with seven meetings
remaining between the two teams.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was witnessed by 52,003 fans _ 68 shy of the
regular-season Astrodome record. The crowd erupted when Alou tied
the score in the ninth with a blast off Cubs closer Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go to the plate, I'm very confident,'' Alou said.
``I like to be in the spotlight and in the pressure situations.
Beck made some good pitches to me, but he left a (forkball) over
the plate, and I took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs took advantage of Astros starter Mike Hampton in the
third inning, but he eventually got the last laugh. After breezing
through the first two innings without incident, Hampton found
himself in the middle of a crisis in the third when the Cubs sent
10 batters to the plate and scored four runs. Every Cub reached
base in the inning except starting pitcher Kevin Tapani, who struck
out twice, and Manny Alexander, who lined out sharply to center
field.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the third-inning damage against Hampton occurred on
balls that never left the infield. Sammy Sosa, who was hitless in
his first 24 career at-bats against Hampton, drove home one run
with a bases-loaded infield single, and Glenallen Hill followed
with a two-run hit that caromed off Jeff Bagwell's glove and rolled
into foul territory near first base. Jose Hernandez contributed an
RBI double to the scoring spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky, but they were lucky to score four runs in that
inning,'' Dierker said. ``Some of the balls weren't hit very hard
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros knocked a run off the Cubs' lead in the fourth on the
first of Alou's two homers and another in the sixth on a sacrifice
fly by Bell, who has 87 RBIs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Any hopes the Astros had of getting another run in the sixth
died when Ricky Gutierrez lost track of the outs and was doubled
off first base on Bagwell's line drive to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was a different pitcher after the third inning, retiring
12 of the last 14 batters he faced, including 11 in a row during
one stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hampton did an unbelievable job,'' Wagner said. ``He kept his
composure and kept us in the game. You can't ask for much more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After Alou singled and Carl Everett doubled him to third to
start the bottom of the seventh, Sean Berry pulled the Astros
within a run with a sacrifice fly to center. A perfect block of
home plate by Cubs catcher Scott Servais kept the Astros from tying
the score. Everett, perhaps being a bit too aggressive, tried to
score from third with one out on Brad Ausmus' ground ball to
Alexander, who was drawn-in at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the best play he's ever made,'' said Everett,
referring to Servais' block. ``I tried to sneak in the back door,
but he made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's 35th homer of the year _ a leadoff shot off a 3-2 pitch
from Beck _ tied the score in the ninth and forced extra innings.
Rookie righthander Scott Elarton kept the Astros close with two
perfect innings in relief of Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros appeared ready to end it in the 10th when Craig
Biggio drew a leadoff walk and Cubs manager Jim Riggleman
instructed Mulholland to walk Bagwell and Alou intentionally to
face Everett with two out. The move paid off, as Everett bounced
out to third on the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had situations where we could have won the game several
times,'' Everett said. ``But we finally did, and that's the only
thing that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
