<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5947 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMES-AZR &LR;      08-16 2154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LAWS TO GOVERN ARIZONA ELDER CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 and JUDY NICHOLS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last summer, Nancy Neutz made a surprise midday visit to the
adult care home where her mother was living. She found her mom
slumped in a bedroom, so drugged she couldn't sit up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I gave her the sleeping medicine too early,'' the
home's owner said. But Neutz knew instantly that the problem was
more serious than that. Her mother had been given an overdose of
tranquilizers. Neutz soon realized that the reason the house was
always so clean for visitors was that the residents were taken out
of their rooms only for meals.
</P>
<P>
   So she moved her mother to another home. She reports that the
last six months of her mother's life were spent in a caring
facility _ a good home.
</P>
<P>
   Neutz visited the home after ``The Arizona Republic's'' ``Homes
Without Hope'' series in June 1997 raised concerns about the
quality of many elder care homes throughout Arizona. She was one of
about 2,000 readers who sent letters or e-mail or made phone calls
to ``The Republic'' in response to the series, which detailed the
abuse, neglect and financial exploitation of Arizona's frail elders
in care homes.
</P>
<P>
   Although problems continue, the industry is on the brink of
major changes a little more than a year after the series appeared.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, new laws passed by the Arizona Legislature will go
into effect.
</P>
<P>
   After Nov. 1, many of the poorly run care homes will have
difficulty meeting stricter rules written by the Department of
Health Services. Their licenses will be denied as they come up for
annual renewal or apply for a new license.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the progress has come from the raised awareness and
increased involvement of family members and friends. But the most
visible changes are the result of new laws and regulations spurred
by the articles. Among those changes:
</P>
<P>
   _Fingerprinting and background checks will keep criminals from
working as caregivers. It starts Friday. The health services agency
is already swamped with requests for forms from care-home owners.
</P>
<P>
   _A care-home owner's past record can be used to deny a new
license, ending the games played by owners who close a home riddled
with complaints only to open a new one with a new name and a clean
file. It starts Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _New regulations in effect in November will require more
training for caregivers and will give residents and their families
more rights. Consumers' rights as care-home patients are spelled
out: If people want to leave a home because of financial or
physical abuse, they can leave and not be bound by a longer-term
contract.
</P>
<P>
   _Two 24-hour hotlines funded by the Legislature will be in
operation by year's end: One to report abuse and another to provide
information and referral services and emergency placements.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws and regulations offer hope that the adult-care
industry will be cleaned up. But Joan Johnson, who oversees
adult-care home licensing for the Department of Health Services,
sees a great sea of troubles to clean up with a very small mop and
bucket.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, funds for additional inspectors were not
authorized in any of the new elder-care laws. The failure of DHS to
collect nearly $1 million in adult-care license fees angered some
lawmakers, who then balked at any new appropriations for the agency
until it brings in the revenue it is already supposed to have
collected. Caught in the bureaucratic crossfire will be Arizona's
elders.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that new inspectors will be needed: Elder
care is a growth industry, with the number of adult-care homes now
at 880, up from 656 a year ago. The number of Arizonans over the
age of 65 is expected to double over the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcement is nevertheless under way: Ten adult homes have been
closed by DHS during the past year and a half. Johnson promises
that it is just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But homes that have many substantiated claims against them are
still open. The series last summer detailed allegations of abuse,
neglect and financial exploitation in three Valley care homes run
by Pat Glaser. Since then, Glaser, who continues to have complaints
filed against her at DHS, has gotten a new license. An
administrative judge said DHS didn't prove the home was in
substantial violation of state statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser declined to comment for this story. &QL; 
REFERRAL PROBLEMS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; While some of the problems in the care-home industry are being
cleaned up, there have been setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The series last summer found referral agencies engaged in ``body
brokering'' _ moving frail residents from home to home to collect
multiple referral fees _ a practice that elder experts say can
kill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rather than improving, the business, which places residents in
homes, has spiraled out of control the past year.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to regulate the industry died in the Legislature after
accusations were made that it would unfairly benefit the half-dozen
referral agencies that dominate the market.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than clean up practices, some feared, the law would
tighten the grip that agents have on care homes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 care homes and assisted-living facilities have
opened, and the competition for residents has become intense. As a
result, some referral agencies are charging adult-care homes as
much as double the amount they charged last year. Some home owners
are desperate to keep beds filled and will pay agents what they
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, placement agents are demanding that home operators
pay ``protection'' to agents in order to keep the supply of elders
flowing their way, said Sharon Phillips, owner of three care homes
and president of the Arizona Adult Care Home Association.
</P>
<P>
   The ``protection,'' according to Phillips, includes the high
fees and new dues in trumped-up referral associations, which some
financially strapped owners say are so expensive that they would
have to reduce the level of care to residents in order to make the
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Ferseta, into whose home Neutz placed her mother in the
last six months of her life, doesn't believe the new laws and
regulations will affect her much. Her residents at Helping Hand
Care Home receive good food and plentiful liquids, and proper
personal care and attention. The reports at DHS confirm that there
haven't been complaints about care against her home in northwest
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   New regulations will mean that her daughter and husband, who are
certified caregivers, will have to be fingerprinted and attend some
classes if she wants them to continue helping her. But that's no
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the regulations make it harder for the bad homes to
operate, maybe there will be more business for the good ones. That
is the reason I don't lose my hope,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Lindeman, executive director of the Governor's Advisory
Council on Aging, believes legislation is needed to clean up the
placement system.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least,'' she said, ``the law could require
referral agents to be licensed or approved by the state.'' &QL; 
RETAINING LICENSES
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that judges' technical interpretation of the
law can allow homes to continue operating despite long records of
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser retained her license over the objection of the Department
of Health Services, which tried in late 1997 to revoke the license
of one of her care homes in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   DHS said that Glaser or her manager, Fran Wagner, had failed to
get medical care for a week for an 80-year-old woman who fell and
broke her ankle in two places, had failed to properly document
medications for residents and had verbally abused a resident.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser said the 80-year-old had fallen twice, once on April 24,
1997, only spraining her ankle, and again a week later, sustaining
the breaks. Glaser said she had called the family the first time,
and they decided not to take the woman to the doctor, and that the
family was already planning to take her to the doctor the day she
fell the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser said Wagner, accused of the verbal abuse and medication
errors, was no longer the manager of the home, but was still a
caregiver.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative judge, Kay A. Abramsohn, said DHS didn't meet
the burden of proof regarding the broken ankle or the medication
errors. And, the judge said, the verbal abuse was not a substantial
violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Abramsohn said Glaser's home did not threaten the life, health
or safety of residents, and therefore should keep its license.
</P>
<P>
   One particular court decision, however, has put new power into
the hands of families who have had an elderly member in a bad home.
The Arizona Supreme Court ruled in September that relatives can
collect for pain and suffering, even after a victim of elder abuse
dies.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in the case of Fred and Frances Denton, profiled
in the ``Homes Without Hope'' series. &UR; Recently the Denton lawsuit
was settled for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   A continuing adult-care problem is the low pay given caregivers.
The average pay is $6 to $8 an hour for jobs that are physically
and emotionally demanding.
</P>
<P>
   If more care homes have to raise wages to draw workers, those
costs would be passed on to residents of the homes and their
families, said Darlene Pasternak, a registered nurse and owner of
Citrus Manor adult-care home in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the problem of low pay, some care-home owners
worry that new training requirements proposed will result in fewer
people to give care.
</P>
<P>
   The new DHS regulations will require that those who are hired to
care for frail elders have at least 50 hours of training or pass
out of a training course. No untrained person can be left alone
with residents. Currently, anyone off the street can be hired and
be left alone to care for residents that same day. But that will
change when the new training regulations take effect in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless this kind of work gets in your blood like it has mine,
why would anyone work for $7 an hour in a job that is awfully hard
when they could get an easier job at a hotel or store down the
road?'' asked Linda Payne, who has been a professional caregiver on
and off for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasing the requirements for the owners of care homes and
the managers who run them will make more difference than increasing
training or retraining caregivers,'' said Pasternak, owner of
Citrus Manor.
</P>
<P>
   She points out that the proposed new rules still require only
eight more hours of training for a manager than a caregiver. &QL; 
BEST LINE OF DEFENSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best line of defense for families, however, is the concerned
oversight of family members, according to Steve Lacey, an elder
care ombudsmen for Maricopa County. Without personally checking on
the home and its operators, it is impossible to know if your loved
one is in the hands of people who know _ or care _ what they are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Every week Lacey sees advertisements for adult care homes for
sale and it worries him to think who might be buying them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like buying a Dairy Queen,'' he said. ``I worry about
someone buying into this businesses and not knowing what they are
getting into. They are responsible for the care of people in that
home.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still a gap in the law that leaves family members out
in the cold when a home is sold. Family members of residents of the
ill-fated Philadelphia Home on West Park Place in Phoenix, which
was closed July 2, weren't told that the facility had changed
hands. They found out only after six residents, one by one, were
taken to hospital emergency rooms for dehydration and pressure
sores.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hensley's family visited the home and noticed he was
losing weight. They stopped by daily with a hot meal. Viona Bogre,
also at the home, did not have children living locally. Her
daughter found out the day before Bogre died that the home's owner
and caregiver had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the problems of the home were well-known to DHS and
Adult Protective Services workers, relatives were not contacted by
the state agency workers who were in or out of the home.
</P>
<P>
   In Ferseta's home such considerations seem unrealistic. Who
would dream of treating people like that? She makes sure her guests
don't miss the ``Lawrence'' ``Welk Show'' on Saturday evenings and
hires a musician to come once a week to play their favorite songs,
live. Ralph Covell, a lifelong farmer, is at his finest then, and
sings along, she says. Loraine Higley, a former ballerina, moves as
best she can to the shape of the music. During breaks in the music,
Bessie Kubanis, 91, is full of bright conversation and memories of
her long career as an insurance company secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Ferseta, not unlike many other good adult care-home owners,
wants life to be beautiful and peaceful for her guests. And,
mostly, it is.  &QL; 
 &UR; Republic writer Victoria Harker contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0139EDT &QL; 
