<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLERUD POWERS METS PAST D BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In this year of baseball's bulging biceps, it is easy
to overlook a guy who doesn't rattle the fences nearly as often as
Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake _ New York Mets first baseman John Olerud _
a 6-foot-5, 220-pound string bean by comparison _ can swing the
wood very well on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too far-fetched to say that he is a legitimate candidate
for the National League's Most Valuable Player award?
</P>
<P>
   Not if he continues to hit as he has been and the Mets are able
to slip through the wild-card door and into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud collected three hits and drove in three runs Saturday
night _ two with a home run in the first inning _ to help lead the
Mets past the Diamondbacks, 5-4, at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with the Chicago Cubs' loss to Houston, the Mets (66-54)
inched in front of the Cubs (67-56) by a half-game in the NL
wild-card race. Arizona, which lost its third straight and sixth in
its last seven, fell to 45-77.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed-hitting Olerud raised his league-leading average
to .355. Olerud, who led the American League in hitting with a .363
average while with Toronto in 1993, is attempting to become only
the second man in history to win a batting title in both leagues.
The other was Ed Delahanty with the Phillies in 1899 (NL) and
Washington (AL) in 1902.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets saw a 3-0 lead evaporate as Arizona scored four times
in the sixth inning against right-hander Armando Reynoso.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White drove in two runs with a single, the 699th and 700th
RBIs of his career. Jay Bell tied it when he drove in White with a
double, and Kelly Stinnett drove in Bell with a single to make it
4-3.
</P>
<P>
   New York regained control with a pair of runs in the seventh off
Diamondbacks right-handed reliever Bobby Chouinard (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Matt Franco drove in the first with a single, and
Tony Phillips, who drove in the winning run in a 3-2 New York
victory on Friday night in the series opener, put the Mets back in
front for good with an RBI double to left.
</P>
<P>
   The rally enabled Reynoso to remain unbeaten at 4-0. Greg
McMichael, Mel Rojas and John Franco shut the Diamondbacks down in
the last three innings, with Franco earning his 25th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets gave Reynoso a 2-0 cushion in the first inning when
Phillips led off with a single to right field and scored on
Olerud's 16th home run of the season. It came as right-hander Bob
Wolcott hung a 2-2 breaking pitch over the plate and Olerud, who
resides part time in the Valley and whose wife, Kelly, is a former
volleyball player at Arizona State, hit a line drive into the
right-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   Wolcott appeared to be headed for more trouble when Mike Piazza
hit a looping double down the right-field line. Arizona right
fielder Karim Garcia dove in an attempt to catch it but missed, and
the ball rolled a short distance away, not enough for Piazza to
take a chance on going to third. Wolcott then escaped further
trouble by getting Brian McRae on a called third strike and getting
Todd Hundley on a grounder to third.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Reynoso cut down a potential Diamondbacks rally
almost before it began.
</P>
<P>
   White led off with a walk and stole second. Then with two out
and Stinnett at the plate, Reynoso, known for a strong pickoff move
at first, caught White napping at second and picked him off as
second baseman Carlos Baerga snuck in behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud gave the Mets a 3-0 lead in the second inning. Edgard
Alfonzo hit a one-out double to left field and scored on Olerud's
single to left. Olerud moved to second as Diamondbacks left fielder
and former Met Bernard Gilkey attempted to throw Alfonzo out at the
plate, but was stranded as Piazza flew out to Garcia in right and
McRae fouled out to first baseman Travis Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso breezed through the third and fourth, then got into
trouble in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Bell doubled to left with one out. Garcia moved him over to
third with a groundout to first for out No. 2. Reynoso then hit
consecutive batters _ Stinnett and pinch-hitter David Dellucci _
and almost hit a third, Andy Fox, before Fox tapped back to Reynoso
for the third out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
