<SLUG> BC-FBO-RATTLERS-PREDATORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SNAKE EYES ROLLED  
 ORLANDO GAMBLES PAY OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Rattlers Coach Danny White couldn't help but admire
the risks that his Orlando counterpart, Jay Gruden, took Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man after my own heart,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it was causing White's heart to palpitate.
</P>
<P>
   The Predators converted two huge fourth-down plays in the final
quarter, leaving the Rattlers among the national viewers who will
watch next week's historic ArenaBowl XII at Tampa Bay after a 38-33
loss before 14,015 fans at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando, after beating the Rattlers twice at the Snake Pit this
season, will try to capture its first title against its Florida
rival, the Storm (14-2), in the first ArenaBowl to be televised on
a national network.
</P>
<P>
   Forget last year's championship and the one they won in '94 in
Orlando against the highly favored Predators. This game was bigger
to the Rattlers because ABC Sports will show the title game. And
the loss hurt more than any other in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just from an organizational standpoint, this was probably the
biggest game we allowed to slip out of our hands,'' quarterback
Sherdrick Bonner said. ``All week, Coach White told us there would
be 50 million people watching two teams play'' in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rattlers (11-5) are among the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   One could blame a sputtering offense that continually couldn't
deliver on third-down plays, or eight blown points by the kicking
game.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, blame Orlando receiver/defensive back Barry Wagner,
who showed why he's the Michael Jordan of this league.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who won the league's Ironman Award as most valuable
player the past six years, returned the opening kickoff for a
touchdown. He scored on a run. He made the catch that kept alive a
scoring drive on fourth and 10 at the 2 with less than nine minutes
to play and the Rattlers leading by a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   He scored the winning points on an 18-yard catch with six
seconds left. And he intercepted Bonner's desperation pass off the
end-zone net as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a championship team, they know how to overcome
adversity, they know how to fight back,'' Wagner said. ``When they
need a big play, they're going to get it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers, who lost a two-point heartbreaker to the Predators
(11-5) on June 20, never led until Bonner found Hunkie Cooper from
11 yards out for a 33-26 lead with 10:58 left.
</P>
<P>
   Pat O'Hara completed just 18 of 38 and had only two touchdown
strikes, horrible by Arena standards. He was getting rushed and
looked out of sync with his receivers in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara was picked off by Carlos Brooks at the 1 early in the
period, then, on the next possession, threw three straight
incompletions from his 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona came with the big heat,'' Gruden said. ``But when the
game's on the line, Pat makes the big throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest came on fourth and 10 with the noise of
14,000 fans ringing in O'Hara's ears.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Wagner caught a crossing route for a 12-yard gain.
O'Hara completed four more in a row, finding Robert Gordon for a
12-yard score with 5:15 left. A high snap and a wobbly pass by
holder Connell Maynor kept Orlando from regaining the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers could have run out the remaining five minutes, but
they couldn't manage a first down after taking over on their 5 with
4:38 to play.
</P>
<P>
   On first down, Bonner went deep to Calvin Schexnayder, but
all-league defender Chris Barber made a great play to deflect the
ball away and prevent a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On second down, Bonner's short pass missed Cooper. On third
down, Bonner had Randy Gatewood open over the middle for a first
down but missed him by inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to come up and press us,'' White said.
``We knew the short passing game wasn't going to work, and they
were ready for the run, so you go deep. We had our chances. We had
guys open twice. Barber makes a great play on the deep one to
Calvin, or the game's over.''
</P>
<P>
   That set up the winning drive. Gruden was ready to let kicker
David Cool decide it with 19 seconds left on fourth and 4 from the
Arizona 24-yard line. But Gruden changed his mind, and O'Hara
passed 11 yards to Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to leave it up to the offense and make our drive
the last drive of the game,'' said Gruden, who led Tampa Bay to
four Arena titles as the quarterback. ``Pat made a big throw, and
Robert made a great catch.''
</P>
<P>
   After an offside penalty on Orlando, O'Hara got the ball to
Wagner in the corner of the end zone for a 38-33 lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
