</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON HAS PLENTY OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, WASH. - Phil Mickelson shot himself out of another
major championship Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what happened, what went wrong ``this'' time, Mickelson
pressed his lips together and tilted his head as if to consider the
question from another angle.
</P>
<P>
   He said . . . let me get the exact quote. Here it is:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really couldn't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lefty can't, who can?
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson had just signed his scorecard, the one that featured
five straight bogeys on the front nine and added up to 78 shots, 8
over par.
</P>
<P>
   His third round in the PGA Championship _ one of the worst
scores of the day _ had to be fresh in his mind. Yet when pressed
to assess the disaster, to explain how a player with his talent and
potential could start the day in the hunt, 4 strokes off the lead,
and fall 15 shots back, he didn't have a good answer.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson wasn't uncooperative, or evasive. ``It's not like I
was hitting the ball bad,'' he volunteered, trying to be
responsive. He mentioned 3-putting No. 1. Then there was the shot
at the fourth hole that found the rough and started the bogey
slide.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtfully, Mickelson kicked the ashes of his round, like an
insurance adjustor at the scene of a house fire.
</P>
<P>
   The best he could come up with was a shrugging, ``I just
couldn't hit enough good shots to make par.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson doesn't owe anyone an explanation why he hasn't won a
major, and the PGA is his 26th. He didn't proclaim himself the next
Jack Nicklaus. The media did.
</P>
<P>
   The former three-time NCAA champion who won his first pro
tournament when he was a junior at Arizona State is more
disappointed in his failure to win a major title than he ever will
show publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson doesn't strike me as the type who is going to beat his
head against a ball washer or take out his frustration on his
clubs. According to legend, a Tour player mired in an awful slump
once tied his putter to the rear bumper of his sedan, like tin cans
decorating a wedding getaway car, and sped down the highway
gleefully dragging the offending stick behind him, orange sparks
flying.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson is still young, 28. He has won a dozen PGA Tour
titles. His bank account is as green as his golf bag. When he
counts his blessing, it takes a while. Overall, his life is good,
very, very good.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because he hasn't won the Masters, the U.S. or British Opens
or the PGA, Mickelson is labeled as an underachiever. His failures
are rehashed at each major championship.
</P>
<P>
   This year Mickelson tied for 12th at The Masters after he hit a
ball into the water on the final day. He tied for 10th at the U.S.
Open but never seriously threatened. He shot 85 _ 85! _ in the wind
at the British Open, finishing 28 over par.
</P>
<P>
   Now this. On what in tournament parlance is known as ``moving
day,'' Mickelson packed his game and went south, again. His solemn
march through the evergreens solidified his reputation as a player
who, like Dorothy's friends in ``Wizard of Oz,'' is incomplete.
Something is missing.
</P>
<P>
   If so, what? What prevents this player who can hit every shot
other golfers can _ and a few shots most others can't _ from
reaching the next level? You would like to think it's only a matter
of time. Look at the late-blooming Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Until Mickelson wins a major, he will retain the dubious title
as the most analyzed player in golf.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, what is it? Are you putting too much pressure on
yourself?
</P>
<P>
   ``Possibly,'' he said, responding to a question he has asked
himself countless times. After Saturday's round, he put himself on
the shrink's couch. He said he is not visualizing good shots. ``I'm
waiting for something bad to happen, and that's no way to play the
majors.'' No, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't break through soon, Mickelson may become the first
golfer featured in ``Psychology Today.'' This week he picked up a
national magazine and saw his face on the cover. Beneath the
pensive photo of the winner of the Mercedes Championship, the first
event Lefty played this year, ``Golf World'' asked, ``Does Phil
Mickelson Have What It Takes To Win A Major Championship?''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously not yet. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
