<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-THIRD-ROUND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA'S FINAL 18 A TEST FOR GOLFERS  
 SINGH, STRICKER UP BY 4 STROKES AFTER 3 ROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Neither Vijay Singh nor Steve Stricker has ever
won a major golf title, and there is no reason to believe that the
80th PGA Championship will be a first. The signs are too ominous.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's pretty hard to argue with a 4-shot lead, which Singh
and Stricker maintain with 18 holes to play at Sahalee Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are pretty good players at the top,'' noted Mark
O'Meara, who is seeking his third major victory of the season, as
well as a piece of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will find out a lot about themselves'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Singh knows it, just as he is aware that his best finish in 23
majors is fourth place in the 1993 PGA. He has never contended,
really.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody within 5 or 6 shots still has a chance,'' said Singh,
who was shaky early in Saturday's third round, then rolled in three
straight birdies beginning at the 13th hole for a 3-under 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's more pressure on me and Steve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker, who never has cracked the top 10 in 11 previous
majors, was slightly tentative after his 66. Like Singh, he is at
7-under 203.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't ever been in this position before, so hopefully, I
can come out like I did (Saturday) and play aggressive,'' said
Stricker, who fired bogey-free golf, capping his round with a huge
save from the trees at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm playing well, and Vijay is playing well. We both
had a good tournament last week'' at the Buick Open.
</P>
<P>
   Good, but not great. Stricker actually shared the lead in that
event with Billy Mayfair going into the final round, and Singh was
1 shot back. Stricker ended up tied for sixth, while Singh tied for
eighth. Neither broke par.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is this trend to the 1998 season: The winner in the
three previous majors has come out of the blue. O'Meara did not
lead The Masters until the last hole and never lead the British
Open until late on the back nine. U.S. Open champ Lee Janzen
trailed by 7 strokes with 16 holes to play in that tournament
before an unbelievable rally overtook Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there are some thoroughbreds left in this horse race that
are capable of making up ground quickly, the most notable being
Davis Love III. The defending champ shook off a poor start with
three late birdies for a 69 that got him to 3 under.
</P>
<P>
   Also at that number were 1995 PGA champ Steve Elkington, who
bogeyed the last hole for a 69, and Mayfair, the Buick winner, who
shot his second straight 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm swinging so well and putting so good that when I hit a bad
shot, I'm not worried about it,'' said Mayfair, who made his second
eagle of the tournament at No. 2, where a 3-iron from 200 yards set
up a 6-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really the difference when you're in a (groove) like
I'm in. That, and you're making a few more putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Four players were at 2 under, including O'Meara with a 69 and
his sidekick, Tiger Woods, who overcame ``control problems'' for a
70.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can go out and shoot a good, solid round in the mid-60s,
you never know,'' said Woods, who made a strong showing three weeks
ago in the final round of the British, where he came up 1 stroke
shy of making the playoff won by O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Woods needs a round like the course record 65 posted by
Greg Kraft on Saturday, when the temperatures _ and the scores _
dropped at Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone got hot. There were several major pileups,
most notably by Colin Montgomerie, who started the day 3 back of
Singh and limped in with a 77. Scottsdale's Phil Mickelson wasn't
much better. He trailed by 4 to start the day before disappearing
with a 78 that pushed him 15 shots to the rear.
</P>
<P>
   But Sahalee can do that to a player in a subtle way, especially
if you get lost in its deep, dark woods. Whether that happens to
Singh, a five-time winner, or Stricker, who has won twice, remains
to be seen. They certainly have the big-time games to hold up.
</P>
<P>
   The majors, however, are a strange brew. Winning that first one
often takes a player to the outer limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you win a major, it changes everything,'' O'Meara said
earlier in the week. ``But it's a very unpredictable, unscientific
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 17 years, and I thought I was a very good
player.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
