<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-KEALY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEALY TOUGH NUT TO CRACK  
 ASU QUARTERBACK IS READY TO LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAYSON, ARIZ. - Behind every good man . . . is a sister knocking
his backside into the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to know where I learned to be tough?'' Ryan Kealy said.
``When I was young I lost to a ``girl.'' A lot. That'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Arizona State quarterback's successful freshman
season was his resiliency after knockdowns, injuries,
interceptions. To trace the genesis of this mental toughness, check
out the bloodlines.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy's father, Joe, was his coach throughout much of Pop Warner
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a definite sign of weakness when you show emotion,
especially when your parental figure is in front of you,'' the
younger Kealy said. ``I learned at a young age to keep it inside
and turn it into a positive thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a stickler. And I learned early to respect that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad used to play quarterback for Kealy and his older sister,
Shelby. One sibling would play receiver and the other defensive
back. Kealy quickly learned a lesson in humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to kick my butt,'' he said. ``But she pushed me. And
that helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy's subconscious recalled those moments during a game at
Oregon State last season, and it proved to be a career turning
point.
</P>
<P>
   He threw back-to-back interceptions in the second quarter and
was pulled. He was embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an inner thing,'' he said. ``It's tough to compete and
fail, to let down your team. My concern wasn't with me but my team
and how we were going to come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Coach Bruce Snyder put him back in for the second half,
Kealy dusted off his pants and went after it, just as he used to
do.
</P>
<P>
   How much of an impact did that moment make? In the last six
regular-season games, Kealy completed 94 of 169 passes for 1,264
yards, 11 touchdowns and only three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   His resilience also surfaced against Washington State. After he
passed for 185 yards and three touchdowns in the first half, the
Cougars rebounded and took a 25-24 lead in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy responded by engineering a drive that he capped with the
go-ahead touchdown. He was a big reason the Sun Devils won six of
their last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``His confidence level really changed over the course of the
season,'' wide receiver Lenzie Jackson said. ``He tried to be a
leader in the huddle early on, but you could tell he was nervous. I
could see it in his eyes later how much more confident he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Snyder, ``There's nothing wrong with his toughness. He's
mentally tough. When he gets knocked down, I don't even think he
knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bright. He has a quick arm. That's why we're all very
excited that he's going to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest test yet may come early in the season. He underwent
surgery late last year after tearing the anterior cruciate ligament
in his right knee during the regular-season finale against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   His rehabilitation was successful and Kealy feels 100 percent,
but some wonder whether he's mentally prepared to withstand a hit.
Kealy says, ``No problem,'' and that may be because he overcame
similar surgery on his left knee out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   If he has a shortcoming related to his emotions, it's how much
he demands of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real hard on himself,'' Joe Kealy said. ``If there's a
chink in the armor it's that he expects perfection most of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Snyder, ``He can really get frustrated with himself. I've
never seen him frustrated with wide receivers, protections or
play-calling. That's not an issue. But when he doesn't do what he
thinks he should, I bet his blood pressure shoots up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was more of a problem early last season, when he struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Against Brigham Young, for example, he completed just 12 of 29
passes. Those first few games were difficult on him, especially
when he had to go into the huddle and try to rally the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awkward,'' he said. ``I hadn't performed yet. It's hard
to have the respect of your teammates if you haven't played. It's
hard to say stuff if you haven't done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, some of the other guys, like (former guard) Kyle
Murphy and (center) Grey Ruegamer, stepped in and helped me out.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew more comfortable with the role. He'll never be a rah-rah
guy, but if he performs well and has confidence in the huddle, he
believes he can be a leader by example.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy is ready to take the next step to becoming a better
quarterback. He needs to throw the long ball better. And at times
he chose to pass for a first down when it might have made more
sense to run.
</P>
<P>
   But he still managed a prolific season for a freshman. In fact,
he registered the third-highest yardage total, fourth-most
touchdown passes and third-most completions ever for a Pac-10
freshman quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I learned to turn those negatives into positives,''
Kealy said. ``Some of the mistakes I made will help me this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe most important, he has commanded the respect of his
teammates, even if they do pick on his appearance at times. Some
call him ``Pigpen'' because he'll go for a week without shaving, or
his hair will be disheveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to be comfortable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy can look any way he wants if the Sun Devils keep winning
behind him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
