r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-MONARCHS-     08-16 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-MONARCHS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY PUTS ON GAME FACE TO MAKE FINAL RUN AT PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Mercury has never lost to the Sacramento
Monarchs. This is no time to start.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Phoenix's final three regular-season WNBA games, all
must-wins if there is to be a postseason, are against the Monarchs
(7-20 before a Saturday night game against Utah). The other
opponent, on paper quite dangerous, is Utah (8-20 before Saturday).
They will play Monday in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury (16-11) has no excuse for losing to the Western
Conference cellar candidates, especially in the heat of a playoff
chase. But the last trip to Utah ended in a 90-80 loss. And
Sacramento, in games at 6 tonight and Wednesday at America West
Arena, can salvage nothing more from this season than to spoil
Phoenix's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take these games like we're playing in the
playoffs,'' guard Bridget Pettis said, a mode the Mercury adopted
Monday. ``If we win these three games, we're in it for sure, and
we're going to take it step by step and do what we do best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing great defense. If we keep our defensive
intensity where it is right now, especially against teams like this
that haven't had a great season, I think we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, 6-0 all-time vs. Sacramento and winner of four of
its past six games, has motivation and momentum on its side.
Phoenix routed Detroit, 84-59, on Friday to eliminate the Shock
from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Mercury improved from a three-point winning margin in
the season opener against Sacramento, when Ruthie Bolton-Holifield
was healthy, to a 21-point margin, 88-67, when the teams last met
July 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm worried about is Sacramento,'' Coach Cheryl Miller
said. ``It's a young team and Heidi (VanDerveer) has done a great
job of keeping them energized, regardless of their record. They
play hard, they're physical, and anything can happen. We cannot
take anything lightly or for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether VanDerveer will return for a second full season is the
hot topic here. She was promoted from assistant to replace the
fired Mary Murphy for the second half of last season, then
retained.
</P>
<P>
   The knee injury that took out Bolton-Holifield, the league's
second-leading scorer in 1997, in the fifth game assured a second
rocky season. Sacramento has started three rookies: Ticha
Penicheiro at point guard and Tangela Smith and Adia Barnes from
the University of Arizona at forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our individuals got better, our team got better, and I think
there's only so much in this season, a short season, that you can
hope for,'' VanDerveer told the ``Sacramento Bee''.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Jerry Reynolds said a decision on the coach's
status will be made after the season. Five coaches, including two
in Los Angeles, have been fired since the now 10-team league
debuted. Two, Washington's Cathy Parson and Los Angeles' Orlando
Woolridge, have interim status. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
