<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS MUFFLE RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Kevin Paul Dupont 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was a lot less thunder _ but still a dash of
fireworks _ when the Red Sox and Twins met again late Saturday
afternoon at Fenway Park. Over the previous two nights, the clubs
piled up 40 runs, resulting in a pair of Sox wins by a cumulative
score of 21-19.
</P>
<P>
   Volume 3 in the four-day Book of Big Hits and Interminable Games
had the clubs producing rather modestly. And in the end, the Twins
shingled together their first win of the series, a 3-2 squeaker
that was decided on a Pat Meares one-out single in the seventh that
brought in Marty Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   A Fenway crowd of 32,412 (sellout No. 26) saw the Townies erase
a 1-0 deficit on a Mo Vaughn homer in the first, move in front,
2-1, on a Mike Stanley double in the fourth, then lose the lead in
the fifth on three singles off starter John Wasdin that evened it
at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The winning hit by Meares came off reliever Pete Schourek, who
took over for Wasdin in the sixth and was greeted by a Cordova
triple. One out later, Meares delivered the RBI safety to left,
what proved to be the end of three days of big hits, tons of runs,
and more offense than you get at your typical company slow-pitch
tilt.
</P>
<P>
   The most commotion all day came in a bombastic first inning when
Twins cleanup hitter David Ortiz, with a man on, drilled a shot
over the right-field foul pole. As the ball hooked and landed in
the seats, and first base umpire Marty Foster called it fair, Ortiz
broke into his home run trot.
</P>
<P>
   Up with the music. Twins, 3-0. Another one of those games.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Vaughn was leaping mad, Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams was asking the umpiring crew to consult (till they got it
right). After a minute or two, the umpires wiped the homer off the
board. The home plate umpire, Terry Craft, ruled the shot foul _
and his word was final.
</P>
<P>
   Outcome: a major league do-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it, I threw him a fastball in and he turned on it,''
said Wasdin, who threw five good innings, constantly pitching out
of trouble. ``It was definitely foul and I was helping it go foul
(by waving his hands). The right thing was done. All the umpires
had in mind was to make the right decision. It would have been a
costly decision. The right call prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, the Twins were hot, especially first base
coach Ron Gardenhire. If there is ever a Gardenhire movie made,
only Jack Nicholson could do the guy justice in this scene. He
pulled one of those five-star nutties that really only happen in
baseball. Anyone remember Carl Yastrzemski hunkering down to cover
home plate with dirt after he was called out on strikes? It was one
of those.
</P>
<P>
   For all his anger _ appropriate though it was _ Gardenhire was
sent to the showers. Ortiz then returned to the plate and was
fanned on one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped out of the box and headed to the dugout, the
frustrated Ortiz cracked his bat over his leg. Craft was in no mood
for histrionics at this point and he summarily tossed Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox evened it, 1-1, in their half of the first when Vaughn
sent a screaming bullet into the Twins bullpen. In the fourth,
Boston touched up former Red Sox pitcher Frankie Rodriguez for its
only other run, Stanley's double knocking home Vaughn after the
first baseman reached on a slow roller to third. Rodriguez allowed
seven hits over seven innings and looked like a guy you'd want in
your rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Runs in the fifth and sixth clinched it for the Twins. In the
fifth, three singles led to Otis Nixon coming across with the
equalizer. And Cordova's leadoff triple off Schourek, still getting
accustomed to American League relief duty, set the stage for the
end.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, on a day when Boston paid tribute to Babe Ruth, it
was a game to be remembered for some decent pitching and an
overruled home run that turned into a strikeout. Ortiz didn't like
it. And if you're wondering what the Bambino might have thought,
then you better consult your Baseball Encyclopedia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
