<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEDGE TO RE WORK DEAL LATER MIGHT SATISFY WADSWORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an easy way for the impasse between unsigned first-round
draft pick  &UR; Andre Wadsworth and the Cardinals to end _ a win-win
solution for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals promise to renegotiate Wadsworth's contract after
three seasons, regardless of whether it's a four-, five- or
six-year deal. That way Wadsworth would get the big bonus he's
looking for _ the team already has said it will pay him $10.44
million on a six-year deal _ and he would be out of the contract in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The contract wouldn't void, which would make the Cardinals
happy. There wouldn't be a buyback, which also would satisfy owner
 &UR; Bill
 &UR; Bidwill. But Wadsworth would get a new deal after the third season,
possibly a lucrative contract that would pay him as much as the top
defensive linemen in the league, something he is demanding, if his
play reaches that level.
</P>
<P>
   So how would Wadsworth's agents know that the Cardinals actually
would keep their word to tear up the contract after three seasons?
</P>
<P>
   The team could put it in writing.  &UR; Bob Ferguson, vice president
of player personnel, could even sign it in blood, although
Wadsworth's agents,  &UR; Eugene Parker and  &UR; Roosevelt Barnes, know his
word is good.
</P>
<P>
   They've dealt with the Cardinals for the past three seasons and
have four other clients on the team _ defensive end  &UR; Simeon Rice,
offensive guard  &UR; Lester Holmes, linebacker  &UR; Tony McCombs and
second-round draft pick  &UR; Corey Chavous, a defensive back from
Vanderbilt. None of the negotiations were contentious. Some were
tedious, but in the end, deals were done.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth's deal also will get done. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   He cannot afford to leave a bonus of between $8 million and $11
million on the negotiating table. If he sits out the season and
goes back in next year's draft, he'll never get that money back.
Plus, there's no guarantee he will be picked as high as third
overall again. In fact, if the draft were held today, Kentucky
quarterback  &UR; Tim Couch, Ohio State linebacker  &UR; Andy Katzenmoyer and
Texas running back  &UR; Ricky Williams might be the first three players
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth's agents cannot afford for the player to go back in
the draft. It would kill their recruiting for next season. Rival
agents would remind players that the agents couldn't get Wadsworth
signed.
</P>
<P>
   Rice didn't sign two years ago until Aug. 19. They made sure he
got in before the last preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the foot injury to starting defensive end  &UR; Brad Ottis,
the Cardinals have a bigger need to get Wadsworth in soon.
</P>
<P>
   The best guess here is that Wadsworth will agree to terms and
report before the last preseason game, Aug. 28 at Oakland. &QL; 
Stick to football &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Being a native of Washington, Ferguson recently bragged about
Sahalee Country Club in Redmond, site of this weekend's PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a beautiful course,'' he said. ``The last time I
played it, I shot 158. I bought a dozen balls before I teed off and
lost every ball by the eighth hole. I bought nine more at the turn
and lost them all by the 13th hole, and nobody in the foursome
would loan me any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping that in mind, here's an idea. Ferguson puts his best
offer on the table. Allow Wadsworth to put his next to it. Then,
play 18 holes. The winner's offer stands.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. Given Ferguson's game, that could mean fore
years, fore fore-ty million. A really bad idea. &QL; 
For richer, for poorer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rookie quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf's San Diego teammates knew he had
just signed a six-year, $31 million deal. So, they figured he could
afford to buy them a few things.
</P>
<P>
   That's why middle linebacker  &UR; Junior Seau swiped Leaf's credit
card and treated 25 veteran teammates to dinner at a posh La Jolla,
Calif., restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tab Leaf picked up without knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought me a receipt and said, `Here you go, we had a good
time,' '' Leaf said.
</P>
<P>
   Seau said Leaf wasn't pleased, but it is a long-standing
Chargers tradition for a suddenly rich rookie to take care of other
team members. &QL; 
Short shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret the Cardinals aren't happy with their
place-kicking situation. They will take a long look at the waiver
wire when cuts are made beginning next week. Here are four players
they could be interested in if they become available _ Green Bay's
 &UR; Brett Conway, Tampa Bay's  &UR; Pete Elezovic, Oakland's  &UR; Cole Ford (a
Tucson native) or Indianapolis'  &UR; Matt Vanderjagt, who played in the
Canadian Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys, who will play New England Monday night in
Mexico City, are winless in international preseason games in Tokyo,
London, Mexico City and Monterrey, Mexico, since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Giants offensive lineman  &UR; Ron Stone, on facing the NFL's top
defensive linemen in the NFC East: ``We're going to have a bunch of
werewolves this year. We have a bunch of monsters coming at us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
