<HEADLINE>
VALLEY'S PRACTICE TONE DIFFERS FROM FLAGSTAFF'S RIGOROUS LOAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. The Cardinals don't know whether to thank the
schedule makers or curse them.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL season will begin one week later than usual. This means
a change in preseason plans for the Cardinals and other NFL teams
that conduct training camps on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, this would be the Cardinals' final week of camp at
Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff. But school is starting at
NAU, so the Cardinals had to clear out. They've returned to the
Valley, and, after a players' day off today, will resume practice
Monday at their facility in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the players: It gets them out of one week
of those dreaded two-a-days. The bad news: Their only workout now
is in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin could continue two-a-days in Tempe but
doesn't think it would be wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to drain everything out of this team practicing
twice a day in the heat,'' Tobin said. ``I want something left when
we play our first game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin will have the team on the field early _ 8:15 a.m. _ to
beat the heat. A tent has been erected between the practice fields
as a respite where ice and water will be available.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a case study for those who believe teams overtrain
with double workouts and lengthy meetings. The long-term results
might be a team that is fresher mentally as well as physically. &QL; 
Ottis heads injury list &QL; 
The Cardinals are down to their third-level left defensive end
after &UR; Brad Ottis re-fractured his left foot in Friday's 27-24
preseason win over the Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Ottis initially fractured his foot while running before minicamp
last spring. A screw was implanted surgically.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin described the aggravation as ``a hairline fracture that
barely shows up on the X-ray.'' Ottis might be back in three weeks
for the season opener at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He had been on the first unit while first-round draft pick
 &UR; Andre
 &UR; Wadsworth holds out. Without Wadsworth and Ottis,  &UR; Jerry Drake
moves from backup left tackle to first-team left end.
</P>
<P>
   Several offensive linemen suffered injuries that will sideline
them at least a week: backup rookie tackle  &UR; Anthony Clement
(strained knee), backup guard  &UR; Jerome Daniels (strained knee),
backup center  &UR; Allen
 &UR; DeGraffenreid (sprained ankle) and backup guard  &UR; Tom Guynes
(fractured finger). Rookie receiver  &UR; Kevin Drake's neck injury was
believed serious, but X-rays were negative. He might be back
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver  &UR; Rob Moore (groin), fullback  &UR; Larry Centers
(hamstring), and cornerbacks  &UR; J.J. McCleskey (hamstring) and  &UR; Ty
Howard (knee) are expected to return Monday. &QL; 
Evaluations &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The coaches still are not ready to make a call on a No. 2
quarterback. Tobin added that he plans to keep both  &UR; Stoney Case
and
 &UR; Dave Brown, &UR; no matter how the competition ends.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Scott Player remains ahead of rookie  &UR; Marcus Williams in the
punting derby. Kicker is more perplexing: Tobin didn't like
 &UR; Corey Wedel's &UR; short kickoffs but was impressed with Wedel's 45-yard
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pat Tillman, the rookie safety from Arizona State, once again
was the team's leading tackler.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in the Bears game was the defense not allowing
Chicago to score after it recovered an  &UR; Adrian Murrell fumble at
the Cardinals' 25-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense should be proud of that. I was,'' Tobin said.
``That's the key to winning football games _ rising to the
occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have 10 days before they are required to trim the
80-man roster to 60, and they might begin the week thin at some
positions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
