<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS COLLAPS ING  
 FANS BELIEVE AN NUAL RITE HAS AL READY BEGUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cubs fans are once again expecting the worst from their beloved
boys from Chicago's north side.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, probably the most endearing yet most frustrating club
in the majors, has one of the largest legions of loyal fans in the
game. They continue to wait for the Cubs to win another World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   And wait, and wait, and wait . . .
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the zanies who follow the Cubs' every move were
riding high, believing this might finally be the year the Cubs
break through and reach their first World Series since 1908. For a
while there, the dream looked real. Now it might be nothing more
than a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's worse, either having the Cubs start out
the season like they did last year, just totally out of it, or
teasing us the way they have this year,'' said  &UR; Joe Hutchinson, a
Valley resident who echoes the belief of so many other Cubs
fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is horrible. I'm just depressed. . . . I'm ever the
optimist, but I'll tell you what, it doesn't look good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It really does not look good for the Cubs right now. While they
watched division rival Houston swing the deal of the year in
acquiring
 &UR; Randy Johnson, the Cubs countered by trading for relievers  &UR; Matt
 &UR; Karchner and  &UR; Felix Heredia.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trading deadline passed, Houston has widened its lead
in the National League Central over the Cubs from 3{ games to eight
as of Saturday. During the same time span, the Cubs also have seen
their lead in the wild-card race go from 3{ games ahead to a slim
half-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fans are expecting the worst. Only a miracle run during the
final six weeks of the season will make them believe. After all,
this is a club that has endured as many collapses as any other team
in major league history. &QL; 
Been there, done that &QL; 
Yes, that was Oakland's  &UR; Rickey Henderson talking to  &UR; Albert Belle
last week, trying to offer the enigmatic Chicago outfielder some
advice on dealing with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I've been through this period a little,' ''
Henderson said. ``I didn't want to talk about the game. I wanted to
be in a shell. Then they say you're cocky and stuck up and all
that, but that's not how it is. I told him to keep his head high.
He's a good man, no matter what they say.''
</P>
<P>
   After reaching 100 RBIs last week, Belle refused to talk to
reporters, who, whether Belle likes it or not, will continue to
cover baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that lesson when I got traded back to the A's the
first time,'' Henderson said about negative media treatment after
he continually avoided the press. ``The media in New York could be
tough on me, but when I left, they said, `We love you. We were just
doing our jobs. Don't feel bad about anything.' That got me to
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the message that the media is not an enemy will get
through to Belle, who, believe it or not, can be engaging. &QL; 
Bobby boo &QL; 
Los Angeles'  &UR; Bobby Bonilla, who has been relegated to left field
while rookie  &UR; Adrian Beltre takes over at third base, was booed
loudly by the folks at Dodger Stadium on Tuesday, when he let a
very catchable ball drop in front of him for a single and later let
a fly ball get by him, a play that was ruled an error.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was asked if he heard the booing and facetiously
offered, ``I'm crushed. I don't know what to do with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who has been booed by the best in New York and
Baltimore, then basically challenged Dodgers fans to raise their
efforts to higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way,'' Bonilla said. ``I've got a thick
skin. I'm not trying to start anything, but they've got a ways to
go before they catch up to New York. It's going to take a long time
before they rattle my cage. I've been through a lot worse.'' &QL; 
The prosecution rests &QL; 
How much worse can things get with the Florida Marlins? Owner and
blight on the game  &UR; Wayne Huizenga has a standing $150 million
offer from  &UR; John Henry to buy the struggling and gutted club, but
the man who made his money in garbage and movie rentals refuses to
take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Now the sordid details of why Huizenga won't listen to Henry's
offer are surfacing, and, as we've said repeatedly in this space,
Huizenga is the man to blame. In reality, Henry, who also has said
he is willing to privately finance a new park, has virtually no
chance to buy the Marlins, and it has everything to do with
Huizenga's greed.
</P>
<P>
   His nearly yearlong song and dance to sell the club to  &UR; Don
Smiley and his legion of wobbly investors has several provisions
that would continue to generate money for Huizenga. Henry's
proposal, an all-cash deal, does not.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Huizenga's deal with Smiley would include the sale of
SportsChannel Florida to cable magnate  &UR; Charles Dolan, but only if
the new Marlins ownership group agrees to show Marlins games on the
cable outlet through 2024.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Huizenga has a clause with Smiley that would pay
Huizenga a $15 million fee if the Marlins leave Pro Player Stadium
for another venue in South Florida before Dec. 31, 2007, or a $20
million payment if the Marlins leave the area completely.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga is seeking $169 million for the Marlins, which is
probably $50 million more than they are worth. As one South Florida
columnist so eloquently stated, ``Rich people are never rich
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if your World Series trophy, which will forever be
tarnished in the eyes of serious baseball fans, brings you
happiness, Wayne? &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
