<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  GLF-PGACHAMPIONSHIP-BOS     08-16 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH, STRICKER TIED FOR LEAD AT PGA
</HEADLINE>
 GLF-PGACHAMPIONSHIP-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Joe Concannon 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Vijay Singh grew up in the scenic splendor of
the Fiji Islands, heavily populated by people of Indian ancestry.
In Hindi, his first name means ``victory.'' Saturday, Singh kept
alive his dream of capturing a precious major golf victory, as he
shot a 3-under-par 67 for a three-round total of 203 that leaves
him tied with Steve Stricker (66) for the lead of the 80th PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   After Singh birdied four holes out of five on the back nine at
Sahalee Country Club, starting at the 11th, and executed a
marvelous curling putt from the fringe on the 18th to save par, he
talked about what winning his first major championship Sunday would
mean. ``You don't think about it when you're on the range,'' said
Singh. ``I'm not thinking right now about winning the golf
tournament. You can't help but feel your time may be soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, who is one of the game's most dedicated believers in
practice _ has been seen in the lingering dusk on practice tees
around the globe _ ended up in the tie for the lead after Stricker
also made a remarkable par on the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Singh and Stricker, who were paired together last week in the
Buick Open, own a four-shot lead over Davis Love (69), who is
bidding to become the first repeat winner since Denny Shute in
1937; Billy Mayfair (67), a two-time winner on Tour this year, and
Steve Elkington (69), a former PGA champion. Mark O'Meara's 69 made
him one of four players at 208, keeping him in contention to become
the only player other than Ben Hogan to win three majors in the
same year. And Greg Kraft set a course record with a 65, tying him
with four others at 209.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker, who won the Kemper and Western opens two years ago but
had a down year in 1997, has had five top-eight finishes in his
last seven tournaments, restoring his confidence. Saturday he
played what he termed one of the best rounds of his life on a
difficult course, highlighted by some par-saving play on the 18th,
where he was awarded a drop after hitting into one of the towering
pines that line the fairways, then chopped a sand wedge to within
10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had kind of a hanging lie,'' said Stricker. ``The ball was
above my feet. I was trying to fly it on the green, and even if it
rolls through the back, I've got it up on the tier where the pin
was.''
</P>
<P>
   As Stricker was signing his scorecard, Singh was still out on
that dreadful 18th hole, which normally plays as a par-5 but was
converted to a 475-yard par-4 for the tournament. After his second
shot strayed to the left, he made a high, breaking putt that
nestled in within a foot of the pin. This was a fine finishing
touch, after he had birdied the 11th, saved par on the 12th, and
birdied the 13th, 14th, and 15th holes to complete a tour of
36-31_67.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about 35 feet,'' said Singh, ``and I had to go over the
fringe most of the way. So it was a pretty good putt, I thought. It
was really an up-and-down round, especially the first few holes. I
got my thoughts together on the back nine. I think the shot of the
day was on the 12th when I put my tee shot in the bunker and I was
just trying to play anywhere in front of the green. The ball just
came out really well, and that really got me fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker's round showed few flaws, and when he opened a
three-shot lead, it seemed he might be on his way to his first
major championship. He had learned on Friday it isn't easy, when he
was at 5 under before hitting his tee shot in the water at the
par-3 17th to set up a double bogey and fall out of the lead.
``Anything can happen on those last four holes,'' he said. ``You
need to be patient, not try and be a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Love seemed to be falling out of contention with three bogeys in
the first six holes, but he made a comeback with birdies on the
seventh (8-iron, 20 feet), eighth (6-iron, 30 feet), 13th (6-iron,
15 feet), and 16th (8-iron, 2 1/2 feet) to set up a run at his
second major championship. ``I hit a lot of bad shots starting
off,'' he said. ``I was lucky I wasn't more over par. Maybe part of
it is trying too hard to defend.''
</P>
<P>
   The group tied with O'Meara at 2 under included Skip Kendall
(68), Frank Lickliter (69), and Tiger Woods (70). Woods opened with
a 12-foot birdie putt but failed to make a sustained move. He
remained in the fray by making an 18-foot birdie putt on the 15th.
``It was a long day for me,'' said Woods. ``I had to do a lot of
scrambling. I'm pleased to be par for the day. It could have been a
lot worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
