<HEADLINE>
FABREGAS HAPPY IN ROLE WITH METS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In some ways, not much has changed for  &UR; Jorge Fabregas
since the Diamondbacks traded him to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   He's still the odd man out. Only Fabregas is a little more
comfortable with that role in New York than he was in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   After emerging from spring training as the Diamondbacks starting
catcher, Fabregas suffered an ankle injury, struggled at the plate
and lost his job. He shared time with  &UR; Kelly  &UR; Stinnett and  &UR; Damian
Miller, but he knew it was only a matter of time before he had a
new address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an idea'' a trade was coming, he said. ``I knew the
three-catcher thing wasn't working. That's not healthy for a
pitching staff to have a different catcher every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't think any of us (catchers) were happy. It wasn't
really working out for any of us. None of us was extremely happy
about it. I didn't know what my role was anymore. I knew what it
was at the beginning of the season. I was the everyday catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabregas knows he isn't going to be the Mets' starter, at least
not this season. It's  &UR; Mike Piazza's job. Still, Fabregas is
content. Piazza is a free agent at the end of this season. If he
goes elsewhere, Fabregas and  &UR; Todd  &UR; Hundley, who is being used in
the outfield now, might be left to battle for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to give Mike a day off now and then, pinch-hit when
I'm needed,'' said Fabregas, who homered in a loss to St. Louis in
his only start for the Mets, equaling the number of home runs he
hit for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a thing where I have to look at the long term,''
Fabregas said. ``I accept that. I have to be smart and look at the
big picture. I'm trying to do what I can to contribute and help
this team make the playoffs. That's the exciting thing about it. We
have a chance to go to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role is definitely reduced, but obviously, I'm not
expecting to play a lot with a Hall of Famer catching.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabregas said he still is healing from the ankle injury, and he
only regrets that he didn't live up to expectations in Phoenix,
where he lost in arbitration over his contract, only to have
Managing General Partner  &UR; Jerry Colangelo tear it up and give him a
new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad that I wasn't able to fulfill my obligation here,''
he said. ``I take things personally. I take things very hard. Maybe
I tried too hard.'' &QL; 
Signed, sealed &QL; 
The Diamondbacks signed catcher  &UR; Luis Urueta, the first prospect
the club has signed out of Colombia. A 6-foot-2, 180-pound
17-year-old, Urueta is a switch-hitter who will play this season
for the Diamondbacks' Boca Chica club in the Dominican Summer
League.
</P>
<P>
   Urueta was signed by  &UR; Junior  &UR; Noboa, the team's scouting
coordinator in Latin America. &QL; 
Familiar face &QL; 
Anyone who got to the ballpark early the last couple of nights may
have noticed a young middle infielder who bears a striking
resemblance to first baseman  &UR; Travis  &UR; Lee. It's Lee's 17-year-old
brother,  &UR; Taber. &QL; 
Injury update &QL; 
Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said tests showed that shortstop  &UR; Danny
Klassen suffered a slight fracture in his left shoulder while
making a diving play against the Dodgers in Los Angeles. Still,
Klassen, who is with the club's Triple-A affiliate in Tucson, is
expected to be back in action within another week to 10 days, as
initially projected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
