<HEADLINE>
ASU IS 8TH IN POLL  
 ARIZONA RATED 24TH; OHIO STATE IS NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL BRADLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The college football season will start with a double
dose of Arizona in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State was ranked No. 8 and the University of Arizona was
No. 24 in the preseason Associated Press Top 25 media poll, which
was released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils received two first-place votes as well and 1,256
points, five behind Pac-10 rival UCLA, which got one first-place
vote. Ohio State, ranked No. 1, had 30 first-place votes in one of
the closest preseason polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said of the Top 10
selection. ``We're just trying to get from day to day.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that stuff is flushed out. We're not talking about it. It
doesn't mean much.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Arizona State was No. 9 and Arizona No. 25 in the
ESPN/USA Today coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Bowl Championship Series, formerly the Bowl
Alliance, will match the No. 1 and No. 2 teams in the Fiesta Bowl
on Jan. 4, based on a new and complex ratings system that involve
polls, computer rankings, strength of schedule and won-loss record.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has an edge on any team on the road to Tempe. It has
been 30 years since the Buckeyes won their third national
championship in 1968 under Coach Woody Hayes. Now, a year after
watching rival Michigan win its first title in 50 years, the
Buckeyes are primed for another championship run under Coach John
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being No. 1 is something you shoot for, so we're certainly not
going to apologize for being picked as the best team to start the
season,'' Cooper said. ``The expectation level has always been high
here, and it's a compliment to our program. It's something we'll
try to live up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State, which is led by Mesa product Joe Germaine at
quarterback, received 1,668 points, edging No. 2 Florida State by
five points. The voting was the second closest in the 48-year
history of the AP preseason poll. In 1994, Florida beat out Notre
Dame by two points.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles received 22 first-place votes and 1,663 points in
gaining their 11th straight Top 5 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and Nebraska split the 1997 national title, the
Wolverines finishing No. 1 in the AP poll, the Cornhuskers No. 1 in
the coaches' poll. Arizona State finished 14th and Arizona was
unranked.
</P>
<P>
   Notable in the poll were:
</P>
<P>
   This is the lowest preseason ranking for Notre Dame (No. 22)
since 1986, when the Irish did not make what was then the Top 20.
Notre Dame will visit ASU on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten and the Southeastern Conference led all conferences
with five teams apiece in the Top 25. The Pac-10 had four: ASU,
Arizona, UCLA and Washington at No. 18. &QL; 
Staff writer Paola Boivin and the Associated Press contributed to
this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
