<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-QBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOMIES RIVALS, BUT SHARE GOAL  
 ARIZONA'S SMITH, JENKINS BOTH WANT TO BE TOP QB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. - As roommates, Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins
are at least an odd couple, if not an apparent impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   Roomies with different personalities are one thing. But rivals?
Joe Frazier never roomed with Muhammad Ali. If he had, the poor
place would have looked like something left by the U.S. Olympic ice
hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   But peace reigns in a dorm room at Cochise College, where Smith
and Jenkins share floor space and time at quarterback during the
University of Arizona's eight-day preseason camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the same team and we want the same thing _ to win,''
Jenkins said. ``It will show everybody out there, especially the
new guys, that it doesn't matter what you've done in the past. You
still have to go out and work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said, ``People can start talking controversy, but there's
no quarterback controversy. I can tell you that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not now, but what about later?
</P>
<P>
   It's an inescapable question. Arizona Coach Dick Tomey intends
to let Smith and Jenkins split time for as long as necessary. It
could be a few weeks into the regular season before he decides on a
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Two quarterbacks often lead to double trouble. But Tomey is
confident that problems will be avoided. He cites their proven
athletic abilities, their friendship and their understanding of the
task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them: `Can you handle being a backup?' '' said Tomey,
who employed two quarterbacks, Ronnie Veal and George Malauulu,
with mixed results in 1989, when Arizona was 8-4. ``They both can.
We've got two great guys here. They both want to play every down,
and they both know that's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The best bet is that a starter will emerge sometime within
Arizona's first four games. Barring an injury, a starter will not
be picked on the basis of what happens in camp.
</P>
<P>
   For now, there is no official rivalry. Unofficially, there is
nothing but one.
</P>
<P>
   From the sidelines during each session of the two-a-day drills,
reporters keep a running tally of pass attempts, completions and
interceptions. Who's ahead? Who's behind? After three days and five
practice sessions, it was within a completion or two of a dead
heat.
</P>
<P>
   For Tomey, the dilemma is that both Smith, a 5-foot-11 junior,
and Jenkins, a 6-2 sophomore, are talented, each in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a darting runner who can throw on the move. In 1996, he
took the starting job from Brady Batten in the second game. He went
on to set a school record for passing percentage and an NCAA
freshman single-game record with 502 total yards in a four-overtime
loss at California.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins is a terrific drop-back passer. He started seven times
last season after Smith was injured in the fourth game against
UCLA. He went on to throw 19 touchdown passes for a freshman record
in the Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the two best I've ever had at one time,'' said Tomey,
who is starting his 22nd year as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Jenkins and Smith could be the unrivaled starter
at any number of schools. That, in itself, poses a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Smith talked about transferring after last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I considered it,'' he said. ``But I never talked to
another school. I wanted the coaches to know I was considering it
and that I was serious. But I also wanted the truth about the
situation, and I got it. Coach Tomey was honest with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomey told Smith that he was still in the hunt. With that as
motivation, Smith was so impressive in spring drills that he
appeared to have an edge over Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jenkins began to talk transfer. A preseason football
magazine quoted him as saying, ``If Dick Tomey comes to me and
tells me I lost the starting job, I'd have to give transferring a
major thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins doesn't deny making the comment. Today, however, he says
he's not going anywhere. If he did transfer, he would leave himself
only one year of NCAA eligibility because he was a redshirt
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their reasons for staying, the underlying message of
their transfer talk is unmistakeble. Both believe they should
start. Jenkins is more outspoken about it than Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I think I should,'' said Jenkins, also a basketball
player, who said he would rather play in the next Fiesta Bowl than
the Final Four because Arizona already has a national basketball
title. ``I think I deserve to start and complete what I did last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Keith thinks the same way. You have to look at his
situation and what happened to him _ the way he suddenly stopped
playing because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand his reasons for wanting to play, and I believe he
understands mine.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Smith sounds as if he is prepared to be half of a twin
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both ready to handle the two-quarterback situation,'' he
said. ``It's something we talked about all summer. We were on
campus, talking, throwing the ball around and having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year offensive coordinator Dino Babers believes this
potential two-headed monster can destroy opponents instead of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two quarterbacks with different styles, it can
be an extremely positive and explosive situation for our offense,''
Babers said. ``I mean, you've got a defense splitting time in
preparation for one style and then another. You'd have one defense
for one guy and another defense for the other guy. I wouldn't want
to be the defensive coordinator in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Babers' argument makes good sense. The trouble is,
neither Smith nor Jenkins is a theory. They have ambitions. And
there is ego, of which a healthy dose is good in any quarterback.
There are also relationships and timing between receivers, running
backs and offensive linemen. There's nothing new about an offense
suddenly falling out of sync after a quarterback change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are cool guys,'' said running back Trung
Canidate, a projected starter and former Central High School star.
``Both want to be the man, because both of them had good years. To
be good, you have to want it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Main thing is, sooner or later, one is going to rise above the
other. There might be a little scuffling and hustling along the
way, but I know whoever emerges will help this team out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
