r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-HALL-REAX-AZR &LR;      08-16 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HALL-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSION COSTLY FOR HALL  
 ENDORSEMENT DEAL CANCELED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Olympic medalist Gary Hall Jr. lost a major
endorsement and a chance to compete in two key meets because of the
provisional suspension that was lifted last week by FINA,
swimming's international governing body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terribly costly,'' Hall said Saturday of a prohibition from
competition that lasted from May 15 through Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   He said his endorsement deal with Speedo was ended by the
swimsuit company when FINA announced its temporary suspension of
the Phoenix sprinter for a positive marijuana test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand when an athlete fouls up like this that, yes,
we're expected to keep the company in mind,'' said Hall, who
withdrew from the Goodwill Games and was unable to compete in
national championships that ended Saturday. ``I can understand how
it would be a concern for a company like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the same company that sponsors the Chinese
National Team.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese women have repeatedly tested positive for steroids and
other performance-enhancing drugs since the 1994 World
Championships in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about Hall's contract with Speedo were not answered by
company executives late last month when the suspension was
announced. Speedo's offices were closed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's attorney, Ed Hendricks of Phoenix, raised the possibility
that Speedo might renew the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume there will be an attempt to reinstate the Speedo
contract in light of the lifting of the suspension,'' said
Hendricks, who successfully argued that the suspension should end
within three months because Hall could not be considered a two-time
offender.
</P>
<P>
   Gunnar Werner, FINA's honorary chairman, said Hall tested
positive at the 1996 Olympics, where he won two gold and two silver
medals. But marijuana had just been added to the banned list and
was not subject to sanctions until after the Olympics. FINA said
Hall then tested positive on May 15 during a meet at Phoenix Swim
Club. As a first-time offender, he could not be subject to more
than a three-month suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hall said he has resumed training. He said his
workout schedule stopped completely when the suspension was
disclosed in a FINA newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just impossible to find the motivation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was ineligible for the national championships, he was
unable to earn a spot on one of three international teams for the
Pan-Pacific, Pan American and World Short Course Championships. The
Pan Pacific meet is considered a key steppingstone to the 2000
Olympics. The site is the Olympic pool in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether he could be added at a later date. Hall
believes he can be added if he goes fast enough in his specialties:
the 50- and 100-meter freestyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that would be unprecedented,'' said Hall's father, Valley
eye surgeon Gary Hall, a three-time Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   USA Swimming has, in fact, already set a precedent of sorts. It
added Hall as a relay member to the team for the World
Championships at Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Hall failed to make that team in qualifying. But he went to
Perth and swam two anchor legs, one for a gold medal and one for a
silver. However, he was not added to that U.S. team for an
individual event. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 0239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
