<HEADER>
A6024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-NAIROBI-COX     08-16 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-NAIROBI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kenyans wondering what position the U.S. has toward their
country
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nairobi, Kenya All David Ndira wanted was to help.
</P>
<P>
   Ndira, 32, an accountant who works in a building 200 yards from
the American Embassy in Nairobi, heard the explosion Aug. 7. He
came running at once, with rescue on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. marines, more worried about maintaining security than
about saving lives, would not allow him into the heavily damaged
embassy, Ndira said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were concerned with their stuff first,'' he said. ''They
were more concerned about the embassy than about the locals.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first of several actions taken by Americans since
the bombing nine days ago that have left some Kenyans wondering
whether Americans value the lives of Africans quite as much as they
value the lives of other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As people lay trapped in the rubble, some would-be rescuers were
driven off for fear they were looters. The dozen Americans who died
seem to some Kenyans to have been mourned more than were the more
than 200 Africans who died in the same explosion. And, said Ndira,
the terrorist attack on the U.S. embassy in Nairobi was ascribed
greater importance than the simultaneous bombing in Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania, because no Americans were killed in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ''That makes you feel like a second-class human being,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, in the view of some Kenyans, then added
insult to injury by advising Americans not to travel to Kenya, a
move the Kenya Tourist Board called ''a major threat to Kenya
tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials have shown that they are aware of the
resentments, and sensitive to them. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright has said she will visit Kenya shortly. U.S. Ambassador to
Kenya Prudence Bushnell said Friday that the U.S. was giving Kenya
tools used in the rescue - helmets, saws, computers, generators and
a firefighting vehicle - as a gesture of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   And the State Department quickly withdrew its advisory against
traveling to Kenya, to the applause and relief of the Kenya Tourist
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, Kenyans seem stunned by the bombing, which blew a
whole in the city center and shattered windows for blocks around.
On Saturday, as they have for the nine days since the attack, they
gathered by the hundreds and even the thousands on the sidewalks
near the site of the explosion to gaze on the scene in silent awe
and bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   Around the city, people continued to clean up. Merchants blocks
from the embassy swept shards of glass into giant piles and covered
their storefronts with plywood. Workmen atop a building 50 yards
from the embassy replaced roofing tiles ripped loose by the force
of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   A bulldozer rumbled through the debris behind the American
embassy. U.S. Marines inside stood guard at the bombed-out windows
with automatic weapons. Above the gutted building, the American
flag few at half mast.
</P>
<P>
   And outside, people piled wreaths, roses and carnations into a
memorial mound. A sign amid the flowers read, ''KENYANS WANT PEACE
NOT BOMBS.'' Another begged, ''GOD HEAL THE HEAVY HEARTS.''
</P>
<P>
   But even into quiet and moving tributes, other feelings intrude,
feelings of annoyance and perplexity at the actions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a resentment,'' said Sam Nyamweya, secretary general
of the Kenyan Football Association, after team members had laid
their flowers. ''They are thinking that the Americans are out for
the interests of the embassy and Americans rather than the
interests of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be overstating the case to say that Kenyans are angry
at the United States. ''Resentment'' is the word most frequently
used. People said the embassy should be rebuilt out of town, where
it would endanger fewer people. They said Bushnell should apologize
for Americans who thought rescuers were looters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they didn't sound angry. They sounded hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the resentment felt by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Americans are just victims,'' Kaboro said as he herded his
children from the scene of the attack. ''The ambassador herself was
also injured. American people got killed. Nothing against the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
