<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. PRESIDENT, SKIP THE WORD GAMES WHEN YOU TESTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A whole lot of people in America think they're having sex, but
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic. It's just a lawyers' definition of sex that Bill
Clinton may use to weasel out of lies he told the American people
about his relations with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton appears Monday before Ken Starr's grand jury, he
may use the definition of ``sexual relations'' accepted by the
judge in the Paula Jones lawsuit:
</P>
<P>
   ``A person engages in `sexual relations' when the person
knowingly engages in or causes contact with the genitalia, anus,
groin, breast, inner thigh, or buttocks of any person with the
intent to arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why you want to get lawyers out of your life, especially
your sex life. Only lawyers could invent a definition of sex that
ignores the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the nation is preoccupied with oral sex and the
Oval Office. As a friend said, ``Thank you, Bill Clinton. Now I
have to explain to my daughter what oral sex is.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this for Nixon: He tried to burn the Constitution, but he
gave us expletives deleted.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the president may tell the grand jury he didn't have
sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky, even though she was having
oral sex with him.
</P>
<P>
   Read that definition carefully, the way a lawyer like Clinton
would. A woman who performs oral sex on a man is having sexual
relations, but the man isn't.
</P>
<P>
   That should give feminists a reason to dislike Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, try that definition on your spouse, significant other,
or mother. See if you don't get thrown out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't having sex, she was.'' Yeah, that'll work.
</P>
<P>
   Philanderers will carry that definition around, and read it
aloud like cops reading Miranda warnings. Call them Monica
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, Bill, but having extramarital oral sex is not the
moral equivalent of raiding the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that a president's sexual activities are his business,
but let's just play the game called ``If I Were President.''
</P>
<P>
   If I were president, I would have to ask advisers what to do
about relations with Saudi Arabia, Russia and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The American people are easier to understand. They appreciate
honesty, not the lawyerly skill of demonstrating that words don't
mean what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   If I were president, I wouldn't fool around with women or
semantics. A president's most important relationship is with the
people, and not worth damaging.
</P>
<P>
   So say I know that, but I'm drawn to a young intern who's drawn
to me. I'm a man of appetites and needy ego, not just a president,
and I've always gotten away with it. What do I do?
</P>
<P>
   I'd say to myself that she's half my age, an employee, and a
young woman who might get so attached she shows up at fund-raisers
and airports where there are many cameras.
</P>
<P>
   I'd take a cold shower, and think about the stock market
falling.
</P>
<P>
   All right, I'm the president and the cold shower didn't work.
I've had contact with the young intern that would get a lamp thrown
at me by my wife. What do I tell the public?
</P>
<P>
   Do I claim I didn't have sexual relations with that woman,
whatever the heck it was she was doing? Well maybe. Everybody lies
about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Show me someone who doesn't lie about sex, and I'll show you the
dullest person in the world, or the most interesting. Show me
someone who redefines sex, and I'll show you a president with major
chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Asia and Russia are going down the tubes. Wall Street is
teetering. Say I'm a popular president, but know my ratings will
crash with the Dow. I have to answer the special prosecutor's
questions via video on Monday. What do I tell the grand jury, and
the American people, who will hear the leaks within minutes?
</P>
<P>
   I guess I'd tell the truth, even if it meant confessing to
cheating and lying in Lincoln's former home. Americans are trained
on Oprah. They'll understand.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'd resign and be remembered as the president who quit at
the height of his popularity for the good of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'm not president, Clinton is, and he's not likely to quit
as readily as I would.
</P>
<P>
   He weaseled his way out of the draft. He weaseled with that ``I
didn't inhale'' thing. He weaseled out of supporting gays in the
military with ``don't ask, don't tell.'' He weaseled his way out of
taking a position on affirmative action. He's practically weaseled
his way out of being a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   He's weaseled every which-way on matters of sex, and it's hard
to see why he won't do it again on Monday. So far the weasel hasn't
gone pop, but gotten more popular.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton knows the whole world will be listening to the
grand jury leaks, and any speech he may give about his testimony.
He knows that Monday could be the final episode of the Clinton
show, firmly establishing his X-rated place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if, just once, he didn't play games with words. He just
might get away with telling the truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
