<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6052 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     08-16 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 23.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COLD MOUNTAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Frazier. Vintage Contemporaries, $13.
</P>
<P>
   This ambitious first novel, which won a National Book Award in
1997, recasts much of the ``Odyssey'' in the South near the end of
the Civil War, with a wounded Confederate soldier standing in for
Odysseus. His journey home resembles ``a Whitmanesque foray into
America: into its hugeness, its freshness, its scope and its
soul,'' James Polk wrote in the Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIG TROUBLE: A MURDER IN A SMALL WESTERN TOWN SETS OFF A
STRUGGLE FOR THE SOUL OF AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By J. Anthony Lukas. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.
</P>
<P>
   The author's teeming journalistic account of the murder of a
former Idaho governor in 1905 and its aftermath is set against the
growing conflict between capital and organized labor, and is full
of historical digressions and fascinating characters, ranging from
Clarence S. Darrow to James McParland of the Pinkerton National
Detective Agency. ``Lukas has done much more than exhume one of the
most dramatic trials of the century; he has excavated a stratum of
American history, tracing the fault line of class that sundered
society in another time,'' Richard Lingeman said here in 1997. A
smaller-scale criminal justice drama,  &UR; MAY GOD HAVE MERCY: A TRUE
STORY OF CRIME AND PUNISHMENT &LR; , by John C. Tucker (Delta, $11.95),
tells of the legal missteps that led to the highly publicized
execution of a possibly innocent man in Virginia in 1992 for the
rape and murder of his sister-in-law. Last year our reviewer, Roger
Parloff, found the book ``a lucid and engrossing exploration'' of
the risks that come with the death penalty and the occasional
tragedy that inevitably results.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRESENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred Corn. Counterpoint, $13.50.
</P>
<P>
   This collection of poems draws from our cultural history to make
surprising links between disparate entities, like Bach and Kafka,
who are shown not only to be driven by the same spiritual forces
but to affect their audiences in similar ways. The author is ``a
stylist of the first order,'' William Ferguson said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COD: A BIOGRAPHY OF THE FISH THAT CHANGED THE WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Kurlansky. Penguin, $11.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author argues that the humble Atlantic cod, dried and
salted, was one of the world's first nonperishable foods and the
fuel that has driven explorers and traders since the Viking days.
Last year, in these pages, Molly Benjamin called this an
``eminently readable book.'' Another briny title from the same
publisher,  &UR; IN THE SLICK OF THE CRICKET &LR; , by Russell Drumm
($13.95), chronicles a reporter's five-day fishing trip with Frank
Mundus, a Long Island charter-boat captain, raconteur and famous
great white shark hunter. The result is ``a lively portrait of a
tobacco-chewing, colorful and crude original,'' Carol Peace Robins
wrote here earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE THREE-ARCHED BRIDGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ismail Kadare. Translated by John Hodgson. Vintage
International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 14th century during another time of social upheaval
in the Balkans, this vivid parable finds the Turkish armies at the
gates of Europe, and various bridges -- both stone and metaphoric
-- rising and crumbling between two cultures. The result is ``a
profoundly atmospheric book'' and ``an utterly captivating yarn,''
Patrick McGrath wrote here last year. The same publisher has
reissued an earlier novel by the Albanian author,  &UR; THE PYRAMID &LR; 
(translated from the French of Jusuf Vrioni by David Bellos, $11),
which focuses on the intrigues behind the construction of the
Pyramid of Cheops in ancient Egypt, a story with echoes of Kadare's
homeland during the communist era. In 1996 in these pages, Bruce
Bawer called this ``a haunting meditation on the matter-of-fact
brutality of political despotism, the harshness of life among the
humble and powerless, and ... the stonelike permanence of death.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A CAB CALLED RELIABLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patti Kim. St. Martin's Griffin, $10.95.
</P>
<P>
   A 9-year-old Korean-American girl is forced to take care of her
demanding father after her mother, tiring of living ``a dog's
life,'' vanishes one day in a taxi. Last year our reviewer, Denise
Gess, called this an ``elegantly and humorously told''
coming-of-age novel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SATCHMO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Gary Giddins. Da Capo, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary jazz trumpeter Louis Armstrong is the subject of
this biographical tribute, which pulls together unpublished photos,
sheet music, letters, diaries and other memorabilia, including an
annotated restaurant menu. ```Satchmo' is a valuable, jubilant look
at a great man and artist,'' Tom Piazza wrote here in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YEAR'S EVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Grunwald. Warner, $13.99.
</P>
<P>
   Heather and Erica are twins whose childhood competiveness is
rekindled in adult life after the accidental death of Heather's
son. Last year our reviewer, Polly Morrice, said this family novel
``depicts this age-old struggle with sympathy and skill.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BOOK OF MIGRATIONS: SOME PASSAGES IN IRELAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Rebecca Solnit. Verso, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual post-modern travelogue, a California author uses
Ireland as a lens for looking at identity politics, history,
culture and the meaning of journeying and attachment to place.
Solnit is ``a writer of startling freshness and precision,'' Rand
Richards Cooper wrote here in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
