A6054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOTERS-COX     08-16 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS BUREAU: AMERICANS TOO BUSY TO VOTE IN 1996 PRESIDENTIAL
CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five million Americans were just too busy to vote
in the last presidential election, one of the chief reasons why the
1996 balloting was the weakest since 1924, a Census Bureau report
to be released Monday shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time constraints are now the single biggest reason Americans
who are registered give for not voting,'' said Loretta Bass, a
co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts on U.S. voting behavior patterns say the low
1996 turnout in 1996 reflects the uninspiring campaigns waged by
the candidates, President Clinton and Republican Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you probe beneath the `I'm-too-busy' excuse, you'll find
that people saw little of importance to decide (in 1996),'' said
Curtis Gans, head of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, a non-profit organization that monitors voting trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not, as some have claimed, a picture of a satisfied
electorate,'' Gans added. ``In the majority of elections, citizens
are decreasingly motivated either by partisan interest or civic
duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 54 percent of the voting age population in the United
States voted in the 1996 presidential election, down from 61
percent in the 1992 campaign, the Census Bureau report shows.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the so-called ``motor voter'' law, which went into
effect in 1995 and made it easier to register to vote, the Census
Bureau found that registration in 1996 was at its lowest ebb since
1968. Some 128 million people, or 66 percent of the voting age
population, were registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 21.3 million who registered but did not vote in 1996, 5
million said they were too busy or could not take off time from
work or school - ``a sign of the times ... hectic schedules and
increasing demands of employers,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why were they really too busy? Because they weren't
interested,'' said Rodolfo O. de la Garza, a professor of
government at the University of Texas in Austin and vice president
of the Tomas Rivera Institute, a think tank that studies Latino
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given a campaign between Clinton and Dole, you think, Hell, I
need to work on my car,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 17 percent of non-voting registered citizens reported
to the Census Bureau that they did not vote in 1996 because of
apathy about the political process, up from 11 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen percent said they disliked the candidates, 3 percent
fewer than in 1980 when President Carter was challenged by Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1980, only 7.6 percent said they were too busy or could
not get time off to vote, compared to 21.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons people gave for not voting were in 1996: illness
or emergency (14.9 percent), out of town (11.1 percent), forgot or
had no transportation to the polls (4.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
   However, Hispanic voters, now being aggressively wooed by
Democrats and Republicans alike, were a significant exception to
the downward trends in 1996, the Census Bureau found.
</P>
<P>
   ``And rightly so,'' said Lisa Navarrete, spokeswoman for the
National Council of La Raza (NCLR), the nation's largest Latino
advocacy unit. ``The anti-Hispanic, anti-immigrant rhetoric (of the
GOP campaign) really spurred a lot of anger among immigrants ...
They took it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Hispanics, naturalized citizens were more likely to vote
in 1996 than native born Hispanics, according to the Census Bureau.
Fifty-three percent of naturalized Hispanics voted while only 42
percent of native born Hispanics voted.
</P>
<P>
   Research soon to be released by the Tomas Rivera Institute finds
the same trends among Hispanics in 1996, de la Garza said. In New
York, for example, naturalized Dominicans were much more likely to
vote than native-born Puerto Ricans. The same pattern held among
native born and naturalized Mexican-Americans in Texas and
Cuban-Americans in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an anti-immigrant election, and they were voting to
protect themselves,'' de la Garza noted.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau report also found that:
</P>
<P>
   - More people voted by absentee ballot in 1996 - 8 percent,
compared to 4 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   - The voter turnout among whites was 60.7 percent, compared to
53 percent for African Americans, 45 percent for Asians and Pacific
Islanders and 44.3 percent for Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   - Voting from 1992 to 1996 declined by much more for whites (8
percent) than for African Americans (3 percent). There was no
significant change for Hispanics or Asian Americans between the two
elections.
</P>
<P>
   - Women voted in greater percentages (59.6 percent) than men
(57.0 percent), continuing a trend that began with the 1980
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   - Suburbanites outvoted the central city, 59.8 percent compared
to 57.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   - Among age groups, the peak years for voting participation were
65 to 74 years of age (70.1 percent) while the least likely voters
were 18 to 19 (30.2 percent) and 20 to 24 (33.4 percent).
</P>
<P>
   - The higher the family income, the more likely a person
registered and voted. Families with incomes above $75,000 had a
73.6 percent turnout rate, more than double the 39.5 percent rate
of families with income below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   - People with college degrees were nearly three times as likely
(74 percent) to vote than those who had not completed high school
(39 percent).
</P>
<P>
   - Southerners were less likely to register (65.9 percent) and
vote (52.2 percent) while Midwesterners were more likely to
register (71.6 percent) and vote (59.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
