<P>
   BOWERS _ Mississippi is preparing yet again to open old wounds
and air out dirty laundry - KKK leader Sam Bowers is going on trial
August 17 - for the fifth time - for the murder of Vernon Dahmer
Sr. A Hattiesburg civil rights activist who died in 1966 when he
tried to protect his family from a band of about 16 klansmen
torching his home. The Dahmer family has waited a long time for
this day; meanwhile, Bowers and his co-defendants are cocky. Bowers
has said he wants to get in court as soon as possible. And Devours
Nix, who was arrested and will stand trial later this year, got out
of jail by claiming he was too ill for it, and then was caught
teeing off at a golf course. Will the state finally put these men
in jail? (Rochell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG _ ATLANTA _ Michael Favorov is a Russian doctor at the
Centers for Disease Control who helped discover a new strain of
hepatitis. Yiannis Ventikos is a Greek scientist at Georgia Tech
whose research helps to save fish endangered by hydroelectric power
plants. Lisa Cregan-O'Brien is a world-class Irish dancer who
teaches American children the traditional steps of her homeland.
All came to Atlanta on a special immigrant visa available only to
the world's best and brightest in science, arts, education,
business or athletics. Known as the national interest waiver, it is
given to immigrants who can prove their skills and talents are so
unique that America would substantially benefit if they were here.
(Kurylo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
