<P>
   HORSEFARM-TROPHIES (Lexington, Ky.) _ After Calumet Farm,
thoroughbred racing's most legendary stable, collapsed in
bankruptcy in 1991, virtually every trapping of the breeding and
racing empire was auctioned to pay debts. Today, all that remains
of the farm's legacy is a collection of some 530 trophies and
awards, housed at the state-run Horse Park since 1982. Now that
those awards seem headed for the auction block, a raucous battle
has erupted in Bluegrass country between those who argue that the
collection should go to the highest bidder and those who say that
it is an important part of Kentucky's heritage and should stay put.
By Barry Meier. 2,000 words.
