<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGAS-AD-COLUMN-600&AMP;A     08-16 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGAS-AD-COLUMN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LAS VEGAS ALTERS ITS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWIN MCDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The city of Las Vegas had an advertising budget of $27 million
last year, or or almost 10 times that of the average state's ad
budget in 1997. No wonder, then, that Las Vegas drew almost 30.5
million visitors for the year, who spent almost $25 billion and
filled 86.4 percent of the city's hotel and motel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those admittedly impressive statistics masked some
fundamental problems with the city's tourist industry, including
falling hotel occupancy and competition from the many casinos that
have sprung up elsewhere in recent years. So this fiscal year, the
Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority has earmarked an
additional $300,000 for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it recently undertook a six-month analysis of Las
Vegas as a destination, after which it adopted its first-ever
multiyear advertising and marketing plan, which will extend through
fiscal 2003. The result is an ambitious plan to reposition Las
Vegas as an entertainment destination, rather than primarily a
gambling mecca.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we did only one-year plans,'' said Rossi
Ralenkotter, vice president of marketing for the Las Vegas
Convention and Visitors Authority. ``But because of the evolution
of our marketplace, it was imperative to do the research and
determine what direction we were going to take from a marketing and
advertising viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for tampering with apparent success are included in
both a 63-page strategic and market analysis released two and a
half weeks ago, and a 222-page marketing and advertising program
released last week. Both analyses were compiled by R&AMP;R Advertising
of Las Vegas, the longtime agency for the Las Vegas Convention and
Visitors Authority.
</P>
<P>
   What both studies show, for example, is that as impressive as
Las Vegas room occupancy was in 1997, exceeding the national
average by almost 22 percentage points, it actually dipped to its
lowest percentage since 1992 and fell four percentage points from
90.4 percent in 1966. At the same time, the five big hotels
scheduled to open within the next 16 months will add 20,000 more
rooms to the existing 106,000-room inventory, putting added
pressure on hotel occupancy and room rates.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a decade ago only two states had legalized gambling
(Nevada and New Jersey), while 30 states have it today. And within
two years, some 90 percent of the U.S. population is expected to be
within 200 miles of casino-style gambling.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the city's worries, 39 percent of visitors said they
would have come to Las Vegas more often had they not had access to
casinos closer to home. Among visitors with a propensity to gamble,
surveys showed, the number of visits to Las Vegas over a five-year
period dropped to seven from 11.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the most surprising finding, perhaps, is that for the first
time more visitors (50 percent vs. 48 percent) consider Las Vegas
an entertainment resort than a gambling resort. And it is in
recognition of that fact that Las Vegas now intends to undertake
what it describes as ``the most dramatic change in its history,''
repositioning itself as a ``world-class entertainment destination''
and going head to head for the tourist dollar with such cities as
Paris, New York, San Francisco, Orlando, Atlantic City and Monte
Carlo, as well as with Disney, Universal and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   That is where the Las Vegas ad campaign comes in. By earmarking
$13.8 million for television (primarily national cable television),
$1.8 million for outdoor ads, almost $1.3 million for newspapers
and $1 million each for radio and consumer magazines, Las Vegas
will try to reposition itself as America's best vacation value for
millionaires as well as those of modest means.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``In prior decades, Las Vegas was marketed primarily as a gaming
destination,'' last week's report said, ``with resorts at the low-,
mid- and high-price range levels.'' Now, ``with occupancy levels
flat and room inventory continuing to increase, Las Vegas must
communicate its message to multiple audiences and consumer
segments.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, ads will gradually shift from image-driven to
retail-oriented, and for the first time the consumer campaign will
focus on such amenities as dining, shopping, recreation,
entertainment, resorts, night life and special events. The current
tag line, ``Open 24 Hours,'' will be retained on all destination
advertising, while the slogan, ``It's Anything and Everything,''
will adorn print and electronic ads. Television commercials will
carry both slogans, but also ask, ``How Soon Can You Get Here?''
</P>
<P>
   Where, then, does this re-emphasis leave gambling, whose slot
machines, tables and roulette wheels took in about $5 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not neglecting gambling,'' said Ralenkotter of the
Convention and Visitors Authority. ``We're still the No. 1 gaming
destination in the world, and still the No. 1 place where people
want to go to gamble. So we're going to speak about the gaming side
of Las Vegas in our promotional literature and collateral
material.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We need to let the traveling consumer know all
the new things we've added in the last five to seven years, like
golf, spas, restaurants with national and international
reputations, and shopping that's comparable to anywhere in the
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
