A6130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAUTAUQUA-125-ART-2T     08-16 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAUTAUQUA-125-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEW YORK'S LAKESIDE UTOPIA, A TIME OF SELF-EXAMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAUTAUQUA, N.Y. _ In 1899, after the philosopher William James
visited Chautauqua, the combination arts festival and resort here
in southwestern New York, he wrote that he was ``spellbound by the
charm and ease of everything, by the middle-class paradise, without
a victim, without a blot, without a tear.'' But James said he was
astonished on entering ``the dark and wicked world again, to catch
myself quite unexpectedly and involuntarily saying: `Ouf! what a
relief! Now for something primordial and savage.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chautauqua, founded in 1874 by Lewis Miller, an Akron,
Ohio, inventor, and father-in-law of Thomas Edison, and John Heyl
Vincent, a Methodist minister, as a summer school for Sunday-school
teachers, is a utopian community of 7,500 summer residents
seemingly devoted to the highest ideals of the spirit and the
intellect. Nestled on 750 acres on the shores of Lake Chautauqua,
the Chautauqua Institution is a place of pastel-colored Victorian
cottages with filigreed trim and gardens coordinated with pink and
white flowers. Children ride their bikes without fear of cars. And
sometimes it does seem a little like Truman Burbank's artificial
hometown of Seahaven in the Jim Carrey movie ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But in its heyday in the 19th century, Chautauqua was one of the
most important cultural institutions of its time, with an
incalculable effect on the dissemination of education and culture
in the United States, particularly for women, who had little access
to higher education. Today, after exhausting its original mission,
Chautauqua, almost incredibly, has carried on, averting financial
crises, and prospering.
</P>
<P>
   Four sitting American presidents have visited Chautauqua,
including Ulysses S. Grant, Theodore Roosevelt and Franklin D.
Roosevelt, who gave his ``I hate war speech'' in the amphitheater
in 1936. President Clinton prepared for his debate with Robert Dole
here in 1996. And George Gershwin composed his Concerto in F in one
of the practice shacks in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as it gears up for its 125th anniversary celebration next
year, Chautauqua is undergoing a profound self-examination, asking
how it can broaden its anachronistic population of mostly white,
older and prosperous Americans so that it can remain true to its
fundamental mission: serious debate about contemporary issues in an
atmosphere of cultural vitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking ourselves a lot of important questions about our
future,'' said Daniel Bratton, Chautauqua's president and a
Methodist minister. ``We're using the anniversary as a time to
bring these issues to a head.''
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly is Chautauqua? ``Even Chautauquans have
difficulty explaining Chautauqua,'' said Joan Fox, the director of
public information. Chautauqua is a nonprofit institution, not too
different from a giant co-op. Most of the common ground is owned by
the Chautauqua Foundation. The 1,100 houses are privately owned,
some of them by eighth-generation Chautauquans. The institution
operates on a budget of some $14 million a year with a year-round
staff of about 90, which in the summer grows to 1,500 people. It is
governed by a 24-member board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The Chautauqua Institution has its own daily newspaper, The
Chautauquan, its own symphony orchestra, conservatory theater,
opera company and ballet company. A total of 8,000 students attend
its schools of music, ballet, opera, theater and visual arts. At
the center of Chautauqua life is the 10:45 a.m. lecture in the
5,000-seat amphitheater, with the summer divided into subject
weeks. This summer's topics have included ``Ethics: Teaching
Virtue, Educating for Character'' and ``The Road to Educational
Excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultural events are open to outsiders, and over the course of a
summer about 142,000 people visit. There is a children's school and
day camps, called the Boys' and Girls' Clubs. Chautauqua has its
own security force, which has little to do but rebuke teen-agers
who pour soapsuds in the fountains. There is a 158-room wooden
hotel, the Athenaeum, built in 1881, also run by the institution.
</P>
<P>
   Chautauqua has its own deeply ingrained rituals, Old First Night
Day, for instance, its annual birthday celebration, and Recognition
Day, when members of the Chautauqua Literary and Scientific Circle,
one of the oldest continuous book clubs in the country, graduate,
each class with its own motto, emblem and officers. Those who read
extra books can join the Guild of the Seven Seals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chautauqua is kind of the memory of America,'' said Jeffrey
Simpson, whose family has been coming here for 88 years, and whose
book ``Chautauqua,'' will be published next year by Harry N.
Abrams. ``One of the reasons it was so successful is that it
reflected a small-town America many Americans were moving away
from. We know from Sinclair Lewis that small towns could be
culturally arid places. But because of its transitory nature,
Chautauqua could be the perfect small town. It reflected that
wonderful American curiosity, that omnivorous interest in
information, and it is contained in this picture-perfect place.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, there was a Catholic Mass in the Chapel of
the Good Shepherd and Jewish Services in the Hurlbut Church,
followed by bridge instruction in the Women's Clubhouse and an
Alumni Association ``Great American Picnic.'' Bard O'Neill,
director of Middle East Studies at the National War College, was
lecturing on Islamic fundamentalism to a group in the Hall of
Philosophy, built to resemble the Parthenon.
</P>
<P>
   Every 15 minutes or so, the bells in the campanile of the Miller
Bell Tower chimed, sometimes pealing out hymns. Down by the lake,
children played not far from Palestine Park, a contour model of the
Holy Land, with a pond representing the Dead Sea, and a trickle of
water the River Jordan. At McKnight Hall there was a School of
Music voice master class, while at the Chautauqua Center for the
Visual Arts there was a demonstration, ``Making an Adirondack Twig
Basket.'' Later, there was another Mass in the Hall of Philosophy,
and a choir rehearsal for Sunday services.
</P>
<P>
   Religion is fundamental to Chautauqua, although many residents
do not attend church. Most Chautauquans are Christian, and about 20
percent are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an inarticulated awareness of the sacred and the holy
in the whole community because of the natural surroundings and
because of the created human beauty,'' said Ross Mackenzie,
director of the department of religion. ``Civil discourse,
friendship, dance, music, all of these are expressions of human
created beauty. They all give us an awareness of the holy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `The Heart' of the Movement
</P>
<P>
   Although Chautauqua was originally founded with a religious
purpose, its major influence has been secular, primarily through
the Chautauqua Literary and Scientific Circle, formed in 1878. The
circle has been called ``the heart of the Chautauqua movement.''
Members were required to read books from a list with the aid of
study guides. In the first 20 years, 10,000 local reading circles
were formed, a quarter of them in villages of less than 500. There
were circles in prisons and country stores.
</P>
<P>
   By 1918, more than half a million people had taken the
Chautauqua correspondence course. ``This permeation of American
life through its smallest units is perhaps the most significant
social fact about Chautauqua,'' said Arthur Bestor Jr.,
Chautauqua's president from 1915 to 1944. Today there are few local
reading circles left, and the movement continues mainly at the
summer institution, with each ``class'' required to read 12 books
in four years. There were 127 graduates this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1883, Chautauqua was chartered as a university and remained
one for 12 years, until other universities began offering summer
courses. By the end of the 19th century, Chautauqua was, Russell
Lynes, the historian, wrote, ``a cultural phenomenon with some of
the sweep and force of a tidal wave.'' There were about 300
independent or loosely affiliated chautauquas. Traveling
chautauquas, or ``tent chautauquas,'' provided forums for famous
speakers like William Jennings Bryan, who once gave 50 lectures in
28 days on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of talking pictures and cars, which enabled
people to travel to find culture, the traveling chautauquas began
to decline. Today there are about 28 loosely affiliated local
chautauquas, including one in Lakeside, Ohio, on Lake Erie, and the
Ocean Grove Camp Meeting Association in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, Chautauqua went into receivership. Money was raised by
deeding back the houses, which had been rented, to members for 20
percent of their assessed value.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, Chautauqua seemed to be going into a decline.
Attendance was lagging; the buildings were in disrepair, and it was
having a hard time meeting its budget. Richard Miller, a Milwaukee
lawyer, and great-grandson of Lewis Miller, became chairman of the
Chautauqua board.
</P>
<P>
   He began an aggressive fund-raising campaign and built up the
endowment. The old buildings were repaired. Today, Chautauqua has
an endowment of about $40 million with another $50 million in
promised bequests from its wealthy members.
</P>
<P>
   But today's typical Chautauquan is no longer a Sunday school
teacher, or a public-school teacher, but is over 50 and a wealthy
professional. Houses can cost up to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to Attract Younger People
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that some of the people who make it interesting
_ like professors _ can't afford to keep coming,'' said Twig
Branch, a fourth-generation Chautauquan, who is an insurance agent.
``We business people are really boring,'' he added with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Chautauqua is also struggling to attract younger people, and
indeed there has been an increase in the number of children on
``the Grounds.'' It is also trying to attract a more diverse
population. For one thing, in order to get foundation support, it
needs diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a rapidly expanding black middle class, and they
haven't discovered it,'' said Bratton, the president of Chautauqua.
``Everybody, including blacks, likes to have people like them
around,'' he said. ``The absence of a critical mass makes it a
longer task.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people believe that diversity will develop. ``This is a
time of growth,'' said Alfreda Irwin, 85, the institution's
official historian, whose family has been coming to Chautauqua for
six generations. ``Learning is a sport here. Vincent and his son,
George, said we needed to stay close to the movements of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the society is diverse, we aim to be like society.
Chautauqua is very open and would like to have all sorts of people
come here and participate. I think it will happen, just
naturally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
