<SLUG> BC-CA-NUKE-CASKS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HI-TECH SOLUTION FOR STORING USED RADIOACTIVE FUEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(With CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION, CA-NUKE-PLANTS) 
(nk) 
 By ANDREW LaMAR NYT Regional Newspapers 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ At the center of Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co.'s
plan to decommission the Humboldt Bay Nuclear Power Plant is a
fundamental technological problem: where and how to store 14,040
spent fuel rods that will give off toxic radiation for tens of
thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the Korean radioactive waste that triggered widespread
protests when it was shipped through San Francisco last month,
Humboldt Bay's used radioactive fuel is a potentially lethal
collection of isotopes that could unleash cancers and other severe
health consequences to anyone exposed.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Korean wastes, high-level American wastes have no
place to go. The Idaho site for foreign radioactive waste was set
aside as part of federal attempts to control the international
spread and use of nuclear technology in the 1950s, but federal
plans to establish a depository for domestic waste have encountered
stiff opposition and left plants such as Humboldt Bay with nowhere
to ship their spent fuel rods.
</P>
<P>
   Technological innovations, however, have provided Humboldt Bay
with an alternative: ``dry cask'' storage. Dry casks are
18-foot-tall concrete and steel cases designed to keep radioactive
waste contained virtually forever, if need be. They are called dry
casks to distinguish them from another common storage method, in
which the waste is submerged in a pool of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows us to move forward with dismantling the plant sooner
and it provides a simpler way of storing the fuel,'' PG&AMP;E spokesman
Alec Arago said of the dry casks.
</P>
<P>
   Since shutting down the Humboldt Bay facility in 1976, PG&AMP;E has
kept the fuel rods in a 26-foot-deep pool of water within the
plant. The water once cooled the rods but now serves primarily to
block radiation from reaching the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fuel pool is safe but it requires a lot of attention and
vigilance,'' Arago said. That attention costs PG&AMP;E $10 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the cost, another disadvantage to the pool is its
potential vulnerability to a major earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The company has kept the Humboldt Bay plant in ``safe storage''
since 1983, delaying full decommissioning. There were many reasons
for the delay, but the principal one was the fuel problem.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, moving the fuel rods into dry casks wasn't
considered feasible because it would have required an expensive and
difficult two-step process in which the rods would have had to be
put in the casks and then taken out and encased in other
extra-strong containers to safeguard them against potential
accidents during shipment to a federal depository.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, with the delay in certification of a federal
disposal site, it was clear the casks would have to remain at the
Humboldt site for some time, and none of the casks met the criteria
for withstanding the kinds of powerful earthquakes they could be
exposed to there.
</P>
<P>
   But all that has changed with the development of multipurpose
canisters, containers that can be used both for storage and
shipment, and with PG&AMP;E's desire to speed up the decommissioning
process.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the nuclear industry's quandary, several companies
have designed the multipurposed canisters now awaiting approval
from the federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the vendors are busy licensing dual-purpose systems
because that way, when the DOE (Department of Energy) comes to take
the fuel, you're done with it,'' Patton said.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E estimates each dry cask will cost roughly $1 million, and
the Humboldt Bay plant will need six to eight casks. The company
has projected a $16 million price tag to acquire and load the
casks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly not an exact reckoning,'' Arago said, noting that
prices differ among vendors.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, PG&AMP;E is seeking a design that will withstand
twice the force of the strongest earthquake ever measured in the
Eureka area. The Little Salmon Fault, which ties into a network of
faults called the Cascadia Subduction Zone, is a few hundred yards
from the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The company has asked the California Public Utilities Commission
to allow money from the plant's decommissioning fund to be used for
the $7 million estimated cost to get the cask designed and
certified, a process expected to take three years.
</P>
<P>
   Under PG&AMP;E's plan, Humboldt Bay's 390 fuel rod assemblies would
end up in stainless steel canisters encased in dry casks bolted to
a 6-foot-thick concrete platform. Where the platform would be
located still must be decided, but it is likely to be near the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   To distant passersby, the casks would look like a giant pack of
beer, Patton said. Although models vary depending on the company
that builds them, a basic dry cask weighs 125 tons and measures 12
to 15 feet in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven nuclear power plants in the United States use dry casks
and nine others are pursuing them.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew LaMar writes for the Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press
Democrat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
