</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-NUKE-PLANT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGING NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS PUT GOVERNMENT GUIDELINES TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Minn., N.Y., Pa.)  (See related: CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION, CA-NUKE-CASKS.) 
(js) 
 BY ANDREW LaMAR   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ Across the nation, nuclear power plants are
coming to the end of their lives, and government and industry
officials are beginning to see whether decommissioning guidelines
work the way they were designed to.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear power plants are required to set aside enough money to
pay for their eventual dismantlement, and for the first few plants
fully decommissioned, the estimates have proved accurate.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly every nuclear power plant is different and
generalizing costs is difficult, said Leigh Ann Marshall, a
spokeswoman for the Nuclear Energy Institute, a trade association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little misleading to say there are 105 plants
operating and the dismantling cost will be X amount because there
are too many variables, like the cost of waste disposal and when
waste is actually moved by the federal government,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government does not plan to have a site that can
take high-level radioactive waste from nuclear power plants until
2010, meaning plants must find a way to store it until then.
</P>
<P>
   Using general NEI estimates, decommissioning those 105 plants
could run in the range of $38 billion to $54 billion. According to
the association, the average size of a nuclear plant is 1,000
megawatts and the cost for decommissioning a plant of that size
runs between $350 million and $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. projects a $195 million bill for
decommissioning the Humboldt Bay Nuclear Power Plant, a 65-megawatt
facility. Dismantling PG&AMP;E's other nuclear plant, the Diablo Canyon
Nuclear Power Plant, is estimated at $1.2 billion. The Diablo plant
is a 2,400-megawatt facility with two reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-nuclear power activists, such as Jim Adams of Redwood
Alliance, say decommissioning contains far too many uncertainties
to be confident about estimates. The Redwood Alliance, an
Arcata-based environmental group, has asked state authorities to
re-examine the estimate for Diablo Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do a national service in pointing out this
decommissioning is a huge sleeping giant,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The first plants to complete the cycle have managed to meet
their budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Two demonstration plants - Shippingport in Pennsylvania and
Pathfinder in Minnesota - were decommissioned in 1989.
Shippingport, a 72-megawatt plant, cost $98 million to dismantle
and Pathfinder, a 58-megawatt facility, cost $81 million to
deconstruct.
</P>
<P>
   The 330-megawatt Fort St. Vrain demonstration plant in Colorado
was decommissioned in 1996 at a cost of $189 million. And New York
State's Shoreham plant, a 849-megawatt plant that operated the
total equivalent of only two days, was decommissioned in 1995 for
$186 million.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, utility companies built nuclear reactors because
they believed nuclear fission would be a cheap source of energy,
said Duke Wheeler, a spokesman for the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of deregulation, utility companies face greater
competition than ever and the costs of decommissioning figure into
making the operation of nuclear power plants more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see is the present generation of nuclear power plants
are reaching the end of their economic viability,'' Wheeler said.
``What we're finding out and what a lot utilities are finding out
very painfully, is it (nuclear power) is not very cheap at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew LaMar writes for the Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press
Democrat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
