<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION-     08-16 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION-ART-640(2TAKES)-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIF. PLANT MAY BE AMONG NATION'S FIRST DECOMMISSIONED NUKE
FACILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867) 
(See related: CA-NUKE-CASKS, CA-NUKE-PLANTS) 
(js) 
 BY ANDREW LaMAR   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ Towering over Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co.'s
power plant complex just south of Eureka is a 250-foot-high red and
white vent stack, a seemingly benign fixture that has dominated
southern Humboldt Bay for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to hundreds of thousands of motorists who stream by
on nearby Highway 101 each year, the stack represents a danger of
frightening proportions. A powerful earthquake, experts say, could
topple the stack into the adjoining Humboldt Bay Nuclear Power
Plant, cracking the structure that contains nuclear fuel rods and
releasing radioactive waste into the surrounding air and water.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, PG&AMP;E will install a smaller, 50-foot-tall steel
vent stack, and then begin taking down the longtime signature of
the Humboldt Bay skyline, the first step toward decontaminating the
plant and removing it once and for all. The entire process is
projected to take seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The Humboldt Bay power plant, shut down since 1976, has been a
source of controversy for decades, as PG&AMP;E and anti-nuclear power
activists struggled over what to do with the aging facility that
sits only a few hundred yards from a network of earthquake faults
called the Cascadia Subduction Zone. The plant originally was
closed for refueling but was never reopened because of earthquake
safety worries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, plant managers agree with activists that the
radioactive waste should be removed and the building taken apart as
soon as possible. If PG&AMP;E wins approval, the West Coast's first
commercial nuclear power plant would become one of the first in the
nation to be fully decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   The move is applauded by Redwood Alliance, an Arcata-based
environmental organization that works on energy issues and has
fought to keep the plant closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is in an earthquake you could have major damage
done to the reactor core and the rods in the pool to the point
where you would have radiation leaking out into the environment,''
said Jim Adams, Redwood Alliance's point man on the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Before PG&AMP;E can rid itself of the Humboldt Bay plant, it must
negotiate a maze of regulatory obstacles and overcome huge economic
hurdles. In the process, it could set precedents that will help
guide demolition of the nation's 105 operating nuclear reactors,
all of which eventually will have to be decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E must find a way to safely store highly radioactive waste,
devise ways to decontaminate the plant and pay an as-yet-unknown
bill. The first, and likely the biggest challenge, will be to win
approval for storing 14,040 radioactive fuel rods in 18-foot-tall
steel and concrete caskets on the plant site. On-site storage is
necessary because environmental concerns have blocked approval of a
federal storage site in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The state will hold hearings on PG&AMP;E's request later this summer
and in the fall. PG&AMP;E hopes to begin work within three years and
the plant could be torn down by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The company decided earlier this year to move ahead for several
financial reasons: storing radioactive waste at the plant costs $10
million a year, decommissioning costs are escalating and PG&AMP;E wants
to sell four gas-generated power plants, valued at $30 million,
that are adjacent to the nuclear plant.
</P>
<P>
   Industry and government officials say the deconstruction of the
Humboldt Bay plant will force the public to address issues that are
being raised as scores of plants built in the 1960s and 1970s _
most of them operating today _ approach the ends of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sleeping and it is going to be awakening here and it's
big,'' said Duke Wheeler, a spokesman for the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission. ``It's not all that big now, but it is going
to become big, much bigger than it is now. It is a substantial,
emerging part of the whole power-generation industry.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Three U.S. nuclear power plants already have been dismantled and
two more are in the process. Humboldt Bay is one of five plants
that have started decommissioning, and it is unusual because the
power plant is built underground and because PG&AMP;E is proposing a
novel way of taking care of radioactive waste by storing it in
earthquake-proof containers.
</P>
<P>
   Nine nuclear plants, including Rancho Seco near Sacramento and
San Onofre in Orange County, have ceased operating and their owners
have decided to maintain them in their current state for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government licenses nuclear reactors for 40 years,
and plants can ask for a 20-year extension. To date, only one
application has been filed for an extension, although more are
expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of the license, plant operators commit to
decommissioning the nuclear plant after it quits producing power,
and that means eliminating radioactive material on site that would
be a danger to public health and safety, or to the environment. To
eventually pay for the deconstruction, plants are required to set
aside enough money to cover the estimated decommissioning costs.
</P>
<P>
   The process is complicated and expensive, and the Humboldt Bay
Nuclear Power Plant will help pave the way for others to follow.
</P>
<P>
   One direct beneficiary of Humboldt Bay's experience will be
PG&AMP;E's other nuclear plant, the much larger Diablo Canyon Nuclear
Power Plant in San Luis Obispo County, which started operating in
the early 1980s and probably will be decommissioned sometime after
2020. With two reactors capable of generating 2,400 megawatts of
electricity, the plant cost $6 billion to build, and
decommissioning it is now estimated to run $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the small Humboldt Bay plant capable of
generating only 65 megawatts cost $24.8 million to build in 1963
but is projected to cost $195 million to decommission.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to tearing down the plant is what to do
with the 390 assemblies of highly radioactive spent nuclear fuel
rods stored in a pool of water at the facility. The assemblies,
which are 6 inches square and 8 feet long, contain the individual
fuel rods in which nuclear fission took place, generating the heat
that transformed water into steam and then turned turbines to
produce electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The rods contain a number of radioactive elements, including
plutonium, which has one isotope that takes 25,000 years to lose
half its radioactivity. The rods are stored in water that
originally served to cool them and now serves to shield the outside
from radiation.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the federal government has planned to build a
repository for the nation's high-level nuclear waste, such as
Humboldt Bay's spent fuel rods. But the current plan to use Yucca
Mountain in Nevada has encountered considerable opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Ann Marshall, a spokeswoman for the Nuclear Energy
Institute, a trade association, said the actual demolition of the
plant is not a difficult process.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really driving the cost of decommissioning through the
ceiling is the high-level waste has no place to go,'' she said.
``The federal government hasn't provided a place for it. The more
plants have to baby-sit that waste, the more expensive it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, nuclear plants have turned to dry storage as an
alternative. As part of its decommissioning plan, Humboldt Bay
proposes putting the radioactive rods in 16-foot-tall concrete and
steel cylinders known as dry casks that would be bolted to a
6-foot-thick concrete pad near the plant.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E expects to pay $16 million to acquire six to eight casks
and load them with the fuel assemblies. But first the company must
find a cask design that can withstand twice the force of the
strongest earthquake ever measured locally.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the storage problem comes the hurdle of how to go
about deconstructing the plant, with little experience to go on.
Company officials said they will reassess their plans and make a
final decision once they receive a license for dry casks, expected
within three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of this is how you do it,'' said Adams, of Redwood
Alliance. ``They haven't done it (decommissioning) with a large
reactor. I'm a little concerned about how the technology will work
_ how you will actually take this apart and how (radioactive)
releases might occur during the work.''
</P>
<P>
   The tall concrete vent stack, which filtered radiation from air
released from the plant, demonstrates the difficulty ahead for
PG&AMP;E. The inside of the base of the stack, where its contamination
is the heaviest, is saturated with cesium _ the same element found
in radioactive fallout from bombs _ at 100,000 times the level
found naturally in the surrounding ground.
</P>
<P>
   The company has contracted with Burns &AMP; Roe of New Jersey to use
a crane with a 300-foot boom to carefully disassemble the stack,
step by step, in 17 different sections. To ensure the interior
contaminated concrete is removed, workers will cut the rings into
pie pieces, seal them and send them off to a waste processing
center.
</P>
<P>
   The stack removal is projected to cost $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the stack. Within the plant's refueling building
are highly contaminated areas, such as the reactor vessel, a
48-foot-long by 10-foot-wide steel tank, that will have to be cut
up and shipped out.
</P>
<P>
   All told, dismantling what's left of the plant after stack
removal is expected to cost more than $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like other nuclear plants that have shut down before the end of
their 40-year license, the Humboldt Bay plant became unprofitable
to operate. That happened after the Three Mile Island disaster
created a slew of new regulations and other unforeseen costs, such
as earthquake safety, surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   But the new requirements generated by Three Mile Island were no
more daunting than the web of state and federal regulations PG&AMP;E
must now negotiate in order to store fuel in dry casks and get
access to money already set aside for plant decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   The Humboldt Bay plant, like all nuclear power plants, is
required to have a decommissioning fund, and it stands at $156
million. The fund has grown through investment from about $45
million in ratepayer money collected in the 1980s, and it is
expected to continue growing to a total of $210 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the money can be used only with the permission of the
California Public Utilities Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, PG&AMP;E asked the utilities commission for $7
million from the fund to pay for design of the dry casks, and to
get them licensed and approved by the federal government. The
company has also requested that the purchasing and loading the dry
casks, estimated at $16 million, be paid for by the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities commission is slated to hold public hearings on
the request later this summer and in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In an ironic twist, the Redwood Alliance finds itself allied
with PG&AMP;E, pushing the utilities commission to pay for the work and
move the process ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our goal, to get this taken apart as soon as we can,''
Adams said. ``In some senses, we're on the same side (with PG&AMP;E)
for the first time because we agree this should go forward at
Humboldt Bay. Everything is moving forward. We just want to make
sure it's done right.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E officials say they have included great leeway in their
estimate that it will cost $195 million to dismantle the plant.
However, one official admitted it is a bit like planning for a
vacation two or three years away because so many variables could
come into play and change the estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Adams fears cost overruns could deplete the fund and force PG&AMP;E
one day to return to ratepayers for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a whole lot of faith in these numbers,'' Adams
said. ``We're just trying to open up the door and get people to
realize what a huge cost uncertainty we have here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew LaMar writes for the Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press
Democrat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
