</P>
<P>
   WASHNGTON
</P>
<P>
   PROBE-COSTS _ WASHINGTON _ Critics of independent counsel
Kenneth Starr have made the $40-50 million spent on the probe of
President Clinton into a rallying cry. Starr's defenders turn the
tables, asserting that White House delay tactics, stonewalling, and
costly court appeals have dragged out the four-year probe and
driven up the price tag. And that is just part of the money battle
that has been a backdrop in this titanic legal struggle. (Malone,
Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL _ If she were President Bill Clinton's lawyer, Susan
Brenner says she would advise him to tell the truth. Brenner, a
professor of law at the University of Dayton, doesn't say that in
an old-fashioned, all-American, cannot-tell-a-lie tone. She says it
because she feels the president is in grave danger of being hung
out to dry by Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr, which could happen
if he lies and perjures himself. (Kline, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   LOGGING _ The era of big timber is over at the U.S. Forest
Service. Or at least that is what Chief Mike Dombeck says. But as
Dombeck moves to reform the agency away from being timber based to
being more ecologically based ,he is facing resistance from within
his own agency, critcism from industry and its allies in Congress
and skeptism from environmentalist who contend that Dombeck is long
on rhetoric but short on action. We focus on how Dombeck's agenda
is affecting the management of the 4.5 million acres of national
forests in the eastern United States. (Harmon, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/ LOGRAGE _ James Sullivan has spent the last 15 years hounding
the Forest Service in the northeast Georgia mountains. Profile on a
volunteer who is part of a band of environmentalists who monitor
Forest Service-sanctioned timber cutting. Sullivan has documented a
disturbing trend of overharvesting in parts of the national forests
seclued from public view. 25 inches. (Harmon, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOGLIFE _ A profile of a mountain logging family who for years
have made their living felling trees in this rugged landscape. We
explore their unique perspective in the battle for the mountains,
as they struggle not to become endangered species of the 21st
century. 25 inches. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOGMAP _ Map of national forests in the Southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   LOGCHART _ Chart that shows declining timber harvest since 1980s
on national forests, decline in forest service budget and decline
in numbers of employees.
</P>
<P>
   LOGBOX _ Box with examples of the ``roadless areas'' areas like
Slide Hollow that survive in the mountains from North Georgia to
central Virginia.
</P>
