<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTIMONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PREPARES FOR ADMISSION AND APOLOGY IN LEWINSKI TESTIMONY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Sunday rehearsed a possible
admission of an ``inappropriate relationship'' with former White
House intern Monica Lewinski as he prepared for make-or-break
testimony before a grand jury investigating his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   White House Deputy Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said the
president had not reached a decision about whether to make a public
statement before departing on a two-week vacation on Martha's
Vineyard, Mass., after his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony caps a seven month investigation by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr into allegations of a sexual
relationship and attempted cover up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats publicly scripted politically
acceptable remarks for Clinton as the president huddled with his
lawyers in the upstairs residence of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
counseled Clinton to be ``blunt _ tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch added: ``If he does that and then really asks the American
people to forgive him or at least work with him, I think the
polling shows that the American people probably are willing to
allow him to finish out his term.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the American people are so eager to put the episode
behind the nation that they are willing to accept that Clinton lied
under oath and to them in public statements when he denied a sexual
relationship with Lewinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing this president could do is say, `Look, I was
trying to protect my wife, my daughter from pain and suffering that
I'd caused,''' Hatch advised.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., the second ranking Democrat on the
House Judiciary Committee and a brother of Ann Lewis, the White
House director of communications, offered a similar assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out that the president is going to say, yes, there
was some sexual activity between him and Monica Lewinsky and he
covered that up to protect his family, herself, himself, et cetera,
I think that will be regrettable, but hardly an impeachable
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and Frank appeared on NBC News' ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta, who served as Clinton's White House chief of staff
through his re-election, said that if Clinton ``changes his
testimony and acknowledges an improper relationship here, he
obviously is going to have to go through a lot of pain himself, not
only in apologizing to his wife and his family, but obviously to
the staff and to those that he misled and to the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Panetta counseled being forthright nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., a high ranking member of the House
Judiciary Committee, signaled that some Republicans may not accept
a presidential admission of a lie with an apology. McCollum, in an
appearance on CBS News' ``Face the Nation,'' said that a president
cannot ``be held to any less standard than we hold somebody else
who has committed a crime, and perjury is a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum added: ``If at the end of the day I concluded that the
president of the United States lied under oath in a judicial court
proceeding, I would have a very hard time not voting to recommend
impeachment to the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Clinton was working on the phrasing, voice tone
and body language that he might use during Monday's closed-circuit
testimony to a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fielded questions from his team of personal lawyers, led
by Washington superlawyer David Kendall and Mickey Kantor, the
tough Los Angeles corporate lawyer who served as a top campaign
adviser in 1992 and later commerce secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said in a terse written statement that he said was
issued to staunch ``an enormous amount of groundless speculation''
about Clinton's testimony that: ``The truth is the truth. Period.
And that's how the president will testify.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' only public appearance on Sunday was to attend
church services at Foundry United Methodist Church. The couple
entered the church holding hands. Clinton clutched his bible. He
waved to a crowd. Mrs. Clinton wore sunglasses on an overcast day
with occasional rain.
</P>
<P>
   During a moment in the service when members of the congregation
exchanged greetings with each other, more than a dozen people
reached out to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Shropshire Jr., minister of the parish, told his
congregation: ``When you have opposition and hopeless situations,
God bears us up on eagles' wings.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly denied having a sexual relationship with
Lewinski, 25, who started working at the White House as a
21-year-old college graduate.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 17 deposition in the Paula Jones' sexual harassment
suit, Clinton said: ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica
Lewinski. I have never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks at the White House on Jan. 26, Clinton publicly
reiterated his denial as his wife stood by his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had sexual relations with that woman, Ms.
Lewinski,'' declared Clinton, wagging his finger for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinski initially denied a sexual relationship with Clinton in
a sworn affidavit in the Jones' law suit. But after winning
immunity from prosecution from Starr, Lewinski told Starr's grand
jury on Aug. 6 that she carried out an 18-month sexual relationship
with the president, according to lawyers familiar with her
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first American president who is the focus of a
criminal investigation who will testify before a grand jury. But
his appearance is carefully circumscribed.
</P>
<P>
   After Starr insisted Clinton testify in a July 17 subpoena,
Clinton's lawyers negotiated unique arrangements that would not be
available to ordinary Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony is limited to a single day in contrast to
some of the more than 70 witnesses who have appeared before the
grand jury since January who have returned four or five times.
Clinton's testimony is scheduled to begin at 1 p.m. EDT Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is being permitted to remain at the White House rather
than being required to appear before the grand jury in person in a
federal court house a dozen blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will have the support of three lawyers during his
testimony _ Kendall and Nicole Seligman of the Williams &AMP; Connolly
firm, and White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony will be relayed to the grand jury via a
closed-circuit one-way television link that will, in effect, work
to limit spontaneous questions from the 23-member grand jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Grand jurors with questions must relay their questions to a
prosecutor in the grand jury room who will then relay it by phone
to one of the prosecutors asking Clinton questions at the White
House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
