<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SILICON-ALLEY-MEDIA-A     08-16 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-ALLEY-MEDIA-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S WEB INDUSTRY MAY BE OUTGROWING ITS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The restless clan of chic geeks and entrepreneurs who
populate New York's new media industry may not be anywhere near as
rich as their West Coast counterparts. But in the pages of Jason
McCabe Calacanis' monthly magazine, Silicon Alley Reporter, they
emerge far more glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry here is driven by people,'' Calacanis, 27,
lectured a magazine job applicant recently over breakfast at
Balthazar's, a trendy downtown restaurant. ``On the West Coast
there are a handful of celebrities _ Bill Gates, Larry Ellison,''
Calacanis said, referring to the chairman of the world's two
largest software companies. ``Those people are boring. They don't
take good pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Calacanis' irreverence is either refreshing or hopelessly
sophomoric, depending on one's point of view. Yet his shameless
boosterism of Silicon Alley _ New York's downtown multimedia hub _
has helped create the aura of community and even home-team spirit
for a disparate group of colleagues and competitors who otherwise
might have little more in common than being located in Manhattan
and trying to find some sort of profitable business on the World
Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Calacanis' application of celebrity journalism to the
world of New York new media has earned him a certain measure of
success. In less than two years the Silicon Alley Reporter has
grown from a few photocopied sheets to 116 glossy pages, on the
strength of advertising sales and revenue from the periodic
industry conferences Calacanis has organized like last month's
``Rising Tide Summit,'' which attracted more than 200 registrants
who paid $500 each to attend.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there is a growing sense in some quarters that the
community identity that Silicon Alley Reporter has worked so hard
to sell may no longer be the way many members of that community
want to see themselves _ or be seen by the larger business world.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are some holdouts, notably the online magazines
Feed and Word, increasingly, the definition of ``new media'' in New
York seems to be moving away from artsy, underfunded Web sites like
Stim, a Prodigy pop-culture project that fell by the wayside, or
the interactive soap opera The East Village. The new media seem to
be maturing instead into online extensions of the old-line
Manhattan media _ whether in advertising, marketing, publishing or
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   And as venture-capitalized start-ups evolve into IPO-financed
corporations, some industry executives are concerned that
Calacanis' unflagging promotion of an image evoking artists' lofts
and SoHo may be at odds with the businesslike demeanor that will
play well in boardrooms and on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a hypester in an industry that could do with less
hype,'' said Kyle Shannon, co-founder of Agency.com. The company's
shareholder is the giant advertising holding company Omnicom and
which through a series of acquisitions has become the largest
agency devoted to creating advertising on the Internet. ``There are
two Silicon Alleys _ the one where people go to the parties and the
one where people actually do the work,'' Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many of the citizens of Silicon Alley are not yet
ready to go completely corporate _ to stop dressing in black or
bleaching their hair blonde or, among the men, raising goatees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work very hard to balance the kind of
accountability we have to have now with the creative risk-taking
that brought us to where we are,'' said Nicholas Butterworth,
president of Sonicnet, an Internet broadcaster acquired last year
by the cable giant Tele-Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move to new office space, and I'm scared,'' said
Butterworth, whose company has been located in a loft. ``One of the
terrible and great things about Sonicnet is we have no walls. What
happens if we put up walls?''
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth said he reads the Silicon Alley Reporter because
Calacanis, a former gossip columnist from Brooklyn, manages to tell
it mostly like it is. ``Is it balanced? No. It's partisan. But it
delivers the goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would fault Calacanis for not speaking his mind _ although
he seems to save his rants for subjects beyond the borders of
downtown Manhattan. Born of a new-media column that he was writing
for Paper Magazine, the first issue of Silicon Alley Reporter
carried the headline ``Microsoft Alienates Alley.'' And in his
daily e-mail feed last week, Calacanis critiqued Texas-based
Zapata's Internet acquisition strategy as ``over-simplistic 1995
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Other characteristic fixtures of Calacanis' magazine include a
controversial map that highlights a revolving _ some say random _
bunch of new media firms below 57th Street. Then there's the
monthly feature labeled ``Digital Dim Sum: They Lead the Charmed
Life so You Don't Have To,'' which presents paparazzi-style
photographs of aspiring Silicon Alley business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason's challenge will be to figure out what his focus is as
the industry fragments into its logical genres,'' said Josh Harris,
co-founder of the online research firm Jupiter Communications and
now chief executive of an Internet television venture. ``I look at
my contemporaries and we've all been through the war and we all
know it's never going to be the same. It's like after my freshman
year, it's time to leave the dorm.''
</P>
<P>
   At last month's conference, for instance, some attendees
grumbled at the hour devoted to interviewing the Belgian anarchist
who won notoriety earlier this year by throwing a cream pie in the
face of Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason doesn't represent Silicon Alley,'' said one attendee,
who insisted on anonymity because he didn't want to risk
retribution in print. ``This is someone who is busy being flip and
glib when the industry is really about serious people who are
running serious businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   But such criticism may also belie a certain defensiveness about
the industry's lingering immaturity, even as it struggles through
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people try to avoid saying about Jason, and it's not
really about Jason but about the industry in New York, is that it's
small-time,'' said Michael Wolff, the newly appointed media
columnist for New York magazine and author of ``Burn Rate'' (Simon
and Schuster, 1998), a book about the rise and fall of his own New
York new media company. ``The point about New York is we have not
had a defining business here,'' Wolff said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The Alley's derivative nickname first caught on in 1995, with
the explosion of Web and the conviction that its ``content'' _ the
techie catch-all for magazines, newspapers, music, movies, TV,
advertising and various vaguely defined interactive stuff _ would
be produced in the world's media capital.
</P>
<P>
   But of all of those things, only advertising has shown a
propensity to make money on the Web. Moreover, the truly successful
Web content _ at least this month _ appears to be the information
tools or ``portals'' aggregated by major search engines like Yahoo,
Excite and Snap!, which are all located on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Still, New York partisans are quick to point to the initial
public offering of Doubleclick, an advertising services firm, which
went public last winter at $17 a share and closed Friday at $43.
City officials cite a survey conducted by Coopers &AMP; Lybrand that
shows that by mid-1997, the number of new- media jobs and companies
had doubled to 105,771 and 4,881, respectively, in a mere 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, shares of 24/7, another Web advertising firm,
rose 45 percent to close at $20.25 in its first day of trading. Two
more New York companies, The Globe, an online community Web site
and Earthweb, an interactive services firm, also recently announced
their intention to go public.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the disadvantage of being across the continent
from Sand Hill Road where Silicon Valley's venture capitalists hold
court is not as sharp as it once was, as East Coast investors like
Flatiron Partners take up some of the slack.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the insular new media community, the fact that Joanne
Wilson, wife of a Flatiron partner, Fred Wilson, sells advertising
for the Silicon Alley Reporter has raised eyebrows in some circles.
</P>
<P>
   Calacanis denies critics' contention that the companies Wilson
invests in get special editorial consideration.
</P>
<P>
   A black belt in karate who put himself through Fordham
University repairing electronic equipment, Calacanis makes no
pretense to vaunted journalistic objectivity. ``It's no secret I'm
a fan of this industry,'' he said. ``We write about every failure.
We cover it. We don't obsess over it.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating with a degree in psychology, Calacanis landed a
job in technical support for Sony Corp.'s legal department. A
habitual hustler, he managed to talk his way into a ride on the
corporate jet to chat about the internet with Sony's
then-president, Michael Schulhof.
</P>
<P>
   A project for America Online that he developed after leaving
Sony did not take off, but in the winter of 1996, Calacanis took
the modest sum America Online paid him for his efforts and started
Silicon Alley Reporter, which he initially wrote, produced and
distributed almost entirely himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a staff of eight helping him put out the magazine,
Calacanis is growing up and branching out. Forsaking neighborhood
loyalties for the prospect of a new market, he has been spending a
lot of time in Los Angeles lately and has begun running a ``Digital
Coast Reporter'' insert in the magazine, appropriating the
appellation a group of Southern California new-media entrepreneurs
recently bestowed on the region.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, meanwhile, to compete with a local online news
service, (AT)NY, Calacanis recently started a daily e-mail news
feed.
</P>
<P>
   And he has entered into a partnership with Gordon Gould, 28, who
has put more than $100,000 into the magazine _ its first
investment. On behalf of the magazine, Gould also organized a
conference last month at the New York Historical Society, where
Palm Pilot-toting new-media executives dined on sushi and were
invited to think beyond their business concerns to the social
implications of the Web and related media.
</P>
<P>
   David Bunnell, a West Coast technology publishing veteran who
attended the conference, said he came away bullish on the New York
new-media enclave and on The Silicon Alley Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What good magazines do is identify some kind of audience and
provide the members of that audience with a sense of membership and
belonging; and they've done that remarkably well,'' said Bunnell,
who runs the trade publication Upside. ``What they lack in
resources they make up for in enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   And as with the industry Calacanis covers, maturity shows signs
of tempering raw enthusiasm. One evening last week, dressed in
black with sunglasses atop his head, Calcanis made an appearance at
a SoHo courtyard party held by the Web ad-tracking company
I-Traffic. Six months ago he might have been carrying a camera to
snap the faces of his favorite entrepreneurs and their hangers-on.
But this time he said there would be no party report in his
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have other things to do; I have to write an analysis of the
Ticketmaster-City Search deal,'' he said, referring to last week's
announcement of a West Coast new-media merger. ``I have to get the
daily out. I have work to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
