<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTONGLOBE-MEDIA-ART     08-16 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTONGLOBE-MEDIA-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUROR OVER GLOBE COLUMNIST EXPOSES FAULT LINES IN BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the top of the first inning at Fenway Park on
Tuesday night, the city's man in the news made his way to his box
seats next to the Red Sox dugout. On either side, people who were
there said, fans cheered Mike Barnicle, the columnist for The
Boston Globe. Hands patted his back. Some well-wishers asked for
his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours before, Barnicle had endured a much less pleasant
encounter. He stood at a news conference and apologized to
colleagues for his ``sloppiness'' and ``creating embarrassment for
the paper'' after he used some jokes from comedian George Carlin in
a column without attributing them.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the well-wishers' reaction at Fenway, their guy
had won. Mike had kept his job. He had taken on the Globe's
management, defied its demand for his resignation. For a proud man,
a two-month suspension without pay was humiliating but a minor
victory nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will say that Barnicle, who is 54, does not matter
as much to Boston as he used to. Even so, he remains enough of a
figure to have turned a painful exercise in journalistic discipline
into a personal referendum, one more swaggering scene in the
long-running Boston drama of Us vs. Them.
</P>
<P>
   For working-class neighborhoods, the Globe has been Them. ``It's
an institution,'' said Carter Wilkie, an aide to Mayor Thomas
Menino, ``that has long been criticized as driven by elites, that
speaks to elites _ the progressive elites, representing the Puritan
tradition of civic responsibility. Mike is the voice of the
unrepentant, unapologetic common man.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, some people say that Barnicle, who grew up
working class himself in Fitchburg, has been an important link to
the blue-collar communities that felt the paper did not care about
them.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers take a slightly different tack, seeing the
columnist as a monument to a time when the city was locked in an
old battle of Yankees vs. Irish, Puritans vs. Catholics, a battle
that is part of the city's past and has little to do with its
high-technology, multiethnic present.
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of people in the city still see the newspaper, which
sends 473,000 copies around the city, state and New England every
weekday and nearly 750,000 on Sundays, as the voice of the elite,
of BMW-driving social engineers who send their children to private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   During the busing controversy of the 1970s, as J. Anthony Lukas
described it in his 1985 book ``Common Ground,'' the Globe became
so identified with the pro-busing forces that bullets were fired
into its lobby. Police snipers briefly hid on its roof.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, the newspaper, said former editor Michael
Janeway, was derided in working-class neighborhoods. It became for
those people ``the voice of some blind avenging abstract justice.
It was a justice located in the western suburbs, that had no
understanding for the feelings and dilemmas of the poor white
people of Boston,'' Janeway said.
</P>
<P>
   As Barnicle remembers the feelings of the white students, ``All
of them knew that graduation from South Boston High wasn't a ticket
to Harvard. If they were lucky they might get a union card. Who was
the Globe to tell them this was what should happen to them?''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1973, Barnicle, who had been an elevator operator in
the Cannon House Office Building and a low-level Democratic
political operative, caught the eye of the Globe's political
writer, Robert L. Healy. At his urging, Jack Driscoll, the editor
of The Evening Globe, looked at Barnicle's work.
</P>
<P>
   He had a strong voice, resonant to blue-collar readers even when
he was taking liberal positions they despised. As recounted in
``Common Ground,'' in the midst of the anti-busing rage in 1974, he
urged Edward M. Kennedy, the state's senior Senator, to speak to
angry demonstrators. ``You could tell them, senator, that law knows
no neighborhood, that justice is not confined to any one block,
that fear must be put aside and the fact of law adhered to.''
</P>
<P>
   His role, said Janeway, who joined the Globe in 1978, after the
busing crisis, was ``papering over busing's wound.'' He added,
``The symbolic importance of someone like Barnicle became
outsized.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle joined the morning newspaper when The Evening Globe
folded in 1985. He got into television. He sometimes got the
newspaper in trouble; over the years the newspaper has paid at
least $115,000 in two legal settlements as a result of his work,
according to two lawyers who have been briefed on the cases.
</P>
<P>
   But he made his voice heard. He wrote angrily about criminals
(``maggots'') and scathingly about political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a member of the state Legislature for six years,'' said
Tom Vallely, a close friend of Barnicle who is now director of the
Vietnam program at the Harvard Institute for International
Development. ``I represented a large part of the gay and lesbian
community. Mike Barnicle wrote an article ridiculing the gay pride
parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organizers came to me and said, `He's your friend. Will
you denounce him?' I said, `No. Mike Barnicle's unfair to everyone.
Including you.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Those attacked by Barnicle often attacked back. The Globe
defended him. But by 1991, when Boston Magazine was making
well-publicized and apparently futile efforts to find some of the
people he quoted, some colleagues wondered whether he cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all these rumors and rumblings about Barnicle, none
of them proven,'' Matthew Storin, the newspaper's editor, said
recently. When Storin was shown evidence in 1995 that another
columnist, Patricia Smith, was fabricating characters, he decided
to avoid an immediate confrontation with Ms. Smith. If she
acknowledged fabrication and resigned then, Storin said, he feared
``Barnicle would be caught up in the wake of that, and I wasn't
sure if I could save him, even if the charges had been unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the case of Barnicle, few reporters or editors brought
their suspicions to those in authority. ``It's my belief that his
work has never been scrutinized to the degree any other reporter's
work would be,'' said Sarah Snyder, an assistant metropolitan
editor. Barnicle and his editors deny that.
</P>
<P>
   For many people in the city, Barnicle's voice, sometimes maudlin
and sometimes pugnacious, had strong appeal. As Wilkie of the
mayor's office describes it, ``It's the voice of Archie Bunker vs.
the the voice of the church lady with her syrupy, self-righteous,
almost silly sense of order and rectitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the elites that Barnicle took swipes at were his
colleagues. In 1992, he wrote, ``missing a story seldom bothers
more than a handful around here,'' a moment recalled in an article
about Barnicle in the current issue of The Boston Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   His relations with the Globe's management were mercurial well
before The New York Times Co. bought the newspaper for $1.1 billion
in 1993. Editors like Thomas Winship sometimes rode herd on him and
sometimes indulged him, according to Winship and two other former
Globe editors, Janeway and Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, as a member of the Newspaper Guild, Barnicle was among
those offered a buyout. After he threatened to take it, saying he
was burned out, Driscoll, then the editor, gave him a three-month
leave without pay. He returned as an associate editor with a hefty
six-figure salary.
</P>
<P>
   The salary, a new office and his television celebrity friends
rankled colleagues who felt ``Boston Mike'' was nothing more than a
persona. ``I never got a sense of the deep hostility there is
apparently out there in the newsroom toward me,'' Barnicle said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He also has ardent newsroom loyalists, from Stan Grossfeld, the
Pulitzer-Prize-winning photographer, to telephone operators. The
sports-media critic Howard Manly, who admires Barnicle's knowledge
of the city, calls him ``a stand-up guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Globe, he has strong partisans, as the scene at
Fenway Park showed. And as Barnicle sees it, the Globe and his
partisans are on opposite sides of the city's cultural divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``As busing recedes into memory,'' he said, ``other social
issues and the Globe's position on them have taken busing's place
and added to the resentment. It has fairly liberal positions on
abortion, sexual preference, affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert S. Larkin Jr., a former managing editor who is the
Globe's vice president and assistant to the publisher, does not
believe Barnicle's old role still makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, he said, Barnicle ``did play the role of
someone who was the voice of the disenfranchised, the powerless.
But that simply is not something that works in the 1990s. A new
generation of leaders has emerged from different groups. The
managing editor of the Globe is an African-American man. Women have
a new voice in the city. The Latino population has a voice of its
own. We're clinging to the old model when the new model has formed
around us.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Barnicle and his partisans, the old model of Us vs. Them
was alive and well when Storin, feeling deceived over the jokes
column, demanded his resignation. This time, it was the people's
writer vs. irrationally rigid journalistic justice. The editors,
however, felt it was less a question of justice than of standards.
In a letter to readers in Sunday's paper, Storin said, ``Members of
my staff want to know that our journalistic standards are not being
compromised. They want to be held to the highest standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, who said Sunday that he ``respects'' Storin's
position, was not so understanding before last week's reprieve. At
that time, the man who once defused the resentment against the
Globe used it in his attack. The street guy also had powerful
advertisers and journalistic heavyweights on his side.
</P>
<P>
   After Barnicle led such a battle, it was inevitable that, when
Storin and Globe publisher Benjamin B. Taylor softened his
punishment to make it ``fit the crime,'' as they said, critics
contended they had retreated under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle survived as a columnist. But his old role may not have.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his colleagues were openly skeptical of his explanation
of the Carlin joke fiasco _ that he had not read the book ``Brain
Droppings'' but had gotten the jokes from friends. On Friday,
Barnicle said that these two friends now ``don't know that they
gave me the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't tell me the source of the jokes,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston Phoenix article, media writer Dan Kennedy said,
``Barnicle is still standing'' like a monument. ``But to what?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
