A6155 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-16 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
     By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     STAYING BUSY AFTER THE PRESIDENCY
<TEXT>
<P>
   He ``got drunk as a fiddle, showed that he could be profligate
as a lord. He fumbled Mrs. A., kissed the shrieking Miss B.,
pinched the plump Mrs. C. black and blue, and ran at Miss D. with
intent to ravish her,'' wrote the  &UR; Earl of Lytton &LR; , Viceroy of
India, after a visit from an American ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, after throwing all the ... female guests into
hysterics by generally behaving like a (musk) elephant, the noble
beast was captured by main force and carried (quatre pattes dans
l'air) by six sailors, which relieved India of his distinguished
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   The mannerly guest was  &UR; Ulysses Grant &LR; . The Earl's comments are
quoted in the Oxford Book of British Political Anecdotes, mined for
Personals by  &UR; Francis Rigney &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING AROUND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The Civil Aviation Authority of England is investigating a
July 26 incident in which dignitaries including  &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR; 
and  &UR; Prince Philip &LR; , gathered for a polo tournament at Windsor,
were rained upon by excrement, presumably falling from passing
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor Castle is near Heathrow airport. According to the CAA
report, quoted in the Telegraph: ``Numerous brown, foul-smelling,
pellets fell into the area. Reporter confirms five similar
incidents in last 10 days.'' A spokesman for Buckingham Palace said
the Queen was unaware of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   - Body-watchers reluctant to leave their scales at home when
they go on vacation will be pleased to learn of Body Logic, a
portable handheld body fat analyzer. This gizmo sends a minor jolt
of electric current into the user, then measures the body's
resistance as the current flows through it. Its manufacturers say
it can be used wherever you go. (Elsewhere in the world of fitness
fanatics, at Second and Folsom streets the other day,
 &UR; Kate Gunnison &LR;  overheard a speed-walking dog owner instructing her
lagging pooch in a stern voice: ``Just shake it off, come on, just
shake it off.'')
</P>
<P>
   - Reading of last week's strict Japanese hotel rules,  &UR; Lori &LR; 
 &UR; Heathorn &LR;  forwards suggestions from a sign in her hotel in
Kusadasi, Turkey, less remarkable for its mangling of English (for
who among us can speak Turkish?) than its relaxed attitude: ``If
the floor is not traversable, close the door and cover door-graps
whit wet cloths. From your window attract the attention of the
rescue party on no account. Attempt to desend from your room by
rope.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WRITTEN ON THE SKIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Madame Chinchilla &LR; , proprietor of the Triangle Tattoo and
Museum, was recently host to a film crew from ABC/Kane TV that was
shooting a documentary for the Discovery Channel. Madame
Chinchilla's mother, 72-year-old  &UR; Morningstar &LR; , was the star model,
having been filmed receiving her sixth tattoo.
</P>
