<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLS-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-16 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: STRIKES RAISE KEY ISSUES OF HOW BELLS CAN COMPETE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AT&AMP;T-TCI-GREENTHAL) 
(js) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock of Bell Atlantic Corp. has lost 11.8 percent of its
value since Aug. 3, when the 73,000 of its employees who are
represented by the Communications Workers of America authorized the
union to call the strike that began the next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, shares of the other four local Bell
telephone companies _ each with their own big union contingents _
have declined by an average of 3.8 percent. While three of them _
Ameritech, BellSouth and SBC Communications _ have signed new labor
contracts since last spring, about 34,000 union workers at U S West
walked off the job early Sunday after failing to reach an accord
over contract issues that include a new performance-based pay
structure.
</P>
<P>
   It was not surprising that Bell Atlantic's shareholders showed
signs of being spooked before the strike. More intriguing was that
investors showed no sign of relief even after workers returned to
their jobs last Tuesday after a two-day walkout. The company's
stock remained essentially flat for the rest of the week, closing
at $41.125 on Friday, down $1.8125. Nor, with U S West's labor
situation unsettled, have the shares of the other Bells rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the stock market's broad downturn, of course, there
may be no need to read labor implications into the dip of the Bell
shares. But strikes, or even the threat of them, raise important
questions about the Bells' ability to compete in the $200 billion
telecommunications industry _ a business where they will try to
move beyond conventional local service to offer long-distance and
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, a key victory for the communications workers at
Bell Atlantic was the union's securing rights to install and
maintain sophisticated new data networks, limiting the company's
ability to use lower-paid nonunion labor for such work.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into this future marketplace, where few of their rivals
are unionized, the Bells will carry a significant labor legacy.
According to the Communications Workers of America, overall union
representation, including the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, at each of the five Bells is an average of 60.7
percent of the work force. Meanwhile, among the companies with
which the Bells will be competing _ alternative local carriers,
long-distance companies, Internet service providers and cable
companies _ only  &UR; AT&AMP;T &LR;  Corp.has a large union work force.
</P>
<P>
   All of this raises key questions. Do their large proportions of
union workers put the Bells at a long-term disadvantage in a
brutally competitive market where almost all of the other players
use mostly nonunion labor? And even if labor costs end up
representing only a fraction of the Bells' business costs, will the
need to negotiate new ways of operating with a big union hamper the
companies' ability to move nimbly in a fast-changing environment?
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic executives refused to discuss these matters last
week. But the issues seem unlikely to go away. True, labor issues
will probably not be the defining factor in the fate of the
regional Bells over the next few years. More influential will be
technological change, regulatory shifts and corporate takeovers.
And as Frank Governali, the head telecommunications analyst for
Credit Suisse First Boston, pointed out, good, creative management
can almost always trump potentially problematic labor questions.
But that management burden will undoubtedly be higher on the
leaders of the Bells than on their counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   And it cannot help but be an issue for the big corporate
customers who will have an expanding choice of service providers.
In awarding contracts, how do they factor in the potential costs of
a strike like Bell Atlantic's, in which installations and repairs
were simply not performed. Corporate communications managers might
ponder: This time the strike was only two days, but what if next
time it's two weeks? Or two months? Or four months, as with Nynex
Corp.in 1989?
</P>
<P>
   Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America,
said that his union's power actually provided a competitive
advantage to the unionized communications companies because they
offer customers a more knowledgeable, better trained work force.
``All the empirical evidence indicates that the best continuous
education programs for workers are in union shops,'' Bahr said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before the U S West strike began, Jerry Brown, a
company spokesman, said that the union provided an efficient way
for management to communicate goals and strategies to its workers.
Yet, he also said that the main sticking point in the talks was the
company's plan to link more of a worker's pay to performance _
which, of course, tends to be the way pay is set in nonunion
workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Such sticking points can only grow more important as competition
heats up in the industry, in the view of Eric Strumingher, a
telecommunications analyst at Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short term, what's going to happen over the next three years,
I don't think labor's a major issue,'' Strumingher said. ``But on a
longer-term issue, and once the marketplace stabilizes and
everything evens out a bit, then we will get down to who has a low
operating-cost structure. The Bells are going to have some
questions to answer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WRESTLING-MEDIA-AR     08-16 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WRESTLING-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE AND NETWORKS CLINCH OVER WRESTLING AD REVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jay Leno, NBC's biggest late-night television star, climbed into
an outdoor ring in Sturges, S.D., on the evening of Aug. 8 and
threw himself into an increasingly ferocious wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the one with Hulk Hogan that Leno and his tag-team
partner Diamond Dallas Page ``won'' in a pay-per-view event staged
by World Championship Wrestling. That one, like all professional
wrestling matches, was only as ferocious as the script allowed.
</P>
<P>
   But in twisting Hogan's arm behind his back and making him howl
for mercy, Leno did become a participant in a wrestling match that
really is for blood: the one between broadcast television and cable
television over millions of dollars in advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast networks became far more concerned about
advertising money flowing to cable this last spring, when for the
first time in several years total money committed to the network's
fall programing lineups declined, from about $6.1 billion last year
to about $6 billion this year. Cable, meanwhile, is projecting an
increase, from about $2.25 billion last year to about $2.8 billion
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling got in the middle of this high-stakes face-off because
weekly wrestling shows on three cable channels have become the
dominant hits of cable television. The cable channels with
wrestling shows, TNT, TBS and USA, are increasingly using this fact
to try to pry more revenue from advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives, meanwhile, are trying, with some forced
subtlety, to reference the stereotype of the wrestling audience _
lower-income, under-educated _ as a reason why cable is not a place
premium advertisers ought to want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Though network executives, not wanting to look like snobs who
are writing off a segment of the American population, never overtly
cite the wrestling audience as an undesirable lot. Nevertheless,
they went out of their way during presentations of their new
programing to advertisers last spring to denigrate cable for its
heavy diet of full nelsons.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, a unit of Walt Disney Co., bought full-page ads in several
newspapers asking advertisers ``wrestling with their mix,'' who
might be ``thinking of shifting ad dollars from broadcast to
cable'' to check out the list of top 15 shows on cable: eight of
them (highlighted in capital letters by ABC) were wrestling shows.
</P>
<P>
   Leno's own network, NBC, which is owned by General Electric,
made much the same point when Don Ohlmeyer, president of the
network's west coast division, noted the prevalence of wrestling
among cable's most popular shows and suggested advertisers would be
getting ``the Gorgeous George Network _ all Hulk Hogan all the
time'' _ if they switched money into cable.
</P>
<P>
   The cable networks who program the bulk of cable wrestling are
not taking these comments lying on the mat. If anything, years of
frustration in finding respect _ and the ad money that goes with it
_ for wrestling have only increased the goal of stealing as much
money as they can from the networks.
</P>
<P>
   The cable networks point to statistics showing enormous numbers
of viewers _ especially young men _ tuning in to wrestling on a
regular basis. ``Between the two networks, 35 million viewers a
week are watching some portion of the wrestling shows every week,''
said Barry Koch, vice president for research at TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Hammer, senior vice president of original production for
USA Networks Inc., said that on a weekly basis, the big wrestling
shows on the two channels on Monday nights reach ``more men between
the ages of 18 and 49 than shows like `Law and Order,' `NYPD Blue,'
`Homicide,' `Third Rock From the Sun' and `Spin City.'''
</P>
<P>
   In order to achieve these impressive numbers, the cable
executives are comparing five hours on two channels with individual
half hours and hours on the networks. But the fact that the
audience for wrestling is young, male and growing is not in
dispute. And those three factors almost always add up to increased
commitment from advertisers because young men are among the hardest
viewers for advertisers to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither network would cite specific revenue totals for
wrestling, Joe Uva, president of sales for Turner Entertainment, a
unit of Time Warner Inc., said that since 1994, ``revenues for
wrestling have increased tenfold.'' And Tim Brooks, senior vice
president of research for USA Networks, said that commercials in
wrestling that had once sold for as little as $5,000 are now
bringing in as much as $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Siegel, president of TNT, said, with a note of resentment
in his voice, that he had ``been out pounding the pavement for
three years'' trying to stir advertisers to put more money into
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed some bitterness that he was being asked about how
successful wrestling is becoming only after the networks started to
take on wrestling's popularity and a mainstream star like Leno
chose to participate in an event. ``ABC's full-page ad was borne of
ignorance,'' Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited deals with advertisers like Pepsi, which after a lot of
effort, committed to a long-term deal for its Mug root beer, as
evidence that higher-profile advertisers were starting to accept
the value of wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Uva cited other new advertisers who have put money into
wrestling, including Procter &AMP; Gamble, MCI Communications and
numerous movie companies. ``We used to mainly have advertisers like
motor oil and do-it-yourself companies,'' Uva said.
</P>
<P>
   The cable executives are emphasizing the growth of wrestling's
popularity beyond what was thought to be its base: rural areas of
the South and Midwest. Now, Siegel said, there are wrestling
viewing clubs on colleges like the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and the University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a limit to the kind of advertisers that the
wrestling shows can reach, and that may be where the broadcast
networks look to score points.
</P>
<P>
   In several demographic categories that networks use to elicit
premium prices from advertisers, wrestling does not seem to have
shed what Siegel labeled a ``stigma that it's a lower-income,
lower-educated phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the wrestling shows are short of competitive in
three audience breakdowns frequently employed by network salesmen:
homes with a professional or manager as head of household, homes
with a college graduate with $50,000-plus income and households of
$75,000-plus income.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, shows bring in the extra advertising dollars when
they can score more than 100 per cent in the index for attracting
homes in those three categories. For example, ``Monday Night
Football,'' which is broadcast head-to-head with the highest-rated
wrestling shows in the fall, scores 126 in the professional and
manager category and 133 in homes with more than $75,000 in income.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling shows, meanwhile, never come close to a 100 score
in any category and sometimes fall into the 40s or even 30s. Koch,
the head of research for Turner, acknowledged these results and
said, ``We're not selling an upscale audience.'' Brooks, the head
of research for USA, said that wrestling needs to be sold to
advertisers of ``mass market products,'' not high-priced items like
BMW automobiles. ``You don't sell a Beamer to people watching
wrestling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said that the wrestling shows on the two Turner channels
have consciously set out to expand the traditional audience for
wrestling by making it ``family entertainment.'' Thus, wrestling
long ago abandoned any pretense of being a sports event. As he put
it, ``it's a soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bischoff, president of World Championship Wrestling (when
he's not wrestling against Jay Leno as he did a week ago), talks
openly of ``creating the soap storyline.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea to involve Leno arose, he said, after Hogan made an
appearance on the ``Tonight'' show and his segment did especially
well in the ratings. So much for sniffing at the low-brow wrestling
audience: ``Tonight'' executives started calling, Bischoff said,
looking to find some wrestling role for Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Bischoff said he came up with a storyline that started off with
a faked takeover of Leno's set one night by Hogan and Bischoff,
leading to a challenge to settle it in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   For Leno, who donated his entire fee (which he said would
surpass $1 million) to charity, all of this was about ``having a
little fun in the summer when everything else is dead.'' He said,
``It's no different from going to Disneyland, with all these funny
characters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
