<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLERKIDS-LAWYERS-1     08-16 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLERKIDS-LAWYERS-1,145(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS FACE UNIQUE OBSTACLES IN DEFENDING CHILDREN ACCUSED OF
VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As a lawyer for the likes of Rodney King, Latrell
Sprewell and Tupac Shakur, John Burris has experience handling
difficult, highly charged cases. But Burris, a prominent California
lawyer, wondered if he had met his match with a client he agreed to
defend two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The client, accused of attempted murder, whiled away strategy
sessions playing with Batman toys and action figures. In court,
Burris recalled, ``he would draw, he would get in his mother's lap,
he would sleep, he would make funny faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris found himself struggling with how to best represent his
client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communicating with a 6-year-old about legal matters is
impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first-grader was charged with trying to kill a neighbor's
newborn baby by dumping the infant out of his bassinet and
punching, kicking and beating him with a stick. In defending the
boy, Burris became one of a relative handful of lawyers
representing young children accused of deadly crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It is a world of unexplored legal ground, raising a battery of
questions for defense lawyers. Do young children always understand
the charges against them? Can they assist in their own defense?
What happens when parents and lawyers have different definitions of
the child's best interest? If children are too young for juvenile
detention centers, where should they be held? If they confess to
crimes, have they knowingly waived their right to remain silent?
</P>
<P>
   Issues like this came to the fore again last week when two
Chicago boys, ages 7 and 8, were charged with murdering an
11-year-old girl, Ryan Harris, in an apparent attempt to take her
bicycle. Police officials said the boys began throwing rocks and
struck Ryan in the head, causing her to fall off her bicycle,
knocking her unconscious and fracturing her skull. They said at
least one of the boys then molested her with a tubular object, and
suffocated her to death by stuffing her panties in her mouth and
leaves and grass in her nostrils.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the arrests, defense lawyers have challenged
confessions the police said they obtained from the boys. The
lawyers have complained that parents were not in the room when the
boys were being interviewed and argued that the boys were incapable
of waiving their Miranda rights.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, faced with an Illinois law that bars children
under 10 from being confined in a locked facility, and reports from
psychological experts that the boys did not seem dangerous, a
Juvenile Court judge forged a Solomonic solution. He allowed the
boys to go home with their parents, but ordered them to stay inside
at all times and to wear electronic monitoring bracelets on their
ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Cases like this are uncharted territory, said Robert Schwartz,
executive director of the Juvenile Law Center, a nonprofit legal
service in Philadelphia that represents abused children and
children charged with crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know a whole lot about kids who kill at this age
because there aren't a whole lot of them,'' he said. ``It's not
like kids who set fires, or kid sex offenders, where we know there
are certain patterns. These cases are all different _ in age,
premeditation, the weapon that's used.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the scarcity of meaningful precedents, defense lawyers in
these cases are feeling their way.
</P>
<P>
   Burris, a well-known Oakland civil rights lawyer, said that for
a meeting with his young defendant, he brought in his 8-year-old
son's toys, ``rolled up my sleeves and got on the floor and sought
to communicate that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the boy knock an action figure down and pop it right up
again, Burris said he could tell the boy had no sense of the
permanence of death. He also said his client ``never understood who
I was. It took him a long time to call me Burris. I was the talking
tall man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gagen, who represents 11-year-old Joshua Almaguer-Mendez,
charged with killing his 13-year-old neighbor by firing a rifle out
his bedroom window in Antioch, Calif., in June, consulted the
priest in his client's church, who ``came in and talked to Josh
about how it was important to talk to me, and I was a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has had some practice with children accused in killings,
with eight cases in the last 25 years involving children younger
than 11, including the 1994 case of two boys, ages 10 and 11,
accused of dropping a 5-year-old from the 14th floor of a housing
project.
</P>
<P>
   Darron Bowden, until recently the supervising attorney in the
Cook County Public Defender's juvenile criminal division, said
lawyers in his office have used stick figures and sports analogies
(``our team, their team''), and drawn on their own experiences
raising children. Bowden, now in charge of the civil division, says
he tries to involve the child as much as possible with his own
defense, using whatever knowledge the child has. For example, the
child or his family might be able to lead the lawyer to witnesses
who have been identified only by their street names.
</P>
<P>
   To find out more about a client who might be too young to
describe himself, lawyers talk to teachers, coaches, even Cub Scout
leaders, as they try to understand how to frame the child's defense
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Often, defense lawyers wrestle with whether to claim their young
clients are incompetent. There are, first of all, gradations of
competence. Does the child understand right from wrong? Does he
understand that shooting a gun can kill someone? Does he understand
what it means to be on trial?
</P>
<P>
   Burris chose to argue incompetence for the 6-year-old from the
San Francisco suburb of Richmond, convinced that, even though the
charges were reduced to assault with great bodily injury, it was
best to ``get him out of the criminal justice component of the
system.'' A juvenile court referee agreed in July 1996, three
months after the charges were filed, and since then the boy has
been receiving treatment and other social services, Burris said.
</P>
<P>
   Gagen considered taking the same tack with Joshua, but he was
concerned about the time it would involve: weeks for psychiatric
evaluations, months or years in treatment, and, under California
law, the possibility of facing criminal charges once he was deemed
competent (a risk Burris' client also faces). For children this
young, he and other lawyers said, weeks can seem like eons, so
lawyers try to move the cases along as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 10, Joshua was convicted of a lesser charge, involuntary
manslaughter. But Gagen said he was never entirely convinced that
his client understood the magnitude of the legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't one occasion in a 10-day trial when he leaned
over and asked me something or complimented me about something or
expressed any anger,'' Gagen said. ``I didn't see much interest in
`Are we winning or losing? What are those witnesses saying or our
witnesses saying?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   William Lansat's client, Nathaniel Abraham, has already been
found competent to stand trial as an adult for fatally shooting an
18-year-old in Pontiac, Mich., last year, when Nathaniel was 11.
Lansat said he was considering a plea of diminished capacity,
claiming that Nathaniel could not have formed the intent to kill
and drawing on evaluations that he says show Nathaniel functions at
the level of a child three to five years younger.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, defense lawyers have trouble dealing with a child's
parents, who may disagree with the lawyer's strategy or may even
wind up unwilling accomplices to a defense that claims the child's
problems were due to parental abuse or neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these parents come in and say, `Find my kid guilty. I
want to get him help.''' Lansat said. ``They don't understand that
the role of an attorney is to represent the client.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris came to believe early on that his client should not be
returned to his parents, something the boy's mother, naturally,
objected to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where were my loyalties here?'' he said he asked himself. ``I
could talk to the mother and the granddad, but I couldn't really
talk to the child.'' He ultimately succeeded in having the child
placed elsewhere. ``In terms of the gravity of what had happened, I
thought it was clear there was something wrong with that
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Howard, the lawyer for Mitchell Johnson, who pleaded guilty
last week to the school shootings in Jonesboro, Ark., a crime
committed at 13, said he had a difficult time with Mitchell's
parents, who are divorced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was constant friction between the two, and I was pretty
much in the middle,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Once in court, some lawyers try to showcase the youth of their
clients. The private lawyers defending the 8-year-old charged in
the Ryan Harris case stood him on a chair when one witness was
testifying and, on Thursday, brought a physician's scale into the
courtroom, propped the boy on it, and suggested that a child of 56
pounds and 4 feet 2 1/2 inches could not have committed such a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Bowden, are wary of going overboard. Often, he
said, a member of the public defender's staff is assigned the job
of calming, distracting and comforting the child in the courtroom.
The lawyers in the Ryan Harris case have kept both boys occupied
with toy cars, candy and coloring books.
</P>
<P>
   Most defense lawyers seek to avoid having their young clients
testify, fearing they could be ``pinned down by the rapid-fire
questions of the prosecutor,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these children are too young to be tried in adult court,
even under a rash of new state laws that have lowered the minimum
age. But defense lawyers say that as a result of recent
high-profile juvenile crimes, one of the main official distinctions
between juvenile and adult criminal proceedings _ that the approach
in adult court is adversarial, while juvenile court takes a more
collaborative route to a resolution _ has become a myth when
serious crimes are involved. Juvenile prosecutors are under
pressure to exact a tough price for an egregious crime.
</P>
<P>
   And, Bowden said, ``when you've got a kid who's incarcerated
looking down the barrel of some heavy-duty time, it's everything
but non-adversarial.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These lawyers say the crucial difference with juvenile court is
that there is usually a judge instead of a jury and that juvenile
court judges have broad discretion in sentencing. And sentencing,
the lawyers say, is a crucial phase, as they try to convince a
judge that locking up a child for his impressionable adolescence
would not be in anyone's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``With older kids, they tell you `I did three years. I did the
crime.' They develop a philosophy,'' Schwartz said. ``The
7-year-old doesn't develop a philosophy. We have to worry about the
short-term and the long-term issues. Coming out of institutions
today are kids who we put away five or 10 years ago because we
thought they would be a danger to themselves or others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
