<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC- &UR; BC-COX-CLINTON-1stLE     08-16 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-1stLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT FACES HISTORIC ENCOUNTER WITH GRAND JURY
</HEADLINE>
 BC- 
 Appends 2 graf shirttail describing Clinton day  By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Monday faces the painful
prospect of becoming the first chief executive in U.S. history to
testify to a grand jury as the primary target of a criminal
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   He spent much of Sunday preparing for his historic encounter
with independent counsel Kenneth Starr, who is weighing possible
perjury and obstruction of justice charges against him that could
in turn lead to an impeachment inquiry by Congress in the fall.
Starr's questions are likely to delve into the most intimate
details of the president's extra-marital sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who turns 52 on Wednesday, has pledged to testify
``completely and truthfully,'' via a secure one-way closed-circuit
video link, about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, 25, the
former White House intern who earlier this month went before the
same 23 grand jurors under a broad grant of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sen. Orrin Hatch, the Republican chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee, again urged Clinton to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   As he put it on NBC's Meet the Press: ``If he does that and then
really asks the American people to forgive him or at least work
with him, I think the polling shows that the American people
probably are willing to allow him to finish out his term and wait
to replace him until the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Hatch added, ``if he lies before the grand jury, that would
be grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes session with Starr and his prosecutorial team is
expected to begin at about 1 p.m. (EDT) and consume much of the
afternoon. It will take place in the Map Room of the White House,
where Franklin Roosevelt once followed the course of World War II
and where Clinton sipped coffee with wealthy backers in building a
huge political war chest for his 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Michael McCurry told reporters that
Clinton would probably make a televised appearance after his
testimony to the grand jurors, who will be at the federal
courthouse, 12 blocks away down Pennsylvania Avenue, watching on
large color monitors. He will then leave for a two-week vacation at
Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton evaluated his embarrassing legal and political
problems with his wife Hillary and with a tight circle of lawyers,
the president's official aides and friends were spinning various
scenarios of just how his responses on Monday might differ from
what he said when the scandal first broke last January.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Clinton emphatically denied having any kind of
``improper'' relationship with Lewinsky and, specifically, of
having ``sexual relations with that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent effort to dampen such scenarios, David Kendall,
Clinton's chief private lawyer, issued a rare statement stating:
``There is apparently an enormous amount of groundless speculation
about the president's testimony tomorrow. The truth is the truth --
period. And that is how the president will testify.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached with Starr last month, Kendall will
accompany Clinton when he testifies to the grand jury, a privilege
not normally available to witnesses. In agreeing to appear, Clinton
has waived his constitutional protection against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kendall, Clinton will have access in the
ground-floor Map Room to Nicole Seligman, a Kendall associate, and
to White House counsel Charles Ruff. Along with the first lady, it
is only this group that knows how the Clinton will deal with his
extraordinary interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not diminish a rash of conjecture that the
president was about to change his story after nearly seven months
and admit to having a sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has already queried everyone from Linda Tripp, who taped
20 hours of conversations with Lewinsky, to several dozen Secret
Service agents who protect Clinton, to the president's closest
confidants. Lewinsky, who worked at the White House as an intern
from July 1995 to April 1996, visited the White House on 37
occasions after April 1996, most recently in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Clinton tells the grand jurors, his testimony almost
certainly will not put an end to his woes. Congress is due to
receive a secret report from Starr, probably in September, which
will be referred to the House Judiciary Committee. That panel must
then decide whether to hold an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his grand jury preparations, Sunday appeared to be a
normal day for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Arm-in-arm with his wife and Bible in hand, he went to church
with his wife. Later in the day, he was briefed by his national
security team, which is tracking situations in Northern Ireland,
where 28 people were killed Saturday in a car bombing, and in
Africa, where civil unrest raged in Congo and investigations
continued into embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania.
 &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
