<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A soaking rain will accompany low pressure tracking through the
Middle Atlantic States on Monday. The area of rain, which will
contain a few embedded thunderstorms, will spread from Pennsylvania
Monday morning to southeast New England by afternoon. In general,
rainfall tallies will average near one-half inch, though higher
amounts will occur locally. Scattered thunderstorms will also erupt
in the Southeast near the Appalachians as a jet stream disturbance
passing overhead lifts very sultry air enveloping the region.
Intervals of clouds and sunshine and spotty thunderstorms will
cover the remainder of the Southeast, including Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine will boost daytime readings to near 100
degrees from northern Texas to western Kansas while temperatures
hold near 90 degrees in the central Rio Grande Valley as a cluster
of showers and thunderstorms crosses the region.
</P>
<P>
   A broken line of strong thunderstorms will precede a cold front
advancing through the Middle West. Behind the front, cooler and
drier air will spread into the upper Mississippi Valley. Farther
west, brisk winds gliding up the sloping terrain will fuel a
cluster of potent storms in eastern Montana and the western
Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   Gray and cool weather will persist in northern sections of the
coastal Northwest while California stays mainly sunny and hot,
except for the coast where patchy clouds and cooler conditions will
occur. Ample sunshine will be seen in the interior West with
isolated afternoon storms in many of the mountains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Shower Cycle  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A lattice work of fog covered parts of southern Georgia and
Alabama on Sunday morning. The lower part of the atmosphere was
rather sultry. Afternoon thunderstorms seemed certain like previous
days, but the pattern of where they would first form was already
spelled out by the cloud configuration. A few slivers of clear sky
would give a head start to the day's heating, and cumulus clouds
initially grew over the clear patches. As the day progressed, these
billowy clouds became the first storms, but the areas that stayed
foggy the longest escaped the cycle of thundershowers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
