<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVENGERS-COX     08-16 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVENGERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uma's Emma, `Avengers' slip on a Peel
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Avengers''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ralph Fiennes, Uma Thurman, Sean Connery. Directed by
Jeremiah Chechik. Rated PG-13 for action violence and some
innuendo. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Mrs. Peel, we're in need of a script doctor. And
another Mrs. Peel.
</P>
<P>
   In between sips of champagne and civilized quips, secret agents
John Steed (Ralph Fiennes) and Mrs. Emma Peel (Uma Thurman) foil
criminal masterminds plotting against the British government. It's
a shame Hollywood can't hire this pair to track down the Warner
Bros. executives responsible for churning out such expensive,
idiotic movies as ``Batman &AMP; Robin,'' ``The Postman'' and
``Sphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the studio's ominous decision not to show the film to
critics in time for Friday's opening, ``The Avengers'' isn't a
stink bomb. At least visually, it pays witty homage to the '60s
British TV series' vein of Carnaby Street surrealism. The flick
unreels in picture-postcard England dappled with the damndest
sights: a boardroom full of men dressed in teddy bear costumes, a
proper nanny who whips knives out of her baby carriage and, of
course, Thurman in leather.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a talent at filling out a catsuit, Thurman is one of
the movie's two big problems. The chief fault: a half-baked script
by Don MacPherson. He also wrote ``Absolute Beginners,'' another
movie long on style but lacking narrative coherence or momentum.
Same goes with ``The Avengers,'' which has Mrs. Peel and Steed
battling Sir August de Wynter (Sean Connery, looking slightly
embarrassed), who has found a way to control the weather. The plot
is less engrossing than it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   MacPherson has watched too many bad American action films,
emulating their lame puns and Schwarzenegger-style taglines. A few
examples: Poor Connery has to say things like ``Rain or shine, all
is mine'' or offer howlingly lame bits of innuendo. As they wander
through a dripping hothouse, he coos to Thurman, ``One should never
fear being wet.'' So what's wrong with Thurman? Easy. She's trumped
by the cool, feline memory of Diana Rigg, who originated the role.
Remember: Mrs. Peel does not sweat. Mrs. Peel does not lose her
cool. Mrs. Peel does not appear unkempt, ever. Thurman manages to
do all three while struggling with her British accent. Perhaps she
never watched Rigg, wanting to make the part ``her own.'' Forget
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Like Thurman, the movie flubs things that made the TV series a
gas. Steed and Mrs. Peel were the prototypes for Mulder and Scully.
They had no personal lives to speak of, lived only for their work,
and shared a relationship that was teasingly ambiguous. Like ``The
X-Files'' movie, ``The Avengers'' film addresses that issue by
tossing in a kiss that flattens the champagne.
</P>
<P>
   And while Thurman works too hard, Fiennes underplays his role to
the point of fading into the wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
