<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOWERS-COX     08-16 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowers facing murder charge for 5th time
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Two people who will encounter each other at
the Hattiesburg courthouse today have met in this court before and
both probably are hoping that after all the years this will be the
last time.
</P>
<P>
   One is Ellie Dahmer, widow of Vernon Dahmer, who was a grocer,
farmer and highly-respected NAACP leader during the civil rights
era. Dahmer died 32 years ago protecting his family from carloads
of Ku Klux Klansmen who attacked his house with shotguns and
firebombs.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Sam Bowers, who stands accused_for the fifth time_
of ordering the attack. The former imperial wizard of the White
Knights of the KKK has been free on $200,000 bond since his arrest
in May; he will drive from his home in Laurel Monday to face murder
charges one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible thing we have to remember,'' Ellie Dahmer
said. ``But we've been preparing ourselves for 32 years, trying to
get here.''
</P>
<P>
   New witnesses_repentant former Klansmen_provided the Forrest
County District Attorney's Office with enough evidence to indict
Bowers in the 32-year-old crime. Bowers was tried in connection
with the Dahmer attack three times in state court and once in
federal court in 1968 and 1969. All the juries deadlocked and the
courts declared mistrials. Records from the racist spy group, the
Sovereignty Commission, made public for the first time this year,
indicated Bowers had tampered with the juries in some of those
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case that's an unsolved mystery,'' said Lee
Martin, special assistant to the state Attorney General, who will
help try the case. ``We know Bowers is responsible for this.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot has happened since the night Ellie Dahmer's world changed
forever, the night Sam Bowers's life attached itself to hers.
</P>
<P>
   Ellie Dahmer was once a mother of eight who spent the 1960s
sleeping in shifts. She and her husband didn't dare sleep at the
same time, for fear of an attack. But, for some reason, on the
January night the Klan showed up, they were both asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 73-year-old widow lives on the exact spot where the
attack took place, in a house rebuilt in 1967 by the Hattiesburg
Chamber of Commerce. Five of her children live near her on the
Dahmer property, land she doesn't dare let anyone but family have.
She works as an election official, a position given to her twice by
the voters of Forrest County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-two years ago, I couldn't have had this position,
because I couldn't vote,'' she said. Her husband was killed days
after he announced he would help black people register to vote by
collecting poll taxes at his store. ``There's been a lot of changes
in Mississippi. Blacks are treated like people now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, Bowers headed an organization dedicated to
preventing blacks from voting or having any of the other rights
that white Mississippians took for granted. The FBI has blamed his
group for 10 killings and dozens of church bombings, beatings and
cross burnings. His philosophy at the time, he has said, was that
he was waging a holy war against communists and blacks bent on
destroying Christian, Anglo-Saxon Mississippians.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers was convicted of conspiracy in a federal court for the
1964 murders of civil rights workers Michael Schwerner, Andrew
Goodman and James Chaney in Philadelphia, Miss. He served six years
in a federal prison in Washington state, and was released in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 73, Bowers is a reclusive businessman with a
mysterious smirk_ is he wincing or holding back a smile?_who leases
out-of-date video games and pinball machines. He lives and works
where he always has, in a squat, sprawling brown warehouse on the
other side of the tracks from downtown Laurel and the Victorian
houses on the hill. He teaches Sunday school. A hero of his is
Mickey Mouse. Last week in court, where the judge in this case
heard and denied his motion to dismiss the charges for lack of due
process, Bowers wore a Mickey Mouse belt, tie and pin on the lapel
of his seersucker suit. Last month, he told those present at
another hearing that Mickey Mouse was a militant. In one cartoon,
the Disney character uses a net to capture U.S. government planes,
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Bowers' neighborhood has become mostly black.
Most of the former wizard's customers are black owners of bars and
cafes along Maple Street. He eats lunch every day at Marie's, a
black-owned cafe. His philosophy today is a mystery. He speaks to
few people, and shuns all media, whom he once called ``whores.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too young to remember all that, but I think if he done
it, he should have to pay for it,'' said Bill Sykes, who is white
and runs an appliance repair shop a few doors down from Bowers.
Sykes rents a video machine from Bowers for his laundromat, but
wishes he didn't have to. ``My wife is black and she didn't want me
doing business with him. And his machines are all old, but I can't
find someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Sykes represents change in Mississippi. He says he and his wife
get stared at, but no one threatens them, as they might have back
then.
</P>
<P>
   The older generation is more reticent to bring up race or talk
about the past; having lived through a time when race was a bloody
battlefield, it's harder for them to talk about it now, even if
times have changed. Bill Sykes's father, Dodd, a grocery store
owner who lived through the era when Bowers wore a hood and the
races didn't mix, had nothing to say about the trial that starts
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a working man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And a 52-year-old black man, the Rev. Joe Boykin, who was
shopping at Dodd's store, said people should forget about the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to just let him go,'' he said of Bowers. ``It's in
the past, people's minds is different now. There's no sense in
digging something up from that long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ezekiel Chambers, a younger black man, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he needs to go to trial and get punished for what he
did,'' he said. ``That should have happened 30 years ago. He's been
walking around free all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped talking and watched a 1961 powder blue Ford Falcon
round a corner. It was Bowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he is now,'' he said. ``Talk about the devil and you'll
see the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in the 1990s that Mississippi
prosecutors have used new evidence to resurrect the state's past.
In 1994, Byron de la Beckwith was convicted of assassinating NAACP
worker Medgar Evers in 1963. Beckwith, who is spending his final
days in the Rankin County prison, was tried twice in the '60s, but
all-white juries deadlocked, as they did in the Bowers trials.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Beckwith case that inspired the Dahmers to push the
Forrest County D.A. to look anew at the Vernon Dahmer slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be tried in the same courtroom where Bowers stood
trial three times before. It has been renovated in the last decade,
but the Jim Crow, blacks-only balconies remain, although now the
press usually sits there.
</P>
<P>
   Several Klansmen who participated in the attack were convicted
in the 1960s. Two Klansmen who were not convicted, Devours Nix, 72,
and Charles Noble, 55, were arrested the same day last spring as
Bowers. Nix was released on his own recognizance because he has
cancer and said he was too ill to sit in jail, but he was arrested
again a few weeks later when he was caught playing golf. Nix and
Noble are out on bond and will go to trial this fall.
</P>
<P>
   For the prosecution, these cases are about the Dahmers more than
they are about Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family lost a husband and a father, when in the middle of
the night, two carloads of cowards come and burn and shoot up his
house and kill him,'' said Martin, the assistant attorney general.
``They are a family of great integrity. They're not bent on
revenge. They just want justice. If somebody killed my daddy, I'd
be real hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Helfrich, the assistant Forrest County D.A., has an even
deeper personal sympathy for the Dahmer family.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad also died in 1966, of cancer, and I think of him almost
daily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also sees the larger implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is some of Mississippi's past that needs to be
cleansed,'' he said. ``It's very difficult to resurrect a case
that's 32 years old. There are no transcripts from the Bowers
trials because they ended in hung juries. And some people do not
want to remember. There are those who feel we shouldn't bring up
the past. But I'm sure if it was their father, they'd feel
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
