<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN15-COX     08-16 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bid even Huizengamighty can't refuse
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The promise made in this space on May 25
of this year _ my personal pledge to refrain from writing any more
columns about the Florida Marlins _ is about to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   But not without good reason.
</P>
<P>
   There's news here.
</P>
<P>
   J. Gregory Stoda, 45, worth whatever modest sum his brilliant
and beautiful wife, Pat, has managed to accumulate through a
determined savings plan mixed with savvy investments, is hereby
announcing a bid to buy the team.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Everybody else is.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing owner H. Wayne Huizengmighty can, and probably
will do, is turn me down.
</P>
<P>
   Which, basically, is what he's doing to Marlins President Smiley
Don, who every day looks more and more like the mark in a
Huizengmighty shell game. Which, basically, also is what he's doing
to Joe Cubas and John Henry by pretending they don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   The H. in H. Wayne, we now know, stands for Hesitant.
</P>
<P>
   Money, quite obviously, is not an object. Not with Henry having
offered a reported $150 million in cash to take the Marlins off
Huizengmighty's greedy hands.
</P>
<P>
   Good. Because money is not an object with The StodaGroup,
either.
</P>
<P>
   That's the name of my organization. It helps, advisers tell me,
to have a fancy title with words shoved together and capital
letters in places where it doesn't seem capital letters belong.
</P>
<P>
   Looks important, advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   Lends legitimacy, advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are no advisers to The StodaGroup. There's only
an adviser. Singular. And, truth be told, he isn't an adviser.
</P>
<P>
   He's the money guy.
</P>
<P>
   And the money guy, an acquaintance of mine for almost two
decades, has no problem _ none whatsoever _ with the price tag.
He's a relatively young man, and already a billionaire or on his
way to being one. His financial portfolio is more than sound, and
its growth is predicted to be exponential.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, my contribution of $1,810.23 is gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Our proposal?
</P>
<P>
   The StodaGroup will go to $180,001,810.23 _ more than a 20
percent increase above any previous reported high offer _ for the
Marlins. But only for the Marlins and their spring training
complex. Nothing else. No television deal involving SportsChannel
(see, there's another title with words shoved together and a
capital letter in a strange place). No buyout on any departure from
Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Huizengmighty takes our money and gets out. He can negotiate all
ancillary issues on anyone else's dime he hopes to steal.
</P>
<P>
   The StodaGroup has received corporate assurance that money
necessary to build a retractable roof, baseball-only stadium at a
site to be determined near the Palm Beach County/Martin County line
and its burgeoning corridor will be available. The facility will be
the central block of an expansive entertainment/recreation area
that will include a mall with three anchor stores, an eight-screen
theater multiplex, restaurants and a water park.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland will be retained as manager, if he desires to
return. Dave Dombrowski will move from general manager to
president, if he desires to return. John Boles will be offered the
general manager's position.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate builder, of course, gets naming rights: Swoosh
Park at Nike Village.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the point man purchasing the team _ the $180million guy,
not the spare-change guy _ wishes to play left field himself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan would prefer to bat third in the order.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes his column for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
