<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-GREENTHAL-AR     08-16 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-GREENTHAL-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CHARGE IN THE MALE WORLD OF BIG DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (See also BELLS-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the new professional ethos of Wall Street, back-slapping has
replaced bravado. Investment banks talk up teamwork. Even big-name
deal makers, like star wide receivers, say they could never go it
alone.
</P>
<P>
   So it is only reluctantly, and a little brusquely, that Jill
Greenthal, a media banker for the investment banking firm of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, &UR;  &LR; speaks about the thing that makes
her stand out from her colleagues, her competitors and most of her
clients. That is, that she is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay much attention to it; it's a fact of life,'' she
said, studious-looking and reserved. ``For clients, it doesn't make
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, though, it does.
</P>
<P>
   However hesitant Ms. Greenthal may be about calling attention to
it, she was the lead banker for Tele-Communications Inc.'s recent
agreement to be acquired by AT&AMP;T Corp. in a $70 billion deal. And
that work, which earned her firm a $40 million fee, one of the
largest of its kind in banking history, is a milestone of sorts for
women in investment banking. It was one of the few times that
anyone in the business can recall a woman taking the lead role in a
headline-grabbing public acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greenthal, 42, has been in the investment-banking game for
15 years, longer than many of her female peers. She has also carved
out a niche advising the constantly agglomerating giants of the
media and telecommunications world, where most deals are between
men, brokered by men.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Greenthal's work for the cable giant TCI has made her _
she would say her team _ a leading name in media mergers and
acquisitions. The deal stood out for a few reasons, and not simply
because of its size. One is the ground-breaking nature of the
AT&AMP;T-TCI alliance, joining the businesses of communications and
entertainment, cable and phone wires.
</P>
<P>
   It is also significant, from Wall Street's perspective, because
the Denver-based leaders of TCI _ John Malone, the chairman, and
Leo Hindery, president _ make so many acquisitions that they
generally act as their own bankers, rarely seeking outside advice.
Malone in particular hates to pay the huge percentage commissions
bankers charge. Some people close to him said the $40 million
Donaldson bill was his biggest _ and hardest to swallow _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We typically don't hire bankers, John and I,'' Hindery said.
``But we were talking about a fundamental change in TCI and we
needed outside advice.'' He said a key factor in selecting Ms.
Greenthal was that she had an ability to  &QL; 
adapt her ways to suit hands-on clients. ``She can listen as well
as talk, react as well as initiate,'' Hindery said.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that Ms. Greenthal is a woman? Hindery says it
does, at least to him. ``This was one of the largest fees ever
paid, and it was important to me that it go to her,'' he said.
``This is an industry that's full of aggressive people, most of
them men. It needs more women to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was far from Ms. Greenthal's first, of course. She
worked at Smith Barney and Lehman Brothers before joining
Donaldson, and has represented big clients before, including
companies like U S West and Comcast. But none had ever propelled
her to center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see many of the people who do deals in my business, and the
percentage of women is extremely low,'' said Joele Frank, who
specializes in mergers and acquisitions for Abernathy, MacGregor
and Frank, a public relations company. ``Especially at the highest
levels, and the biggest deals, women do not play much of a role,''
Ms. Frank said, adding, ``They often don't stick around that long''
as investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage, it is true, can be overemphasized. Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co.; Morgan Stanley Dean Witter; Allen &AMP; Co., and many other
investment banks do have women deal makers. Sitting across the
table from Ms. Greenthal during negotiations between TCI and AT&AMP;T,
in fact, was Katherine Dietze, a managing director of Credit Suisse
First Boston who was part of the team advising AT&AMP;T _ though not
the team leader.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greenthal says she does not encounter many other women in
her duties, especially as team leaders. The reason, she said, is
probably the conflict between raising a family and being on call
day and night. That is a hurdle for women in many service
industries, but a brick wall for many at the top levels of
investment banking, where every deal is viewed as a patient in
intensive care, liable to expire without constant attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not really be an issue for women more than for men;
family should be important for both,'' she said. ``But I suppose it
is harder for women. It takes a family that is really
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greenthal, who is married and has two children, said that
while she had been unwilling to sacrifice everything for her
career, the high-wire act of balancing job and family required
extreme flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Tom Eisenmann, was himself on a similarly demanding
career track, as a partner at the consulting firm of McKinsey &AMP; Co.
But he opted to return to school, earning a doctorate at Harvard
Business School, where he is now a tenure-track professor. The
family moved to Boston from New York in 1994, and Ms. Greenthal now
works out of Donaldson's Boston office, where she is the co-head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he was in the consulting business, he understands the
life style,'' Ms. Greenthal said of her husband, interrupting her
summer vacation on Cape Cod to take a reporter's telephone call.
``If it weren't for a supportive family, my career would not be
possible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A native of Milwaukee, she considers her business career a
natural outgrowth of her business-oriented family life _ her father
and three siblings, all of them brothers, pursued corporate
careers. When she graduated from Simmons College in 1978 she went
straight for Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   It was between years at Harvard that she had her first taste of
finance, working as a summer associate at Goldman, Sachs. She
developed a speciality in media banking at Smith Barney and later
joined the media department at Lehman, where she stayed for 10
years before joining Donaldson in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As a media expert, Ms. Greenthal developed a reputation for
being assiduous, in a lawyerly way, and for providing solid
technical banking advice to businessmen filled with their own
ambitions for buying companies and spinning off divisions. At
Lehman, for example, she advised a consortium of companies
including U S West on its 1993 investment in Time Warner
Entertainment, an early melding of telecommunications and
programming. She later helped prepare Lin Broadcasting, a cellular
phone company, for its sale to AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But her big break came in developing a relationship with TCI and
some affiliate companies. In 1995 and again in 1997, she helped TCI
set up tracking stocks for the sometimes oddball collection of
companies that Malone spun off from the TCI mother ship. (Tracking
stocks are investment vehicles that track the performance of a
business without conferring ownership rights.)
</P>
<P>
   She also forged close ties to Hindery even before he joined TCI
last year. Recently, she helped him establish Intermedia Partners
VI for investing in cable ventures around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up to the big TCI deal came earlier this year, when
Hindery recruited Ms. Greenthal to advise the company on a much
smaller business link-up. TCI and AT&AMP;T were thinking about becoming
partners in TCI's At Home Corp., an online TCI affiliate. In the
course of those talks Malone and Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's
chairman, agreed instead upon a full acquisition of TCI. At that
point, TCI kept Ms. Greenthal and the Donaldson team as their sole
bankers, excluding Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., which some on Wall Street
had considered TCI's leading bankers.
</P>
<P>
   There are no secrets to being a good banker, male or female, Ms.
Greenthal says. But if she emphasizes one thing, again invoking the
new Wall Street mantra, it is teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   She calls attention to her partnership with Dennis Leibowitz,
Donaldson's leading media analyst. Leibowitz has closely followed
trends in media and telecommunications, and has been involved in
many of same deals Ms. Greenthal has worked on, only from the
analyst's side. A report he wrote last spring sought to decipher
the structure and strategy of TCI, one of the media world's most
complex companies, in part because of its many spinoffs and
tracking stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to DLJ in large part because of Dennis,'' she said,
adding that clients count on research analysts to cover their
company closely, and inform investors, especially after the bank
arranges a key transaction for the company. ``A strong research
analyst can be very helpful in generating business.''
</P>
<P>
   Leibowitz calls their banking relationship ``love at first
sight.'' He said he took the initiative to lure her to Donaldson,
where the two have formed a banking-analyst partnership on most of
the big deals the firm has undertaken in the media field.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery also emphasizes teamwork when describing why he chose
Donaldson as his lead bankers. He said one of Ms. Greenthal's
strongest attributes was running a tight organization and
concentrating her colleagues' energy on a common goal. For the
TCI-AT&AMP;T deal she led a group of 10 bankers. ``It's like
Normandy,'' he said. ``You've got to get all these people focused
on one target in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no way of telling if Ms. Greenthal, or any other
investment banker, can hope to achieve many monster payouts like
the $40 million fee she brought home for Donaldson. But Ms.
Greenthal says she sees nothing that would take her away from her
banking career now, particularly since she views the TCI-AT&AMP;T deal
as opening the path to a slew of copy-cat mergers in an industry
eager to embrace the next trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reverberations,'' she said, ``are just starting to be
felt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
