is ``better than anything _ except sex.'' Allen Smith,
vice-president of a pharmaceuticals company who owns another L-39,
disagrees. ``He's wrong _ he hasn't flown enough _ it's better than
sex.'' Ron Whitt, a shampoo bottler who just bought his L-39 on
Thursday, said he bought it to ``crank and bank'' _ and to
advertise: He'll paint the sides with the name of a new product,
Race Glaze, and fly the jet to airshows. Others say they see the
two-seater jets _ used as trainers for the various Soviet forces _
as a way to educate the young about flying.
</P>
<P>
   As Ian Johnson, the doctor's 21-year-old son and an aspiring jet
pilot, said: ``We grew up with jets.''
</P>
<P>
   The public may also not understand that the sight of a fighter
jet bearing red stars and Russian warnings doesn't exactly make the
Pentagon tremble. Real military jets carry a ``friend or foe''
warning system which has been disabled in the surplus jets, said
Jack Harrington, an aviation lawyer who is also president of the
Warbirds of America, a group dedicated to the preservation of
fighting aircraft of all vintages. In addition, the jets file
flight plans and maintain routine contact with air controllers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplane community knows these jets,''said Jon Galt
Bowman, who owns several of the fighter jets and represents the jet
owners of the Warbirds' board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a certain mystique when you say jet _ even a
certain apprehension,'' said Rudy Beaver, president of
International Jet in Gadsden, Ala., the country's largest importer
of the surplus fighter jets. ``But in many ways, jets are simpler:
a little twin-engined Cessna has six levers to manage the engine _
a jet only has one.'' And, the jet pilots say, their engines are
more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   But they do burn a lot more fuel. Because of it, they are often
flown to airshows, where the pilots all seem to know each other,
standing in groups on the tarmac near their planes, laughing. About
20 of the jets _ most with their Russian warnings intact _ showed
up in Oshkosh. But the most fun may well be the mock dogfights they
get into on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got my fighter jet, I headed up to the Wisconsin
border,'' Petersen said. ``There's a lot of P-51s up there, and I
went after them. We got into a dogfight and they shot me down.''
Not to worry. ``Oh, not really shot down _ I have a gun sight
hooked to a camera _ I get 'em in the cross hairs and snap a
picture, for proof.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although they don't come with fax machine ports, microwave ovens
and CD players the way the new corporate jets do, the military jets
offer the following advantage (depending, of course, on how you
look at it): In the corporate jets, you can't feel the enormous
pull of gravity that make most earthlings very, very sick to their
stomach. In the MiGs and Sokos, the pilot-owners revel in the fact
they can take up to 8 ``G's'' _ a gravitational force equal to
eight times one's body weight.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Soviet Union, its former republics
``were desperate for cold, hard cash,'' said Doug Schultz, a
fighter pilot and jet owner who recently tried _ and failed _ to
bring some of the newest surplus planes into this country. Schultz,
who said he ran into ``political cobwebs and dead-ends,'' bought
his planes from an importer in Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government does not sell its surplus fighter jets to
its citizens: They chop them up, said Carol Simpson, a spokeswoman
for the Defense Department's Reutilization and Marketing Service.
To find one _ and there are some _ you'd have to buy them from
another country or from a dealer who did.
</P>
<P>
   To find a fighter jet these days _ from any country _ Schultz
said, potential top gunners might subscribe to Trade-A-Plane, a
yellow-paged classified paper that comes out three times a month
(800-337-5263; $42 a year).
</P>
<P>
   Or they could call International Jets, Inc. in Gadsden, Ala.,
which offers old fighters including L-39s, Iskras and several
British planes.
</P>
<P>
   The company lets you take a half-hour ``demonstration'' flight _
the equivalent of a test drive. But unlike your local used-car
dealer, they charge for it: $1,000, which is deducted from the cost
of the plane if you buy it. They can also obtain the FAA's
certification for the plane _ the equivalent of running it through
the department of motor vehicles for a car registration.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the importers pay about half of the retail price of
the plane, or even less. But they have to pay the duty, reassemble
the pieces (it's taken apart for shipping), and remove any obsolete
navigation equipment. They may also paint it _ although some of the
owners prefer to leave the planes with their original, if faded,
Soviet warnings and decals.
</P>
<P>
   When they decided to call a halt to their import in 1993, the
FAA was ``worried a lot of millionaire playboys would be hurling
themselves around and falling into schoolyards,'' Schultz said.''
Both the federal officials and the pilots say that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys treat them the way they do classic cars,'' said
Terry Allen, of the FAA's certification service in Washington
``They preserve them; they practically worship them.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1996 regulations, the FAA requires that pilots be
trained by an FAA approved trainer and must have logged 1,000 hours
of flying time _ in contrast to the young Soviet pilots who
originally flew the planes, who, jet enthusiasts claim, were
required to show only 50 hours of flying. Nowadays, most of the
pilots receive their training in the United States; Gilbert, an
early customer, bought his plane from an importer in Burlington,
Vt., but flew over for 10 days of training in the Czech Republic.
He later spent more time training with a Russian pilot _ in Lock
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, from Chicago, trained with the same Russian pilot in
Gadston, Ala. ``When he first came over, he only knew three English
commands: `Speed big,' `speed small' and `don't do that,''' the
builder recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, the FAA spokesman, said that since the first
civilian-owned foreign fighter jets were allowed into the United
States, there have been no accidents that killed people ``on the
ground,'' meaning innocent bystanders. How about the pilots
themselves? ``That's different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On August 2, in Oshkosh, the wife of one of the civilian jet
pilots was killed when her husband crashed their two-seater Spanish
Saeta, one of the rare Spanish military jet ``warbirds'' in the
United States. The jet struck a tree and some power lines before
crashing onto a residential street. No one on the ground was
injured. The cause of the crash is still being investigated.
Nevertheless, both the jet owners and the FAA say that the number
of fighter jet deaths have been low, maybe even proportionately
less than for the country's other 186,000 private planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time you have the money, you're 55 and married with a
house full of kids,'' said Don Kirlin of Quincy, Ill., president of
the Classic Jet Airplane Association. ``That's not the stereotype.
These are definitely not guys boozing and looking for babes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
