<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-BOOK-REVIEW-530     08-16 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BOOK-REVIEW-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW GHOSTS, OLD GHOSTS': IF NOT A GULAG, A SYSTEM OFTEN CRUDE AND
HARSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One reason China presents such a large human rights question is
the very opacity of the country, its vastness and its invisibility
to the outside world (even though things are a lot more visible
today than they were in the past). There is no doubt that some
peaceful protesters, independent labor-union organizers and
human-rights campaigners have been imprisoned. But how many? And
what can be said of conditions in the fabled labor camp system in
the country's remote northwest? Does it, as some critics have said,
produce a substantial portion of China's exports? Is it a vast
state within a state in the spirit of the former Soviet Gulag
Archipelago?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions have never before received more careful answers
than they get in ``New Ghosts, Old Ghosts,'' James Seymour and
Richard Anderson's important and timely examination of the Chinese
prison system. The overall conclusion of those two respected
experts on human rights in China may come as a surprise to those
who have become accustomed to the image of China as a kind of
post-Stalinist hell.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in ``New Ghosts, Old Ghosts'' that would remove
China from the list of countries with major human-rights
violations. But Seymour and Anderson, while detailing abuses,
correct many of the exaggerated visions of the Chinese picture,
which, they argue, is bad but not nearly as bad as some have
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at its worst, the laogai is not, as some have claimed,
`the Chinese equivalent of the Soviet Gulag,' '' they conclude.
(Laogai is the Chinese expression for reform through labor and is
used in this book as a synonym for the Chinese prison system.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The crudeness of China's judicial procedures does result in
people sometimes being convicted of crimes by mistake,'' the
authors continue. ``Still, it must be said that the overwhelming
majority of prisoners have been incarcerated for the same reasons
they are in other countries: they are believed to have committed a
crime. Only a tiny percentage of post-Mao-era laogai prisoners have
been sentenced for political reasons.'' Moreover, addressing
another issue that has been treated with more emotion than lucidity
by other analysts, the authors of this book conclude that the
laogai system is economically minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although much has been made of the economic importance of
forced labor in China, in fact prison output makes no significant
contribution to the gross domestic product,'' they conclude.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour and Anderson concentrate on China's vast and sparsely
populated northwest. These are the territories _ Gansu and Qinghai
provinces and the Xinjiang Autonomous Region _ where large numbers
of China's most notorious prison camps have been built, especially
in the long, harsh years of Maoist dictatorship. The authors warn
early on that ``the Chinese government's distortion, obfuscation
and secrecy make it difficult to count many of China's penal
institutions or to estimate how large each is.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, ``New Ghosts, Old Ghosts'' provides an
impressively detailed portrait of prison conditions in each of the
three areas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Seymour and Anderson begin with a kind of walking tour of the
several detention centers and laogai factories that one would see
in Xining, the major city of eastern Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour and Anderson estimate the number of prisoners in each
area, the totals being large but far from Maoist or Stalinesque in
dimension. They estimate the Xinjiang prison population to be about
85,000, down from 160,000 in 1955. This would strongly indicate
that the nationwide prison population is a small fraction of the 6
million to 8 million estimated by another human rights campaigner,
Harry Wu. Among the prisoners in Xinjiang are a substantial number
of political prisoners, especially Muslims who have been rounded up
by Chinese police intent on suppressing separatist sentiment in
Xinjiang, largely populated by Turkic-speaking Uighurs.
</P>
<P>
   The economic output of the Xinjiang prison system, the authors
believe, is ``well under 1 percent of the regional total output.''
Some prison-made products are exported to foreign countries,
despite Chinese denials, the authors conclude, but not very many of
them and mostly over the border to Russia, not to the West.
</P>
<P>
   The serious human rights problem that Seymour and Anderson
stress is not the size of the prison population nor that prisoners
are made to work (they are in other countries also) but their
treatment, which is often abysmal. Tibet is not an area studied by
the authors, but they remark in a footnote that the problem of
torture in Tibetan prisons is well documented.
</P>
<P>
   In Xinjiang, they collect information on a ``secret laogai
operation known as the Gray (Huise) Uranium Mine,'' which they call
``the grimmest laogai unit that our research turned up.'' The death
rate in this camp, probably because of the radioactivity of the
uranium ore mined there, is between 10 percent and 20 percent per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Other prisoners work in coal mines, where ``some become ill from
black-lung disease, but many do not live long enough to develop
that malady, as safety conditions are atrocious.'' These
institutions seem exceptionally bad even by China's low standards.
Seymour and Anderson conclude, for example, that, while Xinjiang's
prisoners are generally badly treated, those in neighboring Qinghai
by and large are not.
</P>
<P>
   This careful, sober study might well induce human rights
activists to turn their attention away from the size of China's
prison population to what the authors describe as the more
fundamental concerns: ``the substantial number of prisoners who do
not belong there and the harshness of the conditions in the less
well-managed institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   In reaching that overall conclusion, ``New Ghosts, Old Ghosts''
clears away both the pro-Chinese apologies and the anti-Chinese
hysteria that has often surrounded this question, providing instead
the most objective and dispassionate evaluation of the real
situation that we are likely to have.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NEW GHOSTS, OLD GHOSTS: PRISONS AND LABOR REFORM CAMPS IN
CHINA'
</P>
<P>
   By James Seymour and Richard Anderson
</P>
<P>
   Forward by Fan Sidong. 313 pages. M.E. Sharpe. $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORSEFARM-TROPHIES-1     08-16 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSEFARM-TROPHIES-1,050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF TROPHIES LATEST CHAPTER IN LEGENDARY STABLE'S COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ One week ago, a moving van pulled up in front
of the International Museum of the Horse at the Kentucky Horse Park
here to take away some pieces of racing history and carry them to
the ``21'' Club in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   On the shipper's manifest were the glittering trophies won by
thoroughbred racing's most legendary stable, Calumet Farm. The
trophies bore the names of the horses that once made Calumet
pre-eminent, names that resonated even with those who had never
placed a bet: Citation, Whirlaway, Tim Tam, Alydar.
</P>
<P>
   But after Calumet collapsed in bankruptcy in 1991, virtually
every trapping of the breeding and racing empire was auctioned to
pay debts. Today, all that remains of the farm's legacy is the
collection of some 530 gold, silver, crystal and pewter trophies
and awards, which have been housed at the state-run Horse Park
since 1982. And now that those awards also seem headed for the
auction block, a raucous battle has erupted in Bluegrass country
between those who argue that the collection should go to the
highest bidder and those who say that it is an important part of
Kentucky's heritage and should stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be an embarrassment to the state and the
racing industry to have this great historical collection dissolved
to satisfy some desperate creditors,'' said James E. Bassett III,
chairman of the Keeneland Association, which operates the Keeneland
racetrack, and head of the Save the Calumet Trophies committee. A
newspaper ad run to benefit trophy supporters compared their
possible loss to the selling off of the symbols of the state's
other great passion, the University of Kentucky's basketball
trophies.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional debate over the fate of the Calumet collection _
the sleek Tiffany-designed Triple Crown trophies won by Citation
and Whirlaway in the 1940s, the gloriously engraved bowl made from
melted silver coins hoisted over Bull Lea in the 1938 Bluegrass
Stakes _ is the latest chapter in the sad downfall of a sports
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   It is a saga riddled with greed and miscalculation, one that
left once-rich heirs to the Calumet Baking Powder fortune bankrupt
and a proud racing name in shambles. And like the war over the
trophies, it is a tale that is far from over. Federal officials in
Houston are investigating whether former top Calumet officials,
desperate for cash, might have killed one of the stable's
most-beloved horses, Alydar, in 1990 in order to collect an
insurance windfall.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest turn in the fate of the trophies, Calumet
supporters and others appeared in U.S. Bankruptcy Court here to
block removal of any trophies to the ``21'' Club. Guernsey's
Auction House, a New York company, had arranged to display them
there and at sites like Saratoga Springs to generate publicity for
the planned sale next month.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers argued that the trophies might be damaged during
shipment or display and were not fully insured. Federal Bankruptcy
Judge Joe Lee, who is presiding over a tangle of bankruptcies
involving the heirs of Calumet's founders, agreed, keeping the
collection at the Horse Park and ruling that anyone with the means
to buy the trophies could afford to fly here to see them. Besides,
he added in a courtroom aside, he understood that the ``21'' Club,
the swank Manhattan restaurant, attracted flamboyant celebrities
like Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the auction will only take place if a qualified bidder
steps forward by the end of the month and offers at least $2.81
million for the collection, which also includes 40 oil paintings of
horses. That is because the Horse Park has already raised $2.7
million in public donations and funds from the Kentucky state
legislature to buy the trophies out of bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors say they deserve to get as much money for the Calumet
collection as possible, and a Tennessee businessman who has bought
bankruptcy debts of the farm and the heirs in recent years at deep
discounts will be the big winner in any sale. Still, local lawyers
involved in the case say they have little doubt about the tide of
public sentiment. Not long ago, for example, officials at the Horse
Park gave bankruptcy trustees a videotape presentation celebrating
the area's thoroughbred tradition. Included was a television news
report which showed schoolchildren putting pennies and nickels into
a glass jar to save the trophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public opinion is running dead against us,'' said James Lyon,
a lawyer here who is a bankruptcy trustee for one of the heirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Calumet collection, housed in 15 display cases including one
that recreates how the trophies were exhibited at the farm's
mansion, testifies to the thousands of victories won by jockeys
wearing the devil's red-and-blue silks of Calumet, including nine
Kentucky Derbys. Along with traditional loving cups, trophies and
plaques, the collection includes other valuable objects given to
race winners like ornate punch bowls, urns, tea services, serving
trays, samovars and smaller awards known as julep cups.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the trophies often became ensnared in the same
passions and intrigues that embroiled Calumet.
</P>
<P>
   John Morgan, a lawyer involved in the bankruptcy proceedings who
has researched the trophies' history, said that initially Lucille
Parker Wright Markey apparently thought about donating the
collection to Churchill Downs, the site of the Kentucky Derby.
Markey was the widow of Warren Wright Sr., the man who presided
over Calumet's glory days in the 1940s and 50s.
</P>
<P>
   That plan changed in 1968 when Dancer's Image finished first in
the Kentucky Derby but was disqualified by judges, making Forward
Pass, a Calumet horse, the winner. Because Churchill Downs
officials dawdled for five years before handing over the trophy,
Markey cut them out, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1982, when Markey died after owning Calumet for 51
years, that the fates of both the farm and the trophies were set.
That year, J.T. Lundy, a man who had married into the Wright
family, took over the stable because the children of Warren Wright
Jr. did not want to run it. And by most accounts, it is Lundy, who
spent lavishly on leased jets and a fleet of cars and also borrowed
heavily from banks to buy new horses, who is blamed for Calumet's
collapse in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1980s Lundy staked the farm's financial fortunes
on Alydar, a horse that won the hearts of racing fans by finishing
second to Affirmed in all three Triple Crown races in 1978. After
his racing days, Alydar commanded top stud fees. But Lundy, who
faced a cash shortage, quickly exhausted the horse's value by
selling his breeding rights into the distant future. As a result,
some suspected foul play when Alydar, who was covered by a $36
million insurance policy, was discovered in his stall one night in
1990 with a shattered right rear leg. Despite efforts to save him,
he had to be put down.
</P>
<P>
   Lundy and others involved in the farm's operation have long
maintained that the tragedy was an accident. But even before
Markey's death, both she and her second husband, Gene Markey, who
operated Calumet with her, distrusted Lundy and decided to put the
trophies out of his reach, said Margaret Glass, who served as the
stable's secretary for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Horse Park had come into existence a few years
earlier, and Glass said she urged Gene Markey to place the trophies
there in 1982. Officials of Sotheby's appraised the collection that
year, valuing it at $1.2 million, and the trophies were leased to
the Horse Park for the annual fee of $1.
</P>
<P>
   The trophies might have quietly resided there forever had one of
the Calumet heirs not listed a share in the collection as an asset
when she went bankrupt in the mid-1990s. Ever since, creditors and
buyers have been eagerly circling the collection.
</P>
<P>
   One Louisville business offered to buy them for $1.2 million.
Two years ago, Horse Park officials started a public drive to raise
a similar amount. But last year, to determine the collection's
value, Judge Lee ordered the bankruptcy trustees to hire an auction
house to appraise it.
</P>
<P>
   Guernsey's was selected and the company soon shocked local
trophy supporters by estimating the awards could bring over $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ettinger, Guernsey's president, said he believed that
Sotheby's, which appraised the collection at $1.2 million again in
1995, had been far too conservative because it had based its
estimate on the weight of the precious metals contained in the
statues rather than their value to racing fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like, guess the worth of a Picasso by the value of the
paint and the canvas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the Calumet collection is sold to the
Horse Park or auctioned, the big winner will apparently be G.
Donald Puckett, a businessman from Kingsport, Tenn. In recent
years, Puckett, who is related to one of the Calumet heirs by
marriage, has been buying up creditors' claims at deep discounts.
Now, he stands to reap from 80 percent to 85 percent of any money
collected by the sale of the trophies and other bankruptcy assets,
said lawyers involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Puckett, who declined to be interviewed, has also apparently had
his eye on the Calumet collection for some time. He already owns a
stake in the collection, having purchased it from an heir. And in
the mid-1990s, he contacted lawyers involved in the bankruptcy
proceedings offering to buy their share of the awards for $6,000,
said Lyon, the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to call him `The Trophy Man,''' Lyon said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Horse Park officials said, Puckett contacted them
and asked whether they would be interested in leasing the trophies
from him if he spent $5 million to buy them. Bill Cooke, a Horse
Park spokesman, said that he did not recall the precise annual fee
suggested by Puckett, though he recalls that it was over $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it was, it was absurd,'' Cooke said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Jeffrey Landen, a lawyer who represents Puckett, said the
businessman believes that the collection should go to the top
bidder and that the estimate by Guernsey's is more in line with its
value than the lower price put on it by Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Ettinger, the Guernsey's president, said that a bidder had
recently emerged who had tentatively expressed interest in
guaranteeing the $2.81 million minimum. Under the guidelines
established by Lee, the collection must be sold together, though
the buyer could then break it up for resale.
</P>
<P>
   As with much of the Calumet story, what will happen next is
anyone's guess. These days, the farm appears to be thriving again
under the guidance of a new owner, Henryk De Kwiatkowski, and on a
mid-summer's day soft shadows fall over the grave of Alydar, which
is marked ``Chestnut Horse.'' Litigation over the stable's collapse
continues, and creditors and others continue to hunt for Lundy, who
disappeared not long after declaring bankruptcy in 1992 and has
been evading subpoenas and process servers since, said lawyers in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Margaret Glass, the long-time Calumet secretary,
said she believes the trophies should stay at the Horse Park, where
she helped put them. She says that while the stable heirs neglected
the operation, it was the Horse Park that cared for the collection,
and the creditors can look elsewhere for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the centerpiece of that place and they belong there,''
she said. ``They belong in Kentucky and they belong intact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
