<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASRAIL-COX     08-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASRAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An analysis of the Pepsi 400 at Michigan Speedway
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The First 50:
</P>
<P>
   The race was only two laps old before Jeff Green hit the wall,
which brought out the first caution and allowed teams to top off
their tanks, knowing that every gallon in the tank was precious.
Six laps later, however, Sterling Marlin ran into rear deck of
Derrike Cope's Pontiac, which then ran into the Chevrolet of Morgan
Shepherd. Both cars were damaged enough to remedy them useless.
Marlin's team owner Felix Sabates ran down to pit of Cope's car
owner Chuck Rider and apologized. ''We pulled out all stops, leased
an engine from Bobby Labonte's team,'' Rider said. ''This really
hurts.'' On the restart, Ernie Irvan, Mark Martin, Jeff Gordon,
Bobby Labonte and Dale Jarrett pull away from rest of pack. Nobody
was worrying about gas mileage at this point despite the torrid
pace. There were only two lead changes, twice by Martin for two
laps; three from Irvan for 40.
</P>
<P>
   The Second 50:
</P>
<P>
   The second round of pit stops began with Jarrett the first in
and out in 16.7 seconds. Chassis adjustments were the order of this
round, along with four tire changes and fuel. Kenny Irwin cut it
close on his stop, coasting into the pits on gas fumes only. Dale
Earnhardt didn't pit and picked up the five bonus points for
leading a lap. When he did pit, he did so in 13.3 seconds. The top
10 at the point: Jarrett, Irvan, Martin, B. Labonte, Gordon, Jeff
Burton, Jeremy Mayfield, Wally Dallenbach, John Andretti and Ward
Burton. Irvan regains lead on lap 60 and Earnhardt, with a loose
car, falls back to 22nd and goes down a lap on No. 79. Martin is
second and Gordon sixth. Irvan picked up the $10,000 bonus for
leading at the halfway mark. now on the the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   The third 50:
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett takes has 27.3-second pit stop for track bar adjustment
trouble with lug nuts on tire change. Track bar adjustment on 88
car 27.3 seconds. Bill Elliott was penalized a stop-and-go for
speeding down pit road and went down a lap. After starting 23rd,
Jeff Burton moves to third on lap 112. At this points Gordon is no
factor, running sixth on lap 113.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff start 25th now up to third on lap 112. Jarrett falls back,
the victim of an ill-handling car. The battle for the lead remains
between Irvan and Martin, whose car doesn't handle as well when
running right behind Irvan. Gordon still hasn't led. The last time
he didn't lead a lap was at Texas when he wrecked on the second
lap. Elliott was back up to 14th when his motor quit on lap 135. On
lap 142, only 10 cars are on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   The final 50:
</P>
<P>
   Eight cars on the lead lap with Martin, Irvan, Burton, Jarrett,
Bobby Labonte, Jeremy Mayfield, Wally Dallenbach and John Andretti.
The final round of pit stops are hurried and harried. Gordon still
hasn't led a lap, but is running sixth on his stop. Irvan still
leading and takes two tires; Martin takes four in 17.1 seconds.
Irvan pays dearly as Martin on fresh tires, on lap 167 pulls away.
Burton goes low and passes Irvan on 172; Jarrett gets him on lap
174 and takes third. Gordon still hasn't led.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton's motor blows, bringing out caution on lap 179. The
nine cars on the lead lap hit pit road. Jeff Burton, Martin and
Gordon take right side tires. Burton crew blew it, didn't put lug
nuts on tightly causing Burton to come back in. He takes on four
tires, but it's too late. He came in second and went out ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Impact
</P>
<P>
   With 20 laps to go Sunday, Jeff Gordon was running fourth a half
lap behind and destined for no more than a top five finish. Then
came the blown motor in Ward Burton's Pontiac, bunching up the
field and bringing it down pit road for the last gasp. It was all
Gordon needed. He took on two right side tires, came out third and
blew away the field for his eighth victory of the year and fourth
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Who was hot
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's crew. They got him out of the pits in third place
behind Martin and Jarrett and once in front never had to check his
rear view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Who was not
</P>
<P>
   Martin. He also took on two tires during that last stop, got out
first, and held Gordon off for six laps before fading to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Points update
</P>
<P>
   The beat goes on. With his victory, Gordon moved 97 points in
front of Martin and 233 ahead of third place Dale Jarrett. The top
five: Gordon, 3262; Martin, 3165; Jarrett, 3029; Rusty Wallace,
2863.
</P>
<P>
   Did You Know?
</P>
<P>
   With his victory Sunday, Gordon moved to 15th on the all-time
victory list, tied with Bobby Issac. It was Gordon's 37th career
victory, eighth of the year, fourth straight and 26th on a
superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   The four straight tied the all time modern era record, dating to
1972, held by Mark Martin, '93; Bill Elliott,''92; Harry Gant, '91;
Dale Earnhardt, '87; Darrell Waltrip, '81; and Cale Yarborough,
'96. He led only nine laps, but they were the last nine. His margin
of victory was 1.8 seconds, amazing when you realize with 20 laps
to go he was more concerned about going down a lap than winning the
race . . . Only nine cars finished on the lead lap . . .
</P>
<P>
   Next week's story line
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett defends his title in the Goody's 500 at Bristol,
but Gordon will be the man to beat as he goes for his fifth victory
of the year and fourth in his career at Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
