u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GRANDJURY-HNS     08-16 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GRANDJURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON FACES CRITICAL TEST BEFORE GRAND JURY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By NANCY MATHIS &QL; 
and JOHN C. HENRY &QL; 
c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pondering full disclosure and a national apology,
President Clinton breaks his silence today about his relationship
with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Political advisers, hoisting trial balloons all weekend,
suggested the president may concede an ``inappropriate
relationship'' with Monica Lewinsky and may seek forgiveness from
the American people who have shown little interest in delving into
his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   On the most critical day of his presidency, Clinton will make an
unprecedented closed-circuit televised appearance before a
23-member grand jury probing allegations that he lied about his
relationship with Lewinsky, 25, and urged her to lie as well.
Later, the president may make a statement to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Former aides and allies contended Sunday that Clinton should
throw himself on the mercy of the court, and the mercy of the
public, in an effort to save his beleaguered presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on ABC's This Week, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.,
noted this nation's dominant faith is based on redemption. ``It is
a forgiving country. If there is a contradiction, and it appears
there might be, he has to explain it. But I think he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Davis, a former White House lawyer, suggested Clinton
address the nation and release a transcript of his videotaped
testimony to avoid having portions of his statements released by
others.
</P>
<P>
   Republican adversaries warned of serious consequences if Clinton
testified less than honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ask the president to testify truthfully because, so
help me, if he lies before the grand jury, that would be grounds
for impeachment,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee, during an appearance on NBC's Meet the
Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all that's involved here is the president lying under oath,
which is terribly serious but to protect his wife and daughter from
serious pain, the American public I think will be willing to wait
until the year 2000 to replace him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton may find little sympathy from the Republican
majority serving on the House Judiciary Committee which would have
to recommend any impeachment proceedings to the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``If at the end of the day I conclude that the president lied
under oath in a court proceeding, I would have a very hard time not
recommending impeachment to the House,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla, a committee member appearing on CBS's Face the Nation. The
House votes for articles of impeachment while the Senate conducts
the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The vast speculation about Clinton's testimony prompted his
personal attorney David Kendall to release a terse statement Sunday
afternoon: ``There is apparently an enormous amount of groundless
speculation about the president's testimony tomorrow. The truth is
the truth. Period. And, that's how the president will testify.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady, arm in arm, attended church on
Sunday morning and he spent much of the day huddled with his
personal attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   At noon CDT today, Clinton will enter the Map Room in the White
House, the ground-floor room where President Franklin D. Roosevelt
kept track of troop movements during World War II. It is here for
the first time that a president will testify in a criminal
investigation in which he is the target.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton for the first time will confront prosecutors from
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's office, and perhaps Starr
himself, who has spent four years investigating the president's and
first lady's business and personal dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Communications Agency, the military unit that
provides the communications support for the presidency, will set up
a secure closed-circuit television feed to the federal courthouse
located near the Capitol. Unlike most grand jury witnesses, Clinton
will be allowed to have his personal legal team and White House
counsel Charles Ruff in the room with him.
</P>
<P>
   But political advisers, who have been at odds with Clinton's
legal team, spent the weekend spreading the word that the president
may alter his previous denials of any sexual relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Such a monumental change would prove painful to Clinton's family
and friends and could severely undermine his credibility even if he
remains in office. The public so far has repeatedly given the
president some of his highest approval ratings while also
indicating a majority believe he did have a sexual relationship
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president changes his testimony and acknowledges an
improper relationship here, he obviously is going to have to go
through a lot of pain himself, not only in apologizing to his wife
and his family, but obviously to the staff and to those that he
misled and to the American public,'' former Chief of Staff Leon
Panetta said on Meet The Press.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   After seven turbulent months, the sex-and-lies scandal is at a
turning point.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation began in January when Linda Tripp, a
former Lewinsky friend, provided him with secretly reported
telephone calls in which her co-worker spoke of her affair with
Clinton in graphic detail. Tripp also provided the same information
to attorneys for Paula Jones, the former Arkansas government clerk
who sued Clinton for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition in the Jones' case that same month, Clinton
denied a sexual relationship with Lewinsky, suggested he had not
been alone with her in the White House and could not recall if he
had given her gifts. As the scandal became public, Clinton also
appeared before television camera to forcefully maintain, ``I did
not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue was not only whether Clinton lied in his deposition but
whether he conspired to cover up the perjury but suggesting ``cover
stories'' for Lewinsky and whether he urged help for Lewinsky's job
quest in an effort to keep her quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, after holding out for months, recently testified
before the grand jury that she and Clinton did have a sexual affair
and while he suggested hypothetical cover stories that he never
urged her to lie. She also provided a navy blue cocktail dress
reportedly containing DNA proof of a sexual encounter. The results
of that test is Washington's best kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that Clinton may concede an
``inappropriate relationship'' with Lewinsky but decline to go into
details. He may also maintain he did not commit perjury in his
initial deposition which rested in a legal definition of sexual
relations provided by Jones' attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported Clinton was considering altering
his denial to acknowledge a sexual encounter but found his most
difficult decision was how to inform the first lady, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, and his daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Daily News reported that the president already has
informed the first lady in a ``brutally honest'' discussion. There
was speculation that advisers were floating the trial balloons as a
way of informing Clinton's family.
</P>
<P>
   But even Clinton's testimony will not draw the case to an
immediate end. Starr can still recall Lewinsky and continues to
question Secret Service agents about what they may have seen in the
White House. Indeed, there may be months to go before the matter
comes to a rest.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor reportedly will try to complete a report
outlining possible impeachment activities to the House within a
month. The Republican-led House already has geared up its Judiciary
Committee for possible impeachment hearings. McCollum suggested the
panel could take weeks more to review the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
