<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week in the National League
 &HT;    (EDITORS: Sunday's games still in progress at time this story
sent to wires: Cubs-Astros, Giants-Marlins, Brewers-Padres (both
games), Braves-Dodgers, Mets-Diamondbacks.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Mets 4-1 (66-54), Phillies 4-2 (60-62), Braves 3-2
(82-41), Marlins 3-3 (44-79), Expos 0-6 (49-75).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Mets lead league, Phillies 7 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Braves rigthhander Dennis Martinez became the
all-time winningest Latin pitcher with 244 wins while the Mets took
over the lead in the wildcard race..
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Montreal brothers Guerrero, Vladimir and Wilton,
drove in all four of the club's runs in Saturday's 6-4 loss to the
Reds, going a combined 4-for-8 with two homers and four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Braves closer Kerry Ligtenberg has saved 20 of
22 opportunities and 14 straight.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Before Sunday's win, the Phillies had been
outscored 87-52 in their last 16 games, 12 of them losses.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Phillies lefthander Matt Beech was placed on the
DL with a stretched ligament in his elbow and was replaced on the
roster by former Brave Paul Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Philadelphia's Pat Burrell, the top pick of the
draft, won't be ready until late next season and is being converted
from third base to first.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The Mets have back-to-back
doubleheaders with the Cardinals on Thursday and Friday in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Astros 5-1 (76-47), Cubs 3-2 (67-56), Pirates 4-2
(56-68), Cardinals 3-3 (59-63), Reds 3-3 (56-68), Brewers 0-5
(58-64).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Cubs 1/2-game back, Cardinals 8 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Since making the deal for Randy Johnson, the
Astros are 11-3 while Sammy Sosa hit his 47th homer Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Cardinals' Ray Lankford has 11 homers since the
All-Star break, one more than teammate Mark McGwire. At one time
last week McGwire went nine straight plate appearances without
putting the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Pittsburgh's Francisco Cordova is 10-10 but has
the best ERA for a starter in the division at 3.26.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Cubs closer Rod Beck has blown six of 41 save
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Brewers placed first baseman John Jaha on
the DL with a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Cardinals have seen Mike Piazza come to St.
Louis on three different teams this season, the first week with the
Dodgers, then Florida in May and the Mets last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: At Wrigley Field on Saturday, it's
Kerry Wood of the Cubs against Houston's Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Rockies 3-2 (56-67), Padres 3-2 (79-43), Giants 3-2
(65-58), Dodgers 1-4 (61-62), Diamondbacks 1-4 (45-77).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Giants 2 1/2 games back, Dodgers 6 1/2 games
back, 10 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Despite Tommy Lasorda's promise that his team
will make the postseason, the Dodgers continue to fade.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Two Colorado players are pushing New York's John
Olerud for the league's best average. Olerud is at .355 while Dante
Bichette is hitting .346 and Larry Walker is at .342.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: In the league's ERA race, San Diego's Andy Ashby
(2.50) and Kevin Brown (2.58) are Nos. 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: It appears the Giants have lost lefthander
Shawn Estes for the season, out with a strained muscle in his left
rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Padres lost Tony Gwynn for at least two
weeks, the outfielder having an Achilles tendon problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Dodgers starter Darren Driefort is 1-5 in his last
eight starts and the club feels he is not used to the workload (157
1/3 innings, 47 1/3 more than his previous high). He had been a
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Having taken two of three from the
Braves last week in San Diego, the Padres come to Atlanta for two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
