<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: EDS TRIES TO SLOUGH OFF PEROT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As hard as Electronic Data Systems has tried to define
itself as something other than the company that Ross Perot founded,
it has never quite escaped his legacy. Fourteen years after Perot
sold the company to General Motors, it is still run by his former
lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   All that is about to change. The board has pointedly announced
plans to hire a new chairman and chief executive from outside. News
earlier this month of the retirement of Lester Alberthal Jr. and of
the board's intent lifted shares of EDS $5.125, or nearly 14
percent, to $41.8125 in one day. In a choppy market, they have
since settled to $40.50.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the company's ultimate boss is James Baker III, the
former secretary of state and chairman of the board's governance
committee. In discreet maneuvering worthy of Middle East diplomacy,
he arranged for Alberthal to step aside and is now leading the
search for a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, disappointed by EDS, have drawn confidence from
Baker's leadership and the demonstrated independence of a board
Alberthal appointed just two years ago, when General Motors spun
off EDS.
</P>
<P>
   Alberthal's virtues were distinct from those of Perot. Even as
he succeeded in vastly expanding the company, especially abroad,
and helping to redefine the computer services business as an
essential element of corporate strategy, he remained quiet,
cautious and shy. For all the company's efforts to build its own
identity, Alberthal was a reluctant pitchman.
</P>
<P>
   Employees, seeing corporate jets and huge management bonuses
even as profitability and the stock price crashed, grew
disenchanted.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think that EDS should simply find the best
available person from within the computer services industry. But
some big investors and many employees hope for a marquee name, a
business leader so prominent and capable that the public will have
another name to associate with EDS besides Perot. ``When they
presumably bring in somebody of substance, there's another uptick
to come,'' a person who has been briefed on some of the board's
deliberations said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, can the new chief see that the uptick becomes a
full-fledged recovery, back toward the peak share price of $63.375
two years ago?
</P>
<P>
   There are already some signs of a turnaround. The company has
booked $16.7 billion in new business over the last four quarters,
up 38 percent from the previous four. Its earnings for the second
quarter exceeded analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company had to acknowledge that some of its
largest contracts were yielding lower profits than its previous
earnings reports had reflected. As Myrna Vance, a vice president
for investor relations, pointed out, the company has become far
more conservative in reporting profits on new contracts
</P>
<P>
   But for now, there are other risks. These begin with General
Motors, the company's largest customer at $4.3 billion last year,
or about a quarter of EDS revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Damage resulting from the recent GM strike might already be
priced into the computer services company's stock. But as the
automaker looks for ways to cut costs, the first initials that come
up after UAW are EDS. ``The new CEO will have a challenge getting
their arms around the General Motors business,'' said Greg Gould,
an analyst with Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   The success of EDS in winning new business has come at the cost
of accepting lower profit margins. Under a new chief, said Stephen
McClellan, a Merrill Lynch analyst, ``cost-cutting has got to play
a major new role''
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, turnover in top management is compromising
the company's ability to take a new direction. Since February, EDS
has been searching, without success, for a chief financial officer.
The new chief executive is bound to remake the rest of the
executive team.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone at EDS is looking for a return to the forceful
style of Perot. At least on a smaller scale, his decisive, military
manner can still succeed, as a pending public offering of shares in
his Perot Systems is likely to prove. Perot Systems, too, is run by
executives whose history with Perot goes back decades. But Perot's
prediction in 1988, that having the new company he founded compete
with EDS would be ``like turning a bunch of bulldogs loose on a
bunch of poodles,'' has been proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Poodles? Ever since, Perot's challenge has made Alberthal and
his crew all the more determined. Perot, in the meantime, made EDS'
success a premise of his presidential races. Lacking direct
dealings with consumers, EDS had few chances to tell everyone that
it was no longer a Perot company.
</P>
<P>
   Now EDS has that chance. ``Whomever they pick,'' an EDS manager
said, ``the perception of that person will be the perception of
EDS.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
