<SLUG> BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN BEENE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You've been tempted, I know; one can live on
baseball, golf and tennis for only so long without wanting a little
contact in your sports.
</P>
<P>
   But do try to resist the temptation of exhibition football.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition football _ we simply refuse to call it anything else
_ is a lot like watching a Milli Vanilli concert. The crowd seems
into it, but you know these fakers are not what you paid to see.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, amazingly, still gets people to attend what it
euphemistically calls ``preseason games'' in August. This is a
shrewd marketing move that antedates by many years baseball teams
giving out Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Do not think you are watching the NFL. The players might wear
the uniforms of your favorite team, but in reality they are closer
to the World League than the NFL. Exhibitions feature a bunch of
guys you've never heard of from Middle Tennessee State or somewhere
else where schools' football teams play second fiddle to their
cotton-judging teams.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition football is about coaches trying out kickers and
third-string quarterbacks, about Dallas Cowboys scandals and about
the John Elways and Barry Sanderses trying not to get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Do not watch these games on television, do not look for stories
on them in the paper. Glance at the scores as you would look at the
weather forecast. Peek if you must, but be strong. The real games
begin Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   __ Six words no one wants to hear while sitting in the barber's
chair: Michael Irvin will cut your hair.
</P>
<P>
   __ Always thought that when players get cut from training camp
it meant they were off the team, not sliced with scissors. Maybe
that's why I never played high school football.
</P>
<P>
   __ Don't bet on the Buckeyes. Ohio State, which was the
Associated Press' No. 1 team in the preseason poll, has about as
much chance ending up No. 1 as John Cooper does of beating
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   And that reason _ Cooper's failings against the Wolverines _
will guarantee Ohio State will have at least one loss on its
record. Ohio State is 1-8-1 against the Wolverines under Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Reason No. 2: The Buckeyes were the No. 1 team five times in
previous preseason polls. They didn't wind up No. 1 in any of those
years.
</P>
<P>
   Reason No. 3: Since the AP began preseason rankings in 1950, no
team has held the top spot from start to finish. Eight teams that
were No. 1 in the preseason ended up No. 1 after the bowls _ the
last was Florida State in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   __ So THAT was USC's problem last year. They had a tight end
playing quarterback. It all makes sense now.
</P>
<P>
   __ When they write the obituary on the Dodgers season _ and
believe me, it's almost complete _ this is one stat to which they
can point: The Dodgers won only three times in a nine-game,
mid-August stretch against Montreal, Pittsburgh and Florida. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   __ There's no truth to the rumor that O.J. Simpson has stopped
looking for the real killers and is now helping Tommy Lasorda look
for the Dodgers' next general manager.
</P>
<P>
   __ Here's one for the refrigerator door: No one will break Roger
Maris' record this year. Free bonus forecast: The New York Yankees
won't win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   __ Obscure baseball stat of the week: John Olerud of the New
York Mets is trying to become the first player since Ed Delahanty
in 1902 to win hitting titles in both leagues. Olerud, the 1993 AL
batting champion with Toronto, is hitting .355 after Saturday's
game to lead the NL.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kansas City will wind up with former Crespi High pitcher Jeff
Suppan after he clears waivers, writes Ken Daley of the Dallas
Morning News. Suppan, the second overall pick of the expansion
draft, is going from Arizona to the Mets as the player to be named
in the Willie Blair deal, then is being dealt to the Royals to
complete the trade for Jermaine Allensworth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
