   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   KILLERKIDS-LAWYERS (Chicago) _ They form a tiny subspecialty in
the legal profession: lawyers who represent children who kill. Why
they do it, and what they say about their clients. By Pam Belluck.
(The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIG-PLAYTHINGS (Lock Haven, Pa.) _ Since the end of the Cold
War, more and more Americans have been rushing to buy surplus
Russian MiGs, Czech L-39s, Polish Iskras and Yugoslavian Sokos as
private playthings. Starting with a handful of planes, the fad has
caught on, and now there are hundreds of civilian-owned fighter
jets. By Tracie Rozhon. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
With photos.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELS (Kinshasa, Congo)_ After several days of relative
quiet in their brief war, both the government and rebel forces here
began furious preparations for what each side expects to be
critical fight for control of this capital city. By Howard W.
French. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Kotradic, Yugoslavia) _ Even as NATO is to begin
military exercises on Monday intended to intimidate the Yugoslav
government into stopping its attacks on civilians in Kosovo, and
despite what Western governments call intense diplomatic pressure,
the shelling and burning _ and now possibly bombing _ are
continuing. By Mike O'Connor. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.) With map.
</P>
<P>
   HORSEFARM-TROPHIES (Lexington, Ky.) _ After Calumet Farm,
thoroughbred racing's most legendary stable, collapsed in
bankruptcy in 1991, its trappings were auctioned off to pay debts.
Today, all that remains of the empire's legacy is a collection of
some 530 trophies and awards, and now that those awards seem headed
for the auction block, a raucous battle has erupted in Bluegrass
country. By Barry Meier. (The story has moved in ``s'' news file.)
2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PGA (Redmond, Wash.) _ Final round of the PGA Championship.
By Clifton Brown. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s'' news
file.)
</P>
