A6229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADN-SECEDE-MEDIA-ART     08-16 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-SECEDE-MEDIA-ART-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER'S GIVING UPSETS SOME ON ITS STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map showing Los Angeles and San Fernando Valley is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You would have had to be looking for it to find
it. But buried in the Aug. 7 edition of The Daily News of Los
Angeles was a disclosure that the newspaper had contributed $60,000
to a group advocating the first step in the San Fernando Valley's
secession from the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution is the largest among known donations to the
group, Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment, amounting to
nearly a third of the $200,000 it has received.
</P>
<P>
   The donation has sparked concern among reporters and editors at
the paper that their impartiality on a divisive issue in Los
Angeles has been compromised. The newspaper's management denies
this is the case, and in an open letter to readers published on the
editorial page on Friday, the newspaper said that future stories on
secession would contain a disclosure about the contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The valley group is petitioning for a state study of whether the
secession idea is feasible, and it needs tens of thousands of
signatures by Aug. 27. ``There weren't enough people behind it for
public debate, so they put money in to ensure public debate,'' said
Amy Collins, an assistant city editor.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNary, a business writer who is president of the paper's
chapter of the Newspaper Guild, said, ``This, for a lot of people
at The Daily News, is difficult, because it's real hard not to come
to the conclusion that this is a partisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the valley have long complained that, besides
enduring its decidedly unglamorous suburban reputation in northern
Los Angeles, on the far side of the Hollywood Hills, the region
does not get a fair return in services for the tax dollars it pays.
So in recent years, support has grown for the valley to break away
from the city of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News, a scrappy 205,000-circulation paper based in the
valley and owned by William Dean Singleton's Medianews Group, which
also owns The Denver Post, has long argued on its editorial pages
that the valley does not get its share of services.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ike Massey, publisher and chief executive of
The Daily News, said that the integrity of the newsroom was not
compromised by the donation and that he had never asked a reporter
or editor to slant a story in favor of the secession movement.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that other newspapers, including The Los Angeles
Times, made donations to causes. (A spokeswoman for The Times,
Laura Morgan, said it had a policy against contributing to
politicians, parties and ballot initiatives.)
</P>
<P>
   Massey rejected the comparison of the donation to a political
contribution, saying it was made to support only a petition drive
for a secession study, not secession itself. But he acknowledged
that he thought The Daily News would benefit from the valley's
becoming a separate city, saying the newspaper would automatically
become the paper of record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we played a major role in the success of the petition
drive,'' Massey said. ``I hope we play that role. I'm not going to
apologize for making this contribution. I'm very proud of making
that contribution. I think the study needs to be done so people in
this valley can make their own decisions about how workable and
beneficial it may or not be to break away from L.A. and create a
new city.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Massey nor David Butler, the editor of the newspaper,
would discuss the timing or circumstances of the contribution.
</P>
<P>
   At a 90-minute meeting attended by about 35 reporters and
editors last Tuesday with Butler and Ron Kaye, the managing editor,
staff members raised concerns that the donation took the paper
across the line between reporting the news and making the news, and
that it would hurt the paper's public perception and trust with
readers, McNary said.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the staff's mood over the donation as one of
resignation and disappointment. Ms. Collins compared the feeling to
what people experience after being betrayed by cheating spouses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's very upsetting,'' Ms. Collins said. ``You work hard, you
make a lot of sacrifices, and one day you wake up and find out: `We
deceived you. We lied to you. We're not working for objectivity;
we're working for Valley VOTE.' Or they're working for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Loeb, the editor of Columbia Journalism Review, agreed:
``When you write an editorial, readers think you are speaking for
what you believe is in the best interests of the people. But when
you contribute money to a campaign, readers think you are speaking
to what's in the best interests of the company. That's the
distinction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
