u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSYBOMBS-KENYA-44     08-16 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSYBOMBS-KENYA-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES QUESTIONING SUSPECT IN AFRICAN BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EMBASSYBOMBS-RDP and EMBASSYBOMBS-ALBANIA) 
(js) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The Kenyan police and American FBI agents were
questioning a man Sunday whom Pakistani authorities deported to
Kenya because of suspicions that he took part in the bombings of
the U.S. embassies here and in Tanzania, Kenyan officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators declined to say where the man was being held or
what role he is accused of having played in the bombings on Aug. 7.
The simultaneous blasts took more than 250 lives and injured
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But Pakistani and Kenyan officials confirmed that the suspect,
identified only as Mohammed Sadek Howaida, 32, had arrived in Kenya
on a flight Sunday morning and was being interrogated at a secret
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are under orders to be tight-lipped about everything,''
said Hardrick Crawford Jr., the assistant special agent in charge
of the joint Kenya-U.S. task force investigating the Nairobi
bombing, when asked about Howaida. ``Our instructions are to remain
silent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, the Foreign Ministry said that Howaida had been
taken into custody soon after his arrival from Nairobi at the
airport in Karachi, Pakistan, the same day the bombs detonated.
</P>
<P>
   He left Nairobi the night before on a Pakistan International
Airways flight. He was initially detained because customs officers
suspected he was traveling under a forged passport, Pakistani
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. officials said on Saturday that American
investigators had gone to Pakistan to question the man, it was
unclear Sunday whether the American agents accompanied him to
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Sunday, the Pakistani Foreign Ministry took
pains to say that Howaida had been turned over to Kenyan
authorities. One apparent reason is that in the past terrorists
have retaliated against American targets in Pakistan after the
Pakistani police handed suspects over to American investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry identified Howaida as an ``Arab national,''
a phrase which means only that he could be from nearly anywhere in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Among other questions, investigators here are looking into
whether there is a link between Howaida and the Saudi
multimillionaire Osama bin Laden, who has been living in
neighboring Afghanistan for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden is a vocal critic of the United States and has been
identified by American law enforcement officials as a major sponsor
of terrorism. From the moment the bombs detonated, investigators
have suspected bin Laden's loose network of Islamic fundamentalist
organizations, which are said to be among the few terrorist
networks with the technical capability and financial resources to
mount simultaneous attacks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sunday's Pakistani newspapers identified the suspect by a
slightly different name, Mohammed Sadique, and said he had been
detained in Pakistan as he tried to cross the border into
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   One national newspaper, The News, quoted an unnamed government
official as saying that Howaida had confessed to planning the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Foreign Ministry said in its statement only that Howaida
``was interrogated by our concerned agencies and, on satisfaction
about his involvement in these terrorist acts, he was sent back to
Nairobi and handed over to the Kenyan authorities for appropriate
action under their law.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana confirmed that Howaida had
been turned over to the police here and that he was being held in
connection with the car-bomb attacks. He said it was still unclear
if Kenya would turn the suspect over to the United States should
enough evidence be found to charge him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lawyers will have to look at the subject in greater
detail,'' he said. ``Both countries will have grounds for claiming
jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mbuvi, the assistant director of the Kenyan Criminal
Investigation Division, which is working with the FBI on the case,
said he could not comment on the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents who answered the telephone at the headquarters for
the joint investigation also declined to give any details about
Howaida or to explain why he was being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to answer those kinds of questions,'' one agent
said, before hanging up.
</P>
</TEXT>
