<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-WEEK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDITORS: Sunday's games out at the time this story moves to
wires: Orioles-Indians.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 6-1 (90-30), Orioles 5-1 (65-57 through
Saturday), Red Sox 3-3 (71-50), Blue Jays 4-2 (62-61), Devil Rays
3-4 (48-73).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild card hunt: Red Sox lead league, Orioles 6 1/2 games back,
Blue Jays 10 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Yanks keep rolling. They have led in 45
consecutive games and finished their homestand at 10-1. The Yankees
are 60 games over .500 and just one other team ever got to that
point _ the Orioles in 1969 when they were 108-48.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Yankees have batted around 28 times this
year, while Orioles catcher Chris Hoiles became the ninth player in
major league history to hit two grand slams in a game on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Toronto ace Roger Clemens struck out 15 Saturday
but didn't get a win in what turned out to be a 6-3 loss to the
Angels in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Yankees lost a game last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Red Sox DH Reggie Jefferson had his rehab
assignment cut short when he reinjured his back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Baltimore's Cal Ripken played in his 2,600th
straight game Saturday, 486 more than Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Baltimore could move even closer
to the Red Sox in the wild-card race with games against the Twins
and Devil Rays. Boston opens this week with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: White Sox 4-2 (55-66), Royals 2-4 (55-68), Tigers 2-4
(48-73), Twins 2-5 (54-68), Indians 1-4 (66-55 through Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild card hunt: None.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Indians signed Cecil Fielder, hoping he can
fill in at first base some and also in the DH spot until Jim Thome
(broken thumb) gets off the DL. Fielders hit .241 with 17 homers
and 68 RBIs with the Angles.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Royals third baseman Dean Palmer has 21 RBIs in
his last 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Detroit's Bryce Florie struck out a career-high
10 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Twins signed a new two-year lease with the
Metrodome, meaning the club will remain in Minnesota at least
through the 2000 season. There are three one-year options that
could extend it through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Tigers second baseman Damon Easley will miss
four to five games with a broken finger on his right hand while
Minnesota's Paul Molitor injured his right ankle and may have to go
on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Royals did Glendon Rusch a favor putting him on
the DL. Rusch, with tendinitis in his left shoulder, is tied for
the major-league lead in losses with 15 with Willie Blair of the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Poor Kansas City. Already 0-8
against the Yankees this season, the Royals have to face them twice
this week.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Angels 5-2 (66-57), Rangers 2-4 (65-57), A's 2-4
(54-69), Mariners 1-4 (55-66).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild card hunt: Rangers 6 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Angels bounced back, taking over the
division lead as the Rangers ran into the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. ended a 12-game home
run drought on Saturday, his longest in his career. He now has 42
homers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: One pitcher that can beat the Yankees is Todd
Stottlemyre of the Yankees, picking up his fourth straight win at
Yankee Stadium on Saturday. His 12 career wins over New York are
his most against any team.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: A's outfielder Rickey Henderson became the
oldest player to steal 50 bases in a season. He is 39.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Angels activated pitcher Jack McDowell off
the DL over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Mariners starter Bill Swift doesn't need an extra
day of rest. On five days' rest, he is 3-6 while he is 7-0 on his
regular four days.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: A Rangers-Red Sox showdown starts
tonight in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
