<SLUG> BC-ONTHEMONEY-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE FIRMS BEGINNING SUBSIDY FEE 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Starting this month, your phone bill probably will include an extra
charge for the ``Universal Connectivity'' program recently approved
by the Federal Communications Commission. This new initiative
subsidizes the cost of Internet hookups for schools, libraries and
rural health-care facilities.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All telecommunications companies are required to help fund the
program, and &UR;  &LR; they're allowed to recover the cost any way they
want, including passing it along to customers. For example, AT&AMP;T
has added an additional 93 cents to its customers' July bills.
</P>
<P>
   But one AT&AMP;T customer called me to protest the fact that even
low-income customers who qualify for the ``Universal Lifeline''
reduced rates are being forced to pay the extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T representative said its current policy is not to waive
the fee, even in cases of extreme hardship, but that it is
reviewing this policy. You can find out more about the program by
clicking on ``Universal Service'' under the hot-topics section of
the FCC's Web site, www.fcc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE COSTS: From 1980 to 1996, tuition at U.S. colleges and
universities jumped 90 percent, compared with only a 9 percent
increase in average income for families with college-age children,
according to a recent survey by the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the number of students borrowing for college has
more than doubled during the past decade, says the U.S. Department
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   About 52 percent of all students who graduated from college in
1996 had outstanding loans, with an average total debt of $11,950.
That's up from 35 percent who were debt-ridden at diploma time in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION IRAS: The good news in light of the above is that you
now can invest for a portion of future tuition costs on a
tax-favored basis with an Education IRA, the new investment vehicle
created by Congress this year. You can invest up to $500 per child
per year. The amount doesn't count against the maximums for other
IRAs. There's been discussion in Congress about raising the $500
limit, which to many investors seems too low to make a real dent in
future college bills. Last week, Strong Funds launched
www.education &QL; 
IRA.com, which includes information about these funds, interactive
calculators and educational materials for college planning.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Amy Doan can be reached at
doana &LR; sfgate.com or by calling (415) 536-5134.
</P>
</TEXT>
