<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AND IRISH GOVERNMENTS VOW TO HUNT DOWN OMAGH CAR BOMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NIRELAND-BOMB) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The British and Irish Republic
governments said Sunday that they would hunt down those responsible
for Saturday's car bombing that killed 28 people and wounded more
than 200 in Omagh, a usually quiet town in the center of Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the deadliest in 29 years of sectarian violence
in this predominantly Protestant British province. But in a sense,
it was expected by London and Dublin, sponsors of the peace
agreement designed to give the minority Roman Catholics more power
here and to give the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic more
influence in Northern affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As the peace agreement moved close to approval last spring, both
Prime Ministers _ Tony Blair of Britain and Bertie Ahern of the
Irish Republic _ warned that splinter groups, Catholic and
Protestant, would not honor the cease-fires being observed by the
mostly Catholic Irish Republican Army and two major Protestant
paramilitary groups, the Ulster Volunteer Force and the Ulster
Freedom Fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Their worst fears were realized in Saturday's attack, and Sunday
night they met here to discuss how to catch the killers. The most
intense focus was on a group that calls itself Real IRA, because
most officials and ordinary people believe the group placed the
deadly car bomb on Market Street.
</P>
<P>
   Other Catholic groups, the Irish National Liberation Army and
the Continuity IRA, have not been active in recent weeks, although
they have denounced the peace agreement and the cease-fire. A
particularly violent Protestant group, the Loyalist Volunteer
Force, declared last week that it was ceasing military operations.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and ordinary people continued Sunday to discuss the
tactics in the bombing, in which police were apparently misled in a
phone call that warned the attack would be near the courthouse.
Acting on the warning, police moved hundreds of people to a point
nearer the eventual explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Most people said Sunday that it made no difference whether the
group that carried out the attack deliberately or mistakenly misled
the police.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Republic President Mary McAleese seemed to reflect the
feeling of most people in Omagh, 55 miles west of Belfast, after
she inspected the blood-stained rubble there this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever planted that bomb knew exactly what they were doing,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic dissidents say that the peace agreement is a sellout
that will not lead to a united Ireland. Protestant dissidents also
say that the agreement is a sellout _ the first step in an eventual
withdrawal of Britain from the island, leaving the North to be
subsumed in the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA is made up of dissidents who disapprove of the IRA
cease-fire and of the peace agreement involving Sinn Fein, the
IRA's political wing. The splinter group is believed to have about
100 members, some highly skilled in making bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily, newspapers here and in Dublin report that a
mastermind bomber who is a former ranking IRA official lives near
Dundalk, in the Irish Republic near the border. Security officials
say that they do not have enough evidence to arrest him, even
though police and intelligence officers have information on some of
the small units of the Real IRA
</P>
<P>
   ``The intelligence people always have a lot of information, but
they never have enough,'' said David McKittrick, author of several
books on Northern Ireland. This meant, he said, that the police
might thwart 20 planned operations, but the 21st will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Last Spring, five members of the 32 County Sovereignty
Committee, a mostly Catholic political group, were imprisoned for
attempting to highjack a bank truck in County Wicklow, south of
Dublin. The group is led by Bernadette Sands McKevitt, whose
brother, Bobby Sands, became an IRA martyr when he starved himself
to death in a British prison in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Blair said of the dissident terrorists: ``They are a
small group of people, a tiny fanatic group of people. They have no
political base, they have no votes, they have no support in
Northern Ireland, they have just this capacity for evil and yet, I
am sure that the will of vast majority of people in Northern
Ireland is going to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ahern: ``We are determined to defeat this campaign in short
order. Whatever it is necessary to do, we will do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
