<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOUR FIRM KEEPS REFUNDS TO CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:   I work in a doctor's office where patients often end up with
small credits on their accounts. The office policy is not to refund
the money if it is under $10 unless the patient specifically
requests it. But often, the patients don't even know they have a
credit. Are there any laws that set up guidelines for refunds?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; There's a California law that covers instances where
doctors receive two duplicate payments for the same service _ for
instance, one payment from the patient and one from the patient's
insurance company. That law (Section 732 of the Business &AMP;
Professional Code) requires doctors to refund the patient's
overpayment within four months, unless the patient explicitly asks
to keep the credit on his or her account.
</P>
<P>
   There's no similar law aimed specifically at situations where a
patient simply overpays for a service.
</P>
<P>
   But a judge probably would rule that holding onto patients'
overpayments is a violation of state unfair-trade-practice laws,
according to Richard A. Elbrecht, an attorney with the California
Department of Consumer Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This firm should set up a procedure to notify patients and ask
them what they want to do with their credit,'' Elbrecht said. ``If
it doesn't notify them, a district attorney could make a very
persuasive case for a court order requiring the firm to go through
its records and refund those amounts. They could also face fines of
up to $2,500 per violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hats off to you for keeping an independent eye out for what's
legal _ and ethical _ at your workplace!
</P>
<P>
   And let's hope the folks who run the office are willing to
listen to your advice and do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; My friend runs a small six-person office. She needs to fire
an employee who's been there for 12 years, but she isn't sure how
to do it. Any advice?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Let's assume these workers are ``at will'' employees,
people who are not covered by a union or individual contract. Your
friend then has a lot of freedom to decide when and whom to fire,
with certain exceptions:
</P>
<P>
   _ She can't terminate people because of age, sex, race, national
origin, religion or sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   _ She can't fire them for blowing the whistle on illegal company
practices.
</P>
<P>
   _ She may not be able to fire them if they received a written or
verbal promise of job security _ for instance, a manager's
statement that ``if you can handle the work here, you'll have a job
for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Your friend should be especially careful in this case because
she's dealing with such a long-term employee. In some cases, courts
have said that veteran employees who have received a steady stream
of raises and promotions have an ``implied contract'' and may be
fired only for good cause.
</P>
<P>
   To protect herself from potential lawsuits, your friend should
carefully document this employee's performance problems. She should
also provide some warning and some chance for the employee to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's kept this person on for 12 years and suddenly decides
that their work isn't up to snuff, I think she's obliged to give
them some warning,'' said Barbara Kate Repa, a lawyer who has
written several books on employment issues for Nolo Press in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should be very specific and relate it to the employee's
job duties,'' Repa continued. ``She should say something like,
`This is what you need to do differently. If you haven't done it
within two weeks (or some other window of time), we will have to
dismiss you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Want to know more? This is an area where it pays to be very,
very careful _ both to avoid lawsuits and to ensure that employees
are fairly treated.
</P>
<P>
   One excellent resource is ``The Employer's Legal Handbook'' by
Fred Steingold, available from Nolo Press at (800) 992-6656.
</P>
<P>
   Other relevant books are ``The American Bar Association Guide to
Workplace Law'' by Barbara J. Fick (Times Books) and ``Rightful
Termination'' by Ron Visconti and Richard Stiller, which is
available from Crisp Publications at (800) 442-7477. The California
Chamber of Commerce also sells a guidebook on hiring and
terminating employees, at (916) 444-6670.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; What's the point of having sick time or vacation time if
you can't use it? My wife's boss tells her she must ``clean her
desk'' before taking any time off. But there's never an end to the
work she's assigned. The boss complains when she tries to take even
a day or two off. The last time we took a long weekend, my wife got
a letter of reprimand in her file about delaying some project.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Before blaming the boss, consider whether your wife may be
responsible for part of the problem. Has she done enough to train
co-workers to carry the ball while she's gone? Does she organize
her work flow well enough to anticipate problems that could arise
during her time off?
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, does she know how to say ``no'' to her boss?
</P>
<P>
   It can be scary to say, ``I'm sorry, I can't take on this new
project right now because I have a vacation coming up.'' But it
certainly beats taking on the assignment and then flubbing it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that your wife IS great at training colleagues,
organizing her work and saying ``no'' _ but the boss still grumbles
when she takes time off.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the problem may be that your wife's department is
chronically understaffed, suggests Gae Shulman, a small-business
consultant with the Portable Personnel Dept. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Your wife should ask for a performance review to raise her
concerns, Shulman says. If her immediate boss isn't receptive, try
someone higher up the ladder or in human resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should talk about the job description and the company's
expectations of her work,'' Shulman said. ``She should also get a
sense of what's expected from the same job at other companies. It
may be that her boss doesn't realize it's time to add another staff
person.''
</P>
<P>
   There's yet another possibility. Your wife may simply be stuck
with an inflexible, endlessly demanding supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, her only recourse may be to start looking around
for a new job that allows room for a reasonable amount of time off.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; OVERPAYMENT NOTE: Several weeks ago, I had an item about a
company that had overpaid its workers and was demanding the money
back. Karen Moffitt, a payroll tax analyst at Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.,
offers a tip to employees who have had to return overpayments: Make
sure the overpayment is not counted as part of your income in your
W-2 tax form at the end of the year. After all, you don't want to
pay taxes on money that you've had to give back.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or
send e-mail to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query in person, but we will answer as many
in print as we can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
