<HEADLINE>
FINDING CELLULAR CALLERS IN AN EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Calif., Mo.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Silicon Valley start-up company has begun the
first public-safety trial of a system that will enable
cellular-telephone users to broadcast their locations to 911
emergency-system operators. It has implications, as well, for
commercial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The trial _ which is being undertaken by officials of the city
of Denver, Denver County and Adams County, Colo. _ uses special
software inside the cellular handset in combination with a central
office system employing global positioning, or GPS, technology to
determine a caller's location.
</P>
<P>
   In tests in the Denver area, the system is providing accuracy at
distances just over 100 yards, which permits dispatchers to make
better decisions on which public-safety officers should respond to
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The software-based system was developed by Snaptrack Inc., a San
Jose, Calif.-based company whose approach differs in its
technological design from competing systems being developed by
companies like True Position, Grayson and Sirf Technology, another
Silicon Valley-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Snaptrack embeds software in the phone that takes advantage of a
specialized high-speed chip known as a digital signal processor, or
DSP. All cellular phones employ such chips, but in the Snaptrack
system, the cellular phone's software works in concert with a
central computer that provides additional processing and data to
improve accuracy in determining the phone's location and thus
improves emergency response time.
</P>
<P>
   There is now an industry-wide rush to develop technology for
cellular location detection because the Federal Communications
Commission has required that wireless carriers be able to provide
location information that is accurate within 125 meters _ 136.7
yards _ at least 67 percent of the time by October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Although the FCC's requirement created an instant market for the
technology, a number of commercial applications will follow,
including navigation systems and mobile yellow pages.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts worry that the commission's role in
creating the market may rush the development of a technology that
would otherwise be driven by new commercial applications as prices
drop for GPS receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market is very distorted because it's being driven by the
911 mandate,'' said Ira Brodsky, president of Datacomm Research, a
market research company just outside St. Louis. ``The problem is
that a lot of technology decisions are being made too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three competing technologies now being tested by
phone manufacturers and wireless carriers has competing strengths
and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   For example, network-based approaches use software in the
cellular operator's equipment to triangulate the location of a
particular cellular phone by comparing the arrival times of signals
from three different cellular antennas.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems may represent the least expensive approach, and
have the advantage of working with existing cellular phones. But
they have raised privacy concerns because location information will
be held centrally within the wireless network. In addition, it is a
passive technology in that the phone company can locate the user
without his even knowing he is being tracked, as long as his phone
is turned on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Location is an important tool, but you're talking about your
physical person,'' said Ellen Kirk, vice president for marketing
and strategic planning at Snaptrack. ``That's information people
don't want to be collected or broadcast. It's a question of whose
finger is on the button.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to beginning the public trial of its technology in
the Denver region, Snaptrack plans on Monday to announce that its
product will be adopted by a subsidiary of NTT, Japan's
telecommunications giant. The Snaptrack technology will be used
first in a wireless palm computer that the NTT unit plans to
introduce in the second quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   It will begin offering the feature in cellular phones sometime
in the second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Snaptrack is in a tightly competitive race with Sirf Technology,
which uses a global-positioning receiver chip to place the entire
information-tracking function inside a telephone or other consumer
appliance. Last week, Sirf announced deals with Nokia of Finland
and Ericcson of Sweden, the world's two largest makers of digital
cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Seven wireless carriers _ Airtouch, Ameritech, Bell Mobility,
GTE, Primeco, Sprint PCS and U S West _ are jointly evaluating the
Snaptrack technology. VLSI Technology is the first chip vendor to
join the testing. Industry reports indicate that cellular-handset
vendors involved in the project include Denso, Hyundai, LG,
Motorola, Nokia and Samsung.
</P>
<P>
   Snaptrack officials said the strengths of their combination
handset and network approach included a cold-start location ability
of only seconds and more precise location accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the principal limitations on GPS technology in the past
has been that the slow rate of data coming down from satellite
transmitters could result in waits as long as 15 minutes to
calculate a precise fix.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Snaptrack technology will use ground-based
transmitters to improve the accuracy of GPS data _ which is
intentionally degraded by the U.S. military _ the technology will
provide best-case location accuracy of five yards or so.
</P>
</TEXT>
