<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARWASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The newest rub for ritzy cars is having them hand-washed while
you socialize
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nothing seems so suddenly, and sudsily, chic as the
once-lowly car wash.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, holding a junk-bond portfolio was a sure mark of
affluence. Now it's having somebody hand-wash your quarterpanels in
public, while you nurse a latte.
</P>
<P>
   The International Carwash Association estimates there are 75,000
car washes in America, up 14 percent from a year ago, with $18.2
billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta has 40 full-service car washes, not counting
scores of mechanical washers in the backs of gas stations and quick
marts.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, what's spurring the boom, is the increased cost and
lifespan of cars, says Mark Thorsby, ICA's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to a house, automobiles are Americans' biggest
investment,'' Thorsby says. ``And, 10 years ago the average length
of ownership was 3.2 years. Nowadays it's a little more than eight
years.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many car owners in a city proud of its reputation as
international and nouveau riche, maintaining the four-wheeled
investment may not be the prime motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a town where people need to impress each other,'' says
Suzanne Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter left her job as an IBM executive and last month bought
the Buckhead Detail Center, which she's begun to refurbish.
</P>
<P>
   She says she's washed just two cars in her life. She's a
marketer. And what she sees in Buckhead is a ripe customer base of
the overpaid and underwashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their cars are an extension of their personality. They say:
`I'm a success,''' Carter says. ``So it helps if they're clean.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been that way. Once, car washing was simply a
chore that needed to be done, as quickly and cheaply if possible.
Even in Atlanta, some people still see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   At the Two Minit Car Wash in Midtown Atlanta , the emphasis is
on speed and price.
</P>
<P>
   The Two Minit is no hand-wash salon. Crews prep cars in the back
and towel-dry them in front, but the bulk of the cleaning is done
by machine. A basic wash takes _ you guessed it _ two minutes.
Cost: $9.95, dollars less than what chic hand-rub places charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Two Minit, which opened in 1955, is probably the city's
oldest car wash.
</P>
<P>
   But it's maybe the last place to be seen if you're concerned
about the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're about is a good wash in a reasonable amount of
time,'' says second-generation owner Paul Coleman. ``There's more
to life than standing around and staring at the walls of a car
wash.''
</P>
<P>
   At the new-generation car washes, such as Avril's Auto Boutique
in Buckhead, however, customers don't have to just stare. They can
also ogle. On sunny weekends, the outdoor deck takes on the
schmoozy air of a trendy restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Well-heeled customers sit under umbrellas, prop their feet up,
and sip gourmet coffee and juice while crews of mostly college kids
hand-wash and wax their four-wheeled darlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say there are bars to be seen in in
Buckhead,'' says Paula Rodgers, 34, on a recent Saturday, watching
her black Lexus SC400 being waxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be the car wash to be seen in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like liposuction clinics or toenail salons, even the
fashionable places have something gritty and grotty to contend
with. Blaine Tyler, a manager at Avril's, recalls a customer a few
weeks ago who left her car windows open overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``A possum crawled in the back seat and had babies,'' he says,
wincing. ``Have you ever smelled a stench like that? It was
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Esposito Jr., owner of the 1-year-old Mammoth Hand Car
Wash/Detail Salon, says he often deals with the aftermath of
customers ``drinking all night and throwing up in their cars.'' He
recalls some exceptional cases as well: Once his crew had to buff
the scratches out of the finish of a brand-new Mercedes. ``The
owner's kids decided to clean the car for dad,'' says Esposito.
``Unfortunately, they used SOS pads.''
</P>
<P>
   With the proliferation of car washes has come a flood of
marketing gimmicks. The biggest trend is ``adding new profit
centers,'' says ICA's Thorsby, and those range from cellular phone
sales, to cappuccino bars, to fast food and dry cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is putting in an expensive sound system at her car wash
and will program it accordingly: ``Peaceful music on Sunday
mornings,'' she says. ``And Friday will be more festive.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plans also call for a coffee bar, Ferrari rentals and maybe
mini-massages for customers.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago Avril's began offering a monthly Club Card for
$44.95, entitling members to an unlimited number of basic washes,
normally $18 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   The card has caught on maybe a little better than hoped. ``Some
people come in every other day,'' Tyler says. ``They'll want the
whole car washed because of a single bird dropping on the
windshield.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Minit's Coleman says he doesn't fret losing business to
fancy swabbie-come-latelys. A quick wash, he says, is like ``fast
food. There's a big demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
