<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6241 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUYOUTS-SLACKERS--SFC     08-16 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYOUTS-SLACKERS--SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BUYOUTS ARE OFFERED TO SLACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Companies have long used voluntary employee buyouts as a way to
trim their workforces with a little less pain than outright
layoffs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The downside? Sometimes, a company's best employees choose to
jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a small number of firms are experimenting with a new type
of buyout aimed at keeping star employees on board. In effect,
they're targeting their golden parachutes at workers who are poor
performers or just-plain-average performers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is offering a generous buyout program to salaried
employees whom it considers underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   And Applied Materials in Santa Clara is in the middle of a
buyout based on a variety of factors _ including a worker's job
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing performance mentioned more and more as a
criteria (in buyouts),'' said John Challenger, with the Chicago
outplacement firm of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas. ``These firms
are doing what every company wants to do _ putting together a plan
to cut costs, limit legal exposure and target people who are the
bottom 10 percent performers.''
</P>
<P>
   Workforce experts note that performance-related buyouts remain
an unusual occurrence. The vast majority of firms offering buyouts
still target them at longtime workers close to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also caution that performance-related buyouts may create
some unintended and unwanted consequences for companies.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, disgruntled employees could sue for defamation or
discrimination if they feel unjustly targeted for a buyout offer.
Or morale among good employees could suffer if they view the
buyouts as an unfair reward for colleagues who never pulled their
own weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``People could see it as a `failure bonus' _ an incentive to be
a poor performer,'' said Charles King, an employee pay expert with
William M. Mercer in San Francisco. ``This could send a hell of a
message to people who are breaking their necks for the company and
feel underappreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyouts first became common in the 1980s, when corporate mergers
and acquisitions fueled a nationwide wave of staffing cuts that
made the term ``downsizing'' a household word.
</P>
<P>
   Many big companies chose to reduce their ranks through voluntary
buyouts rather than forced layoffs. They saw buyouts as more humane
and less likely to lead to wrongful-termination lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical buyout, a company offers employees who agree to
bail out a package of incentives nicknamed a ``parachute.'' It may
include cash plus other perks, such as job-search help or continued
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real sensible approach to start out with voluntary
reductions and, if you don't get enough takers, move to involuntary
reductions,'' said Mitchell Marks, a San Francisco management
consultant who specializes in transitions and downsizing. ``There
are hard business reasons, in that people who leave on good terms
are less likely to be litigious. It's also useful from a morale
perspective, with an eye on (continued loyalty from) the
`survivors.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While layoffs commonly are aimed at poor performers, voluntary
buyouts traditionally have been offered on a basis of age and
tenure _ focused on those people closest to retirement. For
instance, a company might offer buyouts to workers whose age and
years of service add up to 80 _ so a 55-year-old with 25 years on
the job would be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But companies found that this sometimes cost them their most
motivated and skilled employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is that your best people take the windfall and go
find another job,'' Challenger said. ``You keep the mediocre
performers, who don't want to take the risk of leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, some companies now try to design buyout plans that
take performance into account.
</P>
<P>
   William Hollett, a severance expert with the outplacement firm
of Drake Beam Morin, has set up about a half-dozen
performance-based buyouts in the past three years for clients.
</P>
<P>
   Hollett uses a system called ``forced rankings,'' in which
managers sit down and privately rank their employees in a range of
skills. Employees are given points for each skill. Then their
overall results are tallied up, and buyouts are offered to those
with the lowest total scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a little more creativity (than a traditional buyout)
to make sure there's no legal exposure, but it's worked well,''
Hollett said.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials, the world's largest semiconductor-equipment
manufacturer, started a performance-related buyout program in June
aimed at shedding 1,000 of the firm's 15,000 jobs by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Jeff Lettes declined to give details of the
buyout, which is Applied's first voluntary reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Lettes did say the company selected employees for the buyout on
several criteria _ their particular skills, job function, length of
service and ``relative historical contribution to company
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of that, Applied also considered the one-to-five rating
that it gives all employees during annual performance reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we want to keep our best people,'' Lettes said.
``But we've got to weigh all these factors with an eye to best
serving our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ford Motor Co. is putting the final touches on a
performance-based buyout that could eliminate several thousand of
the company's 53,000 nonunion U.S. employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford buyout made national headlines last month when an
internal memo was leaked to the press that said the company intends
to target ``low performers'' and ``average/solid employees with
limited potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's program, which will be officially presented to employees
this fall, is likely to be fairly generous. The Detroit Free Press
reported that employees may receive up to 12 months' ``separation
allowance'' and insurance benefits, a two-year paid lease on a used
Ford vehicle, training or relocation money, cash bonuses and other
perks.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's effort also is particularly unusual in that it seems
aimed at eliminating some average employees as well as
below-average ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the folks will be very strong performers who have made
a strong contribution over a period of years,'' said Ford
spokeswoman Francine Romine-MacBride. ``But if there doesn't appear
to be any room for them to improve, this is an opportunity for them
to separate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers wondered whether Ford was setting a
mathematically impossible, Lake Wobegon-like goal of a workforce
where 100 percent of the people are ``above average.''
</P>
<P>
   Others questioned whether employees who take the buyout will
find their future career prospects clouded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who do go could face a stigma in the marketplace: `These
people were let go because they're underperformers,' '' said
Challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also said Ford could open itself up to discrimination
lawsuits by relying on subjective criteria like performance rather
than objective ones like retirement eligibility or tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When clients ask us about using performance as a criteria, we
caution them about the legal implications because I have yet to run
across a company that's 100 percent comfortable with its
performance-evaluation system,'' Hollett said.
</P>
<P>
   Romine-MacBride responded that Ford will use some other criteria
along with performance, such as eligibility for retirement. And she
said the program will be administered fairly and discretely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to walk down the hall and say, `You're a
loser; you're average; you're great _ everyone's who's below
average step forward,' '' Romine-MacBride said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who try to apply somewhere else may face questions
about whether they were let go for low performance,'' she added.
``But through letters of reference, they can establish what their
strengths and accomplishments were.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ford's program could end up as a national test case, with
employers around the country watching to see how it works.
</P>
<P>
   And if it does succeed, workers across America increasingly may
see the next round of golden handshakes going to the slacker or
sleeper down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, it makes good sense,'' said Rick Beal, a
compensation expert with Watson Wyatt Worldwide in San Francisco.
``If you have to cut, you'd always prefer not to take out the
people who are really good performers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
