<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMARTCARD-VERIFONE--SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART CARDS ON A ROLL IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER SINTON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Visitors to any of McDonald's 870 outlets in Germany soon will be
able to load up on more than fries, shakes and a Big Mac.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using technology provided in part by Hewlett-Packard subsidiary
VeriFone, they will be able to electronically download money from
their bank accounts onto plastic ``smart'' cards to quickly pay for
fast food.
</P>
<P>
   The German program, to be announced today, marks the broadest
deployment of smart cards that can be loaded with monetary value to
pay for purchases at a retail or restaurant chain.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a magnetic stripe, these cards are embedded with a
computer chip that can perform many functions, including storing
money, recording financial transactions and tracking frequent-buyer
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Smart cards have been tested in the United States at the Olympic
Games in Atlanta, selected stores in Manhattan and several other
sites including corporate and university campuses. But ``they have
not worked out in any way, shape or form,'' said Dataquest analyst
Allen Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, smart cards are used to pay for parking,
transportation, phone calls and more. But in the United States,
people are attached to their money. They have not bought the
proposition that there is value not having change rattling around
in your pocket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One way to get U.S. consumers on the smart card bandwagon,
Weiner said, is to offer incentives like frequent-flier and other
loyalty programs.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's is considering ``customer loyalty and incentive
program offers,'' but nothing has been finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Smart cards, though, are far more commonplace in Europe than in
America. In Germany, for example, the GeldKarte &UR;  &LR; smart card program
has distributed nearly 40 million smart cards since early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, users have had to go to banks to transfer monetary
value to their cards. But soon, they will be able to go to any
McDonald's, load value onto their cards at an ATM-like terminal and
then slide their cards through a VeriFone smart card reader to pay
for their meals.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot program at 55 McDonald's Deutschland outlets earlier
this year registered 30,000 smart card transactions in the first 10
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this implementation will help drive smart card
acceptance globally, as other restaurant and retail chains will
want to achieve the same speed of service, efficiencies, security
and marketing advantages McDonald's has today,'' said VeriFone
chief executive Robin Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto-based VeriFone has shipped more than 6 million
electronic-payment systems. Early this year, the Rite Aid drugstore
chain ordered 25,000 VeriFone smart card readers for 3,900 of its
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Although that contract is larger than the McDonald's deal, those
units could deduct purchases only from stored-value cards. They
could not connect with the customer's bank to be reloaded with
cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
