<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE WEIGHS SUING TOBACCO FIRMS FOR HEALTH COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rebuffed by a federal court in their effort to
regulate tobacco products, Clinton administration officials said
Sunday that they were seriously considering lawsuits against
cigarette companies to recover money spent by the federal
government in treating smokers under Medicare and other federal
health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., has repeatedly urged the administration
to file such lawsuits, but White House and Justice Department
officials expressed little interest until a comprehensive tobacco
bill died in the Senate in June.
</P>
<P>
   Now, officials from the White House, the Justice Department and
the Department of Health and Human Services said, they are
seriously considering lawsuits that would seek huge amounts in
damages, possibly tens of billions of dollars. The evolving
strategy was described Sunday in the The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, senior adviser to President Clinton, said Clinton
``has ordered a top-to-bottom review of the options for federal
lawsuits to recover Medicare costs, the costs we've incurred under
Medicare for tobacco-related illnesses.'' Emanuel said, ``We want
to see if we can recoup these costs, just as some states have won
reimbursement for their Medicaid costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for the elderly and disabled.
Medicaid provides care to low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Another White House official said that federal agencies were
collecting data and information needed for lawsuits against the
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are considering similar lawsuits to recover
the federal cost of treating smoking-related illnesses under
veterans' health programs, the Federal Employees Health Benefits
Program and health insurance programs for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, a spokesman for five major tobacco companies,
said he had no immediate comment on the possibility of a lawsuit.
But a consultant to the tobacco industry said: ``Federal officials
have known the health effects of cigarette consumption and have
required warning labels for many years. For them to come in now and
say they want to recover damages, after that long involvement,
would be a very difficult case to make.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal health official said that a lawsuit was ``not by any
means our first choice as a course of action.'' Administration
officials said they still hoped Congress would pass a bill raising
cigarette prices and affirming the government's authority to
regulate tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Richmond,
Va., ruled that the Food and Drug Administration had no such
authority because Congress never intended that the agency regulate
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Several Justice Department lawyers are working full time on the
issue, trying to identify the strongest arguments to make in
lawsuits against the five big tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   One question, lawyers said, is how to prove the amount of
illness caused by the products of each tobacco company. The
question could be complicated by the fact that some smokers say
they do not remember what brands they smoked, or smoked several
brands. Government lawyers said they hoped to use a ``market
share'' theory, under which each company's responsibility for
smoking-related illnesses would be proportional to its share of the
cigarette market.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has drafted legislation that could help the government by
depriving tobacco companies of some of their legal defenses _ for
example, the argument that smokers contributed to their illnesses
by smoking after they knew the risks. Florida adopted such a
measure, overriding the defenses normally available to defendants
under common law, and that apparently spurred the tobacco companies
to agree to an $11 billion settlement with the state last year.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Graham said he might offer such legislation as an
amendment to appropriations bills next month.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation authorizes an ``injured party'' to sue tobacco
companies for costs incurred in treating tobacco-related illnesses.
Justice Department officials have suggested that ``injured party''
be defined broadly to include Medicare, Medicaid, the Department of
Veterans' Affairs, the Indian Health Service and military health
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they did not know if such
legislation was needed. And they could face risks if they
explicitly urged Congress to pass it. For if Congress did not
approve the measure and if the Justice Department filed suit
anyway, the administration would have exposed weaknesses in its
litigation strategy. In other words, tobacco companies could argue,
why would Clinton seek legislation to authorize such lawsuits if
the government already had the right to recover damages, as it
contends?
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers are also studying the use of civil
fraud and racketeering laws as a basis for claims.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they are examining a 1962 law, the Medical Care
Recovery Act, which says the government may recover ``the
reasonable value'' of care and treatment it furnishes to a person
who is injured or suffers a disease as a result of someone else's
negligence. Under this law, the government has recovered the cost
of medical and hospital care provided to members of the armed
services injured in auto accidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
