<SLUG> BC-EMBASSYBOMBS-ALBANIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARS OF VIOLENCE BY ISLAMIC MILITANTS SPUR DIPLOMATS' EVACUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EMBASSYBOMBS-KENYA and EMBASSYBOMBS-RDP) 
(js) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Guarded by marines, American diplomats were
removed from here on Sunday in the face of fears of a possible
terrorist attack on the U.S. Embassy by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
   The worries were fueled not only by the bombings of the American
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, but also by a wave of arrests of
Egyptians suspected of links to the militant Islamic Jihad movement
in Egypt. That movement is, in turn, linked to a prime suspect in
the African bombings, the Saudi financier Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   At least five Islamic militants have been arrested here in seven
weeks. In the latest arrest, on Thursday, an Islamic Jihad member
could face execution in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of August, the group, one of whose splinter
cells assassinated President Anwar el-Sadat in 1981, promised
retaliation against the United States, which it faulted for the
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   That threat was made shortly before the bombings of the
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania that left at least 257 dead and
thousands injured, although it is not known whether the blasts were
directly related to the threat.
</P>
<P>
   But it is known that the leader of the Egyptian group, Ayman
al-Zawahry, has close ties with bin Laden and is believed to be
operating with him from hideouts in Afghanistan. Bin Laden, who
fought the Soviets in Afghanistan alongside Islamic guerrillas, has
been building a worldwide terrorist network, Western intelligence
officials said, to wage what he calls a ``holy war against the Jews
and the Crusaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who were arrested come from a growing body of Islamic
fundamentalist proselytizers, largely from Egypt and Saudi Arabia,
who have recently arrived here trying to spread their faith by,
among other activities, offering to set up village schools or
medical centers in this poverty-stricken land crippled by years of
Communist isolation. Most Albanians are Muslim, a heritage of the
Ottoman Empire. The Islamic recruiting drive comes at a time when
the the mostly Muslim ethnic Albanians in the neighboring Serbian
province of Kosovo are losing a fight for independence against the
Orthodox Christian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those seized here belong to the Islamic Revival
Foundation, which describes itself as a charitable group.
</P>
<P>
   An Islamic organization in London reported that a man named
Ahmad Ismail Ossman was arrested on the street here on Thursday and
faced extradition to Egypt, where he is wanted in connection with
an assassination attempt on former Prime Minister Atef Sebki.
Ossman had been sentenced in absentia to death by an Egyptian court
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ossman was described as ``a volunteer who went to Albania to
help the people,'' by Yasser al-Serri, the president of the Islamic
Observation Center in London, who reported the arrest. Serri
himself is also wanted in Egypt in connection with the attempt on
Sebki. He denies any connection.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The arrests began on June 28 when Interior Ministry police
raided an apartment here, seizing two Egyptians and discovering
apparently official stamps from the Interior Ministry's criminal
police division, customs border crossing posts and the Tirana Bar
Association, along with weapons and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects at first appeared to be placed under house arrest
and asked to leave the country. But at the airport they were
handcuffed by Egyptian officials and taken to Cairo. Albanian
officials identified them as Maget Muhamet Mustafa and Muhamet
Rexhap Houda, but said they had used several different names here.
</P>
<P>
   Less is known about the two subsequent arrests. One man was
identified as Mohammed Hamid Hasan Mahmud. The other was Ahmed
Ibrahaim el-Naggar, whom the authorities here said was the
propaganda chief of Islamic Jihad and had been condemned to death
in Cairo last October for plotting to kill Egyptian officials as
well as plotting to revive the outlawed movement.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian newspapers on Sunday contained fragmentary accounts of
detentions of other Egyptians, including three trying to leave the
country by ferry near the town of Durres.
</P>
<P>
   The hulking tan stucco American embassy building was empty on
Sunday. An Albanian teen-ager in an olive T-shirt and a beret and
carrying a worn AK-47 rifle was posted outside its locked gate.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles up the road, the handful of remaining American
diplomats were under guard in their gated residential compound.
Outside the compound's walls, local women, kerchiefs over their
heads, poked at peasant gardens.
</P>
<P>
   A company of marines from the 22nd Marine Expeditionary Unit
aboard the U.S.S. Austin was called in Friday night, breaking off
from a planned NATO exercise in the area to protect the embassy,
the commander of the operation, Maj. Frank Carroll, said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the marines nor embassy spokespeople would say how many
diplomats left on Sunday. Dependents and nonessential personnel
were evacuated on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
