<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DuPont May Be Seeking to Sell All of Conoco
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, which in May announced plans to sell 20 percent of its
Conoco oil subsidiary to the public, may be looking to sell the
whole thing. Elf Aquitaine, the French oil company, wants to buy
Conoco for $24 billion, according to a report in a London
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes less than a week after British Petroleum said
it would buy Amoco for $48.2 billion in stock and cash, setting off
speculation that more midsized oil companies may merge so they can
hold down costs in an era of cheap oil.
</P>
<P>
   Paper Donates to Secession Cause
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the Aug. 7 edition of The Daily News of Los Angeles
was a disclosure that the newspaper had contributed $60,000 to a
group advocating the first step in the San Fernando Valley's
secession from the rest of the city. The contribution has prompted
concern among reporters and editors at the paper that their
impartiality on a divisive issue in Los Angeles has been
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   A Crack in Banking's Glass Ceiling
</P>
<P>
   The recent work by Jill Greenthal, the lead banker for
Tele-Communications in its agreement to be acquired by AT&AMP;T for $70
billion, earned Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette a $40 million fee, one
of the largest of its kind in banking history, and was a milestone
of sorts. It was one the few times that anyone in the business can
recall a woman taking the lead role in a headline-grabbing public
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping out of Perot's Shadow
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, Electronic Data Systems has tried to define itself
as something other than the company that Ross Perot founded, but
the company never quite escaped his legacy. All that is about to
change as the EDS board seeks a new chairman and chief executive
from outside.
</P>
<P>
   Start-Up Tests Cellular 911 System
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley start-up company has begun the first public
test of a system that will enable cellular-phone users to broadcast
their location to 911 emergency-system operators or to commercial
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The Real Spam Appears on the Web
</P>
<P>
   Hormel stood by for years as Internet users turned its Spam
brand name into a derisive label for unwanted e-mail. But now the
company is looking to the Web as a way to enhance the brand's
image.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones Gets a Make-Over
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones, the counterculture journal of investigative
reporting that catered to the political activism of the baby-boom
generation, is getting a make-over as it seeks to appeal to a
younger audience while at the same time remaining faithful to its
roots. The first issue with the new look _ bigger headlines and
bolder graphics _ will go out this week.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas Shifts Promotion Focus
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority in Nevada has
adopted its first multiyear advertising and marketing plan. The
result is an ambitious program to reposition Las Vegas as an
entertainment destination rather than primarily a gambling mecca.
</P>
</TEXT>
