<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELS-670&AMP;ADD-     08-16 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELS-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT AND REBELS PREPARE FOR BATTLE OVER CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ After several days of relative quiet in their
brief war, both the government and rebel forces here began furious
preparations on Sunday for what each side expects to be a critical
fight for control of this capital city.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who independent witnesses on Sunday said are already
firmly in control of the strategic western port city of Matadi and
the nearby Inga Dam, have reportedly cut off fuel and most food
supplies to Kinshasa and are gathering about 150 miles west of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing to fight to the end, despite a string of major reversals,
the government of President Laurent Kabila said that it had rushed
about 8,000 recently trained troops from a southern military base
toward the capital, where large shipments of weaponry have been
steadily arriving.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-minute effort to shore up his positions, Kabila
reportedly flew to the Angolan capital Sunday for meetings with
that neighboring country's president, Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
Kabila was expected to plead for heavy direct support against the
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila returned to Kinshasa Sunday evening, and heavy security
was in force along the route he took from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The president had spent the last several days in Lubumbashi,
capital of his native southern Katanga region. With the rebels
known to be advancing, his absence from this city was seen by many
as a sign of imminent defeat, at least here.
</P>
<P>
   The question of Angola's position in the war _ which pits
Congolese mutineers backed by Rwanda's experienced military
planners and generous logistical support against a larger but
disorganized and poorly trained government army _ has been seen as
critical to the outcome since the war's start two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since the capture of the far western military base at Kitona by
the rebels on Aug. 4, the rebels have deployed large jet transport
planes apparently financed by Rwanda to mass thousands of their
troops in preparation for an assault on the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Congolese officials and foreign businesspeople
have said that Angola had begun providing heavy air cargo support
to the Congolese army, and had also promised to make available to
Kabila a group of several thousand longtime Congolese exiles, known
as the Katangese Gendarmes, who are veterans of Angola's own
prolonged civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila would undoubtedly like an even more dramatic Angolan
intervention, such as the use of its powerful air force, which was
decisively deployed last June in support of a protagonist in a
civil war in Brazzaville, capital of the neighboring Congo
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   According to African diplomats in this region, Angola
disapproves of Rwanda's second armed intervention in Congolese
politics in as many years, feeling that the east African country is
destabilizing the entire region. It was unclear, however, if
Angola, whose relations with Kabila have been unsteady, would want
to commit its forces heavily in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   With reports from residents and journalists in the west of the
country confirming the worst, Kabila's advisers have dropped the
pretense that the government still controls Matadi, and the crucial
hydroelectric dam at Inga, which supplies the capital and much of
the region with electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them maintained, nonetheless, an air of striking
confidence on Sunday, despite what would appear to be a dire
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not without friends too, and the Rwandans risk learning
that at their expense'' said one of Kabila's senior associates.
``We have begun getting weapons from a lot of places. We have air
transport now, and we have lots of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can survive the next couple of days, this will turn into
a debacle for the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's adviser's timetable seemed to accord with recent rebel
claims that insurgents would take Kinshasa as early as Tuesday. In
apparent anticipation of a final push around that date, Washington
closed its embassy here on Saturday for the first time in this
country's turbulent history.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The closing of the embassy has only heightened anxieties here,
among both remaining foreigners and Congolese, of an unprecedented
battle for Kinshasa. Perhaps inadvertently, it also highlighted an
eerie, almost total lack of high-level international diplomacy in
this crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, and much of the West, seemed to approve of a
previous Rwandan-led intervention here that overthrew the longtime
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko and placed the little-known Kabila in
power in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With a similar Rwandan operation under way now, however, much of
the outside world seems to have washed its hands of the situation,
neither strongly condemning a foreign-sponsored uprising in
Africa's third-largest country, nor supporting Kabila, nor even
pressing for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why everyone is leaving all at once,'' said
Abdoulaye Yerodia Ndombasi, Kabila's Cabinet director. ``If they
know something special, let them say it.''
</P>
<P>
   The government frantically prepared for a final siege as the
rebels, perhaps sensing imminent victory, began cobbling together a
political organization, which they called the Congolese Rally for
Democracy at a news conference at their provisional eastern capital
of Goma.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is composed of political dissidents, former
senior figures from the Mobutu era and politicians who are known to
be close to the leaders of Rwanda and Uganda, both of which
sponsored Kabila's earlier uprising and appear supportive of the
current one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have called it a rally because we want to bring together
all the Congolese, all of the forces fighting against dictatorship
that are determined to eradicate its roots once and for all,'' said
the organization's leader, Ernest Wamba dia Wamba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
