<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-RDP-825     08-16 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-RDP-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXPECTED TO ADMIT TO A RELATIONSHIP BUT DENY PERJURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-TESTIMONY,
CLINTON-PROSECUTORS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic showing a timeline of witnesses appearing before
the Grand Jury is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president's senior advisers late Sunday secured
his agreement to acknowledge to a federal grand jury on Monday that
he engaged in an inappropriate physical relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, but he will deny that he counseled her or anyone else to
lie about their relationship, said an adviser familiar with the
preparations for Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The president will assert that he did not commit perjury in an
earlier sworn deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit, when he denied having ``sexual relations'' or an
``affair'' with Ms. Lewinsky, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser cautioned that Clinton could change his strategy at
the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors are seeking more than a presidential admission
of extramarital sexual activity, said lawyers involved in the case.
Prosecutors from the office of the Whitewater independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, have spent the past seven months investigating
whether Clinton engaged in obstruction of justice, subornation of
perjury or witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
   The president is expected to face detailed questions on those
allegations based on testimony from dozens of grand jury witnesses,
said the lawyers. Nothing could be learned Sunday about how Clinton
intends to address those questions, but in the past he has
vehemently denied any effort to silence witnesses or otherwise
impede the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is considering a brief address to the nation following
his grand jury testimony, said a senior White House official. Such
a statement likely would come at 9 p.m. or later and be broadcast
from the White House residence rather than the Oval Office, the
official said. The official added that Clinton will not decide
whether to speak publicly until after his testimony has ended.
</P>
<P>
   The president's approach to his grand jury appearance emerged at
the end of a weekend of painstaking preparations for his testimony
on Monday, a fateful date with his political and historic destiny.
</P>
<P>
   He took a late morning break from his consultations with his
lawyers to attend church with his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
Their daughter, Chelsea, did not accompany them. Clinton, clutching
a Bible in one hand and Mrs. Clinton's hand in the other, waved to
onlookers as he entered the Foundry United Methodist Church near
the White House, but neither of the Clintons spoke to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The only official word from the group cloistered with the
president was a four-sentence statement from Clinton's lead private
attorney, David Kendall, who attempted to hold back a flood of what
he called ``groundless speculation'' about the president's Monday
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is the truth. Period,'' Kendall said. ``And that's
how the president will testify.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said that the president was ``confident''
that he was fully prepared for Monday's appearance. ``He knows
exactly what he is going to say, which is the truth,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his lawyers have spent seven months throwing up a
succession of barriers in the form of privilege claims and
rebuffing numerous requests from Starr that Clinton appear
voluntarily for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning at 1 p.m. in the White House Map Room, the
president will be confronted by a team of experienced prosecutors
armed with testimony and documents from scores of witnesses, from
the lead agent of Clinton's Secret Service detail to the steward
who brings Clinton his Diet Cokes.
</P>
<P>
   He will become the first sitting president to appear before a
criminal grand jury investigating his actions. He agreed to testify
only after Starr issued a subpoena on July 17 compelling his
appearance, although the subpoena was withdrawn 10 days later when
Clinton agreed to ``voluntarily'' appear on a closed-circuit
television link to the grand jury room in the federal courthouse
here.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about how Clinton will deal with questions about an
alleged sexual affair with Ms. Lewinsky has consumed Washington for
days. But Starr's prosecutors are expected to pursue other lines of
inquiry on Monday that go beyond Clinton's sexual behavior and into
areas that they believe point to allegations of more serious
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky became the center of Starr's inquiry earlier this
year not because the independent counsel was embarked on an
examination of the President's sex life, lawyers involved in the
inquiry said, but because her story appeared to fit a pattern of
denial and obstruction that Starr had seen in four years of
investigating the multi-faceted Whitewater case.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several weeks, prosecutors have been preparing
detailed questions about the president's numerous White House
meetings with Ms. Lewinsky, his advice to her on how to testify in
the Jones suit and whether the two of them discussed ways to
conceal evidence of their relationship from Mrs. Jones' attorneys.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say they were particularly struck by the efforts
made by Clinton, his secretary, Betty Currie, and Vernon Jordan, a
prominent Washington lawyer and close confidant of the president's,
to find employment for Ms. Lewinsky after she had been subpoenaed
to appear in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are expected to ask Clinton to explain those
job-hunting efforts, as well as the 37 visits Ms. Lewinsky made to
the White House after she was summarily transferred to a low-level
job in the Pentagon in April 1996 for ``immature and
inappropriate'' behavior around the president.
</P>
<P>
   On most of her visits to the White House, Ms. Lewinsky was
cleared past security by Mrs. Currie. Clinton was asked during his
deposition in the Jones suit in January whether he was alone with
Ms. Lewinsky on any of those occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall,'' the president replied. But he added that it
was ``possible'' that on one or two occasions they were alone.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's testimony is not corroborated by other
witnesses, most importantly by Mrs. Currie, who testified that
Clinton was alone with Ms. Lewinsky on a number of occasions,
according to lawyers familiar with her testimony. In addition,
Starr's prosecutors have questioned more than a dozen Secret
Service officers who are stationed outside the Oval Office, asking
them if they were aware of occasions on which the president and Ms.
Lewinsky were alone.
</P>
<P>
   Another critical line of questioning concerns the gifts Ms.
Lewinsky has said the president gave her, including a dress, a
brooch, a hatpin and a book of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jones deposition, Clinton was asked about the gifts. He
said he didn't recall whether he had given her gifts, and asked,
``Do you know what they were?''
</P>
<P>
   When told what they were, he said he ``could have'' given her
such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give _ let me just say, I give people a lot of gifts and
when people are around I give a lot of things I have at the White
House away, so I could have given her a gift, but I don't remember
a specific gift,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky has testified that she returned the gifts to Mrs.
Currie at the prompting of the president after they were subpoenaed
by Mrs. Jones' lawyers, said lawyers who have heard her story. It
is not known whether the box containing the gifts was in the
President's possession before Mrs. Currie turned them over to
prosecutors in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's vague answers in the Jones deposition _ he answered
``I don't know'' or ``I don't recall'' dozens of times _ may
protect him from accusations of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   But testimony from Ms. Lewinsky, who was granted broad immunity
from prosecution last month, and physical evidence, including a
blue dress of hers that the FBI has tested for semen stains, could
undercut Clinton's denials of a relationship last January and
narrow his room for maneuvering on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot depends on what the evidence really is, you know,''
Senator Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said on NBC's ``Meet the Press''
Sunday. ``I just asked the president to testify truthfully,
because, so help me, if he lies before the grand jury, that would
be grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch continued, ``And I believe that _ you know, I personally
believe he's going to do that, but, you know, President Clinton
does have a reputation as a kind of a serial legal manipulator of
legal terms, and if he goes in there and tries to manipulate the
terms and use lawyer-like language to try and, you know, not tell
the full truth, I think it's going to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta, Clinton's former chief of staff, said on the same
program that Clinton now has an obligation not only to tell the
truth before the grand jury but to level with the American public
about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be easy for the president,'' Panetta
said. ``This is a tough thing to do, when you have to face the
American people and say you made a terrible mistake and that you
apologize for it. But if he has the courage to do that and put it
behind him, hopefully others will be able to follow suit and begin
the healing process in this country from seven months of turmoil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
