<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURANCE-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN INSURER EXPECTED TO SETTLE HOLOCAUST CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Holocaust survivors and Jewish charities are near an
agreement under which Generali, the giant Italian insurance
company, would pay at least $65 million to settle claims that it
refused to honor the policies of Eastern European Jews after World
War II, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato said Sunday. A spokesman for Generali
confirmed that a settlement was expected in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, R-NY, said that in settling, Generali would become
``the first company to break the code of silence and the wall of
denial about some egregious practices that have existed for many
years.''
</P>
<P>
   By settling now, he said, Generali would avoid ``a nasty and
protracted legal encounter'' that could harm its business around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Four people who have been briefed on the negotiations to settle
a lawsuit filed last year in U.S. District Court in New York said
Sunday and Saturday that the settlement would affect about
one-third of claims by Jews who lived in Eastern Europe, where
Generali was the largest single seller of life and annuity policies
in the years before the war.
</P>
<P>
   Claims against other insurers and against companies operating in
Western Europe would not be affected by the expected settlement.
</P>
<P>
   What is expected to be the final negotiating session with
Generali is scheduled for Monday in Manhattan, but an official
announcement of the settlement is not expected until at least
Wednesday. The delay is planned, said five people who have been
involved in the negotiations or briefed on them, so that the news
is not overshadowed by coverage of President Clinton's testimony
before a grand jury about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two Swiss banks, Union Bank of Switzerland and Credit
Suisse, said they were settling claims by Jewish depositors and
their heirs who were refused the return of their money after the
war. The banks settled for $1.2 billion, twice the amount that they
previously said was the most they would pay.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said there was only ``one last technicality'' to be
worked out before a settlement is signed. The other four people who
know details of the talks said the senator was pressing Generali to
increase significantly the amount it will pay. D'Amato, who has
held hearings on the issue in the Senate Banking Committee, which
he heads, has been in the lead in demanding restitution of assets
stolen from Jews during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Generali's willingness to settle the case increased after it
became widely known in January that in a Trieste warehouse the
company had nearly complete records of all the policies it sold
before the war. A CD-ROM it created with the names of 384,000
people who bought policies closely matched lists of Holocaust
victims compiled in Jerusalem that were developed from Nazi
archives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The settlement is expected to include the disclosure of
competitive information from the years before the war that would
put pressure on Allianz AG, a German concern that is the world's
biggest insurance company, and other big European insurers to
settle claims by Holocaust survivors and the heirs of victims.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is expected to clear the way for Holocaust
survivors to press claims in courts in Eastern Europe against the
successor insurance companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
