<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Meara hardly a disappointment at PGA
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Not bad for a 41-year-old player who began the
season without a professional major championship win. Not bad for a
guy who started the year being known mainly as Tiger Woods' big
brother.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters and British Open champion, Mark O'Meara, was a
factor Sunday at Sahalee Country Club, tying for fourth at the PGA
Championship and pulling to within two shots of the lead at one
stage, but eventually tied for fourth at 4-under 276 on a closing
68. He was trying to become the first player since Ben Hogan in
1953 to win three majors in a season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara jumped into serious contention early by draining a
50-foot putt for eagle at the par-5 second hole, then slipped away
with consecutive bogeys on Nos. 6, 7 and 8 ''that really took the
winds out of my sails.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased with my performance,'' said O'Meara, the oldest
player in history to win two majors in a season. ''I wanted to try
to come and play well here. It would have been a tremendous honor
to alongside Ben Hogan's name, but it just wasn't meant to be. I'm
disappointed I didn't win, but it's not easy winning out here on
tour, let alone another major championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Price makes late run
</P>
<P>
   A favorite before it all started at Sahalee Country Club, Nick
Price finally crawled into the elite area of the leader board
Sunday, matching the course record with a bogey-free 5-under-par 65
and finishing at 4-under 276. It was the best finish in a PGA
Championship for Price, 41, a two-time champion, since his
wire-to-wire win at Southern Hills in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today was probably the best I putted all year,'' said the
Zimbabwean from Hobe Sound, Fla.,''and that's a good sign. These
lst six moths have been awful.'' . . . Price made four par saves
and five birdies at Sahalee, which has played easier the past two
two days with cool temperatures and softened conditions by light
rain. Price's chance at the course record was a putt that hung on
the lip at the par-3 17th. . . . Atlanta's Billy Andrade failed to
keep this game together for two straight days this week, but didn't
blame the inconsistency on his late arrival as the eighth alternate
at Sahalee. Andrade closed with a 75 Sunday, after rounds of
68-77-68 and finished at 8-over 288. ''The problem is still
putting,'' said Andrade, who averaged 31 per round. ''I'm still
kind of in a funk. I'm scratching and crawling. I'm close to
playing better golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
