<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gritz: Rudolph knows about us
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A retired Green Beret colonol heading a volunteer
search for Eric Robert Rudolph said Sunday that the fugitive knows
of his mission to safely deliver the bombing suspect into the
justice system, and that a man fitting Rudolph's description has
been seen in the Nantahala, N.C. area. ``People very familiar and
close to him tell us he's gotten the word,'' said retired Vietnam
Green Beret Col. James ``Bo'' Gritz on Sunday afternoon at a
Nantahala campground his volunteers are using as a command post.
``But we're going to have to come to him. We're trying to close the
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   That distance is one of not only space, but also one of trust,
since Rudolph could face the death penalty for the Jan. 29 bombing
of a Birmingham abortion clinic that killed an off-duty police
officer and maimed a nurse. He also is wanted for questioning in
the deadly explosion at Centennial Olympic Park during the Olympics
in July 1996; a double-blast bombing at a Sandy Springs abortion
clinic in January 1997; and an explosion at an Atlanta gay
nightclub in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot closer today than we were yesterday,'' Gritz said.
``We've actually had some (tips) about live sightings now that were
not reported to federal agents. I'm very plussed.'' Gritz arrived
in western North Carolina on Thursday night with Randy Weaver,
whose 1992 stand-off with federal agents at his remote Ruby Ridge,
Idaho, home cost the lives of a U.S. marshall, Weaver's wife and
son over a missed court date on weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Weaver would attract information,'' Gritz said.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz said reports that Rudolph's hideout is easily accessible
by boat are ``top secret.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about it,'' Gritz said when asked about these
reports. ``It's an operation forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz did confirm that a man fitting Rudolph's description with
a ponytail has been seen ``regularly going in and securing food and
coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not living alone and he's not living all outside,'' Gritz
added. ``We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz, 59, who has dubbed his weeklong mission ``Operation
Cross,'' said that a reward up to $1 million for information
leading only to Rudolph's arrest has made the fugitive a ``raffle
ticket'' for bounty hunters. Gritz's volunteers, who have come from
as far away as Washington state, Boston and Florida, were required
to sign a waiver to any claim on the reward because it will be
turned over to Rudolph's designee, possibly to pay for his defense.
John DeCamp, a former Republican Nebraska state senator, said over
the weekend that he will defend Rudolph if asked as long as Gritz's
involvement has been approved by the U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to make sure he has a fair trial and the truth comes
out,'' DeCamp said in a telephone interiew.
</P>
<P>
   ''Operation Cross'' officially began Friday. The group headed up
a steep mountainside Saturday morning for an overnight
''shakedown'' designed to identify those who were too weak or
antagonistic to continue. But new information brought them down to
camp about 5 a.m. Sunday, only to set out again on their secret
mission about 12 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz said he was asked to make the appeal to Rudolph by Charlie
Stone. Stone is a Georgia Bureau of Investigation agent and
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
