<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon ties modern record
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Miracles appear in the strangest of places.
Jeff Gordon found one Sunday in the blown engine of Ward Burton's
Pontiac, giving him a chance at the victory he thought would not
come.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon locked on to it with six laps to run, charging out of the
Michigan pits to chase down Mark Martin, Jeff Burton, Dale Jarrett
and Ernie Irvan for his season's eighth victory and first ever at
this track.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a miracle,'' said Gordon, standing in a Victory
Lane for the fourth consecutive week. ``We struggled at times, got
loose, and had our hands full staying on the lead lap. It's nice.
The next time we come here we won't be asked, 'When are you going
to win at Michigan?'''
</P>
<P>
   For 194 laps, it didn't appear it would be this year, either. It
was one of those weeks when Gordon didn't appear to have it. He
never was awful, just good enough to hang around and be there when
the door opened.
</P>
<P>
   It came on the backs of Burtons, Ward and Jeff. Ward for the
blown engine to bring the caution, and Jeff for leaving his pit
with loose lug nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real frustrating,'' Jeff Burton said. ``We had a fast car
enough to win the race and took ourselves out of it. The pit crew
feels terrible, but it's not about the pit crew having a bad stop
or me messing up. It's all about us getting it done together, and
we just didn't get it done today.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton had company in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Pole sitter Ernie Irvan was the early rabbit, leading nine times
for 112 laps, but none of the final 35. Martin was in front eight
times for 60, but he faded to fourth over the last nine. Jarrett
plugged along, never out of the top 10, but never in the top three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it my best,'' Martin said. ``I dedicate that losing
performance to my dad and Shelley and Sarah (in last week's plane
crash). We just couldn't beat Jeff. When you've got that much
speed, there ain't no holding it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon didn't have all that speed until Burton gave the Rainbow
Warriors one last shot. Two new left side tires were part of the
mix, the removal of a right rear spring rubber, changing the
handling of the car. All in 9.2 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got nothing to lose, it's kind of easy
sometimes,'' said crew chief Ray Evernham. ``It's a lot harder to
make that call when you've got a good car and you don't want to
screw it up. Our car really wasn't good all day long.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when there's 15 or 20 laps to go and you can put the
leaders in his sight, he's got a sight line like a jet fighter. He
can pick it up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   And discourage the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like it was going to be Gordon's day,'' Jeff
Burton said. ``It's ridiculous that he won that race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
