<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singh captures victory at Sahalee
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ He hit no range balls Sunday night. He remained
off the putting green. For one night at least, Vijay Singh, the
hardest working man in golf, accepted the results and savored his
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Winning what evolved as a head-to-head duel with Steve Stricker
Sunday at Sahalee Country Club, Singh secured the 80th PGA
Championship by two strokes with a score of 9-under-par 271,
closing with a 2-under 68 for the first major of his 16-year
professional career.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, 35, a native of Lautoka, Fiji, who once held a club
professional job in Borneo and earned less than $200 a month,
collected $540,000 Sunday and much more. With a hard rain falling
on Sahalee, Singh enjoyed the sweet result of those thousands of
range balls blasted into a setting sun. His name in Hindu means
``victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a dream to win this major, although I've been quiet
about it,'' said Singh, who biggest championship previously came in
the 1997 Memorial. ``It's something I never thought was going to
happen. I'm at a loss for words.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh clinched his chance to hoist the Wanamaker Trophy on the
par-3 17th hole, making a 15-footer for par after depositing a
5-iron into the left greenside bunker. Stricker, who also bunkered,
failed to save par from a similar distance and dropped two strokes
behind Singh to 7-under. Stricker, 31, finished second, earning
$324,000, after starting the day tied with Singh and shooting an
even-par 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put up a good fight,'' said Stricker, who broke down several
times in the post-round interview. ``I struggled. I guess it just
wasn't meant to be. That was really the turning point, when he
missed his up-and-down putt (at 17) and I missed. To win this
tournament would have meant a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the stroke of good fortune that Singh received at
the 11th hole, when his ball struck a tree and bounced onto the
green, Stricker said, ``He got some fortunate breaks, but he also
made some great recovery shots, too. I guess when it's your time to
win, those things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian Steve Elkington, after battling sinus surgery and
viral meningitis this year, challenged briefly at the finish for a
second PGA title, but finished third at 274, three shots back, with
a 67. Nick Price matched the Sahalee course record of 65 and tied
for fourth with Mark O'Meara (68), the Masters and British Open
champion, who sought three majors for the first time since Ben
Hogan in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III (70), who started four shots off the
lead, double-bogeyed the fifth hole to drop back and eventually
tied for seventh with Billy Mayfair (70). Tiger Woods tied for 10th
at 1-under-par 279 after a 71.
</P>
<P>
   A smooth, long ballstriker whose putting always kept him from
reaching a major championship level, Singh (171st in PGA Tour
putting last year) finally straightened out his work on the greens.
After trying more than a half dozen putters just this year, Singh
settled on a cross-handed style in June and this week enjoyed ``the
best putting tournament I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never a bad putter,'' Singh said. ``I just wasn't a
great putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
