<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones regains form in West coast trip
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chipper Jones never had a road trip like this one.
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves played the ninth and final game of their only West
coast swing, Jones went into Sunday night at .500 (16-for-32) with
two doubles, a triple, three homers, two stolen bases and eight
runs scored. Moreover, he had 10 RBI in the first eight games, a
major upgrade. When the Braves left town Aug. 6, Jones had driven
in only one run in his previous 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big problem I have is I wrap my bat,'' Jones said. ``I get
it back there so far (in a left-handed stance) that I wind up with
the end of my bat pointing at the right fielder, which makes me
susceptible to hard stuff in(side). It takes a conscious effort on
my part just to relax and not get back so much, and make (my swing)
short and quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We faced the Cardinals in that last homestand and Bobby Witt
and Kent Bottenfield were killing me inside. I knew going on this
trip, with the kind of pitching we were going to be facing, they
were going to be doing mostly the same thing. So you get yourself
in the cage and do the right things over and over until it feels
second nature and it should carry over into the game. Luckily, it
all came together just in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with his slow two weeks before the trip, Jones came into
play Sunday leading the league in runs (100), tied for seventh in
RBI (94) and tied for eight in homers (29). With 39 games he play,
establishing career-highs in each category seems a certainty (114
runs, set in 1996, 111 RBI set last year, 30 homers in 1996). But
with home run fever gripping attention all year and Andres
Galarraga's homers pacing Atlanta's offense, Jones' year has not
received the public notice it might have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all going to (Mark) McGwire this year,'' said manager
Bobby Cox. ''Even (Ken) Griffey (Jr.) and (Sammy) Sosa aren't
getting the attention this year. That's the way it is. People come
to think that this is automatic. It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Over his career, Jones has had trouble playing on the coast,
with a .250 career average in the three NL California cities
entering this year. But Dodger Stadium has been the toughest
(10-for-64) park for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could come in here 20-for-20 and take the collar,'' he said.
``It feels like the pitcher is right on top of you. Tough place to
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood walks
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood anticipates he will make his next start Thursday
as scheduled, though he has yet to test his right ankle which he
sprained badly enough to knock him out of his last game Friday
night just one inning after he injured it running to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was instructed not to throw on the side (Sunday),'' he said,
``but we've got the extra day (today's off-day). It'll be
alright.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood was back to walking without a limp Sunday and is
accustomed to turning his ankles and recovering, after several
similar episodes playing football and basketball at Bessemer City
(N.C.) High School. He has continued with heat-and-ice treatments
to be ready to face the Padres Thursday. Despite the off-day, Cox
had not intended to pass him over and was encouraged to see the
right-hander moving around the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking and pitching,'' Millwood said, ``are two different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer throws
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer threw from the mound Sunday (fastballs only) for
the first time since going on the disabled list Aug. 6 and after
today's off-day, he will try again Tuesday (fastballs and breaking
balls) to gauge how cortisone treatment effected the bone spur in
his right elbow. Springer is eligible to come off the DL Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signs I have now are better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
