<HEADER>
A6314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GRAND-JURY-NY     08-16 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GRAND-JURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY A MODEST ROLE FOR CLINTON GRAND JURORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: CLINTON-STARR-RDP, CLINTON-STARR,
CLINTON-TESTIMONY, CLINTON-PROSECUTORS) 
(lh) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton's image appears on a
television screen on the third floor of the federal courthouse
Monday afternoon, the 23 grand jurors in the room will probably
have little role to play.
</P>
<P>
   Although the presence of the grand jury lends symbolic and legal
gravity to the event, the jurors will be little more than a
backdrop, because it is highly unlikely that they will get to vote
or otherwise pass judgment on the issues covered by President
Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent
counsel, has indicated that he will not have the grand jury
consider whether to indict the president. Instead, Starr's aides
have suggested, he intends to draft a report to Congress, which
then will have the option of considering whether the facts warrant
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors may ask questions of the president, since it is
they who are technically conducting the investigation. But it is
expected that even if the grand jurors pose some questions, the
event will be largely run by the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Most grand juries serve two functions: They investigate under
the direction of prosecutors and then decide what to make of the
investigation. As part of that second function, they may bring
indictments or, in some cases, make presentments, which are usually
reports about broad categories of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But this grand jury is unusual in that it no longer has the
second function, because whether a sitting president can be
indicted is an unresolved legal question. Starr's intention to
compile his conclusions in a report to Congress effectively
sidesteps that issue.
</P>
<P>
   The institution of the grand jury is believed by legal
historians to date to the reign of Henry II of England in the 12th
century. At that time, authorities decreed that 12 knights or
``good and lawful men'' out of every 104 men would decide who was
suspected of public offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was imported to the American colonies by the
British. The ideal purpose of a grand jury, according to a famous
1965 opinion by a U.S. Court of Appeals, was as ``both a sword and
a shield, a sword because it is the terror of criminals, a shield
because it is the protection of the innocent against unjust
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of a grand jury for a prosecutor is that it may
compel testimony from reluctant witnesses. Investigators may not on
their own simply demand that people answer their questions, but a
grand jury is allowed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, however, the system has collected a host of
critics who argue that grand juries are merely rubber stamps for
prosecutorial decisions. In fact, grand juries that decline to
follow a prosecutor's lead to indict are sometimes called
``runaway'' grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   England, the birthplace of the concept, abolished grand juries
in 1933.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
