<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACUNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS FINDS CONSOLATION IN DOUBLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Martina Hingis lost the singles final
to Lindsay Davenport, but she had a consolation when she and
Natasha Zvereva beat Tamarine Tanasugarn and Elena Tatarkova 6-4,
6-2 Sunday in the doubles final of the Acura Classic at Manhattan
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   After the three-set singles final, Hingis returned to the court
for doubles approximately 45 minutes later. The top-ranked player
said she had no fatigue. ``I am kind of used to it now, playing
singles and doubles,'' Hingis said. ``If I didn't play doubles, I
would miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Making contact: Hingis missed an overhead late in the third
set against Davenport and was asked if the sun affected her. Hingis
said the sun played no role because she was wearing brown contact
lenses, which make her eyes less sensitive to sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, whose natural eye color is green, pulled out the brown
contacts for the finals match. In her earlier matches, she said,
``I just had the regular ones.''
</P>
<P>
   __ TV's gone, let's talk: Since the final between Hingis and
Davenport was broadcast on NBC, tournament coordinators had to
postpone the awards ceremonies to allow a commercial. When the
ceremonies continued, Davenport made a terse speech about the
match. Then, when NBC went to another commercial, she said, ``We're
off the air, so we can talk now.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, a Newport Beach resident, then thanked her friends
and family in attendance. She also mentioned a niece, who was
celebrating her first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's alive!: In a question-and-answer session with the crowd,
Davenport announced on Saturday night that women's serve-and-volley
game is dead. Now, women's tennis is more of a power game, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took criticism for that as soon as I said it in the locker
room,'' Davenport said. ``Pam Shriver told me the serve-and-volley
game isn't dead. It's just retired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
