<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTIMONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDE POLITICAL CIRCLES, A DEEP SENSE OF SADNESS AND SHOCK
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: CLINTON-STARR-RDP, CLINTON-STARR,
CLINTON-PROSECUTORS) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton sits before a closed-circuit
camera in the Map Room of the White House on Monday to give
testimony to a federal grand jury about his involvement with Monica
Lewinsky, he will venture into not only the most politically and
legally hazardous moment of his presidency, but also the most
surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some novelist had written this 12 years ago, no one would
have accepted it,'' said David McCullough, who won the Pulitzer
Prize in 1993 for his biography of Harry S. Truman. ``It makes you
feel dizzy _ and sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The widespread feeling expressed in interviews outside political
circles is one of disappointment, sadness and even anger that the
Lewinsky case has reached a new low: A president testifying about
his sexual life before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we curious to expose this thing?'' said the playwright
and actress Anna Devere Smith, who is reworking her latest play,
``House Arrest,'' about politics and journalists, to reflect the
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Just, the former journalist who has written several novels
on Washington political life, said he still could not fathom how a
confluence of seemingly unrelated events and personalities
culminated in the grand jury appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like looking at the heavens and you're seeing these
planets up there and they're all spinning around,'' he said. ``But
unlike the universe, there is no coherence to them. This follows no
path. Weird people emerge and then they disappear in six month's
time. Linda Tripp is going to be a trivia question, my guess, in a
year and a half. The Lewinsky thing is a cartoon. As a morality
tale it's not very interesting, even as an immorality tale,
whichever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ross, a Hollywood screenwriter who wrote the satire
``Dave,'' about a philandering president replaced by a lookalike,
groused: ``I'm surprised and shocked that we're actually talking
about this sort of thing in public as it relates to the president.
Doesn't it shock and horrify you?''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Carolan, who teaches American Government and Citizenship at
St. Albans, an exclusive preparatory school here whose alumni
include Vice President Al Gore, said he was bracing for awkward
moments when his students return next month because ``we've never
gotten into the thick and dirty of the Lewinsky business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to handle it without wallowing in detail,'' Carolan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Woodward, half of The Washington Post reporting team that
helped bring down Richard Nixon in 1974, said the Lewinsky matter
comes nowhere close to the level of Watergate. While the
18-and-a-half-minute gap in the Nixon tapes became an enduring
symbol of Watergate, Woodward noted, Ms. Lewinsky's navy blue dress
may be emblematic of this scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put the two scandals side by side and go to the question of
motivation and the extent of activity and there is a significant
difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said of the Lewinsky scandal: ``It's like World War I.
What triggered it? Was World War I about militarization? About
German aspirations? Is this about a land deal? Is it about FBI
files? It is about the travel office. It's about all those things,
and it's destabilized the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the concerns that the matter has diminished the
presidency, former Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., who helped navigate
Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas through the often seamy
elements of his confirmation hearings, said nothing could be more
important than Clinton's grand jury appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more important than policy,'' Danforth said. ``If what
comes out of this is, `We don't really care, we don't want to be
bothered,' then that is a terrible, terrible outcome. If what comes
out is, `This is wrong and we know it's wrong and we're willing to
forgive it but we don't want it to happen again,' then I think we
have vindicated ourselves as a people who believe in something.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so high minded. For three years, Ed Morris, a
government teacher at Walt Whitman High School in Bethesda, Md.,
greeted his students after summer vacation by passing out a slip of
paper with this conversation starter, ``Is O.J. Guilty?'' Now a new
question awaits his students, ``Is Bill Guilty?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just see where it goes,'' Morris said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
