<HEADER>
A6333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGAL-COX     08-16 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton already at a disadvantage, professor says
 &HT;    By Benjamin Kline
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If she were President Bill Clinton's lawyer at
this point in the proceedings against him, Susan Brenner says she
would advise him to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner, a professor of law at the University of Dayton, doesn't
say that in an old-fashioned, all-American, cannot-tell-a-lie tone,
however.
</P>
<P>
   She says it because she feels the president is in grave danger
of being hung out to dry by Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr and
the federal grand jury investigating the allegations of White House
sex and coverup.
</P>
<P>
   A former defense attorney and co-author of a book on federal
grand juries, Brenner said she thinks Clinton's legal team should
have challenged Starr's subpoena of Clinton ``on some kind of
executive privilege, some kind of immunity. It's very important to
the presidency and the relationship between the executive and
judicial branches.''
</P>
<P>
   But since that didn't happen, Brenner says Clinton's best shot
is to avoid getting caught in a Starr trap, which could happen if
he lies and perjures himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very peculiar situation,'' the professor said.
``Justice (department) guidelines don't normally call in the
targets of an investigation in front of a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton has a slight advantage in having his lawyers
present at the White House video testimony he is to make Monday,
he's already at a disadvantage, Brenner said. He'll be going
head-on with a prosecutor who wants to hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a prosecutor brings somebody in, he doesn't care about
the information. He wants to try and see if the person will lie,
and then prosecute him for perjury,'' she said. ``There's no reason
to bring Clinton in except to try to trap him into perjury. To lie
in front of a grand jury is the most dangerous thing in the world.
That's why I find this case so fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton's advisers were reportedly urging him to be
firm, succinct _ and vague when needed. Can he safely avoid giving
details of his interaction with Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be very difficult,'' Brenner said. ``The prosecutor
will ask, `Were you alone together on such and such a date?'
Clinton can say yes or no. Then they can follow up with questions
designed to elicit the details. If Clinton gives very limited
answers, they can ask additional questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenner said Clinton attorney David Kendall could challenge a
question on the basis of ``some kind of privilege, including the
Fifth Amendment. But once you answer on a topic, you may have
waived your privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   A controversy over privilege could go before the federal judge
who presides over the grand jury, Brenner said. That would again
delay the process.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has every right to take the Fifth Amendment and refuse
to answer questions, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
   America's founders designed the amendment as a counterweight to
the old English grand jury system, ``a shield for the innocent
against government oppression,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury dates to the 12th century in England. It has
always conducted its work in secret. It has never needed just cause
to issue subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   When someone testifies, normally no defense attorney is present,
no judge decides if a question is relevant, no question is too out
of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Amendment against self-incrimination makes sense,
Brenner said: ``It's any citizen's right not to cooperate with
someone who is after you.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically, however, she conceded, ``Most Americans see taking
the Fifth as admitting you're guilty, like some mobster using it.''
</P>
<P>
   If a witness refuses to answer a question for reasons other than
the Fifth Amendment, the prosecutor can seek to have the witness
jailed for contempt, for as long as the grand jury sits. That's
what happened to Susan McDougal, who was jailed for 22 months.
</P>
<P>
   People don't understand that a grand jury is not like the trial
juries they see on TV shows, Brenner said. ``It's not like a trial
jury. It's a police investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Kline writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
