<HEADER>
A6336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROSECUTORS-N     08-16 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROSECUTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROSECUTORS: 2 TIRELESS LAWYERS ASSISTING STARR IN INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: CLINTON-STARR-RDP, CLINTON-STARR,
CLINTON-TESTIMONY, CLINTON-GRAND-JURY) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are biographies of Jackie Bennett and Robert Bittman,
two of the chief prosecutors in the office of Whitewater
independent counsel Kenneth Starr, which, after months
investigating the Monica Lewinsky matter, will question President
Clinton on Monday before a federal grand jury. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Bennett
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jackie M. Bennett Jr. is an overly aggressive
questioner or a principled, straight-shooting public servant,
depending on who ventures an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   One of Kenneth Starr's top deputies, Bennett has questioned some
of the more important witnesses before the grand jury investigating
the Lewinsky matter. Not many lawyers or witnesses would comment on
his tactics.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gloria Cabe, chief of staff for Bill Clinton when he
was governor of Arkansas, would. She recalls that Bennett was
``extraordinarily rude'' to her during a grand jury appearance in
an investigation of the financing of Clinton's 1990 gubernatorial
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Goldstein, a lawyer who won a 1993 courtroom duel in San
Antonio against Bennett, would agree. Bennett was then senior trial
lawyer in the Justice Department's Public Integrity Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bully,'' Goldstein said then after winning an acquittal
for a client prosecuted by Bennett. He told The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram that Bennett had used his power to intimidate ``every
potential witness, no matter how large or small.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bennett rode out of San Antonio with a big trophy _ the
racketeering and bribery conviction of former Rep. Albert G.
Bustamante, D-Texas. For that he won the Justice Department's top
honor for prosecutors, the John Marshall Award.
</P>
<P>
   He also won the respect of the trial judge. ``Very
professional,'' said Judge Edward Prado of federal District Court,
a former U.S. Attorney. ``He's tough but he played within the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who is in his early 40s, is a bulldog in appearance as
well as personality, rather like the offensive tackle he was, for
Hanover College in Indiana. He went on to Indiana University Law
School and became a federal prosecutor in Indiana. His friends say
he is charming and friendly, at least out of court. He and his
wife, Cindy, have four young sons.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bittman
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Though he is only in his mid-30s, Robert J.
Bittman, the youngest of Kenneth Starr's deputies, has instant name
recognition among lawyers. He is the son of William O. Bittman,
nationally known as both a prosecutor and a defense counsel whose
targets included former Teamster boss Jimmy Hoffa and whose clients
have included Watergate conspirator E. Howard Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bittman is known as a dogged researcher willing to put in
long hours to untangle complicated cases. He has been active in the
questioning of witnesses before the Lewinsky grand jury. Early on,
he was opposed to making a deal with Ms. Lewinsky, and instead
advocated a thorough investigation to try to corroborate her
accusations, including questioning Secret Service agents and
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Bittman graduated from the University of Maryland and the
Columbus School of Law at Catholic University in Washington. He
worked for a small firm in Rockville, Md., before joining the
prosecutor's office in Anne Arundel County, Md., in 1988, making
cases against drunks, con men and murderers. He joined Starr in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bittman was described by former Anne Arundel colleagues as
friendly, bright and tireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of lawyer who didn't leave any stone unturned,''
Cynthia Ferris, a former prosecutor whom Bittman considers a
mentor, told The Baltimore Sun recently. ``If there's anything to
be found there, he'll find it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
