<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH WINS HIS FIRST MAJOR CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ As he walked up the 18th fairway Sunday en
route to the most gratifying moment of his career, Vijay Singh was
momentarily engulfed by the gallery rushing to congratulate him.
But then Singh casually emerged from the crowd, calmly separating
himself from everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Unflappable to the end, Singh was alone at the top, winning the
PGA Championship by trusting his newly consistent putting stroke
and his reliable ball-striking, an ability formed through years of
dedication and countless hours of practice. Prevailing over the
challenge of Sahelee Country Club, a world-class field and the
suffocating pressure that comes with Sunday afternoon at a major
championship, Singh won his first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a steady and resourceful 2-under-par 68, Singh finished
at 9-under 271 for the tournament, two strokes ahead of Steve
Stricker and three strokes better than Steve Elkington. Stricker
shot a 70 Sunday, and Elkington made a serious run with a
final-round 67.
</P>
<P>
   It was the end of a long journey for Singh, whose career has
carried him from his native Fiji to Malaysia, Nigeria and Morocco
and finally to the PGA Tour, where he has earned a reputation as
one of the game's hardest-working and most consistent players. At
35, Singh felt a major championship was the missing piece in his
career. So after Sunday's victory, he felt a deep sense of
satisfaction, knowing he had paid his dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I've won this tournament,'' said Singh,
moments after he had earned the first-place check of $540,000. ``I
was laying awake last night at two o'clock, wondering what would
happen today. My wife said, `Are you asleep?' I said, `Yeah, I'm
asleep.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Singh was wide awake, thinking about his game plan,
and Sunday he executed it. Starting the day tied with Stricker,
Singh took sole possession of the lead for good on the sixth hole,
and while he could never relax until after his final putt dropped,
Singh made pressure shots and avoided the crucial mistakes that led
to the demise of other contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The final turning point of the tournament came on No. 17, a
difficult 215-yard par 3, with water on the right side of the
green, and a bunker on the left. Singh reached No. 17 holding a
one-stroke lead over Stricker, but with 17 and the even more
difficult 18th hole still ahead, the outcome was very much in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Both players felt the pressure, hitting their tee shots into the
greenside bunker. But Singh recovered for par, while Stricker did
not. Singh's bunker shot landed about 15 feet short of the pin,
while Stricker hit his bunker shot to within 12 feet. But Singh,
using a new cross-handed putting style that he started last month,
knocked in his putt to save par. Then Stricker missed his attempt
for par just left of the hole, giving Singh a two-stroke lead with
one hole to play. From there, Singh made a routine par at No. 18
and savored the victory, while Stricker thought about the
opportunity that had slipped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled with my emotions and with my swing,'' said
Stricker, who pushed Singh until the end, and recorded his fifth
top-10 finish in his last six starts. ``I had an opportunity to put
a little pressure on Vijay at No. 17, because I had first tee
there, and I didn't hit a very good shot. ``To win this tournament
would have meant a lot. It's hard not to let those thoughts creep
into your mind. It's a little bit of a consolation finishing
second, but I came here thinking I could win. Then again, I hung in
there and played well.''
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Singh became the 10th player in the last 11
years to win his first major at the PGA. And the result ended Mark
O'Meara's bid to become the first player since Ben Hogan in 1953 to
win three majors in the same year. O'Meara shot a 68 Sunday and
finished tied for fourth place at 4 under par (276) with Nick
Price, who shot the day's best score (65), and Frank Lickliter, who
shot a 68. O'Meara made an early run, making a 40-foot putt for
eagle at No. 2, then making a birdie on No. 5 to pull within two
strokes of the lead. But O'Meara faltered on the next three holes,
making three consecutive bogeys, and he never seriously threatened
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a tremendous honor to go alongside Ben
Hogan's name, but it just wasn't meant to be,'' said O'Meara,
winner of this year's Masters and the British Open. ``I'm
disappointed I didn't win, but it was great to see all the people
out here pulling for me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One by one, the other contenders dropped off like dominos,
leaving Singh and Stricker to decide the final outcome. Price
eagled No. 11 to reach for under par, but he never made another
birdie. Davis Love III, the defending champion, finished tied for
seventh (270), seeing his hopes ruined by a double-bogey at No. 5,
when he hit his tee shot into the water. Tiger Woods never made a
charge and shot a 71 Sunday, finishing tied for 10th (279).
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, the 1995 PGA champion, made a serious bid to win,
getting to within two strokes of the lead when he birdied No. 11,
and almost making an eagle there. Elkington's 15-foot putt attempt
for eagle at No. 11 rimmed out of the cup, forcing him to settle
for birdie. Then Elkington's final hope for victory ended when he
bogeyed No. 18, putting him the clubhouse at 6 under par, while
Singh was still on the course at 9 under. But while Elkington was
disappointed, he was encouraged by his third place finish, in a
season that has been marred by sinus problems and meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making a comeback,'' said Elkington. ``But Vijay is a good
friend of mine. He has worn that tag of being a good player that
has never won a major. He will be a good champion. It's good to
see. He has had an enormously difficult road to pick up that
trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh showed all his talents Sunday, and he also took advantage
of breaks. On his second shot at the par 5 No. 11, Singh hit an
errant 3-wood that hit a tree to the right of the green, but it
ricocheted left and rolled onto the green, stopping about 25 feet
from the cup. Singh might not have gotten a bounce any better if he
hit that tree 100 times. From there, he two-putted for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relief to see the ball come onto the green,'' said
Singh.
</P>
<P>
   Singh got another break on No. 14 that he made the most of.
After pulling his tee shot deep into the trees, he hit a delicate
wedge shot through a small opening and onto the green, showing his
touch by intentionally hooking the ball left-to-right, the only
shot he had out of the trees. Singh two-putted from 40 feet to save
par, then made a crucial birdie on No. 15, hitting a radar-like
pitching wedge to within 8 feet of the hole, then making the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 14, I just started to concentrate harder on what I was
doing,'' said Singh. ``I didn't want it to slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not. Singh finally had his long-sought major. Vijay means
`victory'' in Hindu. And Sunday, the name fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win one of these is like a dream,'' said Singh. ``I have to
wait for it to sink in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
