</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-5Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE HEAVYWEIGHTS FIGHT REFORM IN LOS ANGELES CITY GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (with BC-REFORM-HISTORY-LADN and BC-REFORM-LIST-LADN, all for use
by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK MCGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With an our-way-or-else ultimatum, a group of
powerful, downtown corporate executives has raised serious doubts
about efforts to reform Los Angeles city government.
</P>
<P>
   Protective of their influence at City Hall and mistrustful of
homeowner organizations, the Los Angeles Business Advisors has
threatened to use its power and money to defeat efforts to reform
the City Charter in next year's city elections if elected, powerful
neighborhood councils are included.
</P>
<P>
   Formed quietly two years ago with $40,000 each from 24
executives _ almost all from downtown corporations such as Times
Mirror, the parent company of the Los Angeles Times _ LABA started
with a vague agenda of improving the local business environment
while working behind the scenes in support of such uncontroversial
civic projects as funding for the Disney Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, with reform of city government at a critical
point, LABA has gone public in a big way, revealing its members'
identities and taking center stage with a clear agenda in a highly
politicized area.
</P>
<P>
   LABA declared war on proposals to shift some of the power from
City Hall to elected neighborhood councils vested with
decision-making authority, put forward its own plan for 35 council
districts and threatened to ``vigorously campaign'' against charter
reform if a plan for neighborhood councils is put before voters.
</P>
<P>
   The threat has sparked widespread suspicion among backers of
neighborhood empowerment _ from public employee unions to homeowner
groups _ that LABA's power and money will turn political reform
into a step back to the past for the city.
</P>
<P>
   LABA has grown to a committee of 26 and the parallels with Los
Angeles' past Committee of 25 _ led by the Chandler family that
owned the Los Angeles Times and Times Mirror _ are unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   With Times Publisher and Times Mirror CEO Mark H. Willes and two
other Times Mirror board members among LABA's leaders, many fear
that a new corporate oligarchy is attempting to reassert control
over civic affairs, much as the old Committee of 25 did for years
until the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fellow travelers in the corporate boardrooms who
want to further take power from the community and concentrate it
downtown with whatever mayor they can buy,'' said Julie Butcher,
general manager of Local 347 of the Service Employees International
Union, a 10,000-member blue-collar union.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Fine of the Federation of Hillside and Canyon
Associations, a coalition of homeowners groups, said the days when
an elite group of corporate executives can decide what's best for
Los Angeles must not be revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of influence and a lot of power,'' Fine said.
``They can get what they want with a few phone calls. Their
predecessors were the same ones that brought us water. But it is
time for the benevolent dictatorship to cease. It's time to give
the people some power.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have a more benign view and don't think LABA will be able
to wield such extensive influence on the charter reform debate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, questions have been raised about LABA's legitimacy and
the role of the Los Angeles Times, the largest newspaper in
California, and the nine corporate members based outside Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the LABA members are not residents of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Willes was on vacation and unavailable for comment, said Mike
Lange, communications manager for the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Lange said Willes is a member as ``a corporate citizen.'' Lange
and other Times representatives said they could not say whether a
donation was made by the corporation or by Willes as an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Although LABA officials acknowledged each member must meet the
$40,000 donation requirement, Lange insisted Times Mirror corporate
policy is not to make contributions to political campaigns or to
donate to people advocating ballot initiatives, such as creation of
the charter reform commission that LABA members backed.
</P>
<P>
   He said any financial involvement at this point in LABA would be
consistent with that policy because the debate on neighborhood
councils has not reached the ballot yet. The initiative required
that a charter reform proposal go on the ballot next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems far removed from the political process,'' Lange said.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
