<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. COUNCIL PREPARES MILD REPLY TO IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. Security Council is preparing a
low-keyed response to Saddam Hussein's latest attempt to frustrate
its arms inspectors. The response reflects the deep divisions among
members over its approach to Iraq, as well as the unwillingness of
the United States and Britain to threaten military action as they
did during the last standoff, in February.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with Iraq's defiant refusal to cooperate any more with the
U.N. inspectors who are trying to eliminate Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, the Security Council is scheduled to debate a draft
declaration Monday that acknowledges that its plans to disarm Iraq
have suffered a setback. The draft simply instructs the inspectors
to press ahead with their work and report any further Iraqi
obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the alternative?'' said the representative of one of
the five permanent Security Council members, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``We have no volunteers for military action. Not a
single one.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest conflict between the United Nations and Iraq erupted
last week when the two agencies charged with eliminating Iraq's
nuclear, chemical and biological weapons _ the U.N. Special
Commission and the International Atomic Energy Agency _ told the
Security Council that Iraq's refusal to cooperate had halted their
disarmament activities and threatened the long-term monitoring
crucial to prevent Baghdad from restarting its prohibited weapons
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The draft reply to these agencies' complaint, which the Security
Council will consider Monday and which diplomats say appears to
have widespread support, makes no threats of military action
against Iraq if it continues to defy the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it recalls that the council has already condemned
Iraq's refusal to cooperate as ``totally unacceptable.'' And it
acknowledges that ``under current circumstances'' the inspectors
cannot assure the council that Iraq will not ``re-establish its
proscribed weapons program.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also reminds them that they still have a mandate to
``carry out a full range of activities including inspections'' and
says they should report back to the Security Council if they are
``hindered in any way from undertaking these activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the council expresses hope that the current visit to
Baghdad by a U.N. mediator, Prakash Shah of India, will result in
the ``full resumption of cooperation'' between Iraq and the
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   When the Security Council met informally on Thursday to consider
the standoff, diplomats say, divisions between its members quickly
became apparent. The United States and Britain pushed for an
immediate and firm reply, which they wanted the council to issue
the following day.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia, which leads those in favor of relaxing the sanctions
imposed on Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in 1990, called for a
delay. And in the end a majority of members supported Sweden's
proposal that the council postpone any action until this week to
give Shah more time to pursue his efforts in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Japan circulated the draft reply to the
inspection agencies that the council is to debate Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   U.S. and British diplomats acknowledge that the Security Council
has no appetite for a repeat of February's confrontation with
Baghdad, when only a last-minute agreement between Saddam and
Secretary General Kofi Annan prevented new military strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But they say Saddam now appears to have broken that agreement,
which was unanimously endorsed by the Security Council, by saying
he will no longer cooperate with the arms inspectors, although it
is not yet absolutely clear what this means in practical terms.
</P>
<P>
   By avoiding threats and simply telling the arms inspectors to
continue their work as best they can, these diplomats argue that
the council will test Iraq's true intentions and, if Baghdad
remains defiant, eventually force all members to face the fact that
their orders are being flouted.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the inspection agencies say, Iraq is stopping them
from following up fresh intelligence by visiting new sites. Instead
they are limited to around 300 weapons sites, where they have
already found evidence of prohibited weapons production.
</P>
<P>
   Although they say Iraq's nuclear weapons programs have probably
now been effectively dismantled, they continue to have reservations
about the degree of disarmament achieved in the fields of
biological and chemical weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of the VX nerve gas recently found on missile warheads
cast doubt on Iraq's claim that although it produced some 3.9 tons
of that deadly substance, it never loaded it into a weapon, as well
as raising questions about the total number of special missile
warheads Iraq says it manufactured for delivering other chemical
and biological agents.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is also refusing to hand over documents arms inspectors
have seen that record its use of chemical weapons during its war
with Iran. The inspection agencies say the documents would help
them verify the scale and nature of its chemical weapons program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
