<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6351 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-2ndTak     08-16 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: process,'' Lange said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   LABA members said they have no intent to dictate how Los Angeles
will be run and have the city's best interests in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can make a contribution,'' said LABA board member
Eli Broad, chairman and chief executive officer of SunAmerica Inc.,
a $55 billion financial services company specializing in retirement
savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can use our leadership ability to help make Los
Angeles a better city.''
</P>
<P>
   The CEOs of some of the region's largest companies came together
two years ago to fill a vacuum of leadership in civic affairs by
the business community, according to Broad, a close friend and
adviser of Mayor Richard Riordan, his neighbor in Brentwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no such group,'' Broad recalled. ``The purpose of
getting together was to talk about what was needed in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the group's organizers included Atlantic Richfield Co.
CEO Mike R. Bowlin, who is now LABA's chairman, and Edison
International CEO John E. Bryson, both of whom are also friends of
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The LABA board also includes Bruce Karatz, chairman of Kaufman
and Broad. Karatz, who last week hosted President Clinton for a
political fund-raiser at his large home in Santa Monica, is also a
close friend of Riordan's, having chaired the mayor's task force to
raise money to provide computers for the Los Angeles Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Other LABA board members include Tom McKernan, CEO of the Auto
Club of Southern California, and Ronald Burkle, head of The Yucaipa
Cos., which owned Food 4 Less and Ralphs supermarkets. The group
includes CEOs for major corporations including Hilton Hotels Corp.,
BankAmerica Corp., Wells Fargo Bank and H.F. Ahmanson and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by criticism that it was another group of white males, the
group added attorney Joan Payden, a resident of Santa Monica, to
its membership and Japanese executive Yoshio Ishizaka, the head of
Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc., based in Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   The newest member is Los Angeles attorney Warren Christopher,
the former U.S. secretary of state who headed the citizen
commission that investigated the LAPD after the Rodney King
beating.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 26 corporations represented on LABA, 17 are headquartered
in Los Angeles, while two _ Wells Fargo and BankAmerica _ are based
in San Francisco. Two firms have their headquarters in Beverly
Hills, two in Pasadena and one each in Torrance, El Segundo and
Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   McKernan said LABA's goal is to give business a stronger voice
in civic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time now, with all of the changes in the Los Angeles
business community, there's been some criticism that business isn't
as involved as it should be in civic affairs,'' McKernan said.
``There is a vibrant, intelligent group of business leaders that
can at least add to the discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The original mission statement of the group talked about the
need ``to create an environment in Greater Los Angeles in which
business can succeed and generate jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad said the group has focused on welfare and reform of Los
Angeles' education system among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   On charter reform, the group has retained some of the city's
premier lobbyists and political consultants, including Cerrell
Associates, the Kamber Group and former Deputy Mayor Mike Keeley.
</P>
<P>
   The group fought unsuccessfully behind the scenes against the
city's adoption of a ``living wage'' ordinance and is entering the
fray in support of expansion of Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   LABA was instrumental in the effort to save the foundering
Disney Concert Hall project, which has since achieved its
fund-raising goals.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its first two years, the group worked in a cloak of
secrecy, refusing to reveal its members or budget.
</P>
<P>
   (3RD TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
