<HEADER>
A6352 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-3rdTak     08-16 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-3rdTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: its members or budget.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, the group still won't talk about its budget and says it's
premature to discuss how much it might spend on the charter reform
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At least 11 board members live outside the city, including two
who live in San Marino, two in Pasadena, two in Santa Monica, one
in Beverly Hills, one in La Canada Flintridge, one in Orange
County, one in Valencia and one in Arcadia, according to voter
registration records and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Rinehart, who heads the parent company of Home Savings,
lives in Orange County, although he will soon be leaving the group
because of a company merger.
</P>
<P>
   The significant membership from outside the city draws charges
of carpetbagging from Los Angeles activists, including Richard
Close, president of the Sherman Oaks Homeowners Association and
chairman of Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment, the group
petitioning for a study of San Fernando Valley secession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because many of them live in Santa Monica and Beverly Hills,
they don't have to live with the consequence of their actions,''
Close said.
</P>
<P>
   Fine said she is outraged that charter reform might be dominated
by people who live and work outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have absolutely no business dictating to the city of Los
Angeles how a city of over 3.5 million people should be run,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, who ran against Riordan
last year, said it is ironic that many of the corporate leaders
already enjoy in their small towns what Los Angeles residents are
seeking, a government that is closer and more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Living outside Los Angeles destroys their credibility for
participating in the neighborhood council debate, Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who would be less concerned with neighborhood
issues such as air pollution, traffic congestion and
overdevelopment in Los Angeles because they don't live in these
neighborhoods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McKernan, a resident of Arcadia, said LABA board members who do
not live in Los Angeles still care about the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``As large employers we have an interest in the future of Los
Angeles,'' said McKernan, whose company employs 6,000 people and is
headquartered in Los Angeles, although it recently moved many of
its offices to Costa Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   He said the group is approaching issues from a regional
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where you live in Southern California, Los Angeles
has an influence on you,'' McKernan said. ``So we all should
contribute positively to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian D'Arcy, who heads a DWP union, said he is not concerned
that some LABA members live outside Los Angeles. ``They certainly
have an economic interest in the city,'' D'Arcy said, adding that
he also opposes elected neighborhood councils.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Fernando Guerra also believes LABA's role is
a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important,'' said Guerra, who heads Loyola
Marymount University's Center for the Study of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1970s, Los Angeles has lacked a corporate
community with a strong voice, Guerra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem of the Los Angeles business community in the past
is that it had distanced itself and disassociated itself from civic
concerns,'' Guerra said. ``They need to reassert themselves. But if
they do it in a way that alienates other stakeholders it's not
productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of style.''
</P>
<P>
   (4TH TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6353 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-4thTak     08-16 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-4thTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: question of style.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   McKernan dismissed concerns that LABA represents a return to the
old Committee of 25, which would set policy for the city, hand-pick
political candidates and tell them how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a different time,'' he said. ``Perhaps Los Angeles
was more monolithic then. It isn't now. I don't think this group
has any delusions that it can control the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad agreed, saying: ``Times have changed. We're advisory.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observers like Guerra said the city is less homogenous
today and less likely to be influenced by a corporate elite.
</P>
<P>
   The old committee represented firms that employed a much higher
percentage of the city's population and generated much more of its
economic output than the new group, Guerra said.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted LABA lacks representation from some of the biggest
sectors of the city's economy, including the entertainment
industry, which dilutes its influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that they've annoyed some people on charter
reform by saying, this is our position _ as if they have a veto on
the thing,'' Guerra said.
</P>
<P>
   LABA President Sam Bell angered many people earlier this month
when he announced that the group would use its financial and
political muscle to defeat any proposed city charter that calls for
elected neighborhood councils.
</P>
<P>
   ``If required, we will vigorously campaign against elected
neighborhood councils if they are included in a new city charter
ballot measure,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin Chemerinsky, chairman of the elected Charter Reform
Commission, said the threat is not productive to efforts to reach a
consensus on reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are using the rhetoric of threats,'' Chemerinsky said.
``I believe that the business community is very important to pay
attention to, but I do not believe our commission is going to be
intimidated by what they are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Butcher, whose union has been a leading proponent of
powerful neighborhood councils, ``I think it's pretty outrageous
for them to draw this line in the sand at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   While other downtown groups have lined up with LABA, the most
influential Valley group, the Valley Industry and Commerce
Association, voted to back a strong form of neighborhood councils
despite an intense lobbying effort by downtown business interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the battle lines have been drawn,'' said Scott, a
Woodland Hills attorney and VICA board member. ``They (LABA) are
downtown interests that believe all power and resources should
remain downtown and that the Valley is a colony and we should keep
our mouths shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad and McKernan said the whole city will suffer if the city
bureaucracy is expanded to include another level of
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about creating another layer of government,''
Broad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have elected neighborhood councils we think it will be a
disaster for the city. You will end up with a lot of political
wanna-bes who want to run for school board or the City Council,
rather than volunteers who care about the city.''
</P>
<P>
   (5TH TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
