<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-5thTak     08-16 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-5thTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: about the city.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   McKernan said the city was not a friendly place to do business
before Riordan won election and streamlined government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough issue. People want more representation. By
the same token, it wasn't too long ago that everyone was
complaining that it took too long to get things done,'' McKernan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primarily the concern is balancing more representation and
more input with the ability to move and get things done,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The LABA plan for charter reform would provide the Mayor's
Office with more authority to run the city on a day-to-day basis
while expanding the City Council from 15 to 35 members to provide
better representation and access.
</P>
<P>
   Despite LABA's public ultimatum, some of its board members said
privately that they might accept advisory neighborhood councils
appointed by the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Close said LABA's position has put it on a collision course with
many Valley leaders who see neighborhood empowerment as the only
alternative to secession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (LABA) are a respected, legitimate organization that has
political clout and can raise a lot of money,'' Close said. ``Their
goals are different from the goals of businesses and residents in
the Valley. That worries me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question they are the biggest threat to charter
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine agreed, saying, ``They can do a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 15-member elected commission, which has tentatively
endorsed elected councils with decision-making over small local
budgets, the 21-member commission appointed by the City Council has
recommended advisory neighborhood councils controlled by City
Council members.
</P>
<P>
   George Kieffer, chairman of the council-appointed Charter Reform
Commission, said his group's backing of advisory neighborhood
councils was a conclusion reached independently of LABA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been done anywhere else in the country,'' he said.
``We made our decision about what we were doing before LABA weighed
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Chemerinsky said LABA's threats may be posturing. ``My hope is
that there is still plenty of opportunity for compromise and
conciliation and the will to come up with a positive resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leader Butcher said there is a coalition of labor,
homeowner leaders and average residents who are willing to fight
LABA at the ballot box if it comes to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, frankly, they've already got all the power they
need,'' Butcher said. ``Whether it is as the downtown power elite
operating out of the 37th floor of some building or living in gated
communities of San Marino and Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is it's time to spread some of the power out
to the communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Close said LABA's hard-nosed tactics could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their bullying tactics may generate backlash on the commission
and get us what we are asking for,'' Close said.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Rita Walters agreed, saying, ``I think their
threats will probably have the opposite reaction among the
electorate than they desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electorate may feel it's special-interest groups
determining for the people what their government will be,'' she
said. ``I think a lot of people feel that business has an
inordinate influence here anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
