u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-GOVERNOR-785&AMP;     08-16 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-GOVERNOR-785&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FLORIDA, GOVERNOR `NO' MAKING LAST-YEAR EFFORT TO KEEP GOP AT
BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ In his last year in office, Florida Gov.
Lawton Chiles has been busy saying no.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of vetoes this summer after the legislative session,
Chiles, a Democrat, struck down bills passed by the Republican
majority that would have required parental notification of a
teen-ager's plans for abortion, made it more difficult for
consumers to sue businesses, and allowed drivers to purchase
special license plates with the message ``Choose Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17 vetoes this year did not rank as a record for Chiles; in
1995 he vetoed 28 bills. But they have come at a critical juncture,
only months from an election in which Republicans, who already
control the House and the Senate, are poised to win the
governorship and thereby dominate state government for the first
time this century. Jeb Bush, the Republican nominee, is considered
to have a commanding lead over his Democratic opponent, Lt. Gov.
Kenneth MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Chiles, who has sparred with a Republican
legislative majority for the last two years and is barred by law
from seeking a third term, is highlighting the conservative
policies that await if voters throw the Democrats out of the
governor's mansion. It is, in short, a statehouse version of the
rationale for divided government so often made in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his office here, Chiles asserted: ``The
Republicans tend to be dominated right now by the Christian right,
the moral right, and they tend to force the agenda for those
Republicans. Just look at the things I vetoed. A lot of items like
that tend to balance out a lot better if you have some check.''
</P>
<P>
   Some items, like bills that would have allowed school prayer and
banned late-term abortions, both of which he vetoed in past years
as well, were actually popular. Even so, those vetoes have not
affected Chiles' standing among voters: A poll last month by
Florida Voter, a nonpartisan polling organization in Fort
Lauderdale, showed his approval rating at 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People believe he's doing it out of conviction and not out of
political gain,'' said Jim Kane, Florida Voter's chief pollster.
</P>
<P>
   The same poll also found that many voters like a division of
power. Asked whether they thought it was very important, somewhat
important or not important at all to make sure that one party does
not have control of both the state Legislature and the governor's
office, 39 percent of respondents answered ``very important'' and
22 percent answered ``somewhat important.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, MacKay is trailing Bush by anywhere from 12 percent to 20
percent in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican legislators say Democrats had their chance in
the nation's fourth-largest state and now it is their turn. They
say Floridians will notice the change in regime on issues like
taxes, family values and approach to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying to the people of Florida, give us a chance,''
said John Thrasher, a Republican from northeast Florida who is
expected to become House speaker next year. There are 66
Republicans in the House and 54 Democrats; in the Senate,
Republicans outnumber Democrats, 25 to 15. ``If we do something
outlandish the voters are going to tell us at the polls,'' Thrasher
said. ``That's the check that works best.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats counter that when they controlled the Legislature
before Republicans achieved the majority in the Senate in 1994 and
won the House two years later, Democratic rule was mostly in the
hands of what Chiles calls ``maverick Democrats,'' conservatives
who can give a moderate like Chiles as much trouble as the
Republicans. Indeed, Chiles, who counts legislation allowing the
state to sue tobacco companies among his major victories but who
has lost battles over health care and taxes, says he has found it
easier to deal with Republicans now that they have a legislative
majority.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats still have a slight majority in voter
registration in Florida, their decline in power here in Tallahassee
has been attributed to defections from whites and the influx of
Republican newcomers to Florida. Chiles also faults the role of
redistricting in carving out minority legislative districts that
left white areas open for a Republican takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The party's troubles, which are mirrored elsewhere in the South,
deepened this year after a rift with black political leaders about
the selection of a white legislator over a black legislator as the
House speaker-designate. That conflict has yet to heal, and many
Democrats fear it will cost their party black votes this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats always had fights, always had falling outs,'' Chiles
said. ``It's going to be the people that are going to make the
decision.''.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By the same token, Chiles said he did not despair thinking what
the Republicans would do to Florida if they took over. Only two
Republican governors, Claude Roy Kirk Jr. (1966-1970) and Robert
Martinez (1986-1990), have served Florida in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view of democracy is that it learns through mistakes,''
said Chiles, a Democrat to the core, who after 40 years in public
office plans to retire to hunt, fish and remain active on
children's issues. ``If the people would choose to have a
Republican governor, I think they'll learn something from that, as
they have the last couple of times they've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, with his vetoes, Chiles is attempting a few
lessons on his own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
