<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-VECSEY-COLUMN     08-16 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SINGH REMEMBERS SANDY GREENS OF EARLY DAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It was 2 a.m., and his wife, Ardena Seth, asked
him if he was asleep, and Vijay Singh said, yes, of course he was
asleep. After all, a man who is about to play for his first major
golf title should be getting a good night's sleep, not tossing and
turning and imagining giant fir trees growing new limbs over the
fairways to swat back his shots.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Singh did not deny he had trouble sleeping. Neither did
his companion on the four-mile walk through the tall timber, Steve
Stricker, who woke up at 5 a.m. and never got back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Four strokes. That was the advantage the two opponents had over
the field in the Professional Golf Association championship. They
would play together, trying to hold off whatever the accomplished
golfers did ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're in the lead, you're bound to be nervous,''
Singh admitted later. ``It's good to be nervous. It makes you
concentrate more.''
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh had time to think in the middle of the night. He had
come further than anybody else in this last of the four major
tournaments that constitute the Grand Slam of golf.
</P>
<P>
   He left Fiji when life become difficult for people of Indian
origin in the mid-1980s, and he became a club professional in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You teach a few lessons in the morning and practice all
afternoon,'' he recalled Sunday after he won the PGA by two strokes
over Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hitting the ball in 100-degree heat and trying to make
some money,'' he said. ``I never thought that I'd ever come to
America, anything like that. My wife and I say we came a long way.
Sometimes my wife says maybe we should just go back there, that it
was the best time of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   People often say that when they have worked their way to another
life, another world. They look back with love and respect for what
they had, for who they were. That would have been all right, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Vijay Singh was a good enough golfer that he went out
searching for championships, and the money they would bring. There
were so many strange golf locales that he found it hard to remember
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Africa,'' he said Sunday. ``Playing on sand greens in
Nigeria when I won that championship. It was a learning process.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved to London, and competed on the big-time tour, a man
with a name that means ``victory'' in Hindi. When he got to the
United States, and ran into its racial history, the legacy that
makes Tiger Woods such a double-edged phenomenon, Singh wanted none
of it.
</P>
<P>
   He just wanted to play golf, not deal with the racial anxieties
of another society. He'd paid his dues in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep or no sleep, Singh was on the course Sunday, in the last
pair to tee off, at high noon. He is tall and full, almost
diffident, with very little tension or energy to him. If he hit a
ball particularly well, and somebody in the crowd yelped ``you the
man'' or ``nice shot,'' Singh did not acknowledge it. The nerves
had translated into something fine, something precise.
</P>
<P>
   On a course of narrow fairways that demanded accuracy over
distance, Singh kept smacking the ball in the right direction. When
he made a particularly good shot, and the crowd cheered, he waved
one hand, briefly.
</P>
<P>
   He putted cross-handed, the way he learned as a child from his
father in Fiji, the way he did it in Malaysia, where he and his
wife met. Along the line, common wisdom said he ought to break the
cross-handed habit, and he did, going from putter to putter, from
style to style the way some people change cars or hair styles.
Earlier this season, his wife suggested he go back to putting the
way he did when they were young.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said I might as well,'' Singh said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So he putted the old way all this week in the shadow of the huge
fir trees. On Sunday, his wife and their 8-year-old son, Qass Seth,
were walking the course, on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have a heart attack before I get to the top of
this hill,'' she said on the 16th, but she was talking about the
steep climb, not the tension. Her husband was well in control. When
he sank the putt that gave him the title, he gave one more modest
wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always set our minds on a major,'' he said later. ``I
always wanted to win one, but you only have four chances every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if the people in Fiji would be celebrating his
victory, and he was not sure. ``The biggest sport in Fiji is
rugby,'' he said. ``Golf is just part-time. I hope I'm a hero
there. I haven't been back there in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   His skill has taken him to other places. Now he has won a major
tournament, and some day soon he and his wife may feel that this,
too, was one of the best times in their lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
