<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-BOMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVASTED NORTHERN IRELAND TOWN EXAMINES ITS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ Pregnant with twins, Avril Monaghan
was holding her 18-month-old daughter Maura and standing next to
her 65-year-old mother Mary Grimes, thinking they were safe behind
a police line, when the bomb went off.
</P>
<P>
   In a flash, three generations of that family were killed. A
grandmother, a mother, a child, and children not yet born, all were
wiped out in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Avril Monaghan, 30, her mother, and her
children captured, in all its horror, the magnitude of the damage
done by a car bomb that exploded Saturday afternoon in the shopping
district of this market town in County Tyrone.
</P>
<P>
   The history books will record that Saturday's bombing was the
worst single act of terrorism in a conflict that has stretched over
30 years and has included great inhumanity. Twenty-eight people
were killed and 220 were injured. Last night, 103 people were still
hospitalized, 11 of them in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The prime ministers of Britain and Ireland met Sunday night and
vowed to track down the bombers, believed to be dissident Irish
republicans who call themselves the ``Real IRA'' and who are
dedicated to wrecking the peace process. The prime ministers said
it was especially dastardly that the bombers had called in an
inaccurate warning that led police unwittingly to move civilians,
many of them mothers with children doing back-to-school shopping,
closer to the hidden bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians continued to squabble over how much the bombing had
destabilized the peace process and the accompanying spirit of
cooperation and accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, as weeping relatives and stunned friends tried to
find out if their loved ones had died or had been injured, it was
hard to dwell on the political fallout of the bombing, so immense
was the suffering in this town of 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   If the minutes that followed the bombing were sheer terror,
Sunday's slow, tedious accounting of the dead and injured was sheer
torture. Relatives and friends of the victims flooded Tyrone County
Hospital, where many of the injured were being treated, and the
Omagh Leisure Center, which had been converted into a makeshift
information center, to learn if their loved ones were killed or
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Silence hung over much of Omagh, but it was occasionally
shattered by a grief-stricken cry, as news of a death or mutilating
injury was passed on.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not officially name the victims, saying that
relatives were still being contacted last night. But Royal Ulster
Constabulary Superintendent Kevin Sheehy did give an account of the
dead, one that underscored the losses felt across Ireland and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of the dead were women, five were men, three were
girls, and four were boys. Two of the bodies were so badly
mutilated they have not yet been identified. When Sheehy announced
that seven of the dead were children, members of the press corps
gathered at the Omagh Leisure Center gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends put a human face on the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the dead boys _ Sean McLaughlin and James Barker, both
12, and Oran Doherty, 8 _ were from Buncrana, a village in
neighboring Donegal, part of the Irish Republic. They were part of
a group that was hosting Spanish students who for the past 10 years
have visited Buncrana to learn English. One of the Spanish
students, a 12-year-old boy, and one of the Spanish teachers, a
24-year-old woman, both from Madrid, also were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven Spanish students remained hospitalized. Jose Maria San
Pastor, Spain's ambassador in Dublin, drove up to comfort the
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could do such a thing, to children?'' San Pastor asked.
</P>
<P>
   San Pastor's question reverberated among the locals, who bore
the brunt of the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Death was cruelly arbitrary in Omagh. The staff at Watterson's
drapery store was evacuated after someone called police and said
the bomb was near the courthouse. Like others evacuated from the
vicinity of the courthouse, the staff at Watterson's were told by
police to stand behind the security cordon at Market Street and
Dublin Road.
</P>
<P>
   But it was at that very corner that a 500-pound bomb exploded in
a maroon Vauxhall sedan that had been stolen from a border town in
the Irish Republic on Thursday. Two of the women who worked at
Watterson's were killed, while another had an arm and leg
amputated. The Watterson's storefront, meanwhile, escaped without a
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Paddy McGowan, a town councilor, said one of the two saleswomen
killed was his friend, Geraldine Breslin, 35, the mother of a young
girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get over the irony of it,'' McGowan said. ``Geraldine
thought she was safe, but she was actually moved so that she was
standing just a few feet from the bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   If the ladies at Watterson's thought they had been moved out of
harm's way, Libby Rushe thought she was already safe, working in a
coffee shop behind the police line. Rushe's body was badly
disfigured, and it was not until 24 hours later that her husband
learned of her death. He pushed past reporters, tears streaming
down his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor man,'' muttered Joe Byrne, the recently elected local
member of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, who like many local
politicians went to the leisure center to comfort their friends and
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were both Protestant and Catholic. They came mostly
from Omagh and the surrounding countryside, in town on a sunny
Saturday afternoon to shop and to watch a carnival to promote
cross-community relations.
</P>
<P>
   Aidan Gallagher, 21, went in town to buy jeans. He was standing
outside the store when he was killed. Lorraine Wilson, 15, and her
friend, Sandra McFarland, 17, worked in a charity store and were
among those evacuated to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Philomena Skelton had gone shopping for back-to-school clothes
for her children. Her husband, Kevin, found her dead, on top of a
pile of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Gibson, 30, was a Sunday school teacher whose cousin,
Oliver Gibson, was elected to the assembly as a member of the party
of the Rev. Ian Paisley, the radical unionist. Paisley cited her
death Sunday as proof that the British government's policy of
``appeasing terrorists'' led to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The misfortunes of the bombing extended beyond this usually
sleepy town. An ambulance transferring one of the more seriously
injured victims to a Belfast hospital collided with a car in
Belfast. The already injured victim survived, but the driver of the
car was killed.
</P>
<P>
   There was almost as much concern for the living as there was for
the dead. Survivors' guilt was said to be developing among many of
those who lived while those around them died.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey Young, a social worker who is trying to help the
survivors, said among those most traumatized by the bombing was the
bus driver who drove the boys from Buncrana and their Spanish
guests to Omagh for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were looking for something to do and the bus driver
suggested they go to Omagh, to the Ulster-American Folk Park. They
had done that and had come into town to walk around the shops,''
Young said. ``Now the driver blames himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Chesters is just 11 years old, but he wonders why he was
spared and so many others were not. Barry and his father, Pat, were
shopping for back-to-school sneakers when the bomb warning came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spanish kids and the boys from Donegal were in the sports
store when I was there,'' Barry said. ``The police told me and my
daddy to move. We didn't. We ran up to my granny's house.''
</P>
<P>
   After the bomb, Pat Chesters ran to the scene to help. He found
a 12-year-old schoolmate of Barry's on the ground, his legs blown
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why them,'' 11-year-old Barry Chesters asked, ``and not me?
Why Omagh?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
