<SLUG> BC-REFORM-HISTORY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES CORPORATE ELITE HAVE PRECEDENT FOR POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (With BC-REFORM-ENEMIES-LADN and BC-REFORM-LIST-LADN for use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK MCGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The decision by 26 of Los Angeles' current
corporate heads to plunge into the city's civic and political
affairs has a precedent in the 1950s and '60s, when a group called
the Committee of 25 dominated the power structure.
</P>
<P>
   Headed by Asa V. Call, the CEO of Pacific Mutual Life Insurance,
the Committee of 25 was a group of white business CEOs and
prominent attorneys who hand-picked mayors and City Council members
and dictated directions to City Hall from their corporate
boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They set policy for the city,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political science professor who has studied the history of city
government.
</P>
<P>
   Former Los Angeles City Councilman Marvin Braude, who was
elected in the 1960s, remembers going toe-to-toe with Call and
other members of the committee over the budget and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very, very powerful in the early days,'' Braude
said. ``When I came along, they were still influential but their
power had started to wane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Encyclopedia of the City and County describes the Committee
of 25 as a group of business executives who ``served as a sort of
shadow government, choosing public officials for appointment or
election and setting the agenda for public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee picked mayors and police chiefs and followed its
conservative business leanings to kill tax increases and other
objectionable city policy decisions with a few phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Call, who Braude described as a charming,
eloquent spokesman for Republican causes, the white male group
included James Lin Beebe, an attorney with the powerful downtown
law firm O'Melveny and Myers, as well as University of Southern
California President Norman Topping, University of California, Los
Angeles Chancellor Franklin Murphy and Norman Chandler, publisher
of the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Like the old group, the new Los Angeles Business Advisors
includes the heads of the Times and USC as well &UR;  &LR; as an attorney,
Warren Christopher, from O'Melveny and Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It resonates of the Committee of 25, although it does not
appear to be as powerful or as institutional,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   The new committee also is mostly made up of white males,
although a woman and a Japanese auto company executive have been
included.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a political standpoint, it would be preferable to look
like the Rainbow Coalition, but it looks more like the old
Committee of 25,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee of 25 lost its influence as the demographics of
the city changed in the 1960s and '70s and Latino and
African-Americans rose up in the political system and formed strong
coalitions that had a voice in city government.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question that caused a diminution of their power and
influence,'' Braude said. He also said that more people became
involved in the political process, reducing the role of a select
few.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community was also broadening out so it just
didn't include downtown businesses,'' Braude said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan said Call was such a commanding figure
that his death in 1978 marked the end of the Committee of 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Asa Call who was the dictator,'' Riordan said. ``He
used that (committee) as a front to try to get things done. He
could get anything he wanted done for businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
