<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAIN-LIBRARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUPTURE IN 100-YEAR-OLD WATER MAIN DOES SEVERE DAMAGE IN LIBRARY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ More than 50,000 Boston Public Library reference books,
maps, and documents were damaged or destroyed Sunday after a
rupture in an 1895-vintage water main sent hundreds of thousands of
gallons gushing into the Copley Square building's vaults.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned library officials called the loss one of the most
``devastating'' in the library's history and closed the building at
least through today to drain about 3 feet of water saturating the
first three shelves of almost every basement book stack.
</P>
<P>
   The book ``US Ocean Policy in the 1970s'' floated by several
city workers pumping out the basement through an entry on Boylston
Street Sunday. In the newly renovated library basement, yellowed
books and maps were submerged in murky water in a darkened
government documents room.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of residents throughout the city felt the
effects of the early-morning water main break when they turned on
faucets Sunday to find rusty _ but safe _ water coming out. Some
residents also felt small declines in water pressure, city
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water is fine,'' said John Sullivan, Boston Water and
Sewer chief engineer. ``It's just discolored.''
</P>
<P>
   Water officials were able to contain the roughly 1 a.m. rupture
within three hours by diverting the pipe's water flow into smaller
water mains. No service was disrupted. But because more water than
usual was rushing through the smaller pipes, rust inside them was
carried into homes. Officials said the discoloration should
disappear by today.
</P>
<P>
   There was no warning the 42-inch cast-iron water main behind the
library at the corner of Dartmouth Street and Huntington Avenue was
going to break. The 100-year-old pipe, the largest main bringing
high-pressure water into the city, was relined with cement only 10
years ago and declared safe, city officials said. But shortly after
midnight Sunday, it developed a 4-foot-long jagged crack, pushing
out millions of gallons of water _ 3 feet deep at some spots _ into
Copley Square.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Green Line Copley Square inbound MBTA station was
closed because water was still lingering in its entranceway, fire
officials said. The Massachusetts Turnpike Copley Square entrance
ramp was also closed and several streets around the library were
shut down to make room for emergency vehicles and more than a dozen
pumps to drain the library basement. Most of the road closures were
expected to end by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he did not know why the pipe burst, but tests in
coming weeks may point to a reason. The main, which runs along
Huntington Avenue to the Boston Common, will be out of service for
three or four days as city officials replace the ruptured section.
</P>
<P>
   The damaged books and materials are replaceable, but library
officials Sunday hesitated to guess at the cost until a full
inventory is conducted this week. Three years ago, the basement
underwent a $20 million renovation, updating reference rooms,
installing new computers, and upgrading machinery that helps run
the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst damage I've ever seen,'' said Joe Sarro,
superintendent of city library buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino, on his way to a Red Sox game to honor
city children in a BPL reading program when called to assess the
damage, said he was ``frustrated'' by the loss of books. ``This is
the gem of our library system ... the best public research library
in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The library houses about 6 million books and is the region's
best resource for government documents.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 15 percent of the library's science reference
material was damaged or destroyed, said Gunars Rutkovskis,
assistant library director in charge of research material. Many
government patent documents, topographical maps, books, and
encyclopedias were in the flooded McKim building basement, part of
the library's original structure. Sarro said he fears that old LP
record jackets in a sound archive room will have to be thrown away
because of water damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, while we've not seen anything of this magnitude, it
will not affect our ability to serve'' customers, said Rutkovskis.
</P>
<P>
   The library is not open on Sundays during the summer and library
officials said all branches will be open today. Bruce Cole, the
library's chief financial officer, said all programs at the library
will be canceled today and, most likely, tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   While weary police, fire, and sewer officials Sunday dodged
gushing water from pumps and tried to divert traffic and curious
bystanders, they said it appeared that not all realized how deep
the water could get during a large water main break.
</P>
<P>
   One man, driving a Mercedes convertible, ignored police warnings
shortly after the rupture and insisted on driving down Huntington
Avenue, police said. He got only a few hundred yards before water
starting pouring in over the top of his car doors. A few minutes
later, his car stalled. A few minutes after that, he got a $100
ticket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
