<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' LINE NOT INSPIRING QB CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells virtually appointed Glenn Foley Sunday as
the Jets' starter in the annual exhibition game with the Giants on
Thursday. Foley's job is not in jeopardy _ but his health could be.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how much the offensive line, which had big
problems against the Baltimore defense on Saturday night, will
protect the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells didn't actually come out and say Foley would start
against the Giants _ whoever is first string in this third
exhibition game will start the season _ but he did tell reporters
on a conference call that nothing has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said that the whole time, it still stands now,'' Parcells
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said he wanted to tell the quarterbacks that himself.
</P>
<P>
   If Parcells literally means nothing has changed, then Foley,
whom the coach has said for months is his starter unless Vinny
Testaverde plays better, remains No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde started against Baltimore in Saturday night's 33-0
debacle, a move Parcells said was made merely to get him experience
with the Jets' first-string offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Testaverde had to play behind a renovated line and it was
hardly a fair test, even though Curtis Martin made his Jets' debut
and carried 12 times for 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Pressured inordinately, Foley did worse.
</P>
<P>
   He was sacked once and two of his passes were intercepted in a
loss in which offense, defense and special teams had one of the
worst performances of the Parcells regime.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde was dumped three times. He completed six of his 10
pass attempts for 54 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Foley completed only a third of his passes _ five of 15 _ for a
mere 37 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our quarterbacks were a little jumpy, and rightfully so
because of mistakes on the offensive line,'' said Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is moaning about left tackle Jumbo Elliott's sprained
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   If Elliott cannot play, the quarterback will feel it because
Elliott is usually matched against the opposition's key
pass-rusher.
</P>
<P>
   He was out Saturday, and rookie Kerry Jenkins was overmatched
against Michael McCrary, so much so that Lonnie Palelei eventually
moved over from left guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pass-protection worries me,'' said Parcells. The revamped
line, besides Jenkins, included Palelei at left guard for Todd
Burger, whose pass-protection concerns Parcells, and the rookie
right tackle Jason Fabini.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Parcells, ``With Elliott in there it looks a little
different _ if he doesn't play this week then I really will have a
concern. Then we have only Chicago to get ready for the season. It
would be hard for me to think he'd be ready for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was indignant that Elliott didn't play _ even though it
was Parcells who kept him on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought he'd probably play,'' Parcells said.
``Looking at him I didn't think he wanted to. If he doesn't feel
good about it then I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells perceived that Elliott was favoring the ankle and
wasn't too happy about playing on it.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it only was an exhibition game _ and on grass, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is happier on artificial turf, which will be in place
when the regular season starts.
</P>
<P>
   So look for Martin to do even better at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better on turf,'' said Martin. ``I'm looking forward to
it. I might have been able to break some runs on turf. I felt I was
in the best shape of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells grudgingly conceded that, well, yes, that really wasn't
his best team out there, especially the special squads.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to play the ``A-team'' against the Giants in hopes
of avoiding another 97-yard punt return. Jermaine Lewis' big play
set the tone against the Jets on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Including the kick-returners and punter, the Jets started 10
players who had been backups when camp started.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has now seen what they can do. Most will go back to
their second-string status.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Parcells is putting pressure on his assistants.
</P>
<P>
   They were forced to come in three hours earlier than scheduled
Sunday to review films in an attempt to prevent such a drubbing in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think,'' said Parcells, ``practices will be easy this
week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
