u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TESTIMONY-BOS     08-16 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTIMONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNUSUAL DRAMA WILL BE PLAYED OUT MONDAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's grand jury appearance Monday by
closed-circuit television will inject a jolt of drama in federal
court proceedings, legal specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite unusual,'' said Paul Cassell, a law professor at
the University of Utah Law School and an advocate for victims'
rights. ``The courts have a strong preference for face-to-face,
in-person testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Televised testimony before a grand jury is virtually
unprecedented, according to Fredric Lederer, a professor at William
and Mary's Marshall White College of Law and a specialist in the
use of technology in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president occupies an anomalous position because this is a
grand jury, and as a rule, the requirements for appearance are
minuscule,'' Lederer said. ``The grand jury could have operated
without Clinton's testimony. It could have considered a written
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Lederer said Clinton's testimony from the White House and
televised to the grand jury room in the federal courthouse a dozen
blocks away, apparently is a tactical move by independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr to get the president to answer questions under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors will be able to write questions that are
relayed to prosecutors questioning Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Michael D. McCurry announced Friday that the
president will testify from the map room in the White House. The
testimony will begin at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   While this will be the first time Clinton testifies before a
grand jury and uses closed-circuit television, he has provided
videotaped testimony three times. Twice he testified via videotape
for trials, of his former political and business associates, that
grew out of the Whitewater portion of Starr's investigation. Those
tapes were played for jurors in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's deposition for the Paula Jones sexual harassment
lawsuit also was videotaped. The lawsuit later was dismissed before
going to trial. But the president's lawyer, David E. Kendall, last
week received permission to review the videotape, which remains
under a court seal.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Starr said Clinton's lawyers will handle the
logistics of the closed-circuit broadcast, including setting the
camera angle and view of the president and the room. Such decisions
could influence the way grand jurors react to Clinton's answers.
</P>
<P>
   If the taped testimony is ever viewed publicly, the image could
have political ramifications. A close-up view of Clinton's face,
for example, could have a different impact than a picture of the
president in a suit and tie sitting behind his desk.
</P>
<P>
   The video signal will be scrambled to foil any outside attempts
to intercept the transmission during the broadcast, partly because
grand jury testimony is secret and largely to prevent anyone from
making a copy of Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Lederer, who has supervised tests on how televised testimony
affects jurors, said a neutral camera angle does not appear to
affect viewer perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can tell you from experimental work conducted down here in
a normal trial, it appears that normal jurors seem to accept remote
testimony the same way that they accept in-court testimony,'' said
Lederer, director of Courtroom 21, a project on how technology can
improve the operation of the legal system. The effort is conducted
by William and Mary's law school and the National Center for State
Courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an illustration of the ways in which technology can be
used in the courtroom,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 2241EDT &QL; 
