<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JOURNEY-BOS &LR;      08-16 1694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JOURNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG JOURNEY LED TO SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inevitably, it had to come down to this: President
Clinton vs. independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances are unprecedented: a sitting president
testifying Monday under oath to a grand jury about sex and perjury,
with his political life at stake. But after four years of
shadowboxing, of throwing mean punches but delivering no knockout
blows, these shrewd and stubborn enemies have anticipated this day
and its decisive fight.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here _ how Starr's investigation of a puny and
obscure Arkansas land deal turned into a titillating sex scandal
that has consumed Washington and threatens the president with
impeachment _ is a tale full of twists and turns. Ultimately,
though, it starts and ends with the man in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``What binds it all _ from Whitewater to Travelgate, from Paula
Jones to Monica Lewinsky _ is the whiff of scandal and corrosive
immorality around a president who has character defects and doesn't
seem to tell the truth,'' said Robert Dallek, a Boston University
history professor and the author of ``Flawed Giant,'' a biography
of President Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton says he will tell the grand jury the truth
about the nature of his relationship with Lewinsky, a former White
House intern. For days, the suspense has built and stories have
been leaked that the president will try to end this sorry saga by
admitting he lied when he denied having intimate encounters with
her and will publicly apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders blame Starr, as obsessed as Captain Ahab
with snaring the Big One, for not shutting down an investigation
that has produced a dozen indictments of minor figures, cost
taxpayers more than $30 million, intimidated hundreds of innocent
people, and cheapened the public discourse and the presidency with
leaks about stained dresses and oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Recent news stories say Starr's expected impeachment report to
Congress will focus almost entirely on whether the president lied,
or asked others to lie, under oath about an alleged sexual
relationship with Lewinsky. Lanny Davis, a former White House
special counsel, said that would prove the independent counsel has
``come up with nothing'' in everything he investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident the president did nothing legally wrong, and I
believe the process has been severely compromised by a prosecutor
who has poor judgment and has lost his sense of proportionality,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Some call Starr a misguided missile on a political mission.
Others think the former judge is a sober truth-seeker thwarted by
White House ducking, delays, and denials. ``The White House has
waged a war to destroy Ken Starr,'' said Theodore Olson, an
assistant attorney general in the Reagan administration. ``I admire
the job he is doing under extraordinarily difficult
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving aside his motives, it is clear that Starr's mandate has
been broadened repeatedly, sometimes not at his request, since he
took over in 1994 from Robert Fiske, the special prosecutor
appointed by Attorney General Janet Reno to look into the
Whitewater land deal.
</P>
<P>
   At issue then was whether Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton and
James and Susan McDougal, their business partners in Whitewater,
personally benefited from an illegal $300,000 federal loan in 1986
for Madison Guaranty Savings and Loan, which McDougal owned.
Investigators wanted to know if Clinton, when he was governor of
Arkansas, had helped the McDougals get the loan _ $50,000 of it
ended up in a Whitewater account _ and what the nature of Mrs.
Clinton's legal work in the Rose Law Firm was for Madison, which
later failed.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1996, Starr, through his grand jury in Little
Rock, Ark., indicted 10 people connected to Madison, including both
McDougals and Jim Guy Tucker, who succeeded Clinton as governor;
Starr also obtained five guilty pleas.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence apparently wasn't there on the Clintons,
lawyers say, even though Starr suspected Mrs. Clinton was lying
about the extent of the legal work she did for Madison and for
Castle Grande, a sham real-estate deal that federal regulators
believed had illegally enriched Webster Hubbell, her law partner,
and Hubbell's father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's suspicions grew only after Mrs. Clinton's long-sought
law firm records mysteriously turned up in the White House
residence in January &UR;  &LR; 1996. In a dramatic confrontation, Starr
subpoenaed Mrs. Clinton to appear before his grand jury in
Washington. She denied any wrongdoing, including hiding documents
or obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's billing records were also the reason Starr's
scope was expanded to the 1993 suicide of Vincent Foster, the
deputy White House counsel who, too, had worked at the Rose Law
Firm. Starr questioned White House aides about the Clintons'
personal papers that allegedly had been removed from Foster's
office after his death. Starr has not brought charges in that case,
and he disappointed conspiracy theorists by confirming Foster's
death was a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the three-judge panel that oversees independent
counsels gave Starr jurisdiction over two more White House
controversies. In the first, the 1993 firing of the White House
travel office, Starr was asked to determine if any White House
officials or Mrs. Clinton had lied about who ordered the
dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, the so-called ``Filegate'' case (distinct from
the so-called ``Travelgate'' case), Starr's office probed why the
White House had improperly collected hundreds of personal FBI files
on former appointees in GOP administrations. The independent
counsel also was asked to find out if former White House counsel
Bernard Nussbaum lied to Congress when he said he did not know who
hired Craig Livingstone, an aide in charge of the files.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said mistakes had been made, but no crimes were
committed. Carl Stern, who was spokesman for the attorney general
at the time, said Starr did the investigating ``for efficiency and
economy of effort. His office was up and running.''
</P>
<P>
   No prosecutions came out of either case, and indeed, it appeared
that the independent counsel might be on the verge of filing a
final report finding no crimes or cause for impeachment hearings,
and close up shop. In February 1997, Starr announced he would leave
his post in the fall to become dean of the law school and dean of a
new public policy school at Pepperdine University in California.
</P>
<P>
   That was a turning point: Pundits, the press, and conservative
politicians criticized Starr for giving up. How could he quit, some
asked, while Starr had both Susan McDougal and Webster Hubbell
serving time _ she for contempt of court, he for bilking money from
the Rose Law Firm _ and there was a chance that either still could
turn on the Clintons and cooperate with him? Starr agreed to press
on.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, his office was questioning whether friends of the
Clintons had arranged about $700,000 in income for Hubbell, a
former associate attorney general, to keep him from talking. One of
those friends was Washington lawyer Vernon E. Jordan Jr. When
prosecutors learned early this year that Jordan might be trying to
buy Lewinsky's silence with job offers, they used the
Hubbell-Jordan connection to justify widening the Whitewater probe
to include the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Linda R. Tripp approached Starr's office on Jan. 12 with
homemade tapes purporting that Lewinsky, her Pentagon coworker, had
had an affair with the president and was asked by him and Jordan to
lie about it in her testimony in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Lewinsky had been subpoenaed by Jones's lawyers,
who were trying to prove a pattern of behavior in the
sexual-harassment case brought against Clinton by Jones, a former
Arkansas state employee who alleged the then-governor asked her to
perform a sex act in a Little Rock hotel room in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, Clinton gave his deposition in the Jones case and
denied a sexual relationship with Lewinsky. The deposition took
place just days after Starr got both his expanded investigation
approved by Reno and the three-judge panel as well as a newly taped
conversation between Lewinsky and Tripp, who had been wired by the
FBI. Earlier this month, under a grant of full immunity, Lewinsky
reportedly told Starr's grand jury that she and the president had a
sexual affair but that Clinton did not urge her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a federal judge dismissed the Jones lawsuit in
April, the president's deposition has become the focus for a
possible perjury or obstruction-of-justice case. The deposition is
expected to be central to his testimony Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Starr may be able to bolster his case with physical evidence,
including a dress the FBI is examining and gifts the president
allegedly gave Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The civility that the Clintons and Starr maintained through the
early Whitewater years has, of course, been poisoned by the nearly
seven-month Lewinsky probe. James Carville, a Democratic political
operative, says Starr is ``obsessed with sex,'' and Mrs. Clinton
has called him part of a ``right-wing conspiracy.'' Starr says the
White House is a ``culture of lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Washington's war of words, the spin, the scorecard of
who's winning and losing, and the leaks, the public still knows
precious little about the four-year-old Whitewater probe. More, but
far from all, may be known when Starr makes what is expected to be
two reports _ one presenting evidence of possible crimes to
Congress, another wrapping up the other probes for a three-judge
panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the independent counsel statute encourages
witchhunts or vendettas,'' said Stephen Gillers, a professor of
legal ethics at New York University School of Law. ``But there is a
human dimension. The White House strategy of demonizing Ken Starr
has probably had the effect of encouraging him to resist the
attack, get all the information he could, and now file the best
report he can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980816.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIE     08-16 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 `A DAY IN THE GARDEN': MEASURING THE DISTANCE BETWEEN THEN AND
NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.Y. _ The mantra of real estate _ ``location, location,
location'' _ was at the heart of ``A Day in the Garden,'' the
three-day rock festival that started here on Friday. The site is a
gently sloping hillside that was Max Yasgur's alfalfa field and
then, more famously, the amphitheater for the 1969 Woodstock
festival. Two major songwriters who rarely perform, Joni Mitchell
and Pete Townshend, headlined Saturday's concert.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Reed, who also performed on Saturday, said backstage that he
wasn't haunted by ``the ghost of Woodstock.'' But most performers
on Friday and Saturday, including some who appeared at the 1969
festival, measured the distance between then and now: between
idealism and disillusionment, between bravado and practicality,
between youth and middle age.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ms. Mitchell sang ``Woodstock,'' about the festival
she never saw, as an elegy for a vanished moment. Introducing the
song, she said, ``My generation, which was given a pocket of
liberty like no other generation in a century, did some of the
right things for a short time.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival site has not been used for commercial events since
1969. Woodstock '94 took place in Saugerties, N.Y., and was
presented by Woodstock Ventures, which owns the Woodstock trademark
but not the site. Alan Gerry, a cable-television billionaire,
bought 2,000 acres here in 1997, including the hillside; ``A Day in
the Garden'' was produced by his Gerry Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   After 1969, visiting Yasgur's farm became a pilgrimage for
people who wanted to commemorate the Woodstock legend of
cooperation, idealism and communal pleasure. Melanie, who performed
on Saturday, has been back each year, singing for the tens or
hundreds of people who have shown up on the festival's
anniversaries. ``I left a piece of me in this field,'' she said
from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   With ``A Day in the Garden,'' the site of the unintentionally
free festival of 1969 unveiled its new commercial role as the
center of a projected theme park devoted to American music. It's
surrounded by split-rail fences now, and the festival setup
included souvenir stands, effective security and a magnificently
clear sound system. A second stage, over the crest of the hill,
presented local bands.
</P>
<P>
   The festival sold 12,000 tickets for Friday, 18,000 for Saturday
and more than 25,000 for Sunday. Even with the addition of children
(admitted free), daily attendance was less than one-tenth the size
of the crowds at Woodstock in 1969 or at Woodstock '94. And where
Woodstock was a youth gathering, ``A Day in the Garden'' started
with two days aimed at baby-boomers now in their 40s and 50s.
Sunday had a schedule of seven younger bands, including Joan
Osborne, Third Eye Blind and the Goo Goo Dolls, and lower ticket
prices; that's when the moshing started.
</P>
<P>
   For the festival, concertgoers hauled out the tie-dyed shirts
and peace-symbol jewelry. And nostalgia was the rule as Don Henley,
Stevie Nicks and Ten Years After dispensed their hits on Friday.
With Ziggy Marley sick, his brother Stephen Marley led the Melody
Makers in songs by their father, Bob. Donovan, Melanie and Richie
Havens harked back to the 1960s on Saturday. Melanie sang about
community; Havens sang about freedom and compassion. Bill Perry,
playing lead guitar with Havens, copied Jimi Hendrix's wrenching
version of ``The Star-Spangled Banner,'' now separated from its
context, the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Mitchell only looked back briefly. The bulk of her set
drew from the albums she has made since she released ``Hejira'' in
1976.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They share a private, contemplative style that barely
acknowledges pop's demands. Wispy, attenuated melodies float in
arrangements without edges, built on reverberating guitar chords
and liquid, shifting rhythms. She writes melodies like a jazz
singer's improvisations, using flexibility and fragmentation
instead of pop's repetition and hooks. One of the least abstruse
songs she performed was from Billie Holiday's repertory, ``Comes
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mitchell's lyrics are diaristic, drifting from reflections
on the news to questions about the purpose of life to updates on
romance. In songs from her next album, due in September, Ms.
Mitchell sang about lovers hiding the sounds of passion behind
train whistles, about bringing a new partner home to a disapproving
mother and about how ``lawyers and loan sharks are laying America
to waste.'' Even when her opinions grow cranky, what holds the
songs together is Ms. Mitchell's voice, pearly and assured, making
her free-floating vagaries sound like shared confidences.
</P>
<P>
   In his set, Townshend looked over his shoulder at the 1969
festival. He played two songs popularized by Canned Heat, who
performed at Woodstock in 1969, and for his finale he played the
same song the Who concluded with in 1969: ``Listening to You,''
from ``Tommy,'' this time joined by a gospel choir. Backstage, he
admitted that the Who had prolonged their 1969 set to play at
sunrise; this year, he stretched songs with long vamps that shifted
from meditation to filler, apparently to end past sunset.
</P>
<P>
   His set ambled through his long career, from mid-1960s Who songs
to one from his most recent album, ``Psychoderelict,'' which, he
cheerfully noted, was a ``complete commercial bomb.'' Songs from
his solo career were about a search for love, including divine
love; songs from the Who, including radically rearranged versions
of ``The Kids Are Alright'' and ``Anyway, Anyhow, Anywhere,'' were
about youthful energy, and Townshend made them explode when he
finally started playing windmill power chords on electric guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, whose 1960s band, the Velvet Underground, wasn't invited
to perform at Woodstock, was a magnificent sore thumb. Amid the
tie-dye, he and his band wore black; amid the greenery, he sang
about urban grit; amid the invocations of love, he sang about
random violence and violent impulses. Mostly, however, his set was
about guitar muscle: lean, wiry guitar riffs, from basic
three-chord rock to a furious funk crescendo. The music was smart,
bruising and elegant, with no wasted motion.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's show could give a younger generation ample reason to
scoff at its elders. Ms. Nicks, playing through the traditional
Woodstock rainstorm, was a model of baby-boomer self-absorption.
``Can we do this again?'' she said after her last song. ``It would
be so good for me.'' Ms. Nicks presented herself as princess,
dreamer and scorned lover; the scratchiness of her voice was once
the earthy balance to her fantasies, but she now sounds mostly
tattered.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Years After trotted out its repertory of leering blues
attached to extended, repetitive jams; in one song, Alvin Lee
played the same speedy guitar lick 26 times in a row. He has
learned one new trick over the last three decades: tapping the
strings with both hands like Eddie Van Halen.
</P>
<P>
   Henley played an indifferent, professional set that reproduced
the album versions of his hits, down to the guitar solos; rather
than introduce any new songs, he sang material by John Hiatt,
Leonard Cohen and Randy Newman. But as the Woodstock site took its
first steps toward becoming a theme park, he did have a song for
the occasion: ``The End of the Innocence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
