<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MATTER WHAT IS SAID, LOOK FOR THE SPIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's testimony today to a federal
grand jury has the making of a media extravaganza. There will be
dozens of televised ``special reports,'' countless legal analysts,
and an untold number of journalists on hand.
</P>
<P>
   But will anyone outside a closed-circuit video connection
between the White House and the grand jury room really know what
Clinton says about his alleged sexual relationship with former
intern Monica S. Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing is sure: There will be spin, and plenty of it.
</P>
<P>
   This being Washington, there is widespread expectation that
details of the testimony will be leaked by anonymous sources. And
both special prosecutor Kenneth Starr and White House aides will
begin ``spinning'' their versions of Clinton's grand jury testimony
as soon as it is over.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a guide of what to expect under two main scenarios:
 &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton changes story, admits an affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If this happens, look for Democrats to say the story is over.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will respond that Clinton's revised story amounts to
an admission Clinton committed perjury in his deposition in the
Paula Jones sexual-harassment lawsuit, in which Clinton said he did
not have sexual relations with Lewinsky, according to the
definition of a sexual encounter approved by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will counter that Clinton's contradiction of his
earlier testimony does not amount to an impeachable offense,
because perjury in a civil suit is rarely prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sticks by his story, saying there was no sexual
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will have little choice other than to stand by their
man and hope he is telling the truth. Look for Clinton allies to
feel free to start raising questions about Lewinsky's credibility,
noting that she previously swore she did not have an affair with
Clinton and then changed her story.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Republicans to call for full hearings in Congress on
whether Clinton is telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spin is especially important because the outcome
for Clinton will likely be determined by the public and Congress,
not by the courts. Starr is expected to send a report within a few
weeks to Congress, which will decide whether to hold impeachment
proceedings. If Clinton can convince the public that he has done
nothing wrong or that he has a reasonable explanation for his
actions, then the House would be less likely to try to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to admit that he had a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky, it would be in the White House's interest to get that
information out as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incumbent upon President Clinton to be sure that his
version of events be told quickly and accurately,'' said former
White House special counsel Lanny Davis, one of Washington's
premier spin meisters. Davis, like a number of former White House
officials, has urged Clinton to speak to the nation after the
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the first spin on the story is crucial. ``That testimony
is going to be leaked, probably inaccurately and probably
incompletely, by people who do not have his best interest at
heart,'' Davis said. ``That has been our experience to date.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the White House says Clinton told the truth and refuses
to elaborate, that won't answer the question of whether the
president changed his January denial of an affair. After all, it
was Clinton who insisted in 1992 that he did not have an ``affair''
with Gennifer Flowers and then admitted having sex with her once in
1977, all without acknowledging that there was any contradiction
between the two statements. Most reporters covering the story are
likely to ask whether Clinton has found a similar sort of semantic
explanation for what happened with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if the White House says that Clinton once again
denied having sexual relations with Lewinsky, reporters will ask
how Clinton defined sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself may try to control the story with silence,
asserting that he does not want to talk about the matter while it
is under investigation. But this tactic, which Clinton has been
using while remaining silent, is not based on any legal
prohibition. Clinton, or any other witness, is allowed to say
whatever he wants. So if Clinton wants to uphold his promise that
he would explain the matter ``sooner rather than later,'' there are
no legal limits stopping him from discussing his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Selective leaks to the news media are just as significant as
spin. For example, after Clinton agreed to testify to the grand
jury, it was leaked that Lewinsky had provided Starr with a dress
that may or may not contain Clinton's DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has not been confirmed that Clinton's DNA is on the
dress, the reports led to widespread speculation that there may be
independent evidence to corroborate Lewinsky's reported testimony
that she had an affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton changes his story today but refuses to acknowledge it
publicly, it is likely that Starr or his allies will leak that
information, thus setting the stage for a tough report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Other takes on the story are likely to come from a host of
surrogates for Clinton and Starr, as well as legal analysts and
others, who may or may not know something about the testimony. This
will fill the airwaves for hours. But given how much misinformation
and disinformation has come out already in the Lewinsky story, it
may not mean much until the president's own words are made public.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it's all spin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Leonard of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
