<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      08-16 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, STARR PREPARE FOR SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton huddled for hours with his
lawyers and family Sunday as he braced for one of the most pivotal
passages in his presidency, an unprecedented session Monday before
a federal grand jury investigating him for possible crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Amid reports that Clinton is poised to retreat from his
longstanding denial of a sexual relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky, the president privately prepared for the crucial legal
and political challenges posed by his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of the potential consequences emerged in a last-minute
frenzy of anticipation by some of Clinton's top foes and allies
alike. Reacting to the possibility Clinton will acknowledge a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky, a former White House intern,
several key supporters expressed bitter disappointment while a
leading rival said the president should resign if he committed
perjury in the deposition he gave in Paula Corbin Jones's civil
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The grand-jury session is scheduled to begin at 1 p.m. in the
White House map room. Clinton will be questioned by Kenneth W.
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, and his deputies. The
session, expected to last several hours, will be broadcast by
closed-circuit to 23 grand jurors in a federal courthouse a mile
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be easy for the president,'' said former
White House chief of staff Leon Panetta on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president changes his testimony and acknowledges an
improper relationship,'' Panetta said, ``he obviously is going to
have to go through a lot of pain himself, not only in apologizing
to his wife and his family, but to the staff and to those that he
misled and to the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Close advisers to Clinton were quoted by several news
organizations Sunday as saying they expected the president to
acknowledge engaging in sexual activity with Lewinsky, who was 21
when the affair allegedly began in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Such an admission could contradict Clinton's sworn testimony in
January, when he said during a deposition in the sexual harassment
case involving Jones that he and Lewinsky did not have a sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The contradiction could lead Starr to conclude that Clinton
committed perjury. Starr is expected to file a report on the matter
with the House, which will consider what action to take, if any.
The most extreme possibility would be impeachment by the House and
a trial in the Senate to determine if he should be removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he lies before the grand jury, that will be grounds for
impeachment,'' said Senator Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican who is
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   However, polls have shown little public support for impeachment
proceedings related to the case, whose underlying allegation
involves sex between consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment issue has been largely overblown,'' said
Representative Barney Frank, a Newton Democrat who is a senior
member of the House Judiciary Committee, which is expected to
receive Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out the president is going to say, yes, there was
some sexual activity between him and Monica Lewinsky and he covered
that up to protect his family, herself, himself, et cetera, I think
that will be regrettable but hardly an impeachable offense,'' Frank
said on ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Although few members of either party supported his view, Senator
John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican with presidential aspirations,
said Clinton should step down if he committed perjury or other
crimes involving the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president is guilty of those things which he's been
accused of doing,'' Ashcroft said on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' ``he
ought to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers, who were quoted on the condition of
anonymity, said the president is expected to deny vigorously that
he broke any laws, including perjury, suborning perjury, and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief outing Sunday with Hillary Rodham Clinton to the
Foundry United Methodist Church in Washington, Clinton made no
public comment. He entered the church holding Mrs. Clinton's hand
and carrying a Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The couple sat in a front pew as the congregation joined in an
inspirational reading that said in part, ``When we have opposition
and hopeless situations, God bears us up on eagles' wings.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, there was no official statement on the
substance of Clinton's pending testimony. ``The lawyers report that
the preparation is going well, that the president is confident
about tomorrow,'' spokesman Joe Lockhart said. ``He knows what he
is going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   As the buzz about the session consumed the morning news shows,
the president's lawyer, David E. Kendall, issued a terse statement:
``There is apparently an enormous amount of groundless speculation
about the president's testimony tomorrow. The truth is the truth.
Period. And that's how the president will testify.''
</P>
<P>
   If the truth is that Clinton did have sex with Lewinsky, he
would need to give the public a speedy explanation in order to
limit the likely backlash, members of both parties said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president were to change his story, I think he needs to
square it with the American people and with the members of
Congress,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat
who serves on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be extremely disappointed,'' Meehan said, if Clinton
changed his testimony. ``And I would feel terrible for Mrs. Clinton
and the president's daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Clinton's top political aides met at the White House
Sunday to discuss how Clinton should address the matter after his
testimony. The options include a televised speech tonight. But
Clinton is not expected to decide how to proceed until his
testimony ends.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Associated Press reported that Starr has gathered
evidence of roughly 75 telephone conversations between Clinton and
Lewinsky. Many of the conversations were initiated by Clinton,
according to people familiar with the investigation, who spoke only
on condition of anonymity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
