<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TELL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDIANA TOWN, PEOPLE EXPECT THE TRUTH
</HEADLINE>
 CITY-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELL CITY, Ind. _ Surrounded by lamps and chairs and curios,
some of them antique, some of them just old, Scott Dixon laid claim
to values that are as timeless as his merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Don't lie. Don't cheat. And if you do cheat, don't lie about it.
That goes for a small-town merchant as well as the president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that he would never stray from his sweetheart of two
years, the 27-year-old Dixon insisted ``a decent person would fess
up if he did.'' He expects no less from Bill Clinton now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he lied, he ought to just go ahead and admit it,'' said
Dixon, who runs a mom-and-pop antiques store on the edge of town.
``We've got hometown values here, and what he's been saying so far
just don't sound right to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tell City, people say they want Clinton to tell the truth in
his testimony before the grand jury Monday. They don't care how he
tells it _ in a quivering voice or in the powerful preacher's
cadence he calls upon from time to time _ as long as he tells it.
Even people who said the president's personal life is none of the
nation's business are waiting to hear his words.
</P>
<P>
   As Josephine Lahee, 64, who helps twist thousands of pretzels a
day at the Tell City Pretzel Co. on Main Street, put it, ``Why cry?
He knew when he said what he said the first time that he was
fibbing. Don't do a Jimmy Swaggart. Just be straightforward and get
it over with already.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why any of this is such a big deal I'll never know,'' said
Sandy Hazelip, 33, a secretary. ``But it's been an issue for long
enough now. He needs to come clean. He better come clean.''
</P>
<P>
   That refrain was heard throughout this town of 8,000 near
Hoosier National Forest on the southern edge of Indiana. It came
from Republicans as well as the Democrats who hold the power in
Perry County, where Tell City was settled by Swiss and German
immigrants who set out from Cincinnati in 1856 to find a new home
along the Ohio River. It came from people who said they appreciate
Clinton the president but despise Clinton the man.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon didn't vote for Clinton, but said he supported him until
the president went on TV in January and adamantly denied having
sexual relations with Monica S. Lewinsky, the former White House
intern. Hazelip said she has never cared for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Over a lunch plate of meatloaf, mashed potatoes, and cornbread
at the Freezer Cafe, factory worker Kevin Beaver said he wants
Clinton to tell the truth and apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is he's not a decent person, but he's done a decent
job as president,'' Beaver said. ``I'd like to hear him say, `I did
it and I'm sorry,' then we can go back to judging him on how he
runs the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton presidency has been good for Perry County in general
and Tell City in particular.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, as technology made manufactuirng jobs obsolete,
the unemployment rate in the area soared past 18 percent. Now new
businesses are arriving, among them the Waupaca Foundry and a
General Electric plant, and unemployment is around 4.5 percent. The
turnaround, said Greg Wathen, executive director of the Perry
County Development Corp., has helped keep young adults from leaving
the area. The county population is almost back to its 1979 peak of
19,432, and per capita personal income now stands at about $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   The people who live in Tell City sound like many other
Americans. They are tired of Washington scandals. They want their
tax dollars spent on something other than investigating the
president's private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did or didn't do with that Monica girl don't matter to
me,'' said Paul Vogelman, 52, who has been unemployed since the
chair factory where he worked folded. ``I want to hear about health
care. I want to hear about jobs. Too many other things are going on
in this country to listen to this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Shirley Vogelman, 56, a nurse's aide who, like her
husband, hasn't voted in years, ``That should be between him and
his wife. He should've said, `It's none of your business' in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   People also said they are wary of what their neighbors will
think of what they think, and many of those interviewed refused to
be identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was elected as a known pathological liar and so that's what
we got,'' a school official who declined to give his name said of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who expressed fears of losing her federally funded job
if her name was attached to her opinion of Clinton, said, ``I want
to hear the truth, whatever it is ... Not that I expect to get it,
mind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever that truth turns out to be, many residents said they
will try to find it in their hearts to forgive him. As much as
truthfulness, forgiveness is a virtue here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't tell the truth, then I would be really angry,''
said Lahee, the pretzel company worker. ``But we probably won't
ever know, will we?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
