<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF SILVER, BACK IN FORM, WINS HER SECOND STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Form was served with precision at
Saratoga Sunday, for a change, when Memories of Silver, the clear
favorite, won the $200,000 Ballston Spa Handicap by two lengths and
the second choice, Witchful Thinking, ran second.
</P>
<P>
   The race was only the second this year for Memories of Silver,
who sustained a stress fracture of her right hind leg last
November. Running with two metal screws in her leg, she won her
second straight race. With Jerry Bailey riding, she won for the
eighth time in 17 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old mare, who is trained by James Toner, ran the mile
and a sixteenth on the grass in 1:40 4/5. She returned $3.60 for a
$2 bet to win and earned $126,600 for a career total of $1.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping she was the same old Memories of Silver,''
Bailey said, ``and she was.''
</P>
<P>
   NTRA Progress Report
</P>
<P>
   The first 100 days of the new National Thoroughbred Racing
Association were depicted in glowing terms before the racing
industry's most prominent owners and breeders at the Jockey Club's
46th annual Round Table conference Sunday at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   The glow was provided by Tim Smith, the Atlanta lawyer who took
office as commissioner of the NTRA on April 1, and by several of
the vice presidents and marketing people he has hired. They said
they had created a ``league office'' for racing, a national buying
service, a national television plan and, pitching the whole effort
toward a young audience, a new slogan: ``Go, Baby, Go.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort cost racing people $22 million, some of it spent to
buy time on the Fox Sports network for a series of eight races next
year for senior handicap horses. The series will begin on Jan. 30
with the Donn Handicap at Gulfstream Park, which has been moved up
one week to take advantage of Fox's broadcast of the Super Bowl the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   Points will be awarded to horses, somewhat in the manner of the
American Championship Racing Series, which went out of business
three years ago. The new series will end in August; Smith could not
say whether Saratoga would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also announced the formation of a committee on racing
integrity and drug testing. It will consist of eight members under
Ogden Mills Phipps, chairman of the Jockey Club, and R.D. Hubbard,
chairman of Hollywood Park. Its chief goal will be to recommend
policies to evaluate and standardize drug-testing procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Cameo for Skip Away
</P>
<P>
   The big gray horse took the track by himself between the fourth
and fifth races Sunday, and the crowd needed no prompting to know
that this was Skip Away, the champion older horse and
second-leading money-winner in racing history. He was dressed in
full battle regalia for his workout, and he even had his regular
jockey, Jerry Bailey, in the saddle as he made a public appearance
booked to soothe people who wanted to see him run at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   Both his owner, Carolyn Hine, and his trainer, Sonny Hine, who
is her husband, were watching from the winner's circle, where Skip
Away has appeared seven straight times while running his career
earnings to $8.9 million, just $1 million behind Cigar. His next
performance will be at the Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Park on Aug.
30.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away was clocked in lightning times: 23 1/5 seconds for the
first quarter-mile, 46 3/5 for the half-mile and 1:10 for
three-quarters of a mile. When he came back to the winner's circle,
Sonny Hine was awarded one of the Skip Away posters given to
spectators as they entered the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they say he doesn't like Saratoga,'' Sonny Hine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to see him go in 1:11, but he always goes
quicker than I want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
