<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.-OPEN-FOOD-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPEN HOPES CATERER'S RETURN WILL BE A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ These days, as New York City prepares to serve up the
last Grand Slam tournament of the year, are tennis die-hards
focused on whether Patrick Rafter can defend his title? Are they
rooting for Pete Sampras to retrieve his No. 1 ranking? Do they
worry whether Martina Hingis can hold off the Williams sisters yet
again?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   This is the U.S. Open at the National Tennis Center in Flushing
Meadows, Queens, the most star-powered fortnight in all of sports.
And naturally, New York's tennis mavens are obsessed with the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot believe the incredible preoccupation with the food
at the Open,'' said the comedian Alan King, who has attended the
tournament since the 1950s and said that the cuisine has become
``just about as legendary as the tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to some stunning culinary volleys recently, courtside
gourmets will be studying the menu with new urgency at this year's
Open, which begins Aug. 31. Last year, when the newly renovated
National Tennis Center made its debut with much fanfare, there were
howls of protest over slow service and the price of pizza. The
caterer, Sportservice Corp. of Buffalo, resigned in February after
completing only two years of its seven-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   So the U.S. Tennis Association brought back Restaurant
Associates, the street-smart New York food provider that served the
Open from 1976 to 1995, introducing courtside delicacies ranging
from quiche to panini and baguettes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in spring, Restaurant Associates _ creator of some of New
York's most popular restaurants, including the Four Seasons and the
Brasserie _ was acquired by a British concern that is the world's
largest food-service company, Compass Group PLC. And suddenly, the
Open became the first public test of this new multinational
corporate pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open food'' has been a subject of compulsive scrutiny since
Restaurant Associates introduced quiche Lorraine in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-breathing news bulletins on such introductions as tamarillo
fruit and ciabatta bread, as well as on the price of pizza, have
been one of the longest-running cliches of the coverage of the
Open. ``When they don't have any interesting matches to show, the
TV crews always feel they have to do reports on the food,'' said
Malcolm Knapp, who heads a restaurant consulting concern in
Manhattan that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   And Restaurant Associates ``will be under the microscope because
they're coming back,'' he added. ``People think the food service
last year stank, so there will be a lot of questions: Is the food
good again? Is it being served on time at parties and in the
suites? Has RA been affected by the acquisition? And what about the
cost?''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the food crews are slaving round the clock at the
Tennis Center, under fierce pressure to prepare for the assault of
the expected 550,000 visitors over 14 days who will buy $12 million
worth of food. Restaurant Associates is putting 1,300 hourly
workers on the front line, and bringing in 200 managers.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the tourney, tennisdom is expected to go through
40,000 pounds of hot dogs, 50,000 pounds of hamburgers, 3 tons of
shrimp, 2,000 gallons of tomato sauce, 12,000 cases of Evian water,
15,000 baguettes and 15 tons of french fries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like the biggest opening of the biggest show you can
imagine,'' said Nick Valenti, chief executive of Restaurant
Associates. ``You have to stay focused or you'll be overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   While most spectators' perception of the cuisine is shaped by
hamburgers and pizza slices, the ultimate judgments are made by
corporations that have parties for hundreds in their hospitality
suites or entertain clients in the restaurants and private boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stadium restaurants have to look permanent and feel
permanent, and then you shut them down in two weeks after
satisfying the most demanding audience in the world,'' Valenti
said. This year the operations include the five restaurants, 35
concession stands and the Food Village stands as well as the 90
luxury suites and the dining operations for the Open staff, the
umpires, the news media and more than 600 players.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the job for Restaurant Associates is the
unpredictability of the demand for food, which ``ebbs and flows
every day due to the match-ups, the scores and the weather,''
Valenti said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, summer brownouts have shut off the electronic
registers. A near-tornado tore down food tents. Hundred-degree days
have tested soda inventory and 50-degree nights have challenged
hot-coffee delivery. ``When the temperature goes above 90 degrees,
we sell no food,'' said Joe Polidoro, the company's vice president
for special events. ``It's just water, soda and beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Knapp, the consultant, said the Open is always a food gamble
because ``all you need is one or two rain days and your profit is
gone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Michael Bailey, president and chief
executive of the North American subsidiary of Compass, the new
corporate parent of Restaurant Associates. ``The risks are always
great at sporting events, the uncertainties many,'' he said. ``But
of course, customers aren't interested in the problems of
organizing the event, they just want a good sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for Compass, the dominant force in the
lucrative European event-catering and stadium-service industry,
which acquired Restaurant Associates ``to move us into the
concession market in the United States,'' Bailey said. ``RA will
allow us to seriously bid for more museums, performing arts centers
and sports groups nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Also under pressure is the Tennis Association, which was stung
last September by corporate displeasure. ``Some people had a bad
time last year,'' acknowledged Suzanne Maguire, who supervises
food-service operations for the association. ``I hope they'll give
us a chance and give Restaurant Associates a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, corporations are pleased. Recently, Restaurant
Associates held a tasting for suite-holders and
corporate-hospitality planners. ``The presentations were beautiful,
and the choices were smart,'' said Rosemarie Salvatore, a
coordinator of the Open suite for Arthur Andersen, the accounting
and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to be eating light in summertime,'' she said,
explaining that ``last year they had hot food in chafing dishes,
all wrong for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a shame _ the stadium was gorgeous but the food
was lacking, disorganized and everything was last-minute,'' she
said. ``So many people had food delivered late, and didn't get what
they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Sportservice Corp. in 1996 generated seismic waves
of food-world gossip thanks to the fame of the restaurant companies
involved. The Buffalo caterer took as its local subcontractors two
of the biggest names in New York's food firmament: Joseph Baum &AMP;
Michael Whiteman Co. in Manhattan and Glorious Food, the upscale
caterer for society, celebrities and art galleries.
</P>
<P>
   But in March, Sportservice exercised the exit clause in its
contract. ``We are in business to make money and, unfortunately,
the way our contract with the USTA was structured, that simply
wasn't possible,'' said Nancy Parker, president of Sportservice.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that was the reason Restaurant Associates decided in
1995 against accepting a stringent contract offered by the tennis
association.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Restaurant Associates is back, Valenti is promising
aficionados better food at a lower price. Slices of pizza will be
$4.25 instead of $5; at $3.25, the all-beef frankfurter on caraway
bun with Grey Poupon mustard will be 25 cents cheaper than its
less-distinguished predecessor last year, and ham and Brie on a
baguette will be a dollar cheaper, at $7.50, than last year's more
ho-hum ham and Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this price-cutting, Knapp said that Restaurant
Associates could make a profit thanks to its ``operating
efficiencies and the economies of scale they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti has no intention of losing money. ``This may be a
high-profile event, but it certainly can't be a loss leader,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for now his troops are focused less on profit, or loss, than
on doing battle. ``This year Yogi Berra is our philosopher,''
Valenti said. ``It ain't over till it's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
