<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Polls just a way to say `We're No. 1'
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ So this year it's Ohio State, unanimous
choice of the media types who order The Associated Press pre-season
poll and the coaches who rank college football teams for USA Today
and ESPN. Works for me, whether the Buckeyes are deserving or not.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the best team will bubble up over the course of an
entire season, not in the collection of one slipshod survey. It is
a law of physics, right after the one that says an object at rest
must remain at rest until the stupid alarm goes off.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State had no business being ranked No. 1 in the AP poll
last August. Neither, in retrospect, did Florida belong atop the
coaches' pre-season poll. Proving the point is simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how the Nittany Lions and Gators met in the Florida
Citrus Bowl on New Year's Day? Should have been yet another Game of
the Century according to the summer seedings, but it didn't even
qualify as the Game of the Afternoon. Michigan and Washington State
easily earned that honor in a Rose Bowl matchup that promised to
settle at least half of the national championship picture. The
other half belonged to Nebraska and Tennessee in the Orange Bowl,
the Game of the Following Day.
</P>
<P>
   What the polls planted in August, in other words, were apples
and what blossomed in January were oranges. Exotic oranges at that,
a juicy Michigan-Nebraska hybrid that tasted sweet to some and sour
to others.
</P>
<P>
   Always constants
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a few reliable factors from year to year.
Florida State and Nebraska will live up to their pre-season
billing. Tennessee will not. Notre Dame will get thrown into the
rankings somewhere just because it is Notre Dame. And Air Force or
one of the other service academies will pick up a few by-the-way
votes just because this is America, pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   Atop this shaky framework a No. 1 team must be tacked every
August. This year it's Ohio State, a team that lost three times
last year and finished at No. 12. Accept that as a coronation or a
curse, but not without reviewing the following list of teams whose
pre-season 1997 rankings varied wildly from the listing that
mattered most, the 1997 put-it-in-granite post-season poll.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, for openers, dropped 15 spots last year from its
original No. 1 ranking in the AP poll. Michigan, the eventual
national co-champion, climbed from 14th to first in the same poll.
Nebraska started No. 6 on both summer charts, then wound up the
coaches' choice as national champion and second in the AP voting.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, Washington State and Georgia were the real movers,
however. Completely unranked in August, each wound up in the top
ten.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, Washington State received one measly vote on the
original AP chart. Incredibly, Rice did, too. Let's face it. Rice
shouldn't start the season on a par with a Rose Bowl team, not even
if Uncle Ben has an AP vote.
</P>
<P>
   It's only paper
</P>
<P>
   Save the indignation, therefore, over FSU being ranked behind an
Ohio State team the Seminoles beat by 17 points in last January's
Sugar Bowl. Save the angst over the Gators starting out behind the
Seminoles, or the Hurricanes being blown off altogether. Save it
all until something significant happens. A kickoff, let's say.
</P>
<P>
   The straw polls of summer may prove to be right about the
Buckeyes and all the rest of it, but you'll need a Ouija board to
convince me just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
