<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLINS-GAME17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins fall to Giants 3-2
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Runs can be deceiving, and they sure were for
the Florida Marlins on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, they got two. They scored one in the first on a
bases-loaded single by Derrek Lee, and another in the sixth on a
solo home run by Kevin Orie.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of this game _ which ended in a 3-2 loss to the
San Francisco Giants at 3Com Park _ was the runs they didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the same story all series,'' Orie said. ``We had our
chances. Usually, if you squander just one opportunity against good
teams you're going to lose. And we had a few today, which makes it
that much more frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Five times in the game, the Marlins had a runner on third base
with less than two outs. Only one of those five scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we obviously need to get better at,'' right
fielder Mark Kotsay said. ``Getting that runner in from third with
less than two outs. It's the fundamentals. You do all the little
things right, and you're usually rewarded with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Little things. Like scoring more than one run in the first
inning if the first four batters get hits.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that's right. The first four Marlins hitters singled off
Giants starter Orel Hershiser. Lee's was the fourth of those
singles, and it came on Hershiser's sixth pitch and drove in Todd
Dunwoody from third.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, Cliff Floyd hit a hard line drive to right that
wasn't deep enough to score the runner from third, Orie popped out,
and Gregg Zaun grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time in a long time that I can recall a
team getting four hits and only one run in an inning,'' Giants
manager Dusty Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Giants got two runs in the bottom of the first
against Marlins starter Jesus Sanchez, Hershiser had a lead in
spite of himself. The Giants extended the lead to 3-1 in the bottom
of the fifth against reliever Brian Edmondson, so Orie's homer
simply cut the lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   They could have had more in the sixth, as Luis Castillo singled
with one out and went to third on center fielder Shawon Dunston's
error. But Hershiser struck out Ryan Jackson and Dunwoody to strand
Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   And they could have had at least one in the eighth, when Orie
stood on third with one out. But former Marlin John Johnstone
struck out pinch-hitter John Cangelosi and Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that many opportunities, you've got to produce
in one of them, at least,'' Dunwoody said. ``There's no excuse.
I've got to perform in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't. And neither did anyone else. Lots of bad things
happened to the Marlins in this one:
</P>
<P>
   _ They failed to get two key sacrifice bunts down, and one of
those failures cost them Sanchez, who left the game in the fourth
inning with a cut on the tip of his index finger where the ball had
hit it on his failed bunt attempt;
</P>
<P>
   _ And they struck out 12 times, including 10 with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Jim Leyland's 2,000th game as a major-league manager
turned into his 1,013th loss. And the Marlins lost all three games
in San Francisco to finish their west coast road trip 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible at-bats,'' Leyland said. ``Terrible at-bats in big
spots. It's the same thing every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Graziano writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
