<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Meara settles for fourth
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It must have been another Sunday at a major,
because the name ``O'Meara'' was once again moving to the top of
the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, bidding to join Ben Hogan as the only golfers to win
three majors in the same year, got within two shots of the early
lead shared Sunday by Vijay Singh and Steve Stricker at the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Meara fell back with three straight bogeys. Typically, he
steadied himself to shoot 68 and finish tied for fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a great dream to go alongside Ben Hogan,
but it just wasn't meant to be,'' O'Meara said. ``Just to be
mentioned in the same breath is pretty amazing,'' O'Meara said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara looked to be following the pattern of his victories in
the Masters and British Open when he made a 40-foot eagle on the
second hole and followed that with a birdie on the fifth. But he
missed the green on the next three holes and failed to get
up-and-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized if I got off to a quick start, I had just as good a
chance as anybody else,'' O'Meara said. ``But unfortunately the
bogeys on six, seven and eight really kind of took the wind out of
my sails.''
</P>
<P>
   Price makes run: Jupiter Island's Nick Price made a late move at
winning his third PGA title, going birdie-birdie-eagle from the
ninth through 11th holes to move into third place. But he never got
closer than four shots after finishing with seven consecutive pars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't give myself much of a chance of winning
because it didn't look like either Vijay or Steve were wavering,''
Price said. ``I felt I had to get it to seven-under, and that's a
tall order on these last six holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Price didn't come away empty, shooting a five-under 65 to match
Greg Kraft's day-old course record. He also finished tied for
fourth, matching his performance at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about the course record a little bit,'' Price said.
``And I had a great opportunity on 16 (missing an 8-footer) and the
ball hung on the lip on 17. But I putted as well today as I have in
a long time, so that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Renwick gets caddy hat trick: Singh may have won his first major
Sunday, but this was the third major victory for his caddy, David
Renwick of Scotland. Renwick also won the 1995 PGA with Steve
Elkington and the 1994 Masters with Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best,'' Renwick said. ``Why? Because of Vijay.
He's a great guy to work for. He never gives you any crap out there
and he listens to you. I know people say he doesn't have a
personality, but that's just the way he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Renwick, 45, started working with Singh 10 months ago. Among the
many players Renwick has worked for during the years was Tequesta's
Jay Townsend on the European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: With O'Meara winning the two majors, Tiger Woods
will be able to join his close friend in the Grand Slam because
Woods had the best performance in the majors among players who
previously had won a major.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was eighth at the Masters, 18th at the U.S. Open, third at
the British Open and 10th at the PGA. They will be joined by Singh
and U.S. Open winner Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
