<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-BISHER-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singh finally wins big one on U.S. soil
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Vijay Singh has now won a golf tournament in 13
countries, and the lucky 13th was the biggest, the sweetest of them
all. And before somebody else says it, let me say the fourth round
of the PGA Championship was a day of Singh-ing in the rain at
Sahalee Country Club, in the suburbs of Seattle. That is to make up
for a week of avoiding any cornball reference to ``Sleepless in
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, of course, is the first Fijian to win one of golf's major
championships. Also, the first Asian Indian. Also, the first former
pro from Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   The world has been Singh's tour since he set out from the
islands in the South Pacific, until he finally settled in the
United States in 1993 in Ponte Vedra, Fla. At the advanced age of
30, he became the PGA Tour's ``rookie of the year.'' At the age of
35 he is the champion of the golf pros' world, the PGA of America,
whose members are the guys dealing from the pro shops of your
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday broke at Sahalee with the possibility of several story
lines. Davis Love III had a chance to win again the championship he
won under the prophetic rainbow at Winged Foot last year. No PGA
champion had successfully defended his title since Denny Shute in
1937. Mark O'Meara had the chance of winning his third major of the
year, to go with the Masters and British Open, which hadn't been
done since Ben Hogan in 1953. Steve Stricker could celebrate his
return from oblivion, from 130th rank on tour to PGA champion.
Frank Lickliter, from out of nowhere, could win one for the
``blue-collars.'' Skip Kendall could win one for all the ``Skips''
in the world. And, was Sahalee ``Tiger-proof,'' as advertised? (It
was. Tiger finished tied for 10th.)
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and devastatingly, all the themes began falling apart.
O'Meara moved within two shots of the lead, then bogeyed himself
out of it with three duds in a row. Love had said, ``I needed to
get off to a hot start. I've made enough birdies. I just need to
eliminate the bogeys.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get off to a hot start again. ``I didn't birdie the
2nd hole and I hit it in the water again on the 5th,'' he said.
``That did it,'' though he picked up three strokes on the back
nine. If he had played the front nine as well as he did the back
nine over the four days, he could have been in the fight. He was
five over on the front nine, five under on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter managed to hang in and collect a check of $118,000 for
a tie-fourth. Kendall flitted across the board and out of sight.
Nick Price put up the best numbers of the day, a 65 that tied Greg
Kraft's course record, and of course, any record was a record for
all time at Sahalee. Colin Montgomerie went into the weekend just a
stroke off the lead, then crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The main event was taking place in the final pairing, Singh and
Stricker, who began the day tied at 203, seven strokes under
par-70. The 2nd hole is a par-5 playing a short 507 yards, the
green guarded by a pond up front and a bunker left. Singh got the
jump here when Stricker pulled his tee shot into the woods and took
two strokes to escape. Then he birdied the 3rd and 4th holes and
took a lead, but by the turn, Singh was two-up again.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of luck, the defining hole was the 11th, the second
par-5 that threads its way through the trees. Singh pushed his
approach shot into trees right of the green, and miraculously the
ball popped out on the putting surface. When he might have been
looking bogey in the face, he birdied, but so did Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good coming down the 18th fairway with a
two-stroke lead,'' he said. ``My caddie had told me about the 14th
hole, `Hey, you can do better than this. You're going to lose this
thing if you keep on playing like this.' '' He birdied the 15th
hole, and the rest was pretty academic.
</P>
<P>
   Singh has circled the globe many times trying to find his place
in golf's world, from South Pacific to Asia to South Africa and the
European Tour before coming here. He is somewhat of an introvert,
more dour than droll, sometimes amiable to arrogant. It is a world
in which he has found success, but somehow appears not to get full
enjoyment out of it. It seems he carried a chip on his shoulder
from some dark chapter in his past. This, then, should be the kind
of glorious event that could bring out a personality heretofore
hidden from public view.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher writes for the Atlanta Journal, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
