<P>
   (NYT7) BETHEL, N.Y. -- Aug. 16, 1998 -- WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIEW,
8-16 -- The Woodstock Festival 1998, ``A Day in the Garden,'' drew
baby-boomers to the same site as the original Woodstock festival in
1969. The festival site has not been used for commercial events
since 1969. Alan Gerry, a cable-television billionaire, bought
2,000 acres here in 1997, including the hillside; ``A Day in the
Garden'' was produced by his Gerry Foundation. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 16, 1998 -- SILICON-ALLEY-MEDIA, 8-16 --
Jason McCabe Calacanis, 27, right, publisher of the monthly Silicon
Alley Reporter, interviewing a job applicant over breakfast at
Balthazar's, in New York. Calacanis' shameless boosterism of
Silicon Alley -- New York's downtown multimedia hub -- has helped
create the aura of community and even home-team spirit for a
disparate group of colleagues and competitors who otherwise might
have little more in common than being located in Manhattan. (Thomas
Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) OSHKOSH, Wis. -- Aug. 16, 1998 -- MIG-PLAYTHINGS, 8-16 --
Owners of Yugoslav Sokos and other fighter jets, which cost between
$50,000 to $400,000, at an Oshkosh, Wis., air show. Since the end
of the Cold War, more and more Americans have been rushing to buy
surplus Russian MiGs, Czech L-39s, Polish Iskras and Yugoslavian
Sokos as private playthings. Starting with a handful of planes, the
fad has caught on, and now there are hundreds of fighter jets owned
by civilians. (Tracie Rozhon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DANVILLE, Calif. -- Aug. 16, 1998 --
KILLERKIDS-LAWYERS-2, 8-16 -- Bill Gagen, a lawyer in Danville,
Calif., consulted with a priest to help him to talk with a child
client who was accused of a fatal shooting. On Aug. 10, 11-year-old
Joshua Almaguer-Mendez, was convicted of a lesser charge,
involuntary manslaughter. But Gagen says he was never entirely
convinced that his client understood the magnitude of the legal
proceedings. ``I didn't see much interest in 'Are we winning or
losing? What are those witnesses saying or our witnesses saying?'''
says Gagen. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OAKLAND -- Aug. 16, 1998 -- KILLERKIDS-LAWYERS-1, 8-16 --
John Burris, a well-known Oakland civil rights lawyer, who has
defended the likes of Rodney King and Tupac Shakur. Burris met his
match with a client he agreed to defend two years ago -- a young
boy accused of trying to kill a baby. Burris found himself
struggling with how to best represent his client. ``Communicating
with a 6-year-old about legal matters is impossible,'' he says.
``One day I brought in my 8-year-old son's toys, rolled up my
sleeves and got on the floor and sought to communicate that way.''
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Aug. 16, 1998 -- AT&AMP;T-TCI-GREENTHAL, 8-16 --
Jill Greenthal, 42, a media banker for the investment banking firm
of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. Ms. Greenthal led a team that
advised Tele-Communications Inc. in its $70 billion deal to be
acquired by AT&AMP;T. Ms. Greenthal's work for the cable giant TCI has
made her a leading name in media mergers and acquisitions. ``I do
not encounter many other women in this type of role, especially as
team leaders,'' says Greenthal. ``The reason is probably the
conflict between raising a family and being on call day and
night.'' (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LODJA, Yugoslavia -- Aug. 16, 1998 -- YUGO-KOSOVO, 8-16
-- A pregnant ethnic Albanian woman, 23, from Lodja, suffering from
a head wound when the Yugoslav Army attacked her village, being
comforted by other women Sunday in the nearby village of Kotradic.
Although the government's stated target, the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, seem to have been hurt in the offensive, the
principal victims are almost certainly civilians. Perhaps 200,000
have fled their homes in recent weeks, and an unknown number have
been killed or wounded. (Stanton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
