<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-1ST     08-16 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-750(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR FINALLY CONFRONTS HIS TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Corrects spelling of Olson in final graf and rewords last
sentence in next-to-last graf.)  (See related stories: CLINTON-STARR-RDP, CLINTON-TESTIMONY,
CLINTON-PROSECUTORS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic showing the chronology of Starr's investigations
of Clinton is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After interrogating President Clinton's wife,
friends and closest political allies, Kenneth Starr's prosecutors
on Monday confront Clinton himself, the ultimate target of an
inquiry that began four years ago with an Arkansas land deal that
few Americans could fathom and became a sex scandal most Americans
say they would rather forget. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's office has been resolutely secretive
about the approach it will use in questioning under oath a
president with enormous popular resilience and a penchant for
hairsplitting. But lawyers familiar with the case say some hints
about the possible character of the questioning can be gleaned from
the roller coaster ride of the past seven months, when Starr's
inquiry abruptly shifted from the Whitewater real estate venture to
a chatty, love-struck former intern named Monica Lewinsky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They suggest that the prosecutors come to the interrogation
steeled by a sense of the Clinton presidency as a recurring pattern
of evasion, coverup and concealment. They suggest that the
questioners are unlikely to be intimidated by Clinton's office.
They suggest that Starr will come fortified with questions about
allegations of obstruction of justice, ranging well beyond the
intimate details of sexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, the prosecutors' decision to turn their attention
to the president's alleged sexual appetites may have seemed like a
radical, even desperate, departure from Starr's mandate. But it was
less of a leap for Starr. His many tentacled investigation, which
first focused on events when Clinton was governor of Arkansas,
evolved through the 1992 election campaign and continued into his
presidency, already focused on whether Clinton's intimates had
sought to suppress information by giving less than forthright
accounts or covering up questionable behavior.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Starr and some of his associates, the allegations of evasive
and deceitful behavior in the Lewinsky case were part of a pattern
they believed they had found in Whitewater, the White House travel
office episode, the death of White House deputy counsel Vincent
Foster and related matters.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the Lewinsky matter, the independent counsel's
staff of more than 40 prosecutors and investigators was sharply
divided, the lawyers disclosed, over how to handle the allegations
that Clinton had sex with the intern and conspired criminally to
conceal the encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors wanted to give Ms. Lewinsky immunity
immediately and quickly deliver a report to Capitol Hill solely on
the allegations surrounding her alleged affair with the president,
according to the lawyers. Others argued for a much more painstaking
approach, in which the grand jury would subpoena every possible
witness or document, assemble a detailed narrative that could
confirm Ms. Lewinsky's story and also draw parallels to alleged
obstruction of justice investigated in the earlier inquiries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was Starr, the deliberative former judge, who made the
decision. A man with no prosecutorial experience and a tendency to
ponder, Starr ultimately sided with those who wanted to squeeze out
every last bit of evidence about the president's relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky, setting the stage for a climactic showdown that poses
a threat of impeachment or a sullied place in history for Clinton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To his supporters, Starr has conducted his inquiry as an
old-fashioned, white-collar criminal investigation _ a meticulous
search for facts and contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was your typical, very plodding, very methodical criminal
investigation that moved toward gathering evidence that gets you
closer and closer to your ultimate target,'' said Barbara Olson, a
Washington lawyer who is a defender of Starr's. ``If you can't get
witnesses to cooperate _ and only one has cooperated here _ then
you get evidence any way you can, and you take as long as it takes,
and you don't worry about what anybody thinks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But to his considerable number of detractors, Starr's decisions
are those of an obsessed inquisitor desperately grasping for
something, anything, that can help him land a blow against a
frustratingly elusive adversary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could possibly perceive Ken Starr as `independent' at this
point?'' asked Nancy Luque, a former federal prosecutor who faults
Starr for lack of discretion in his zeal as independent counsel.
``He has so much riding on his report, a battle to the death. His
ability to continue with credibility in this town hangs on his
ability to get a scalp.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Starr Seeks to Expand Inquiry
</P>
<P>
   The events that will bring Starr to the White House Monday were
set in motion well before Clinton became president. During the 1992
campaign, The New York Times published an article describing the
involvement of Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton in the Whitewater
Development Co. and the role of their partner, James McDougal, an
Arkansas ally who had once run a failed savings and loan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That article prompted federal regulators to look more closely at
Madison Guaranty Savings and Loan, and they emerged with suspicions
of criminality in 1993, possibly by the president or his wife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fiske was named independent counsel to investigate, and
Starr took over in August 1994. His mandate quickly came to include
investigation of the suicide of Vincent Foster, a White House
deputy counsel, as well as charges that Webster Hubbell, the
associate attorney general, had bilked the Rose law firm in Little
Rock, Ark., where he and Hillary Clinton had worked before coming
to Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the inquiry ground on, the career prosecutors who had been
enlisted in the case became convinced that the Clinton camp was
thwarting their work.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Records of Mrs. Clinton's work for Madison Guaranty, which had
been under subpoena for several years but could not be found,
suddenly turned up in a White House room near the area where the
president resides. Companies with ties to Clinton paid Hubbell
hundreds of thousands of dollars in consulting fees, just as
Hubbell faced a prison sentence and prosecutors were pressuring him
to cooperate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so when Linda Tripp, Ms. Lewinsky's erstwhile friend,
approached Starr on Jan. 12 of this year with her surreptitiously
recorded tapes and allegations that the president had an affair in
the White House and tried to cover it up, lawyers say Starr's
office saw it as the latest episode in an ongoing pattern of
duplicity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investigators immediately seized on the purported role of Vernon
Jordan, Clinton's close confident, in counseling Ms. Lewinsky and
helping her find a job in New York after she was called as a
witness in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct suit. Jordan is a
director of Revlon, the company that had hired Hubbell as a
consultant and had agreed to hire Ms. Lewinsky before the
allegations became public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even before they went to the Justice Department, investigators
placed a hidden tape recorder on Mrs. Tripp, who recorded Ms.
Lewinsky making further statements about the effort to keep secret
her relationship with Clinton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With that, Starr felt he had enough to seek a broadening of his
mandate. And there was something more, the lawyers have now
disclosed, that hinted at a coverup and played a role in the
decision. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They say that Mrs. Tripp told investigators that when she had
worked as a White House secretary in the counsel's office, she saw
a memorandum with a notation by Hillary Rodham Clinton related to
the dismissal of the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr had never seen such a document, suggesting the possibility
that evidence in a case he was investigating had been destroyed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never cited publicly, the alleged missing memorandum became an
important element in Starr's argument to the Justice Department
that there was a multifaceted White House pattern of obstructing
justice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Starr presented the ``talking points'' document, which
Mrs. Tripp told prosecutors Ms. Lewinsky had given her to shape her
testimony in the Paula Jones case. Ms. Lewinsky now says she wrote
the document and had no help from anyone in the White House,
according to those familiar with her account.
</P>
<P>
   Reno Acts Quickly to Appoint Counsel
</P>
<P>
   For Attorney General Janet Reno, the decision to enlarge Starr's
inquiry was easy. She and five or six career and political
appointees agreed: Allegations of subornation of perjury and
obstruction of justice in a case in which the president is being
investigated was more than enough to meet the standard set by the
independent counsel statute of a ``conflict of interest'' for Ms.
Reno to conduct the inquiry, several lawyers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting on Jan. 16, they agreed that the case had to be
referred to an independent counsel. The only decision left was
whether it should be given to Starr. As one Justice Department
official put it, ``We knew that the president's deposition was the
following day and that it could take weeks for a new independent
counsel to be named. There was no time. And we didn't want people
to think we dragged our feet to help the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in the Justice Department had just decided that an
independent counsel would not be appointed to investigate campaign
fund-raising calls from the White House by the president and Vice
President Al Gore. They were especially sensitive to criticism that
the Justice Department had made that decision to protect Clinton
and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours of first hearing about Monica Lewinsky, Ms. Reno
referred the matter to a three-judge panel, recommending that the
inquiry be led by Starr. The panel quickly agreed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Long Delay Over Immunity Issue
</P>
<P>
   In the first days of the inquiry last January, the most
contentious arguments inside Starr's office had to do with Monica
Lewinsky. Some prosecutors wanted to make a deal with her _
immediately. Others wanted to wait. A few others wanted to indict
her, and use the threat of jail to make her talk.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 16, within hours of getting jurisdiction, Starr's
prosecutors confronted Ms. Lewinsky at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in a
Washington suburb. They made her an offer that symbolized the
aggressiveness of the office: In return for complete immunity from
prosecution, they asked her to help them secretly record
conversations with the president and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   She steadfastly refused, saying she did not want to do to anyone
else what Mrs. Tripp had done to her. Within several days, Ms.
Lewinsky's lawyer, William Ginsburg, made a ``proffer'' of what Ms.
Lewinsky was willing to testify to: She said she had a sexual
relationship with Clinton, but that he did not encourage her to lie
about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors were convinced that while Ms. Lewinsky was
trying to get herself out of trouble, she also wanted to protect
the president. A second proffer was made in early February. It
added details, and included an admission that she and Clinton had
discussed cover stories to conceal their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Two prosecutors, according to a Starr ally, advocated accepting
that proffer and concluding the inquiry within 60 days by sending a
report to the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   But several senior prosecutors prevailed by arguing that the
inquiry should continue and not rely solely on the word of Ms.
Lewinsky, which could easily end in a ``he said-she said'' case.
</P>
<P>
   The office would not seal a deal with Ms. Lewinsky until July
27, after five more months of inquiry that heard from nearly 75
witnesses. When Ms. Lewinsky testified before the grand jury on
Aug. 6, it is not known whether she added any more information than
she had initially provided in her February proffer.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came time for Ms. Lewinsky to sit down with
prosecutors in late July, she was stunned at how much information
they had. ``They knew everything,'' Ms. Lewinsky told a friend. And
her immunity deal mandated that she tell the whole truth, or face
charges of perjury. A friend said, ``She held nothing back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wide Sweep for Witnesses
</P>
<P>
   The standoff over immunity allowed Clinton's partisans to shift
the fight to the political arena, where they had a considerable
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's approval ratings tumbled toward single digits, his
prosecutors fought back, hauling before the grand jury White House
officials they believed were bad-mouthing the investigation. This
backfired, giving Starr's critics fresh ammunition to attack him as
an abuser, not a defender, of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting creamed,'' a ranking Starr assistant conceded
last March.
</P>
<P>
   At least one decision that was roundly criticized at the time as
a public relations fiasco appears to have paid off. Armed with
several allusions on Mrs. Tripp's tape, the prosecutors subpoened
Ms. Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis broke down under the questions and was portrayed by
Clinton defenders as a victim of sex-obsessed prosecutors
pruriently prying into confidences between mother and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turned out, Ms. Lewinsky had given her mother a
missing piece of evidence, according to those familiar with her
account _ a dress that is being tested at the Federal Bureau of
Investigation for DNA evidence that could link it to the president.
That made Ms. Lewis vulnerable to a possible charge of obstruction
of justice, and gave Ms. Lewinsky more incentive to strike a deal
with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton Faces Questions
</P>
<P>
   As they were closing the deal with Ms. Lewinsky and her mother,
prosecutors made another important decision: They issued a grand
jury subpoena for testimony from the president of the United
States. The subpoena was never acknowledged by the White House
until the day it was withdrawn and it was announced that the
president would testify voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 10 days that Clinton had the subpoena, Starr made
several bold moves and won several important legal victories. He
forced members of the White House Secret Service detail and Bruce
Lindsey, the president's closest confidant, to testify before the
grand jury. His ethics adviser, Sam Dash, meanwhile, was pushing
hard to wrap up the inquiry and arrange for an immunity deal for
Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, the day Clinton's subpoena ordered him to appear
before the grand jury, Ms. Lewinsky, who by now had cut her ties
with Ginsburg and hired new lawyers, stunned Washington with the
announcement that she and her mother had been granted full immunity
for her testimony. News reports said that Ms. Lewinsky would
testify about a sexual relationship. The following day, David
Kendall, the president's personal lawyer, announced that the
president, too, would testify on Aug. 17 from the White House via
closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers have said that he is considering
acknowledging that he had sexual encounters with Ms. Lewinsky, a
concession that might deflate talk of impeachment. But prosecutors
are certain to question Clinton about more than sex, and those
answers could prove more significant to the outcome of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   They will ask the president if he urged Ms. Lewinsky to return
gifts he had given her after they had been subpoenaed by the Jones
lawyers. They will also ask whether the president whether an effort
to find Ms. Lewinsky a job in New York was intended to keep her
from truthfully testifying in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a cliche that this investigation was never about
sex, but it really isn't,'' said Barbara Olson, the Starr partisan.
``It's always been about lies and coverups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
