<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON, KIRALY SERVE UP ANOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN VILLA  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERMOSA BEACH, Calif. _ Adam Johnson played so well on Sunday
that he had Karch Kiraly paying homage to him.
</P>
<P>
   As the three-time Olympic gold medalist and arguably the
greatest player ever to play beach volleyball watched, it was his
partner, Johnson, who carried the top-ranked team to victory. They
defeated the second-seeded team of Jose Loiola and Emanuel Rego
15-11 to defend their title at the 1998 Miller Lite AVP Tour U.S.
Championships in front of one of the biggest crowds ever Sunday at
the Hermosa Beach pier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the greatest serving performances that I've ever
seen,'' said Kiraly, who won his record eighth tournament title at
Hermosa Beach. ``It seemed like every time Adam went to serve, he
got us a point.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Johnson officially had four aces, including the
final point when he aced Loiola and Rego by serving an untouched
ball to the back line that split the defenders.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than the number of aces that made Johnson so
effective. Only a few serves were passed cleanly and the ones that
didn't go off Loiola or Rego's hands for aces were passed so badly
that the Brazilians could seldom set up their offense. Loiola and
Rego took an early 6-3 lead and later held an 11-9 edge, but the
defending champions kept rallying behind Johnson's serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing horribly to start the match and I just finally
said, `Hey, I don't want to go out like this,''' Johnson said. ``So
I decided to serve the snot out of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got in a groove where time _ even when they took
timeouts _ didn't seem to stop. I felt great out there, and I guess
I got into a zone where they couldn't make any clean passes on my
serves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiraly's win was the 136th of his career on the AVP Tour, just
three behind the all-time record held by Sinjin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson, ``I wish I could have played like that all year
long, but I seem to be peaking at the right moment. Besides, when
you're playing with the best volleyball player ever, you better
hold up your end of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiraly and Johnson were undefeated in the tournament and split
$10,416. Loiola, who entered as the tour's top-ranked player, split
$5,937 with Rego. The all-Brazilian team reached the final by
beating fellow Brazilians Roberto Lopes and Franco Neto 15-9.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes and Neto, seeded-seventh in their first season on the AVP
Tour, continued to impress. They finished third and scored
victories over Loiola and Rego and Kent Steffes and Mike Whitmarsh,
the tournament's second- and third-seeded teams. Steffes and
Whitmarsh finished fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
