<HEADLINE>
FASSEL PONDERS A CHANGE AS BARBER'S DROPS ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tiki Barber never thought his second professional
season, a season for which he has held great expectations, could be
disarmed by something so simple: He keeps dropping the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But halfway through the Giants' preseason, after dropping a few
wide-open passes in games and several more passes in practice,
Barber, the starting running back meant to be a multipurpose
offensive weapon, finds himself on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel of the Giants said Sunday that he might start
Gary Brown at halfback instead of Barber in Thursday night's
exhibition game with the Jets. Quarterback Danny Kanell has urged
Barber to take extra time catching before and after practice.
Reporters question him repeatedly about how long he has had this
``hands of stone'' problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any time someone hears my name they're thinking
about me dropping a pass,'' Barber said Sunday. He was the only
player on the practice fields 40 minutes before the afternoon
session was to begin in this final week of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Barber arrived early to practice _ what else? _ catching passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked myself, `What's wrong with me?''' Barber said. ``I
can't catch the ball. It's so odd because it's something I've never
worried about in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber acknowledges that the problem has become a mental one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run out of the backfield, the pass is coming my way, and I'm
thinking, `What are going to be the consequences if I drop this
pass?''' he said. ``That's a self-confidence thing. But I will just
have to work a little harder. A couple of good catches in a row
cures a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel sat down with Barber Sunday morning. The coach did all
the talking. ``I did say, `Yes, sir,' a couple of times,'' Barber
said. ``I always let the coaches do the coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel told Barber he also might reduce his role on third downs
on Thursday to take a longer look at the fullbacks Charles Way and
Greg Comella in third-down packages.
</P>
<P>
   That Fassel has been critical of Barber at all is a significant
change in their relationship. Barber has always been one of
Fassel's favorite players, a running back with the kind of
multipurpose skills that Fassel requires for his offense.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, in fact, was so eager to get Barber that he agonized
when the team took Ike Hilliard in the first round of the draft
last year. Fassel was afraid Barber would not last until the
Giants' second pick. But Barber was still there, and Fassel was
singing his praises the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The compliments have been coming steadily since, until the last
10 days, when the football was too often at Barber's feet and not
in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Barber said he had not been wounded by his coach's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to get on me,'' he said. ``It shows that he cares.
He told me that he's seen me make some spectacular catches and some
great plays and I'm not playing up to my abilities right now. And
he's right.''
</P>
<P>
   That Barber has had to spend so much time discussing what's
going wrong with his performance has been a profound disappointment
to him. Injured often during the preseason and during the regular
season last year, Barber had been counting on elevating his play in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That is because he considers last season _ when he had 810
rushing and receiving yards and quickly became a popular player
because of his darting, elusive running style _ a mediocre year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All during the winter, fans would come up to me and say, `You
had a great year,''' Barber said. ``And I wanted to say, `It was
all right.' It wasn't something I'd go brag about. People saw me do
a few good things, a special run or catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in college, I did that every three plays, not every four
games. I want to be like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday afternoon's practice, Barber did not drop a pass
in the team's seven-on-seven passing drills, and he made one
spectacular grab between two defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't something I should have trouble working through,''
Barber said. ``I guess it's just been concentration. I can renew my
commitment to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected to be out early for practice again on
Monday, Barber nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I need to do,'' he said. ``I understand the
message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
