<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON OFF TO NEVADA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mike Tyson's little end run around Nevada, and the
New Jersey Athletic Commission's irresponsible complicity in the
move have amounted to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who had his license revoked after he bit off a portion of
Evander Holyfield's ear last year in Las Vegas and was eligible to
apply for reinstatement on July 9, decided to try his luck in New
Jersey rather than Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   And New Jersey agreed to consider it _ a move that violated the
spirit of a law that requires commissions to honor the actions of
other states.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   A day before the commission was to announce its decision, it
appeared that Tyson's request for a license would be rejected as a
result of intense media and political pressure to pass the ball
back to Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most vocal politicians were New Jersey state Sen.
William Gormley (R-Atlantic City) and U.S. Sen. John McCain of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a crusader on behalf of boxing who co-wrote the law New
Jersey violated, strongly reiterated his position.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley agreed, saying Nevada had the rights to this one in
spite of the money New Jersey stood to make if Tyson resumed his
career there. And the fact Gormley is the brother of one of the two
men who would have voted on the application wasn't lost on Tyson's
handlers.
</P>
<P>
   Even New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman reportedly expressed
her disapproval, particularly after Tyson lost his composure _ what
else is new? _ during his July 29 hearing there.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Tyson and his handers either sensed or were tipped
off that they had made the wrong move and went back to Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   This certainly isn't the route Tyson should have taken. He
should have sought his reinstatement in Nevada from the beginning.
It only makes sense: That's where his despicable transgression took
place; that's where it should be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   However, the important thing is that it ended up there. Now it
can run its proper course.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing will take place within a month, according to Marc
Ratner, director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission. At that
time, the state's five-member board will vote whether to reinstate
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' Ratner said. ``.... I was very, very
concerned that this could splinter the state commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the sake of boxing, this is the best thing that could've
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Time to go: For Rafael Ruelas, enough is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Kostya Tszyu handed Ruelas the first true beating of his career
in a title-elimination bout Saturday in El Paso, stopping the
former IBF lightweight champion from Studio City in the ninth
round.
</P>
<P>
   Tszyu was much too quick, much too strong and much too good for
Ruelas. Ruelas' battered, bruised face was irrefutable evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ruelas never stopped fighting, which is his nature. He's
a fighter in the literal sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   He beat all but four of his opponents as much with his fighter's
heart as his boxing skills. Ironically, it's that admirable quality
that could cost him in the long run: Sometimes it's the fighter who
refuses to fall who gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if Ruelas decides to continue, it could take him years
to position himself for a title shot and the big money. And there
are no guarantees he'll ever work his way back to the top.
</P>
<P>
   What's the point?
</P>
<P>
   No fighter ever made more of his limited natural ability than
Ruelas. No fighter ever had more determination and courage. And no
fighter ever had more class.
</P>
<P>
   If he hangs around too long, his legacy could suffer. And so
might his health.
</P>
<P>
   He should walk away now, with his mind intact, a good chunk of
change in the bank and the admiration of all who were fortunate
enough to follow his career.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: The HBO card on Saturday is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vargas of Oxnard by the IBF, will face Darren Maciunski
in a 10-round junior middleweight bout on the undercard of the
Arturo Gatti-Ivan Robinson lightweight main event.
</P>
<P>
   Also, talented welterweight Jose Luis Lopez faces Ed Goins....
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Peter Broudy is negotiating to match P.J. Goossen and
Hector ``Macho'' Camacho in October somewhere in the San Fernando
Valley, possibly at the Valley College stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Broudy also is trying to match Jimmy ``The Stump'' Buffo, a
former Valley College football player, against Eric ``Butterbean''
Esch in a four-round bout on the card.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen will face Stacy Lane Goodson on the Sept. 9 card at the
Country Club in Reseda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
