<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NELSON HURTING, YANKS IN SEARCH OF RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Nelson said last week that he would consider
concealing from the Yankees any new pain from the bulging disk in
his lower back if he did not think it would prevent him from
pitching effectively. But when Nelson woke up Sunday and felt some
pain in his upper left leg, he did not hide it. Nelson reported it
to the Yankees and they grimaced.
</P>
<P>
   Both Manager Joe Torre and General Manager Brian Cashman spoke
Sunday about the possibility that Nelson might miss the rest of the
season, and both said they must prepare as if that is a likelihood.
Nelson has not pitched in a game since June 24, when he said he
felt ``pain shooting down my legs'' from the bulging disk.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday Nelson said: ``I hope I can come back. You always
have some kind of twitch and you always have a sense it's going to
come back. That's the biggest fear.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a fear the Yankees have privately harbored about the
future of Nelson, a 31-year-old reliever, and their post-season
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, even though the doctors felt he'd always be back,
I've got to take the position that he won't be back, and try to
strengthen that position,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman's pursuit of a reliever surely intensified after
Sunday's development. It increased the chances that the Yankees
would acquire Brian Boehringer or Jim Bruske, both right-handers,
from the San Diego Padres. A baseball official said the Padres were
expected to review their position on the matter Monday and might
ask the Yankees for Shea Morenz, a Class AA outfielder, for one of
the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if the Yankees added Boehringer, a former Yankee, or
Bruske, who is at Class AAA Las Vegas, neither would replace the
more valuable Nelson. Without Nelson, the Yankees would probably
fill the role of right-handed setup man during the post-season with
Ramiro Mendoza or Mike Buddie, or even one of the starters, Orlando
Hernandez or Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a high probability,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very difficult for us to get a guy of Nelson's
caliber anywhere. Because we're in a trade deadline period where
waivers are required, the odds are remote. It won't be for a lack
of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   While Nelson is 5-3 with a 4.54 earned run average, and has
permitted a .291 average to right-handed batters, his sidearm
motion and wicked slider helped him limit right-handers to a .168
mark last season and .245 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If Torre needs a reliever to retire Juan Gonzalez of Texas or
Manny Ramirez of Cleveland in the eighth inning in October, he
wants Nelson. But there seems less of a chance of that happening
now that Nelson's rehabilitation has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher will be re-examined Monday and the Yankees hope the
pain vanishes as quickly as it appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could just be stiffness from throwing off the mound on
Friday,'' said Dr. Stuart Hershon, the team physician. ``We'll have
to see how he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was preparing for not having Nelson, Torre said:
``Sure. Hopefully, we can get help. You can't rely on that,
basically because of the rules of the league and waivers and stuff.
If you can't get that, you have to see how you can offset it
in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said there was a possibility that Nelson could return by
Sept. 1, but it is also possible that Nelson and Darren Holmes, who
also has a bulging disk in his back, may not be on the postseason
roster. Losing Holmes is not a major concern, but losing Nelson is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put yourself in a playoff atmosphere and you've got a
right-handed hitter coming up, there's not anyone in the world
you'd rather have face him than Nellie,'' Paul O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch to Miss Some Time
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch had his left calf elevated and wrapped in a
device designed to reduce swelling before Sunday's game. Joe Torre
said Knoblauch, who fouled a ball off his calf in Saturday's game,
would miss at least two days because of the injury. Homer Bush
started for Knoblauch Sunday and was 2-for-5 with a run scored.
``He only plays once a month and he still stays aggressive,'' Torre
said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Davis to Return in Kansas City
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Chili Davis, who is hitting .278 with two runs
batted in in five games for Class AAA Columbus, will join the
Yankees in Kansas City Monday or Tuesday. Since Davis will be the
DH, Darryl Strawberry must play left field to play regularly. That
is where Joe Torre said Strawberry would play Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
